@node "Third party material" "MUIbase/Third party material"
@toc "Copying"

Third Party Material
====================

   MUIbase uses external libraries and other material depending on the
operating system.

Windows, Mac OS and Linux Versions
----------------------------------

   MUIbase for Windows, Mac OS and Linux uses the Gimp Toolkit (GTK+)
version 2.6 or higher, copyright (C) 2007-2008 The GTK+ Team.  GTK is a
toolkit for developing graphical user interfaces (GUI) and is
distributed under the GNU Library General Public License (LGPL).  For
more information, see @{b}http://www.gtk.org@{ub}.

   The Windows install script for MUIbase is based on the install
script for The Gimp which is copyright by Jernej Simoncic.

Amiga Version
-------------

                    The Amiga version of MUIbase uses


                        MUI - MagicUserInterface

                Copyright (C) 1992-2008 Stefan Stuntz


MUI is a system to generate and maintain graphical user interfaces. With
the  aid  of  a  preferences program, the user of an application has the
ability to customize the outfit according to his personal taste.

MUI is distributed as shareware. To obtain a complete package containing
lots of examples and more information about registration please look for
a  file  called  "muiXXusr.lha"  (XX means the latest version number) on
your local bulletin boards or on public domain disks.

          If you want to register directly, feel free to send


                         DM 30.-  or  US$ 20.-

                                  to

                             Stefan Stuntz
                        Eduard-Spranger-Straße 7
                             80935 München
                                GERMANY



             Support and online registration is available at

                          http://www.sasg.com/

   MUIbase for Amiga uses NList.mcc, copyright (C) 2001-2008 NList Open
Source Team.  See @{b}http://www.sourceforge.net/projects/nlist-classes@{ub} for
more info or latest version.

   MUIbase for Amiga uses BetterString.mcc, copyright (C) 2005-2009
BetterString Open Source Team.  See
@{b}http://www.sourceforge.net/projects/bstring-mcc@{ub} for more info or latest
version.

   MUIbase for Amiga uses TextEditor.mcc, copyright (C) 2005-2009
TextEditor Open Source Team.  See
@{b}http://www.sourceforge.net/projects/texteditor-mcc@{ub} for more info or
latest version.

   MUIbase for Amiga uses codesets.library, copyright (C) 2005-2009
codesets.library Open Source Team.  See
@{b}http://www.sourceforge.net/projects/codesetslib@{ub} for more info or latest
version.

   Some icons used in the MUIbase for Amiga distribution are from the
DefaultIcons set and are copyright (C) Michael-Wolfgang Hohmann and
Angela Schmidt.


@endnode

@node "Welcome to MUIbase" "MUIbase/Welcome to MUIbase"
@toc "Main"

Welcome to MUIbase
******************

   MUIbase is a fast and flexible database system with graphical user
interface (GUI) and programmability.  It is targeted for advanced
desktop users who want to manage data in a comfortable and powerful way.
MUIbase is able to manage any kind of data, e.g. addresses, CD series,
movies, photo collections, your family tree, your income and expense,
and much more.  The power of MUIbase lies in its clear and powerful
graphical user interface and its programming capabilities.  Programming
MUIbase allows you to process data in various ways, e.g. automatic
calculations upon user input, generation of reports, import and export
of data,  etc.  For example it can be used for calculating the total
amount of income, or the total amount of recorded time on a CD, or to
automatically create and print serial letters to your customers.

   MUIbase offers the following features:

   * Unlimited number of projects, tables, attributes, and records.

   * Attributes can be of type string, memo (multi line text), integer,
     real, date, time, Boolean, choice (one item out of many items),
     reference (easy way to reference a record of another table),
     button (for starting MUIbase programs), and virtual (compute value
     on the fly).

   * The string type can also manage lists of strings, files, and fonts.
     A string can refer to an external image which is displayed in the
     graphical user interface.

   * Dynamic loading of records.  Records which are not needed may be
     flushed from memory (e.g. when memory is low).

   * Programmability.  With the easy and powerful MUIbase programming
     language complex tasks can be implemented.  The language also
     includes a SELECT FROM WHERE query for comfortable and fast data
     retrieval.

   * Ordering of records by any combinations of attributes.

   * Flexible and powerful search and filter facility.

   * Query editor which allows entering and managing of SELECT FROM
     WHERE queries.  The queries can be saved and the results can be
     printed.

   * Import and export facility.

   * Full documentation including user and programming manual in HTML
     and PDF (plus AmigaGuide on the Amiga).

   * The Amiga version provides a powerful ARexx interface for
     accessing MUIbase from other programs.  The ARexx interface offers
     a transaction mechanism similar to other relational databases.

   * Operating system independence.  MUIbase is available for Windows,
     Mac OS, Linux and Amiga.  The source code is available as part of
     a Source Forge project.


@endnode

@node "Getting started" "MUIbase/Getting started"
@toc "Main"

Getting Started
***************

   This chapter describes what the hardware and software requirements
are to run MUIbase on your computer, the procedure for installing and
updating MUIbase, and how to start and quit MUIbase.


 @{" Installing MUIbase on Windows " link "Installing MUIbase on Windows"}  32bit Windows 2000, XP, Vista.
 @{" Installing MUIbase on Mac OS " link "Installing MUIbase on Mac OS"}  Mac OS X, Tiger and Leopard.
 @{" Installing MUIbase on Linux  " link "Installing MUIbase on Linux"}  i386 Ubuntu, Debian, Fedora, Mandriva, ...
 @{" Installing MUIbase on Amiga  " link "Installing MUIbase on Amiga"}  Amiga OS3, UAE, Amiga OS4, MorphOS.
 @{" Updating from a previous version " link "Updating from a previous version"}  Already have installed MUIbase?
 @{" Starting MUIbase             " link "Starting MUIbase"}  From desktop or command line interface.
 @{" Quitting MUIbase             " link "Quitting MUIbase"}  When you are done.
 @{" Filename conventions         " link "Filename conventions"}  Environment variables and assign names.


@endnode

@node "Installing MUIbase on Windows" "MUIbase/Installing MUIbase on Windows"
@toc "Getting started"

Installing MUIbase on Windows
=============================

   MUIbase for Windows runs on Intel 386 compatible computers that use
the 32bit versions of Windows 2000, Windows XP or Windows Vista.
MUIbase requires the GTK+ libraries for Windows to be installed on your
system.  Usually, these libraries are not present in most Windows
installations unless you have installed other software that also
requires them, e.g. Gimp.  The hard disk space required for MUIbase is
moderate (less than 10MB).

   The MUIbase installer is distributed as a Windows executable, e.g.
@{b}MUIbase-2.9-setup.exe@{ub} which you can download from the MUIbase home page
@{b}http://muibase.sourceforge.net@{ub}.  When running the installer, your
system will first be checked for the necessary GTK+ libraries.  In case
they cannot be found on your computer, the installer prompts a message
allowing to download and install these libraries from the Internet.
The installer then resumes to installing MUIbase where you will be
asked several options about where to install MUIbase and which
configuration to use.  In case you have a previous MUIbase version
installed on your computer, the installation procedure allows to update
it to the new version.

   After a successful installation your Windows @{b}Start@{ub} menu should
contain a new entry for launching MUIbase.  You can now remove the
MUIbase installer as it is no longer needed.


@endnode

@node "Installing MUIbase on Mac OS" "MUIbase/Installing MUIbase on Mac OS"
@toc "Getting started"

Installing MUIbase on Mac OS
============================

   MUIbase for Mac OS supports Mac OS X Tiger (10.4) and Mac OS X
Leopard (10.5).  The software is distributed as universal binaries
containing both, a PowerPC and an Intel version.

   A disk image of MUIbase, e.g. @{b}MUIbase-2.9.dmg@{ub} can be downloaded from
the MUIbase home page @{b}http://muibase.sourceforge.net@{ub}.  After
downloading and opening the image, drag and drop @{b}MUIbase.app@{ub} into your
computer's @{b}Applications@{ub} folder.  This installs MUIbase and all
necessary libraries including GTK+ on your system.

   The default appearance of MUIbase for Mac OS uses the default GTK
engine.  If you rather prefer a more native look and feel then rename
the file @{b}gtkrc-quartz@{ub} in directory
@{b}MUIbase.app/Contents/Resources/etc/gtk-2.0@{ub} into @{b}gtkrc@{ub} and restart
MUIbase.

   Note that this setting is experimental and the appearance of some
GUI elements may be broken.


@endnode

@node "Installing MUIbase on Linux" "MUIbase/Installing MUIbase on Linux"
@toc "Getting started"

Installing MUIbase on Linux
===========================

   You can install and run MUIbase on an Intel 386 compatible computer
running the Linux operating system.  Your system should have a recent
X11 server and GTK+ (version 2.6 or higher) installed.  Required hard
disk space is moderate (less then 10MB).

   MUIbase for i386 Linux is distributed both, as a Debian package
(e.g. @{b}muibase_2.9_i386.deb@{ub} for Ubuntu or Debian) and as an RPM archive
(e.g. @{b}MUIbase-2.9-i386.rpm@{ub} for Fedora or Mandriva).  Both versions can
be downloaded from the MUIbase home page @{b}http://muibase.sourceforge.net@{ub}.

   Usually MUIbase installs or updates itself automatically after
downloading it on your computer.  In case the installation process does
not start automatically, the following commands executed as super user
(root) in a command shell install or update MUIbase on a Debian-based
Linux computer:

     dpkg --install MUIBASE.DEB
    where MUIBASE.DEB is the downloaded MUIbase Debian package.

On a Redhat-based system (RPM), the commands are:

     rpm -Uvh MUIBASE.RPM
    where MUIBASE.RPM is the downloaded RPM archive.

After a successful installation you should see a new menu item in the
@{b}Applications - Office@{ub} menu tree of your (Gnome or KDE) desktop.  At
this time the downloaded archive is no longer necessary and can be
removed.


@endnode

@node "Installing MUIbase on Amiga" "MUIbase/Installing MUIbase on Amiga"
@toc "Getting started"

Installing MUIbase on Amiga
===========================

   MUIbase for Amiga runs on Amiga OS version 3.0 or higher and
requires an 68020 processor or better.  Furthermore, MUI version 3.8 or
higher must be present on your system.  A minimum of 4MB RAM and 10MB
of free hard disk space are needed.  The m68k binary of MUIbase for
Amiga has been reported to run stable on UAE, MorphOS and Amiga OS4.
PowerPC binaries for MorphOS and Amiga OS4 are also available as part
of the distributed archive.  A seprate distribution contains an AROS
version.

   MUIbase is distributed as an lha archive, e.g. @{b}MUIbase-2.9.lha@{ub} and
can be downloaded from the MUIbase home page
@{b}http://muibase.sourceforge.net@{ub}.  In order to install MUIbase on your
computer unpack this archive to a temporary directory.  Do not unpack
it to the target directory!

   Double click the MUIbase installer script @{b}Install-MUIbase@{ub} and follow
its instructions.  The script asks for a directory where the software
should be copied to.  Do not enter the directory where you have
unpacked the MUIbase archive to.  The script is also capable of
updating an existing MUIbase installation by entering the directory
where you previously installed MUIbase.

   After successful installation you will find a (new) drawer on your
system containing the MUIbase program along with all necessary files
and some sample projects.  In addition an assign @{b}MUIbase:@{ub} referring to
this drawer has been added to your system file @{b}S:User-Startup@{ub}.  It is
safe to remove the lha archive and the temporary files as they are no
longer needed.


@endnode

@node "Updating from a previous version" "MUIbase/Updating from a previous version"
@toc "Getting started"

Updating from a Previous Version
================================

   When installing MUIbase, you can upgrade from a previous version of
MUIbase or reinstall it as described above.  During the new
installation, all necessary files are replaced by new ones.  This
includes the sample projects in the @{b}Demos@{ub} directory.  It is therefore
not recommended to place your own projects into this directory nor to
use any of the sample projects for managing your own data as they are
overwritten when reinstalling or upgrading MUIbase.

   The recommended way to manage your own projects is to place them
into a separate directory independent of the MUIbase installation
directory.


@endnode

@node "Starting MUIbase" "MUIbase/Starting MUIbase"
@toc "Getting started"

Starting MUIbase
================

   MUIbase can be started either from your graphical environment or
from a command shell.  On Windows you find MUIbase under the @{b}Start@{ub} menu.
On Mac OS, you launch MUIbase using @{b}Finder@{ub} from the @{b}Applications@{ub}
directory.  If you are running Gnome or KDE on Linux, you can start
MUIbase by choosing the corresponding item from the @{b}Applications -
Office@{ub} menu.  On the Workbench (Amiga) you double click the MUIbase icon
or the icon of a MUIbase project which is then automatically loaded
after starting MUIbase (you can also select several MUIbase projects by
shift clicking them and double clicking the last one).

   When starting MUIbase from a command shell on Windows, Linux or Amiga
you can include command line arguments and optional projects to load.
There are two basic ways to start MUIbase from a command shell:

     MUIbase [PROJECT1 ...]
     MUIbase -n

   The first form starts MUIbase and loads the optional projects
specified by their filenames PROJECT1 ....  The second form starts
MUIbase without graphical user interface.  This can be useful for
running MUIbase as a server in the background and accessing it through
its external interface (e.g. ARexx on Amiga, see @{"ARexx interface" link "ARexx interface"}).


@endnode

@node "Quitting MUIbase" "MUIbase/Quitting MUIbase"
@toc "Getting started"

Quitting MUIbase
================

   To quit MUIbase select menu item @{b}Project - Quit@{ub} or close all opened
projects.


@endnode

@node "Filename conventions" "MUIbase/Filename conventions"
@toc "Getting started"

Filename Conventions on Windows, Mac OS and Linux
=================================================

   MUIbase for Windows, Mac OS and Linux has a few special conventions
for filenames that are usually not found in other software on those
systems.

   When MUIbase is starting, an environment variable @{b}MUIbase@{ub} is set
referring to the installation directory of MUIbase.  On Windows this is
the directory specified during the software installation.  On Mac OS,
it is directory
@{b}/Applications/MUIbase.app/Contents/Resources/share/MUIbase@{ub}.  On Linux,
it is directory @{b}/usr/share/MUIbase@{ub}.

   When interpreting filenames (either entered by the user or the
filenames present in this documentation) a filename is examined for the
occurrence of environment variables.  If a filename contains a dollar
sign @{b}$@{ub} then the characters following it until the first
non-alpha-numeric character are interpreted as an environment variable
and, if the environment variable is set, the part of the filename is
replaced by the contents of the environment variable (otherwise the part
of the filename is left unchanged including the @{b}$@{ub} sign).  You can use
parentheses around the environment variable if it contains
non-alpha-numeric characters.  For example @{b}$HOME/data@{ub} expands to the
path where @{b}$HOME@{ub} has been replaced with the path name of your home
directory.

   Furthermore, Amiga-style @{b}assign names@{ub} are handled in the following
way.  If a filename contains a colon @{b}:@{ub} then everything before the colon
is treated like an environment variable (called @{b}assign name@{ub}) and is
replaced by its contents if the environment variable is set.  @{b}Assign
names@{ub} should be at least 2 characters in length, in order to
distinguish them from drive letters on Windows.

   These conventions allow, for example, to refer to the movie sample
database inside the MUIbase installation directory as
@{b}MUIbase:demos/Movie.mb@{ub}.

   Another example is when you set an environment variable, say
@{b}EXTERNAL_DATA@{ub}, referring to the directory where you store external data
like images, etc.  of one of your projects.  You can then access data
inside this directory through @{b}EXTERNAL_DATA:some-file@{ub} and store such
filenames in the database project.


@endnode

@node "Tutorial" "MUIbase/Tutorial"
@toc "Main"

Tutorial
********

   The making of a family-tree database.

   This chapter contains a brief tutorial describing the basic usage of
MUIbase.  Within the tutorial a small project is developed that allows
the managing of your family tree.  The project that results after
applying all steps in this tutorial can be found as the @{b}FamilyTree.mb@{ub}
project located in the @{b}Demos@{ub} directory of your MUIbase installation.

How MUIbase Works
=================

   MUIbase could be said to operate in two different modes,
record-editing and structure-editing mode.

   The record-editing mode is where you add, change, or delete records.

   The structure-editing mode lets you edit how your database should
look like and what tables and attributes it contains.

   Besides this there is the program editor where you enter program
functions that are executed automatically when entering data or
explicitly when pressing a program button.

Starting with a Project, the Structure Editor
=============================================

   To create a database you first need to define it's contents.  In
MUIbase this is done in the structure editor which is opened by
choosing @{b}Structure editor@{ub} in the @{b}Project@{ub} menu.  Here you find three
different sections:

@{b}Tables@{ub}
     Add, change, or delete the tables of your project.

@{b}Attributes@{ub}
     Add, change, or delete attributes of the currently selected table.

@{b}Display@{ub}
     Specify the graphical layout of your database, i.e. how it should
     be displayed.

Adding a Table
==============

   First we need a table, press the @{b}New@{ub} button just below the list view
in the @{b}Table@{ub} section.  You will then see a dialog which asks you to
enter some data:

@{b}Name@{ub}
     The name of the table.  The name must begin with an uppercase
     letter and can consist of up to 20 characters.  The name can be
     changed later.  In this tutorial we set the name to @{b}Person@{ub} since
     it's going to hold all the person's names in this database.

@{b}Number of records@{ub}
     A table can either consist of only one or of an unlimited number
     of records.  In our case it should be set to unlimited since we
     are going to add more than one person.

@{b}Trigger functions@{ub}
     The adding and deletion of records can be controlled by program
     functions.  This is where you set which function to call.  Since
     we don't have written any program functions yet, we leave the
     fields empty.

   When this is done, just press the @{b}OK@{ub} button and we have our first
table, @{b}Person@{ub}.

Adding an Attribute
===================

   Then we need a string attribute for that table, press @{b}New@{ub} in the
attributes section.  Attributes also need some settings:

@{b}Name@{ub}
     The same as for a table: first letter must be uppercase and
     altogether a maximum of 20 characters.  We set the name of this
     attribute to @{b}Name@{ub} as it will contain the names of the persons we
     are about to add.

@{b}Type@{ub}
     Here we choose what type this attribute should be.  There are a
     couple of different ones but for this attribute we use a string
     attribute.

@{b}Max length@{ub}
     Here you can define the maximum number of characters a user can
     enter for the string.  We set this to 30.

@{b}Initial value@{ub}
     It's possible to have some attributes to use an initial value for
     every new record you add, here is where you enter what it should
     contain.  Leave this line blank.

@{b}Trigger@{ub}
     An attribute could also trigger a program function to be executed.
     For example, if you enter a name then you can have a program to
     check if this name already exists.  We leave this field empty.

Displaying the Project
======================

   After pressing @{b}OK@{ub} you now should notice some changes in the display
section.  Change the choice button on the top of the display section to
@{b}Main window@{ub}.  There you see what the main window holds, currently only
table @{b}Person@{ub}.  If you change the choice button back to @{b}Table mask@{ub}, you
can see how table @{b}Person@{ub} is presented.  Currently it's displayed as one
panel with one attribute.

   Now double-click on @{b}Panel(Person)@{ub} at the top of the list in the
display section and a window should appear, allowing you to set how
this panel should be displayed:

@{b}Title@{ub}
     The title of a table can be different to it's name.  Our table is
     called @{b}Person@{ub} but here we could set it to be @{b}THIS IS THE TABLE
     PERSON!@{ub} if we prefer that better.

@{b}Background@{ub}
     The background can be changed to whatever suits your taste.

@{b}Gadgets@{ub}
     Here we can define what gadgets we want the panel to have.

   Press @{b}OK@{ub} and then double-click on @{b}Name@{ub} in the list-view in the
display section.  This brings up the window that contains the settings
for how to display the string attribute @{b}Name@{ub}.

@{b}Title@{ub}
     The same as for the panel.  The string you enter here is what is
     really displayed when in record-editing mode.

@{b}Shortcut@{ub}
     Here you can set a letter that can be used to jump to this
     attribute, when in record-editing mode.  For jumping to the
     attribute you need to hold down the @{b}Alt@{ub} key (Windows, Mac OS and
     Linux) respectively the @{b}Amiga@{ub} key and then press the letter.

@{b}Home@{ub}
     Makes the cursor to jump to this attribute whenever a new record
     is added.  In our case we will always or most of the time enter
     the name first in a new record, so set it.

@{b}Read only@{ub}
     Set this if the attribute should be read only. Leave it unset.

@{b}Weight@{ub}
     Decides how much of this attribute should be visible when
     competing for the space with other attributes.  For example, if
     three 50-character strings resides in a window that only has room
     for 100 characters, then this number decides how much space the
     string gets relatively to the other ones.  Leave it at 100.

@{b}Background@{ub}
     The same as for the panel.

@{b}Bubble help@{ub}
     Here you enter any text you think would be helpful to the user.
     The bubble help appears after holding the mouse still over an
     attribute for some seconds.  Set this to @{b}If you need help, call
     the author at 112@{ub}.

   Leave the structure editor (choose @{b}Exit structure editor@{ub} in the
@{b}Project@{ub} menu) and you are back to record-editing mode where you see how
the database really looks like.  You'll see the headline which is the
string you may have entered in the display section for the panel.  The
record counter should say @{b}#0/0@{ub} since we haven't added any records yet.
Thereafter is a filter button and two arrow buttons.  Below all this
you should have the @{b}Name@{ub} attribute with the text you may have entered
in the display section for this attribute.  If you haven't changed any
text at all when in the display section then the panel should be named
@{b}Person@{ub}, and the string attribute @{b}Name@{ub}.  Move the mouse above the string
attribute @{b}Name@{ub} and leave it there for a couple of seconds.  If you
entered something in the bubble help above then this text should appear
in a popup window.

Adding two Reference Attributes
===============================

   Now we will add two reference attributes.  Reference attributes are
a bit different than other attributes.  As their name might imply they
refer to records.  This will become more understandable as you try it
out for yourself in just a while.

   Enter the structure editor again and add two more attributes to
table @{b}Person@{ub}.  Press @{b}New@{ub} in the attributes section, name it @{b}Father@{ub}, and
change it's type to @{b}Reference@{ub}.  A reference attribute has only one
setting:

@{b}Set reference to@{ub}
     Tells which table the attribute refers to.  It should already be
     pointing to table @{b}Person@{ub}.  Leave it that way and press @{b}Ok@{ub}.

   Add another attribute by pressing @{b}New@{ub} in the attribute section and
call it @{b}Mother@{ub}.  The attribute's type should also be set to reference
and point to table @{b}Person@{ub}.

   As you may have noticed, there are now three attributes in the
display section.  Click on @{b}Father@{ub} and then on the buttons up and down
located just to the left.  This will change where @{b}Father@{ub} is positioned
when looking at it while in record-editing mode.  Put @{b}Father@{ub} at the
top, @{b}Name@{ub} in the middle, and @{b}Mother@{ub} at the bottom.

   Next, we specify what contents the reference attributes @{b}Father@{ub} and
@{b}Mother@{ub} should display from the referenced records.  Double-click on
@{b}Father@{ub} in the display section and then click on @{b}Extras@{ub}.  Here we choose
to display the string attribute @{b}Name@{ub}, then we press @{b}Ok@{ub} and repeat the
procedure for @{b}Mother@{ub}.

Adding Records
==============

   Now we should add some records.  Leave the structure editor and
enter record-editing mode.  To add a new record you choose @{b}New record@{ub}
from the @{b}Table@{ub} menu (on Windows and Linux you find this menu by
pressing and holding the right mouse button inside the table mask).
The cursor should now automatically jump to the attribute we have set to
@{b}Home@{ub} earlier in the display section in the structure editor.  Add two
records, one with your fathers name in @{b}Name@{ub} and another one with your
mothers name in @{b}Name@{ub}.  Thereafter you add another record with your own
name in @{b}Name@{ub}.

   Now it's time to understand those reference attributes.  By pressing
on the list-view button on @{b}Father@{ub} we get a list of all records this
reference attribute could refer to.  Choose your fathers name and do
accordingly down below on the mothers list-view.

   Now you should have three records, you, your father and your mother.
In your record, your fathers name should be visible in @{b}Father@{ub} at the
top and your mothers name should be in @{b}Mother@{ub} at the bottom.  You can
browse through the records by pressing @{b}Alt@{ub} together with the cursor
keys @{b}Up@{ub} and @{b}Down@{ub}.

   But hey! My parents also has/had parents you say!  So let's add
another four records, the third generation.  Just add the records one
by one and write their names in @{b}Name@{ub}.  If you don't remember their
names then just enter @{b}father's father@{ub}, @{b}mother's father@{ub} or something
like that instead.  Then you browse through all the records and set
@{b}Father@{ub} and @{b}Mother@{ub} to what they should contain.  When this is done you
should have at least seven records, your record, your parents records
and your grandparents records.

Filter
======

   Since we now have some records to work with, we could try out the
filter function.  The filter can sort out records you don't want to
display, they will still remain in the database but they are just not
displayed anymore.

   To edit the filter you choose @{b}Change filter@{ub} from the @{b}Table@{ub} menu.  A
window with loads of operators will appear.  This is where you set what
conditions a record must fulfill to get displayed.

   In this small example we will use the @{b}LIKE@{ub} command, which lets you
do a joker comparison of an attribute.  Press once on the @{b}LIKE@{ub} button
to the right and then double-click on @{b}Name@{ub} in the list to the left and
@{b}(LIKE Name )@{ub} should appear in the string just above the @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub}
buttons.  Thereafter you type @{b}"*a*"@{ub} so the whole string shows @{b}(LIKE
Name "*a*")@{ub}.  This means that MUIbase should display all records that
contain the letter @{b}a@{ub} anywhere in @{b}Name@{ub}.

   Press @{b}Ok@{ub} and you may notice that records with no @{b}a@{ub} in @{b}Name@{ub}, no
longer are visible.  Since the letter @{b}a@{ub} is quite common in most
languages and names, all records might still be visible but you can try
other letters to make the filter function more clear.

   As mentioned earlier there is a button on the panel that says @{b}F@{ub}.
This @{b}F@{ub} indicates if the filter is on or off.  Finally when you're done
testing, turn the filter off so that all records are visible.

Queries
=======

   Now that we have played with the filter function a bit, we turn to
the query feature of MUIbase.  Queries can be used to display
information from a database matching certain criteria.

   Choose @{b}Queries@{ub} from the @{b}Program@{ub} menu to open the query editor.  Now
a window with some buttons on the top and two larger areas below appear.
The string to the upper left is where you enter the name of what you
want to call the query you make.

@{b}Run@{ub}
     Compiles and runs the query.

@{b}Print@{ub}
     Prints the result of the query to a file or on your printer.

@{b}Load and Save@{ub}
     Lets you load and save each of the queries.

   The first large area is where you enter the query.  The second large
area is where the result is displayed.

   Now let's produce a list of all those persons we tried to filter out
previously.  Type @{b}Persons with an a in their name@{ub} in the string to the
upper left.  This is the title for this query.  In the upper large
area, type:

     SELECT Name FROM Person WHERE (LIKE Name "*a*")

   Now when you run this query by pressing the @{b}Run@{ub} button it will
produce a list of all persons with the letter @{b}a@{ub} in their name.  Try
changing the letter to see different results.

   At this time we can introduce the @{b}AND@{ub} command.  Press the list-view
button just to the left of the @{b}Run@{ub} button in the query editor.  Then
choose @{b}New@{ub} and name it @{b}Persons with both letter a and s in their names@{ub}.
Then type

     SELECT Name FROM Person WHERE
     (AND (LIKE Name "*a*") (LIKE Name "*s*"))

   Note that we are still using the @{b}LIKE@{ub} command for choosing records
containing the letters @{b}a@{ub} or @{b}s@{ub} in their names, but the @{b}AND@{ub} command
requires that BOTH @{b}LIKE@{ub} criteria are met.  Therefore, only records with
BOTH the letters @{b}a@{ub} and @{b}s@{ub} in their name are displayed when the query is
run.

Adding a Table with a Memo and a Button Attribute
=================================================

   These were two ways of selecting and displaying the database.
Another way of displaying data can be done by a program.  In order to
display data we can use an attribute type called memo.

   Enter the structure editor and press @{b}New@{ub} in the table section.  Name
the new table @{b}Control@{ub} and set it's number of records to @{b}Exactly one@{ub}.
Click and hold down the mouse button on the new table.  Now drag it
just a bit above the middle of table @{b}Person@{ub} and release the button.  In
the table section, @{b}Control@{ub} should now be on top, followed by @{b}Person@{ub}
below.

   Make sure that table @{b}Control@{ub} is selected, then press @{b}New@{ub} in the
attribute section.  Set the type of the new attribute to @{b}Memo@{ub} and give
it the name @{b}Result@{ub}.  Press @{b}Ok@{ub} and then add another attribute to table
@{b}Control@{ub} by once again pressing @{b}New@{ub} in the attribute section.  This
time, set it's type to @{b}Button@{ub} and name it @{b}Pedigree@{ub}.

   To give the database a better look, click once on @{b}Pedigree@{ub} in the
display section and push it to the top by pressing the @{b}Up@{ub} button once.

Programming MUIbase to do a Pedigree
====================================

   Now we have a button that can start a program and a memo to display
data in.  It's therefore time to enter the program editor.  This is
done by choosing @{b}Edit@{ub} from the @{b}Program@{ub} menu.  The editor has three
buttons:

@{b}Compile & Close@{ub}
     Which does just that. It compiles the program and leaves the
     program editor.

@{b}Compile@{ub}
     Compiles the programs but stays in the program editor.

@{b}Revert@{ub}
     Reverts all changes back to the state when you entered the program
     editor.

   As all program functions you write will reside in this one window,
we will need to separate them from each other.  In MUIbase this is done
by the @{b}DEFUN@{ub} command.  Everything between the two parenthesis will be
part of the function @{b}pedigree@{ub} in this example:

     (DEFUN pedigree ()
     
     ; This is DEFUN's end parenthesis
     )

   With this in mind we now type in the first function which will
produce a family tree of the current person in the database and place
the result in attribute @{b}Result@{ub}.  This @{b}pedigree@{ub} function is in fact
three functions:

   * @{b}pedigree@{ub} which sets @{b}Control.Result@{ub} by calling another function.

   * @{b}getpedigree@{ub} which collects the pedigree into a nested list.

   * @{b}pedigree2memo@{ub} which converts this list to the memo.

     ; The program pedigree
     
     (DEFUN pedigree ()
         (SETQ Control.Result (pedigree2memo (getpedigree Person NIL) 0 3))
     )
     
     
     ; The program getpedigree
     
     (DEFUN getpedigree (person:Person level:INT)
         (IF (AND person (OR (NULL level) (> level 0)))
             (LIST person.Name
                 (getpedigree person.Father (1- level))
                 (getpedigree person.Mother (1- level))
             )
         )
     )
     
     
     ; The program pedigree2memo
     
     (DEFUN pedigree2memo (pedigree:LIST indent:INT level:INT)
         (IF (> level 0)
             (+
                 (pedigree2memo (NTH 1 pedigree) (+ indent 8) (1- level))
                 (IF pedigree (SPRINTF "%*s%s\\n" indent "" (FIRST pedigree)) "\\n")
                 (pedigree2memo (NTH 2 pedigree) (+ indent 8) (1- level))
             )
             ""
         )
     )

   When typing this program, make sure that all the parenthesis are
where they should be.  Too many or too few parenthesis is the most
common error you get when MUIbase is compiling your program.  The error
message from MUIbase probably is @{b}Syntax Error@{ub} in this case.  Press
@{b}Compile & close@{ub} and the window closes, which means that there weren't
any mistakes during compiling.

   Don't worry too much if you don't understand all the functions at
first.  There is a complete chapter (see @{"Programming MUIbase" link "Programming MUIbase"})
containing a reference of all functions including their detailed
descriptions.

   Now we have a program to run, but first we have to assign the
program function to the @{b}Pedigree@{ub} button.  This is done by entering the
structure editor, selecting @{b}Control@{ub} in the table section and
double-clicking on the @{b}Pedigree@{ub} attribute in the attribute section.
Then open the list-view @{b}Trigger@{ub}.  In this list, all your program
functions will be listed, currently there should be three functions:
@{b}pedigree@{ub}, @{b}getpedigree@{ub} and @{b}pedigree2memo@{ub}.  Double-click on @{b}pedigree@{ub} as
the program function the @{b}Pedigree@{ub} button will trigger, then press @{b}Ok@{ub}
and leave the structure editor.

   Now if everything is done correctly, pushing the @{b}Pedigree@{ub} button
will produce a pedigree of the current person.  Try changing person to
see some different pedigrees.

Programming MUIbase to List a Person's Children
===============================================

   As the next addition to this database requires some more records,
you should add your brothers and sisters.  If you don't have any then
write @{b}My faked sister 1@{ub}, @{b}My faked brother 1@{ub} which of course should be
set to have the same parents as you have.

   Then go to the program editor and type the following for creating
another program.

     ; The program children counts the number of children of a person.
     ; First we define the variables, e.g. "names" holds the children's names.
     
     (DEFUN children ()
         (LET ( (names "") (count 0) (parent Person) )
     
         ; For all records in table Person do the following:
         ; If the variable parent appears as father or mother
         ; in any of the records then:
         ;     add the name to the variable names
         ;     increase count by 1.
     
         (FOR ALL Person DO
             (IF (OR (= parent Father) (= parent Mother))
                 (
                     (SETQ names (+ names Name "\\n"))
                     (SETQ count (1+ count))
                 )
             )
         )
     
         ; Then we write the result into the Control.Result.
         ; If the current person doesn't have any children, write one string.
         ; If he/she has children then write another string.
     
         (SETQ Control.Result
             (+ Person.Name (IF (> count 0)
                 (+ " is the proud parent of " (STR count) " children.")
                 " does not have any children (yet :-)."
             ))
         )
     
     
         ; If the parent has children then add their names.
     
         (IF (<> count 0)
             (SETQ Control.Result
                 (+ Control.Result "\\n\\n"
                     (IF (= count 1)
                         "The child's name is:"
                         "The children's names are:"
                     )
     		"\\n\\n"
                     names
                 )
             )
         )
     
         ; This is the end parenthesis of the LET-command.
         )
     
     ; This is the end parenthesis of DEFUN children.
     )

   To create variables, we use the @{b}LET@{ub} command.  Variables created with
the @{b}LET@{ub} command are local and only visible within the @{b}LET@{ub} command's
open and closing parentheses.  Thus any command that accesses these
variables has to be placed within these parentheses.

   All we need to execute this program is a new program button.
Therefore, enter the structure editor and add a button attribute in
table @{b}Control@{ub}.  Call it @{b}Children@{ub} and choose @{b}children@{ub} as the program
function it should trigger.

   To bring some order in the mask of table @{b}Control@{ub} it's now time to
introduce groups.  All objects can be ordered into vertically or
horizontally aligned groups.

   In the display section, click on @{b}Pedigree@{ub} and shift-click on
@{b}Children@{ub}, thereafter you click on the @{b}Group@{ub} button to the left.  Now
the two program buttons will be together in a vertically aligned group.
However, we want this one to be horizontally aligned so double-click on
the @{b}VGroup@{ub} that has appeared in the display section.  This will open a
window that lets you change the settings for this group.  Set the title
to @{b}Programs@{ub} and check the @{b}Horizontal@{ub} button.

   At this time we can hide the name of attribute @{b}Result@{ub} in table
@{b}Control@{ub}.  Double-click on @{b}Result@{ub} in the display section and empty the
title field.  This will display attribute @{b}Result@{ub} without any title
string.

   To make things easier, if we add more programs or attributes in
table @{b}Control@{ub}, we should place @{b}Result@{ub} and the @{b}Programs@{ub} group into a
vertical group.  Be sure that you have only marked @{b}Programs@{ub} and @{b}Result@{ub}
then press @{b}Group@{ub}.  This places @{b}Programs@{ub} and @{b}Result@{ub} into a vertical
group.

   Leave the structure editor and take a look at the result.  Then
press the @{b}Children@{ub} button to see the number of children and their names
of the current person.

   This example could very well be extended into a fully-grown pedigree
program.  The only real limits are your fantasy and the size of your
hard drive.


@endnode

@node "Basic concepts" "MUIbase/Basic concepts"
@toc "Main"

Basic Concepts
**************

   Before you start setting up your own database projects and entering
data for them, you should now about some basic concepts MUIbase is
built on.


 @{" Projects                   " link "Projects"}  MUIbase projects.
 @{" Tables                     " link "Tables"}  Basic data management.
 @{" Records                    " link "Records (concept)"}  One row of a table.
 @{" Attributes                 " link "Attributes"}  One column of a table.
 @{" Attribute types            " link "Attribute types"}  Types available for attributes.
 @{" Table of attribute types   " link "Table of attribute types"}  Summary about attribute types.
 @{" Memory consumption         " link "Memory consumption"}  How much space each type needs.
 @{" Relationships              " link "Relationships"}  Connecting tables.
 @{" User interface             " link "User interface"}  Elements for layout.


@endnode

@node "Projects" "MUIbase/Projects"
@toc "Basic concepts"

Projects
========

   A MUIbase project consists of all relevant information you need for
managing your data.  This includes the project's user interface, the
project's data you entered and the programs you wrote for the project.

   A project can be loaded from, saved to, and deleted from disk.  Any
change you make to a project is only done in memory.  At any time you
can go back to the state of the last saved project by reloading it.

   MUIbase is able to handle multiple projects at a time.  Therefore it
is not necessary to start MUIbase twice just to load another project.


@endnode

@node "Tables" "MUIbase/Tables"
@toc "Basic concepts"

Tables
======

   MUIbase manages data in tables.  A table is organized in rows and
columns, where rows are called records and columns are called
attributes.

   See the following table for an example on how to structure a set of
addresses in a table.


    Name              | Street              | City
    ------------------|---------------------|------------------------
    Steffen Gutmann   | Wiesentalstr. 30    | 73312 Geislingen/Eybach
    Charles Saltzman  | University of Iowa  | Iowa City 52242
    Nicola Müller     | 21W. 59th Street    | Westmont, Illinois 60559

   There exists a special table kind which can hold exactly one record.
A table of this kind is sometimes useful for controlling the database
project, e.g. you can put buttons into this table for executing various
actions, or a read-only attribute for displaying project related
information.  For an example suppose you have an account database where
you store all your income and expense.  An exactly-one table now could
have a read-only attribute of type real for displaying the total
balance.

   Each table has two record pointers, a pointer to the record that is
currently displayed in the user interface (called @{i}GUI record pointer@{ui})
and a pointer to the record that is the current one while executing a
MUIbase program (called @{i}program record pointer@{ui}).

   You can define any number of tables for a MUIbase project.  Tables
can be added to, renamed, and deleted from a project.


@endnode

@node "Records (concept)" "MUIbase/Records (concept)"
@toc "Basic concepts"

Records
=======

   A record is one row of a table.  It holds all information about one
set, e.g. in a table that manages addresses, one record holds one
address.

   Each record has a record number that reflects the record's position
in the table.  This number may change when you add or delete records.

   For each table a record called @{i}initial record@{ui} exists that holds the
default values for initializing new records.  The initial record always
has a record number of 0.

   Records can be added to, changed, and deleted from a table.  The
records are not necessary held in memory but are loaded from and stored
to disk when needed.  There are two restrictions for the total number
of records of one table.  The record number is a 32bit integer value,
which (theoretically) limits the total number of records to 4294967295.
Another (and more severe) limitation is that for each record a small
record header is kept in memory.  These limitations still make MUIbase
usable for record numbers of 10,000 and more.


@endnode

@node "Attributes" "MUIbase/Attributes"
@toc "Basic concepts"

Attributes
==========

   An attribute defines one column of a table.  It specifies the type
and appearance of the corresponding column.

   Attributes can be added to, renamed, and deleted from a table.
There is no upper limit on the number of attributes per table.

   For each attribute you have to specify a type that restricts the
contents of this attribute.  See the next section for a list of
available attribute types.


@endnode

@node "Attribute types" "MUIbase/Attribute types"
@toc "Basic concepts"

Attribute Types
===============

   For attributes the following types are available:


 @{" String                    " link "String type"}  Any single line of text. Can also be used to
                                store font-names, filenames, and external images.
 @{" Integer                   " link "Integer type"}  Ordinary numbers.
 @{" Real                      " link "Real type"}  Floating point numbers.
 @{" Boolean                   " link "Boolean type"}  Boolean value.
 @{" Choice                    " link "Choice type"}  One item out of many items.
 @{" Date                      " link "Date type"}  Date values.
 @{" Time                      " link "Time type"}  Time values.
 @{" Memo                      " link "Memo type"}  Multi-line text.
 @{" Reference                 " link "Reference"}  Reference to another record.
 @{" Virtual                   " link "Virtual"}  Compute value on the fly.
 @{" Button                    " link "Button"}  For triggering MUIbase programs.

   Some of the attribute types support a special value called NIL.
This special value has the meaning of an undefined value, e.g. for a
type of date it means an unknown date.  The NIL value is similar to the
NULL value in other database systems.

   Please note that once you have set the type of an attribute, you
cannot change it later.


@endnode

@node "String type" "MUIbase/String type"
@toc "Attribute types"

String Attributes
-----------------

   String attributes can store any single line of text.  Strings are
the most often used attribute type in a database project.  For example
an address database could store the name, street, and city of a person
each in its own string attribute.

   For a string attribute you have to specify the maximum number of
characters allowed in the string.  This number does not directly affect
the amount of memory or disk space that is used by this attribute
because only the actual string contents are stored  (other databases
have called this feature compressed strings).  If necessary the number
can be changed after you have installed a string attribute.

   String attributes can also be used to store font- and filenames.
For filenames external viewers can be launched to display the file
contents.  Furthermore an in-line image class allows displaying the
image of a file.

   String attributes do not support the NIL value.


@endnode

@node "Integer type" "MUIbase/Integer type"
@toc "Attribute types"

Integer Attributes
------------------

   Integer attributes store integral values in the range of -2147483648
to 2147483647.  They are mostly used for storing quantities of any kind,
e.g. the number of children of a person, or the number of song titles
on a CD.

   Integer attributes support the NIL value representing an undefined
integer value.


@endnode

@node "Real type" "MUIbase/Real type"
@toc "Attribute types"

Real Attributes
---------------

   Real attributes store floating point values in the range of
-3.59e308 to +3.59e308.  They are used for storing numbers of any kind,
e.g. the amount of money in an income/expense project.

   For each real attribute you can specify the number of decimal places
used for displaying the real value, though internally always the full
precision is stored.

   Real attributes support the NIL value representing an undefined real
value.


@endnode

@node "Boolean type" "MUIbase/Boolean type"
@toc "Attribute types"

Boolean Attributes
------------------

   Boolean attributes store one bit of information.  They are used for
storing yes/no or true/false values, e.g. in a project managing
invoices a Boolean attribute could store the @{b}has paid?@{ub} information.

   Boolean attributes use TRUE and NIL as Boolean values.  NIL in this
case stands for a value of FALSE.


@endnode

@node "Choice type" "MUIbase/Choice type"
@toc "Attribute types"

Choice Attributes
-----------------

   Choice attributes store one item out of an enumeration of items.
For example, in an address project a choice attribute may be used for
storing a country name, where the country is one out of @{b}USA@{ub}, @{b}Canada@{ub},
@{b}Germany@{ub}, or @{b}others@{ub}.

   A choice attribute does not store the item string but the item
number (index) in a record.  The number of items and the items itself
can be modified after the attribute has been created.  However when
making changes to a choice attribute, values in existing records are
not changed to reflect the new labeling.

   Choice attributes do not support the NIL value.


@endnode

@node "Date type" "MUIbase/Date type"
@toc "Attribute types"

Date Attributes
---------------

   Date attributes store calendar dates.  For example, a date attribute
can be used for storing birthdays.

   The format for entering and displaying date values can be one of
@{b}DD.MM.YYYY@{ub}, @{b}MM/DD/YYYY@{ub}, or @{b}YYYY-MM-DD@{ub}, where @{b}DD@{ub}, @{b}MM@{ub} and @{b}YYYY@{ub} are
standing for two and four digit values representing the day, month and
year of the date respectively.

   Date attributes support the NIL value representing an undefined date.


@endnode

@node "Time type" "MUIbase/Time type"
@toc "Attribute types"

Time Attributes
---------------

   Time attributes store the time of day or a period of time.  For
example, a time attribute can be used for storing the durations of
music titles on a CD.

   The format for entering and displaying time values can be one of
@{b}HH:MM:SS@{ub}, @{b}MM:SS@{ub} or @{b}HH:MM@{ub}, where @{b}HH@{ub} represents the hours, @{b}MM@{ub} the minutes,
and @{b}SS@{ub} the seconds.  Internally time values are stored as the number of
seconds since 0 AM.  Time values larger than 23:59:59 up to the maximum
value of 596523:14:07 are possible but negative values are not
supported.

   Time attributes support the NIL value representing an undefined time.


@endnode

@node "Memo type" "MUIbase/Memo type"
@toc "Attribute types"

Memo Attributes
---------------

   Memo attributes store multi-line text of any size.  Text size is
handled dynamically which means that memory is only allocated for the
actual text size.  In a project managing movies for example, a memo
attribute can be used to store summaries of the movies.

   Memo attributes do not support the NIL value.


@endnode

@node "Reference" "MUIbase/Reference"
@toc "Attribute types"

Reference Attributes
--------------------

   Reference attributes are a special type of attribute, normally not
found in other database systems.  Reference attributes store a pointer
to another record.  The referenced record may reside in the same or in
any other table the reference attribute belongs to.

   For example in a pedigree project two reference attributes can be
used for storing pointers to the father and mother record.  Or in a
project managing CDs and music titles, a reference attribute in the
table holding the music titles can be used to point to the records of
the corresponding CDs.

   For displaying a reference attribute, any attributes of the
referenced record can be specified.  Entering a reference attribute can
be done by selecting a record from a list of records.

   Reference attributes support the NIL value.  Here a value of NIL
stands for a pointer to the initial record of the referenced table.


@endnode

@node "Virtual" "MUIbase/Virtual"
@toc "Attribute types"

Virtual Attributes
------------------

   Virtual attributes do not store any information in the database
itself, but compute them on the fly when needed.

   For example, in a project managing invoices where a real attribute
holds the amount of money excluding tax, a virtual attribute can be
used to "store" the amount of money with tax.  Every time the value of
the virtual attribute is needed, e.g. for displaying it, it is computed
from the corresponding value without tax.

   For displaying virtual attributes three kinds exists: Boolean,
string and list.  These three kinds allow showing the value of the
virtual attribute as a TRUE/FALSE value, as a single line of text
including numbers, dates, and times, or as a list of several single
lines, e.g. for listing all music titles of a CD.

   Virtual attributes support the NIL value standing for FALSE (Boolean
kind), undefined (string kind), or empty (list kind).


@endnode

@node "Button" "MUIbase/Button"
@toc "Attribute types"

Buttons
-------

   Actually, buttons are not a real attribute type as they cannot store
or display any information.  Buttons are just used for triggering
MUIbase programs.


@endnode

@node "Table of attribute types" "MUIbase/Table of attribute types"
@toc "Basic concepts"

Table of Attribute Types
========================

   The following table summarizes all available attributes types:

@{b}Type@{ub}        @{b}Description@{ub}                             @{b}Nil allowed?@{ub}

String      For strings of lengths 1..999.          No
            A string can also be used for storing
            filenames, font-names or one-string-
            out-of-n-strings.  For filenames you
            can add a field where the contents
            of the file are displayed as an image.

Integer     For storing integer values.             Yes

Real        For floating point numbers.             Yes

Boolean     TRUE or NIL.                            Yes (NIL = FALSE)

Choice      One number out of n numbers.  Numbers   No
            are represented by label strings.

Date        For storing a date value                Yes
            (1.1.0000 - 31.12.9999).

Time        For storing time values                 Yes
	    (00:00:00 - 596523:14:07)

Memo        Multi-line text of unlimited length.    No

Reference   For storing a reference to a record     Yes (NIL means
            of another table.                       initial record)

Virtual     For displaying results from a MUIbase   Yes
            program.

Button      For triggering a program function       No (N/A)


@endnode

@node "Memory consumption" "MUIbase/Memory consumption"
@toc "Basic concepts"

Memory Consumption
==================

   Each attribute type needs a certain amount of memory for storing one
value in a record.  All types except virtual and button have in common
that they need a 2 bytes header holding internal information.
Additionally, type dependent space is needed for storing the actual
value.  The following table lists how much memory including a possible
2 byte header one value of the given type needs in memory and on disk.


@{b}Type@{ub}               @{b}Memory space@{ub}               @{b}Disk space@{ub}

String             2 + 4 + STRING-LENGTH + 1  2 + STRING-LENGTH + 1
Integer            2 + 4                      2 + 4
Real               2 + 8                      2 + 8
Boolean            2 + 0                      2 + 0
Choice             2 + 2                      2 + 2
Date               2 + 4                      2 + 4
Time               2 + 4                      2 + 4
Memo               2 + 4 + MEMO-LENGTH + 1    2 + MEMO-LENGTH + 1
Reference          2 + 4                      2 + 4
Virtual            0                          0
Buttons            0                          0

   Here STRING-LENGTH stands for the length of the string to be stored
and MEMO-LENGTH for the text size of the memo to be stored.


@endnode

@node "Relationships" "MUIbase/Relationships"
@toc "Basic concepts"

Relationships
=============

   Up to now you know how to organize your information into tables with
records and attributes.  But you may also want to setup relationships
between tables.

   For example if you want to collect CDs in a database project you
would have two tables, one for the CDs themselves and one for the music
titles of the CDs.  Of course you could also have all music titles
within the CD table but then you would have a fixed number of music
titles for each CD.

   So having these two tables, you now need a link for each music title
to the CD containing this title.  This is called a @{i}relationship@{ui} between
the two tables.  In MUIbase you use a reference attribute for setting up
such a relationship.

   By installing a reference attribute into a table you automatically
have a relationship between the table the attribute resides in and the
table it refers to.

   The following classes of relationships can be distinguished:


 @{" One to one relationships            " link "One to one relationships"}  Simple ones.
 @{" One to many relationships           " link "One to many relationships"}  Most often used ones.
 @{" Many to many relationships          " link "Many to many relationships"}  Complex ones.


@endnode

@node "One to one relationships" "MUIbase/One to one relationships"
@toc "Relationships"

One to one Relationships
------------------------

   One to one relationships are very simple relationships where for
each record you have one or zero partners in another or in the same
table.

   For example in a database project that manages your favorite movie
actors you could setup a reference attribute called @{b}married with@{ub} that
shows the person the actor is married with.  An actor that is currently
not married does have a NIL value for this reference field.

   Of course, no one prevents the user to set the @{b}married with@{ub}
references of several actors all to the same person.  However by
programming MUIbase it is possible to detect such cases and handle
accordingly.


@endnode

@node "One to many relationships" "MUIbase/One to many relationships"
@toc "Relationships"

One to many Relationships
-------------------------

   One to many relationships are useful for connecting a set of records
to one record in another or the same table.

   For example in a project managing your bank accounts you could have
one table for all bank accounts and one table for all transactions.
Now you surely want to know which transaction belongs to which account
so you setup a reference attribute in the transaction table referring
to the account table.

   One to many relationships are the most often used ones.  You can use
them for managing any hierarchical-like structures, e.g. CDs with music
titles, bank accounts with transactions, family trees, etc.

   One to many relationships are also the basis for realizing many to
many relationships as described in the next section.


@endnode

@node "Many to many relationships" "MUIbase/Many to many relationships"
@toc "Relationships"

Many to many Relationships
--------------------------

   Many to many relationships are used when you want a set of records
to refer to another set of records.

   For example in a project that manages movies and actors you would
have two tables, one for the movies and the other one for the actors.
Now for each movie you want to know the actors that took part in the
movie.  So you might think to setup a reference attribute in the actor
table that refers to the movie table.  But when doing this you could
only have one movie referenced for each actor because there is only one
reference field in the actor table.  So what you need is an unlimited
number of references from the actor table to the movie table.

   This is done by adding a new table that just has two reference
attributes, one pointing to the actor table and the other to the movie
table.  Now you can enter the relationships by adding new records to
this table.  For each movie-actor constellation you add a new record
and specify the movie and actor by setting the corresponding reference
fields.

   If you want to know in which movies an actor took part then you only
have to search for all records in the new table that refer to the actor
in question and look at the movie records the found records refer to.
Such a search can be done automatically by MUIbase and the result can
be displayed in a list-view.

   The following tables show an example of how to connect a set of
actors to a set of movies.


      Title           Country
      ----------------------------
m1:   Batman          USA
m2:   Batman Returns  USA
m3:   Speechless      USA
m4:   Tequila Sunrise USA
m5:   Mad Max         Australia
m6:   Braveheart      USA


      Name
      -------------------
a1:   Michael Keaton
a2:   Jack Nicholson
a3:   Kim Basinger
a4:   Danny DeVito
a5:   Michelle Pfeiffer
a6:   Geena Davis
a7:   Christopher Reeve
a8:   Mel Gibson
a9:   Kurt Russell
a10:  Sophie Marceau
a11:  Patrick McGoohan
a12:  Catherine McCormack
a13:  Christopher Walken


      MovieRef  ActorRef
      ------------------
      m1        a1
      m1        a2
      m1        a3
      m2        a1
      m2        a4
      m2        a5
      m2        a13
      m3        a1
      m3        a6
      m3        a7
      m4        a8
      m4        a5
      m4        a9
      m5        a8
      m6        a8
      m6        a10
      m6        a11

   From these tables you can find out for example that Mel Gibson took
part in the movies Tequila Sunrise, Mad Max, and Braveheart, or that in
movie Batman the actors Michael Keaton, Jack Nicholson, and Kim
Basinger took part.


@endnode

@node "User interface" "MUIbase/User interface"
@toc "Basic concepts"

User Interface
==============

   MUIbase uses a graphical user interface (GUI) organized in a
hierarchical way for displaying record contents and for entering data.
Each project owns its own main window in which further GUI elements
(including sub windows) can be placed.  The GUI elements are also
called @{i}display objects@{ui}.

   A table is displayed in an own GUI element called @{i}mask@{ui}.  A mask can
display only one record at a time.  Its layout and the attributes
included in the mask are customizable by the user.

   The following GUI elements are available for designing a project's
GUI layout:


 @{" Windows                    " link "Windows"}  Main and sub windows.
 @{" Masks                      " link "Masks"}  Displays a table.
 @{" Panels                     " link "Panels"}  Controls a table.
 @{" Attribute objects          " link "Attribute objects"}  Shows a data item of one record.
 @{" Text objects               " link "Text objects"}  Static text descriptions.
 @{" Images                     " link "Images"}  Static images for decoration.
 @{" Space objects              " link "Space objects"}  Layout and separator item.
 @{" Groups                     " link "Groups"}  Groups GUI elements vertically and horizontally.
 @{" Balance objects            " link "Balance objects"}  Dynamic sizing of group elements.
 @{" Register groups            " link "Register groups"}  Pages of GUI elements.


@endnode

@node "Windows" "MUIbase/Windows"
@toc "User interface"

Windows
-------

   Windows can be used to spread information of a project across
several independent areas.

   Each project automatically has its own main window.  If needed, e.g.
if the space of the main window exceeds, additional sub windows can be
created.  Sub windows can also have further sub windows.

   For each sub window a window button can be placed into the parent
window allowing to open the sub window.  The window button looks like a
normal text button but may show a small icon to distinguish itself from
other buttons.

   Main windows do not have a parent window and therefore have no
window button.  Closing a main window means closing the whole project.

   A window can have other GUI elements as children.  If no child has
been added to a window then a default image is shown.


@endnode

@node "Masks" "MUIbase/Masks"
@toc "User interface"

Masks
-----

   A mask is used to display the contents of a table.  Only one record
of the table can be shown at a time.

   The mask may include a panel (see next section) for controlling the
table.  Other GUI elements like attribute or text objects can be placed
into a mask to show the record contents.

   Masks cannot be placed inside other masks as this would lead to a
hierarchy of masks and therefore to a hierarchy of tables.  To setup a
hierarchy of tables, use an 1:n relationship between the two tables.


@endnode

@node "Panels" "MUIbase/Panels"
@toc "User interface"

Panels
------

   A panel is a small and wide rectangular area placed at the top edge
of a mask.  A panel can display a title, e.g. the name of the
corresponding table, a pair of numbers showing the record number of the
current record and the total number of records, and several buttons for
controlling the table, e.g. for displaying the next or previous record.

   Only one panel can be defined for a mask.  If you setup a panel for
a mask then an additional border is drawn around the mask, otherwise no
border is shown.


@endnode

@node "Attribute objects" "MUIbase/Attribute objects"
@toc "User interface"

Attribute Objects
-----------------

   Attribute objects are used to display the contents of one item of a
record.

   Depending on the type of the attribute the GUI element is either a
string field (types string, integer, real, date and time), a check-mark
button (type Boolean), a cycle button or a set of radio buttons (type
choice), an editor field (type memo), a pop-up list-view (type
reference), a text, check-mark, or list-view field (type virtual) or a
text or image button (type button).  In some cases the GUI element may
also be a simple text field if the attribute object is set to read-only.


@endnode

@node "Text objects" "MUIbase/Text objects"
@toc "User interface"

Text Objects
------------

   Text objects are used for describing the various field elements of a
record mask or just to display some static text.


@endnode

@node "Images" "MUIbase/Images"
@toc "User interface"

Images
------

   Images can be displayed anywhere in a window.  An image can be a
pattern, a simple color field, or a pictures in an external file.  The
image size can be resize-able or fixed.

   The image is static.  For storing images in a table you use a string
attribute (see @{"String type" link "String type"}).


@endnode

@node "Space objects" "MUIbase/Space objects"
@toc "User interface"

Space Objects
-------------

   Space objects are used to insert space in the layout of a window or
a table mask.  A space object can have a vertical (or horizontal) bar
for delimiting other GUI elements.


@endnode

@node "Groups" "MUIbase/Groups"
@toc "User interface"

Groups
------

   GUI elements can be grouped into horizontal or vertical groups.  A
group places its children from left to right (horizontal group) or from
top to bottom (vertical group).

   A group can surround its child objects with a rectangular frame, can
display an optional title at the top of the group, and can insert space
between its child objects.


@endnode

@node "Balance objects" "MUIbase/Balance objects"
@toc "User interface"

Balance Objects
---------------

   Balance objects can be placed between other child objects of a
window, mask, or group object.  A balance object allows the user to
control the weight values of the other child objects and therefore how
much space each child gets.


@endnode

@node "Register groups" "MUIbase/Register groups"
@toc "User interface"

Register Groups
---------------

   A register group can be used to layout GUI elements into several
pages where only one page is visible at a time.  This is useful if the
user interface becomes too large and you don't want to spread it over
several windows.


@endnode

@node "Managing projects" "MUIbase/Managing projects"
@toc "Main"

Managing Projects
*****************

   In this chapter you find:


 @{" File format               " link "File format"}  MUIbase project file structure.
 @{" Info                      " link "Info"}  Information about the current project.
 @{" New project               " link "New project"}  Starting a new project.
 @{" Clear project             " link "Clear project"}  Resetting a project.
 @{" Open project              " link "Open project"}  Loading project from disk.
 @{" Save project              " link "Save project"}  Saving project to disk.
 @{" Admin and user mode       " link "Admin and user mode"}  Restricting access to project structure.
 @{" Check data integrity      " link "Check data integrity"}  Salvaging a corrupted project.
 @{" Swap records              " link "Swap records"}  Memory management of records.
 @{" Close project             " link "Close project"}  Freeing project resources.


@endnode

@node "File format" "MUIbase/File format"
@toc "Managing projects"

File Format
===========

   A MUIbase project consists of several files stored in a directory
owned by the project.  This directory is first created when you save
the project.  Do not make any assumption about the directory structure
or filenames inside the directory.  In particular, do not remove or
place any files or further directories in this directory!  They will
get lost when reorganizing the project.

   The directory contains a file called @{b}Structure.mb@{ub} where the
descriptions of all tables, attributes, filters, etc. are stored.  The
record headers are also placed here.  For each table you will find a
file with the table's name.  Here all records of a table are stored.
Last but not least there is a file called @{b}.lock@{ub}.  This file is used for
locking a project, that is, MUIbase first locks this file exclusively
and then opens other files.  If the locking fails, MUIbase knows that
there is already a MUIbase application working on this project.  Only
one MUIbase application is allowed to work on a project at a time since
record files are opened in read/write mode and we certainly do not want
to have data mixed together by write operations of two or more
applications.


@endnode

@node "Info" "MUIbase/Info"
@toc "Managing projects"

Info
====

   MUIbase keeps some information about each project.  Select menu item
@{b}Project - Info@{ub} to get information about the current project.   The
information you get consists of the project's name, the number of
tables, the total number of records in all tables, and a value that
shows how many bytes a reorganization of this project would gain.  The
gain is however only a rough estimate and should not be treated as an
exact number.  Especially if you have made many changes to the
structure of the project (adding or removing attributes) then this
value is far from accurate.


@endnode

@node "New project" "MUIbase/New project"
@toc "Managing projects"

New Project
===========

   MUIbase can handle any number of projects at a time.  You are only
limited by the available memory.  In order to start another project,
choose menu item @{b}Project - New@{ub}.  This opens a new window with an empty
project.  You can now define the structure of this project (see
@{"Structure editor" link "Structure editor"}) or load an existing project from disk (see
@{"Open project" link "Open project"}).


@endnode

@node "Clear project" "MUIbase/Clear project"
@toc "Managing projects"

Clear Project
=============

   To reset a project select menu item @{b}Project - Clear - Project@{ub}.  This
closes the current project and replaces it by an empty project.  After
starting MUIbase without projects you arrive in this state
automatically.

   By selecting menu item @{b}Project - Clear - Records@{ub} you start a new
project using the structure of the current one.  This means that all
except the record data of the current project is used for the new
project.

   If the current project at the time you selected one of above menu
items has not been saved to disk then a safety requester appears asking
for confirmation of the operation.


@endnode

@node "Open project" "MUIbase/Open project"
@toc "Managing projects"

Open Project
============

   To load a project select menu item @{b}Project - Open - Project@{ub}.  This
opens a file-requester where you can choose a project from.  It's also
possible to only load the structure of a project, that is, the whole
project is loaded except the record data.  To do so, select menu item
@{b}Project - Open - Structure@{ub}.

   If the loaded project has its program source set to external, the
external source file is created after opening the project (see
@{"External program source" link "External program source"}).

   If you were editing a project at the time of choosing any of the
above menu items and the project has not been saved then a safety
requester appears asking for confirmation.


@endnode

@node "Save project" "MUIbase/Save project"
@toc "Managing projects"

Save Project
============

   All changes you make to a project are only done in memory or stored
temporarily when swapping records (see @{"Swap records" link "Swap records"}).  Thus if you
want to make them permanent you have to save the project to disk.  This
is done by choosing menu item @{b}Project - Save@{ub}.  If your project doesn't
have a name yet then a file-requester asking for a filename appears
first.

   The reason why MUIbase does not automatically save a project when it
is changed, is that, this way, it is you who decides when to save a
project!  You can always go back to the last saved version of your
project by choosing menu item @{b}Project - Revert to saved@{ub}.  This
mechanism is similar to the @{b}COMMIT@{ub} and @{b}ROLLBACK@{ub} commands in SQL
database systems.

   If you save a project, all modified records are written to disk and
the file @{b}Structure.mb@{ub} is recreated.  Before creating the new
@{b}Structure.mb@{ub} file, MUIbase first renames a possibly existing
@{b}Structure.mb@{ub} file to @{b}Structure.old@{ub} to have a safety copy in case the
save operation fails.

   This mechanism guarantees fast load & save operations but it is not
free of reorganization.  If you have modified many records then the
physical place where the records lie and the resulting fragmentation
may become disadvantageous.  Therefore a menu item @{b}Project - Save &
reorg@{ub} exists that does a save & reorganize operation.  This operation
may take some time depending on the number and size of the records.
The save & reorganize operation creates a new directory and rewrites
all project related files.  The old directory is deleted on success.

   Another good time to schedule a reorganization is when you have done
changes to the data-structure of a project, e.g. after you have
installed a new attribute in a table.  These changes are not applied
immediately to all records because it would take too much time to load
each record, modify it, and save it back to disk.  Therefore these
changes are put on an internal @{b}todo@{ub} list which is applied after loading
a record.  Applying this list to a record takes only little time.
However the longer the list gets the more time it needs.  Reorganizing
a project causes the @{b}todo@{ub} list to be applied to all records, so if you
have made many changes to the project structure then reorganizing a
project will shorten the time for loading records.

   You can also save & reorganize a project to a new filename keeping
the old project untouched.  To do this select menu item @{b}Project - Save
& reorg as@{ub} which prompts you to enter a new name for the project.


@endnode

@node "Admin and user mode" "MUIbase/Admin and user mode"
@toc "Managing projects"

Admin and User Mode
===================

   MUIbase operates either in admin mode (default) or in user mode.
You can change between these modes by choosing menu item @{b}Project -
Change to admin mode@{ub} and @{b}Project - Change to user mode@{ub}.  When in user
mode, several menu items are disabled and structure, program and query
editor are not available.  Therefore, only basic record editing is
possible.  In admin mode all operations are permitted.

   An admin password can be set for a project by selecting menu item
@{b}Project - Change admin password@{ub}.  Once set, the password has to be
entered when changing into admin mode, or permission is denied leaving
the project in user mode.

   When opening a project that has an admin password set, the project
is started in user mode, otherwise (no admin password has been set), it
is started in admin mode.


@endnode

@node "Check data integrity" "MUIbase/Check data integrity"
@toc "Managing projects"

Check Data Integrity
====================

   MUIbase can verify if all data in your project is still valid and
not corrupted by programs trashing your project files or by system
crashes.   Choose menu item @{b}Project - Check data integrity@{ub} for starting
this process.

   Usually you should never need this functionality and MUIbase should
always report that data integrity is perfect.  But if it ever happens to
you that your project contains  @{b}internal errors@{ub}, that is, some records
can't be loaded anymore, then you can repair your project by using this
menu item.

   MUIbase will write a log file of all affected records and you can
save and reorganize the project afterwards.  In the log file, records
that might be corrupted and records that are not accessible anymore and
therefore have been deleted are listed by their record number in the
old (corrupted) project and by their record number (in parenthesis) in
the reorganized project.


@endnode

@node "Swap records" "MUIbase/Swap records"
@toc "Managing projects"

Swap Records
============

   MUIbase doesn't need to keep all records of a project in memory.
Thus loading and saving of projects is much faster. When loading a
project, a record header is allocated for each record. The data itself
is only loaded when needed, e.g. when it is displayed on the screen.
The total number of records is still limited by available memory since
each record header needs some few bytes of memory.

   You can specify how much memory MUIbase should use for the records
of a project.  Choose one of the predefined values found in menu item
@{b}Preferences - Record memory@{ub} (see @{"Record memory" link "Record memory"}).  MUIbase does not
preallocate a block of the specified memory size, it only checks from
time to time if the current size of allocated memory is larger than the
specified value.

   If MUIbase runs out of memory or if the upper limit for the record
memory size has been reached then MUIbase tries to free as much record
memory as possible.  In this case MUIbase may write modified records to
disk to get the maximum available memory possible.  You can also force
MUIbase to do this by choosing menu item @{b}Project - Swap records@{ub}.

   MUIbase maintains a free list for each record file. If you delete a
record then the record's file space is added to the free list.  Also if
you change a record and the record needs to be written to disk then the
old file space is added to the free list.  However MUIbase makes sure
that by reloading you can always go back to the point of the last save
operation.  MUIbase will not write into areas which are free but where
a record still exists that could be reached by reopening the project.


@endnode

@node "Close project" "MUIbase/Close project"
@toc "Managing projects"

Close Project
=============

   When you are done editing a project you can close it by selecting
menu item @{b}Project - Close@{ub}.  This frees the memory and all resources
belonging to the project.  If the project contains changes that have
not been saved yet then a safety requester appears first offering to
save, continue or cancel the operation.

   For closing a project you can also select menu item @{b}Project - Save &
close@{ub} which saves the project first if there were any changes and then
closes it.


@endnode

@node "Preferences" "MUIbase/Preferences"
@toc "Main"

Preferences
***********

   MUIbase offers several preferences items the user can set to his
likes.  This chapter shows what preferences items are available and
gives general information about how the preferences system works.

   All preferences items can be divided into user settings and project
settings.


 @{" User settings            " link "User settings"}  Global settings stored in user environment.
 @{" Project settings         " link "Project settings"}  Settings stored with a project.
 @{" Save as default          " link "Save as default"}  Saves project settings for future projects.


@endnode

@node "User settings" "MUIbase/User settings"
@toc "Preferences"

User Settings
=============

   The user settings contain preferences items that depend on the
choice of a user, e.g. the user's language, country or taste.  The user
settings are shown and can be customized in the top part of menu
@{b}Preferences@{ub}.

   User settings are stored in the environment of the user.  On
Windows, Mac OS and Linux they are kept in the home directory of the
user as @{b}.MUIbase.prefs@{ub}.  On the Amiga they are stored under
@{b}ENV:MUIbase.prefs@{ub} and @{b}ENVARC:MUIbase.prefs@{ub}.

   The user settings contain the preferences items listed below.
Whenever any of these items is changed in the @{b}Preferences@{ub} menu, the
settings are written to disk in order to make them permanent.


 @{" Formats                    " link "Formats"}  Real and date formats.
 @{" External editor            " link "External editor"}  Specify your external editor.
 @{" External viewer            " link "External viewer"}  Specify your external viewer.
 @{" Extra buttons in Tab chain " link "Extra buttons in Tab chain"}  Include extra buttons in the Tab chain.
 @{" Advance on Enter           " link "Advance on Enter"}  Move to next field when pressing @{b}Enter@{ub} key.
 @{" Confirm quit               " link "Confirm quit"}  Safety requester when quitting MUIbase.
 @{" MUI                        " link "MUI"}  MUI's preferences.


@endnode

@node "Formats" "MUIbase/Formats"
@toc "User settings"

Formats
-------

   By selecting menu item @{b}Preferences - Formats@{ub} you can specify the
formats used when displaying or printing real and date values.  After
selecting the menu item a new window appears containing the following
items:

   * a field @{b}Real format@{ub} for setting the decimal character of real
     values.  You can choose between @{b}Decimal point@{ub} and @{b}Decimal comma@{ub}.

   * a field @{b}Date format@{ub} for specifying how date values are output.
     You can choose between @{b}Day.Month.Year@{ub}, @{b}Month/Day/Year@{ub} and
     @{b}Year-Month-Day@{ub}.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   The initial values for real and date formats are determined
according to the information found in the operating system's @{b}locale@{ub}
environment.

   When you are done with all settings, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to leave
the window and update the display.


@endnode

@node "External editor" "MUIbase/External editor"
@toc "User settings"

External Editor
---------------

   Besides providing an internal editor built into MUIbase through the
employed GUI toolkit, MUIbase also offers to edit text contents by
using an external editor (e.g. the context menu of the built-in editor
includes an item that allows to call the external editor for editing
the contents).  The name of the editor and its parameters are specified
by selecting menu item @{b}Preferences - External editor@{ub}.  You should enter
a command string that gets executed when calling the external editor.
The special string @{b}%f@{ub} can be used at the place of the filename and is
replaced with the actual filename (or a temporary filename MUIbase
creates for exchanging the text data) before execution.

   For example, on Linux you can specify @{b}emacs %f@{ub} for using the
powerful GNU Emacs editor, or on the Amiga, you can use @{b}CED %f -keepio@{ub}
for switching to the famous CED editor as external editor.

   Default is @{b}Notepad %f@{ub} on Windows, @{b}open -t %f@{ub} on Mac OS, @{b}gvim -f %f@{ub}
on Linux, and @{b}Ed %f@{ub} on the Amiga.

   Note that on Mac OS, the default setting always starts the external
editor asynchronously, i.e. MUIbase never waits for the editor to quit.
If you are running Mac OS 10.5 or higher then you can use @{b}open -tWn %f@{ub}
for enabling synchronous editing.  This is required when using menu
item @{b}External editor@{ub} in the context menu of a Memo attribute (see
@{"Changing records" link "Changing records"}) and when using the @{b}EDIT@{ub} command for programming
MUIbase (see @{"EDIT" link "EDIT"}).

   On the Amiga, additionally the sequence @{b}%p@{ub} can be used in the
command string.  When calling the external editor this sequence is
replaced by the name of the public screen MUIbase is running on.


@endnode

@node "External viewer" "MUIbase/External viewer"
@toc "User settings"

External Viewer
---------------

   MUIbase uses an external viewer for displaying the contents of
external files, e.g. images, movies or any kind of documents.  For
example you can use the string data type for storing filenames in a
table and then let MUIbase display them using the external viewer.  To
specify this viewer select menu item @{b}Preferences - External viewer@{ub}.
Like for the external editor (see @{"External editor" link "External editor"}) you have to enter a
command string here.

   Default is @{b}%f@{ub} on Windows (using ShellExecute), @{b}open %f@{ub} on Mac OS,
@{b}gnome-open %f@{ub} on Linux, and @{b}Multiview %f@{ub} on the Amiga.

   Note that on Mac OS, the default setting always starts the external
viewer asynchronously, i.e. MUIbase never waits for the viewer to quit.
If you are running Mac OS 10.5 or higher then you can use @{b}open -Wn %f@{ub}
for enabling synchronous viewing.  This is required when using the @{b}VIEW@{ub}
command for programming MUIbase (see @{"VIEW" link "VIEW"}).

   On the Amiga, additionally the sequence @{b}%p@{ub} can be used in the
command string.  When calling the external viewer this sequence is
replaced by the name of the public screen MUIbase is running on.


@endnode

@node "Extra buttons in Tab chain" "MUIbase/Extra buttons in Tab chain"
@toc "User settings"

Extra Buttons in Tab Chain
--------------------------

   In the graphical user interface specified in the structured editor
there might exist several extra buttons.  Under extra buttons fall
popup buttons, e.g. file, font or listview popups beneath a string
field, auto-show and filter buttons of a reference field, and view
buttons next to a string field.

   These buttons are usually not included in the cycle chain, that is,
you can't use the @{b}Tab@{ub} key to activate them.  However if you check menu
item @{b}Preferences - Extra buttons in Tab chain@{ub} then these buttons are
also included in the Tab chain.  Default is checked.

   On the Amiga please note that changing the status of this menu item
has only an effect after rebuilding the user interface, e.g. by
switching to the structure editor and back to the user interface.


@endnode

@node "Advance on Enter" "MUIbase/Advance on Enter"
@toc "User settings"

Advance on Enter
----------------

   When the cursor is in an editable single-line text field in the user
interface of a project, pressing the @{b}Enter@{ub} key can either advance to
the next item in the user interface or keep the cursor in the current
text field.

   If you check menu item @{b}Preferences - Advance on <Enter>@{ub} then the
cursor jumps to the next item in the user interface, otherwise it stays
on the current text field. Default is checked.

   Note that in any case, pressing @{b}Enter@{ub} confirms and stores the
entered text.


@endnode

@node "Confirm quit" "MUIbase/Confirm quit"
@toc "User settings"

Confirm Quit
------------

   If you try to quit MUIbase and there are unsaved projects then a
safety requester pops up asking for confirmation.  However if all
projects have been saved, MUIbase quits silently.

   In order to always enforce a requester when quitting MUIbase, menu
item @{b}Preferences - Confirm quit@{ub} has to be checked.  In this case you
always get a safety requester when selecting menu item @{b}Project - Quit@{ub}
or when closing the last open project.  Default is unchecked.


@endnode

@node "MUI" "MUIbase/MUI"
@toc "User settings"

MUI
---

   Amiga only.  As MUIbase on the Amiga is a MUI application, you can
also specify the MUI preferences for this application by choosing menu
item @{b}Preferences - MUI@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Project settings" "MUIbase/Project settings"
@toc "Preferences"

Project Settings
================

   Project settings consists of preferences items that are stored along
with a project.  These items are shown and changeable in the lower part
of menu @{b}Preferences@{ub} and in menu @{b}Program@{ub} (the reason to spread these
among two menus is to keep menus compact and clear).

   The following preferences items belong to the project settings.
Whenever any of these settings is changed, the count of changes for the
project is incremented.


 @{" Record memory            " link "Record memory"}  Size of record buffer.
 @{" Record delete requester  " link "Record delete requester"}  Safety requester when deleting records.
 @{" Paths relative to project " link "Paths relative to project"}  How relative path names are treated.
 @{" Confirm save & reorg     " link "Confirm save & reorg"}  Safety requester when saving and reorganizing a project.
 @{" Program source           " link "Program source"}  Internal or external program source.
 @{" Cleanup ext. prg. source " link "Cleanup external program source"}  Delete external source files when no longer needed.
 @{" Embed debug info         " link "Program debug information"}  Compile with or without debug information.
 @{" Obsolete functions       " link "Obsolete functions"}  How to handle calls of obsolete functions.
 @{" Sort trigger functions   " link "Sort trigger functions"}  Alphabetical sorting in pop-up windows.
 @{" Program include dir      " link "Program include directory"}  Where to look for external include files.
 @{" Program output file      " link "Program output file"}  Where program output goes.


@endnode

@node "Record memory" "MUIbase/Record memory"
@toc "Project settings"

Record Memory
-------------

   MUIbase does not need to keep all records of a project in memory.
Instead it uses a buffer for holding only a small number of records.
By choosing a value from menu item @{b}Preferences - Record memory@{ub} you can
set the size of this buffer.  Each project has its own buffer, so if
you have opened two projects each having a record buffer size of 1MB,
MUIbase will use up to 2MB for the records of both projects.

   MUIbase does not allocate the memory a priori but uses a dynamic
allocation scheme.  Furthermore, the specified buffer size is only a
soft limit and occasionally MUIbase might exceed it.

   Once the buffer gets full, or if MUIbase runs out of memory, all
records are flushed from the buffer.  This means that unchanged records
are simply freed and changed records are first written to disk and then
freed (see @{"Swap records" link "Swap records"}).

   By giving MUIbase a higher value for the record buffer you can notice
a speed increase in accessing the records as more records can be held
in memory and fewer disk access is needed.  If there is enough memory
to hold all records in memory and if you have specified a large enough
memory limit (e.g. @{b}unlimited@{ub}) then MUIbase operates with optimal speed.

   Default is @{b}unlimited@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Record delete requester" "MUIbase/Record delete requester"
@toc "Project settings"

Record Delete Requester
-----------------------

   You should check menu item @{b}Preferences - Record delete requester@{ub} if
you want MUIbase to pop up a safety requester asking for confirmation
whenever you try to delete a record.  Leave the item unchecked if
records should be deleted silently.  Default is checked.


@endnode

@node "Paths relative to project" "MUIbase/Paths relative to project"
@toc "Project settings"

Paths Relative to Project
-------------------------

   If you want to reference external data (e.g. documents or images)
then the filename of these data need to be stored in the project.  For
this purpose you can use absolute path names or path names containing
assign names (see @{"Filename conventions" link "Filename conventions"}).  Another way is to store
external data relative to the directory of the project (note: this is
not the project directory itself but the directory containing the
project).

   By activating menu item @{b}Preferences - Paths relative to directory of
project@{ub}, MUIbase changes the current working directory to the directory
containing the project.  This means that if you have several projects
open, MUIbase changes directories according to the currently active
project.  Once this menu item has been activated for a project,
filenames can be specified relative to the directory of the project.
This makes a project independent of where it is stored in the file
system.

   If you leave this menu item unchecked, MUIbase uses the initial
working directory when the program was started.

   Default is unchecked.


@endnode

@node "Confirm save & reorg" "MUIbase/Confirm save & reorg"
@toc "Project settings"

Confirm Save & Reorg
--------------------

   Saving and reorganizing a project can take quite some time depending
on the size of the project.  Therefore, if you select menu item @{b}Project
- Save & reorg@{ub} or @{b}Project - Save & reorg as@{ub}, a safety requester pops up
asking for confirmation of this operation.  The requester only appears
if menu item @{b}Preferences - Confirm save & reorg@{ub} is checked, thus you
can disable this requester by de-selecting the menu item.  Default is
checked.


@endnode

@node "Program source" "MUIbase/Program source"
@toc "Project settings"

Program Source
--------------

   You can set the program source of a project in menu item @{b}Program -
Source@{ub} to be @{b}Internal@{ub} or @{b}External@{ub}.  If set to @{b}Internal@{ub}, you can use
MUIbase' built-in editor for editing and compiling the project's
program. This is the default.  If you wish to use an external editor
for programming, you choose @{b}External@{ub} and enter the name of a new file
to which MUIbase then writes the program source.  This allows to load
and edit the program source into your favorite editor.  For more
information about how to use this feature, see @{"External program source" link "External program source"}.

   Note that when setting this menu item from @{b}External@{ub} back to
@{b}Internal@{ub}, the last successfully compiled version of the program is kept.


@endnode

@node "Cleanup external program source" "MUIbase/Cleanup external program source"
@toc "Project settings"

Cleanup External Program Source
-------------------------------

   Menu item @{b}Program - Cleanup external program source@{ub} decides if the
external program source file of a project should be deleted  when
closing the project or when changing menu item @{b}Program - Source@{ub} back to
@{b}Internal@{ub}.  See @{"External program source" link "External program source"}, for more information about
external source files.  Default is checked.


@endnode

@node "Program debug information" "MUIbase/Program debug information"
@toc "Project settings"

Program Debug Information
-------------------------

   For compiling a project's program, you can choose whether debug
information should be included in the executable or not.  If you
compile without debug information and a run-time error occurs then an
error description is generated but there is no information about where
exactly the error occurred.  If you compile with debug information then
you also get the exact error location.  Compiling with debug
information is a bit slower, requires more memory and the resulting
program is slightly less efficient.

   Use menu item @{b}Program - Embed debug information@{ub} to turn debug
information for compilation on and off.  Default is checked.  After
changing this state, don't forget to recompile the project's program by
choosing menu item @{b}Program - Compile@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Obsolete functions" "MUIbase/Obsolete functions"
@toc "Project settings"

Obsolete Functions
------------------

   Since MUIbase version 2.7 a few programming functions have been made
obsolete (see @{"List of obsolete functions" link "List of obsolete functions"}).  The functionality of these
obsolete functions have been replaced by other mechanisms and the
functions do not work as expected any longer.  When opening projects
containing programming functions which are now obsolete, you can choose
how to handle them.

   Menu item @{b}Program - Obsolete functions@{ub} specifies how to react when
an obsolete function is called.  When choosing @{b}Ignore silently@{ub} any call
of an obsolete function is ignored and program execution continues by
skipping over the function call.  @{b}Warn when called@{ub} opens a dialog
window informing the user whenever an obsolete function is called and
allows to continue execution or to abort with an error message.  This
is the default.  If @{b}Treat as error@{ub} is selected, any call of an obsolete
function generates an error and compilation of programs containing
obsolete functions fails with a proper error message.

   It is recommended to choose @{b}Treat as error@{ub} after all calls of
obsolete functions have been removed from a project program.  In order
to find out if your project contains any calls of obsolete functions
select @{b}Treat as error@{ub} and recompile the project program.


@endnode

@node "Sort trigger functions" "MUIbase/Sort trigger functions"
@toc "Project settings"

Sort Trigger Functions
----------------------

   If menu item @{b}Preferences - Sort trigger functions in pop-ups@{ub} is
checked then functions available as triggers are sorted alphabetically
for display in requesters for creating and changing tables (see
@{"Creating tables" link "Creating tables"}) and for creating and changing attributes (see
@{"Creating attributes" link "Creating attributes"}).  Otherwise, functions are listed as they occur
in the project's program.  Default is unchecked.


@endnode

@node "Program include directory" "MUIbase/Program include directory"
@toc "Project settings"

Program Include Directory
-------------------------

   The programming feature of MUIbase allows to include external source
files within the project's program (see @{"#include" link "#include"} for more information).
Menu item @{b}Program - Include directory@{ub} allows to set a directory where
MUIbase should search for such include files.  Default is
@{b}MUIbase:Include@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Program output file" "MUIbase/Program output file"
@toc "Project settings"

Program Output File
-------------------

   When executing a MUIbase program all output directed to @{b}stdout@{ub} is
actually printed to a file.  The name of this file can be entered in a
dialog by choosing menu item @{b}Program - Output file@{ub}.  You also specify
if the output should be appended to the file or if the file should be
erased and re-created on new output.

   On Windows, Mac OS and Linux you can direct the output to an
external program for processing the data.  For this, the first
character of the filename must be the pipe symbol @{b}|@{ub} followed by the
external program and its arguments.  The external program has to read
the data from its standard input.  This allows on Linux for example the
following re-directions:
   * @{b}|lpr@{ub} prints the output on the default printer.

   * @{b}|mknod /tmp/pipe p; (xterm -e less -f /tmp/pipe &); cat >
     /tmp/pipe; rm /tmp/pipe@{ub} displays the output using the program @{b}less@{ub}
     in its own @{b}xterm@{ub} window.

   * @{b}/dev/pts/0@{ub} writes the output to a terminal connected to @{b}pts/0@{ub}.  On
     some desktop environments, e.g. KDE, a daemon listens to this
     terminal and the output gets displayed in a window.

   * @{b}/dev/stdout@{ub} passes the output to the standard output channel of
     MUIbase.  This is the default.

   On the Amiga there are a few special filenames for directing the
output, e.g.:
   * @{b}PRT:@{ub} prints the output on your printer.

   * @{b}CON:////MUIbase output/CLOSE/WAIT@{ub} prints the output in a Shell
     window.

   * @{b}CONSOLE:@{ub}  prints the output in the Shell window where MUIbase has
     been started from.  This is the default.


@endnode

@node "Save as default" "MUIbase/Save as default"
@toc "Preferences"

Save as Default
===============

   The project settings are individual for each project, i.e. different
projects can have different settings.  For new projects a default
setting is chosen.  This default setting is stored together with the
user settings in the user environment (see @{"User settings" link "User settings"}).

   In order to customize the default settings to your needs, you can
store the settings of the current project as the default settings for
new projects by choosing menu item @{b}Preferences - Save as default@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Record-editing" "MUIbase/Record-editing"
@toc "Main"

Record-Editing
**************

   In this chapter you find:


 @{" Active object            " link "Active object"}  Where your input goes.
 @{" Adding records           " link "Adding records"}  How to add new records to a table.
 @{" Changing records         " link "Changing records"}  How to edit record contents.
 @{" Deleting records         " link "Deleting records"}  If you don't need some records any more.
 @{" Browsing records         " link "Browsing records"}  How to view other records.


@endnode

@node "Active object" "MUIbase/Active object"
@toc "Record-editing"

Active Object
=============

   MUIbase uses a cursor for displaying which object is the active one.
If the active object is a string object, the usual text cursor appears,
other objects get a special frame around them.  You can cycle through
the active objects by pressing the @{b}Tab@{ub} or @{b}Shift-Tab@{ub} keys.  If you press
the @{b}Help@{ub} or @{b}F1@{ub} key, an external viewer is loaded with helpful
information about the active object.

   The table in which the active object resides is called the @{i}active
table@{ui}.  The panel of a table can be set to the active object.  This
ensures that you can always set a table to be the active one, although
the table may not contain any other activate-able objects.

   On Windows, Mac OS and Linux each table has a context menu
containing menu items for manipulating the table.  This context menu
can be opened by pressing the right mouse button somewhere inside the
table mask (but outside any other GUI object that has its own context
menu).

   On Mac OS and Amiga the table menu items are part of the global menu
found at the top of the screen.


@endnode

@node "Adding records" "MUIbase/Adding records"
@toc "Record-editing"

Adding Records
==============

   If you select menu item @{b}Table - New record@{ub} a new record is allocated
in the active table.  The record is initialized with the initial values
for all attributes.  It is also possible to duplicate the current
record of the active table by selecting menu item @{b}Table - Duplicate
record@{ub}.

   If you have installed a trigger function for adding a new record
(see @{"Creating tables" link "Creating tables"}) then this trigger function is called for
creating the record.  For more information on this mechanism, See
@{"New trigger" link "New trigger"}.


@endnode

@node "Changing records" "MUIbase/Changing records"
@toc "Record-editing"

Changing Records
================

   To change the current record in a table you can activate any
attribute object within the table's mask and enter a new value.  For
string, integer, real, date, time, and memo attributes you can use the
usual editing commands.

   An attribute object may have been configured as read-only.  In this
case you can't change its value (exception: string attribute with
pop-up button).

String Attributes with Pop-up Button
------------------------------------

   If a string attribute has a pop-up button attached to it then you
can press the pop-up button and get a requester to set the string
contents, e.g. a file-requester for choosing a filename, or a list of
strings to choose one from.  The pop-up button can always be used to
set the string attribute's value even if the attribute is set to
read-only.

   Right to the string field another small button might appear.
Pressing this button calls an external viewer to display the file
specified in the string field.

Entering Integer Values
-----------------------

   When entering an integer number, one can use an octal notation
(leading 0) or hexadecimal notation (leading 0x) besides the usual
decimal notation.

Entering Boolean Values
-----------------------

   The checked state of Boolean attribute can be toggled with the left
mouse button, or with the space bar if the object is the active one.

Entering Choice Values
----------------------

   For choice attributes you can choose a value by clicking onto it, or
by using the @{b}Up@{ub} and @{b}Down@{ub} cursor keys to browse through all choice
labels.

Entering Date Values
--------------------

   Date values can be entered in one of the formats @{b}DD.MM.YYYY@{ub},
@{b}MM/DD/YYYY@{ub} or @{b}YYYY-MM-DD@{ub}, where @{b}DD@{ub}, @{b}MM@{ub} and @{b}YYYY@{ub} are standing for two
and four digit values representing the day, month and year of the date
respectively.  It is possible to omit the year value of a date.  In
this case the current year is used.

   By inserting a single integer value, a date value relatively to the
current date can be specified, e.g. when entering @{b}0@{ub} the today's date is
used, or when entering @{b}-1@{ub} yesterday's date is used.

Entering Time Values
--------------------

   The format for entering time values is specified in the structure
editor (see @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}).  Possible formats are @{b}HH:MM:SS@{ub},
@{b}MM:SS@{ub} or @{b}HH:MM@{ub} where @{b}HH@{ub} represent the hours, @{b}MM@{ub} the minutes, and @{b}SS@{ub} the
seconds.

   It is possible to omit parts of the format, e.g. entering @{b}6:30@{ub} under
the format @{b}HH:MM:SS@{ub} automatically expands to @{b}00:06:30@{ub}.  When entering a
single number, it is regarded as the number of seconds (formats
@{b}HH:MM:SS@{ub} and @{b}MM:SS@{ub}) or as the number of minutes (format @{b}HH:MM@{ub})
respectively, and the corresponding time value is computed.

Memo Context Menu
-----------------

   Memo attributes have a context menu that offers further editing
possibilities:
   * @{b}Cut@{ub}, @{b}Copy@{ub}, and @{b}Paste@{ub} allow exchanging data with the clipboard.

   * @{b}Delete@{ub} erases selected text and @{b}Select all@{ub} allows to select all
     text (Windows, Mac OS and Linux).

   * @{b}Clear@{ub} deletes all text in the memo (Amiga).

   * @{b}Undo@{ub} and @{b}Redo@{ub} allow going back and forth the changes you made to
     the memo contents (Amiga only).

   * @{b}Input methods@{ub} and @{b}Insert unicode control character@{ub} are
     GTK-specific menu items (Windows, Mac OS and Linux).  Please refer
     to the GTK documentation.

   * With @{b}Open text@{ub} and @{b}Save text@{ub} you can load and save the memo
     contents from/into a file.

   * @{b}External editor@{ub} launches an external editor for editing the memo.
     See @{"External editor" link "External editor"}, for more information about the external
     editor.

Entering Reference Values
-------------------------

   For reference attributes the record reference can be entered through
a pop-up list:

   * To the right of a reference attribute you find a pop-up button
     which, if pressed, opens a list of records.  Choose a record from
     the list to set the reference to this record, @{b}Initial@{ub} to set the
     reference to the NIL value, or @{b}Current@{ub} to set the reference to the
     current record of the referenced table.

   * You can search for an entry in the referenced table by using the
     keyboard.  After the first key press an input field is opened
     allowing to enter more characters for the search pattern.  After
     each key press, a search is started immediately (case-insensitive)
     and the first matching entry is selected.  The search method can
     be specified in the display object of the attribute (see
     @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}) under the @{b}Quick search@{ub} category.  You
     can use the characters @{b}*@{ub} for matching an arbitrary sequence of
     characters and @{b}?@{ub} for matching exactly one arbitrary character.
     Using the cursor keys @{b}Down@{ub} and @{b}Up@{ub}, the next respectively previous
     matching entry is selected.  A selected entry is stored when
     acknowledged by pressing the @{b}Enter@{ub} key.  If you leave the search
     window by other means, e.g. pressing @{b}Esc@{ub}, then the attribute stays
     unchanged and keeps its previous value.

Entering NIL Value
------------------

   To enter the NIL value, enter any invalid string for the given
attribute type, e.g. if you enter @{b}xyz@{ub}  in an integer attribute then the
value of this attribute is set to NIL.  Please note that not all
attribute types support the NIL value.  See @{"Table of attribute types" link "Table of attribute types"},
for an overview of all attribute types.


@endnode

@node "Deleting records" "MUIbase/Deleting records"
@toc "Record-editing"

Deleting Records
================

   To delete the current record chose menu item @{b}Table - Delete record@{ub}.
Before deleting the record a safety requester may appear asking you for
confirmation.  You can enable and disable this requester in the
preferences settings (see @{"Record delete requester" link "Record delete requester"}).

   If you have installed a trigger function for deleting records (see
@{"Creating tables" link "Creating tables"}) then this trigger function is called for deleting
the record.  For more information on this mechanism, see
@{"Delete trigger" link "Delete trigger"}.

   It's also possible to delete all records of a table by choosing menu
item @{b}Table - Delete all records@{ub}.  Only records matching the record
filter of the corresponding table are deleted.  Before deletion a
safety requester appears, if enabled.  No trigger function is called
when deleting all records.


@endnode

@node "Browsing records" "MUIbase/Browsing records"
@toc "Record-editing"

Browsing Records
================

   To view other records than the currently displayed one, select one
of the sub menu items in menu item @{b}Table - Goto record@{ub}.  You can go to
the previous, next, first, or last record, jump several records
backward or forward, or enter the record number of the record you want
to view.  The record number in this context is the number that is
displayed in the corresponding panel for that record (see @{"Panels" link "Panels"}).
The panel may also include two arrow buttons for going to the previous
and next record.

   Record browsing can be easily done using the @{b}Up@{ub} and @{b}Down@{ub} cursor keys
in combination with the @{b}Shift@{ub}, @{b}Alt@{ub}, and @{b}Ctrl@{ub} keys.  All possible
combinations are listed in menu item @{b}Table - Goto record@{ub} and in the
following table:


         @{b}Alt@{ub}                 @{b}Shift-Ctrl@{ub}         @{b}Shift-Alt@{ub}

@{b}Up@{ub}       Previous record     First record       Jump backward

@{b}Down@{ub}     Next record         Last record        Jump forward


@endnode

@node "Filter" "MUIbase/Filter"
@toc "Main"

Filter
******

   Filters can be used to hide records.  This chapter describes what
types of filters are available and how to use them.

   MUIbase knows two types of filters, record filters and reference
filters.


 @{" Record filter            " link "Record filter"}  Using a Boolean expression as filter.
 @{" Reference filter         " link "Reference filter"}  Using a record reference as filter.


@endnode

@node "Record filter" "MUIbase/Record filter"
@toc "Filter"

Record Filter
=============

   A record filter can be installed into a table to filter out records
that are not of interest to you.  Records that are filtered out are
excluded in the table mask and thus the user can't see or browse to
them.


 @{" Filter expression    " link "Filter expression"}  How a filter looks like.
 @{" Changing filters     " link "Changing filters"}  How to specify filter expressions.
 @{" Filter examples      " link "Filter examples"}  Some examples.


@endnode

@node "Filter expression" "MUIbase/Filter expression"
@toc "Record filter"

Filter Expression
-----------------

   A filter is defined by specifying a Boolean expression that may
contain calls to MUIbase programming functions.  For each record of the
table the filter is specified for, this expression is evaluated.  If it
returns NIL then the record is filtered out, otherwise it is included
in the table mask.

   Each table can have its own filter expression.


@endnode

@node "Changing filters" "MUIbase/Changing filters"
@toc "Record filter"

Changing Filters
----------------

   To change the filter of the current table select menu item @{b}Table -
Change filter@{ub}.  This will open a window containing

   * the name of the table you install the filter for in the window
     title.

   * a list of all attributes of the table that can be used in the
     filter expression.  This list is placed in the left part of the
     window.  If you double click a name then the name will be inserted
     into the filter expression at the current cursor position.

   * a table of buttons displaying MUIbase programming functions and
     operators placed in the right part of the window.  Click on one of
     the buttons to enter the corresponding function in the filter
     expression.  Please note that the presented list of functions and
     operators is not complete.  Other MUIbase functions not shown in
     one of the buttons must be entered manually.  Only those MUIbase
     functions can be used that don't have side effects, e.g. it is not
     possible to write data to a file within a filter expression.

   * a string input field to enter the filter expression.  The
     attribute and function/operator names are inserted here.  You can
     also directly input your filter expression.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} to leave the window.

   After you are done with the specification of the filter expression
click on the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to leave the window.  The entered expression is
now compiled and on successful compilation, the expression is evaluated
for all records.  Those records for which the Boolean expression
doesn't hold are then discarded in the table mask.

   In case the expression doesn't compile you will get an error message
displayed in the window title bar.

   A filter can be turned on and off by clicking on the @{b}F@{ub} button in the
table's panel (if it is installed).  After you have specified a filter
expression for a table the filter for this table is turned on
automatically.

   If you (re-)activate a filter then all records of the table are
checked whether they match the filter or not.

   If a filter is currently active and you change a (filter relevant)
attribute in a record of this table then the match-filter state of this
record is not recomputed and stays unchanged.

   If you allocate a new record in a table with an activated filter
then there is no check if the new record matches the filter and the new
record has its match-filter state set to TRUE.


@endnode

@node "Filter examples" "MUIbase/Filter examples"
@toc "Record filter"

Filter Examples
---------------

   Here are some examples for valid filter expressions:

   * @{b}NIL@{ub} filters out all records.

   * @{b}TRUE@{ub} doesn't filter out any record.

   * @{b}0@{ub} has the same effect as @{b}TRUE@{ub} because for MUIbase all expressions
     not equal to NIL are considered as TRUE.

   * @{b}(> Amount 100.0)@{ub} only displays records where the @{b}Amount@{ub} attribute
     is greater than 100.0 (we assume here that the table has an
     attribute @{b}Amount@{ub} of type real).

   * @{b}(NOT (LIKE Name "*x*"))@{ub} filters out all records that have the
     letter @{b}x@{ub} in the @{b}Name@{ub} attribute (a string attribute).

   Please note that MUIbase' programming language uses a lisp-like
syntax.  For more information about the programming language, see
@{"Programming MUIbase" link "Programming MUIbase"}.


@endnode

@node "Reference filter" "MUIbase/Reference filter"
@toc "Filter"

Reference Filter
================

   Reference attributes can also have a filter behavior.  This is
useful e.g. for building a hierarchy of tables.  As an example see the
project @{b}Albums@{ub}.

   If the filter of a reference attribute is turned on then the
following features are activated:

  1. The user can only access records in the attribute's table that
     have the reference set to the current record of the referenced
     table.

  2. If the referenced table changes its current record then also a new
     current record is searched and set for the attribute's table.

  3. When allocating a new record the reference is automatically set to
     the current record of the referenced table.

   Note: Cascading delete has to be implemented manually (by using a
delete trigger function).

   Do not use the reference filter on cyclic graphs, e.g.
self-referencing tables, as it doesn't make much sense.


@endnode

@node "Order" "MUIbase/Order"
@toc "Main"

Order
*****

   For each table in your database you can specify in which order its
records should be displayed.  This chapter describes how you can
specify an order and what consequences it has.


 @{" Empty order          " link "Empty order"}  If you don't want to order your records.
 @{" Order by attributes  " link "Order by attributes"}  Easy ordering by comparing attributes.
 @{" Order by a function  " link "Order by a function"}  Customized ordering.
 @{" Changing orders      " link "Changing orders"}  How to specify an order.
 @{" Reorder all records  " link "Reorder all records"}  If they ever become unsorted.


@endnode

@node "Empty order" "MUIbase/Empty order"
@toc "Order"

Empty Order
===========

   By default each newly created table has an empty order.  This means
that if you enter a new record, the created record is inserted at the
current position, that is, behind the current record of the table.  If
you change some fields of a record, the position of the record within
the table stays unchanged.


@endnode

@node "Order by attributes" "MUIbase/Order by attributes"
@toc "Order"

Order by Attributes
===================

   Sometimes it is useful to have the records sorted by a certain
attribute, e.g. by the @{b}Name@{ub} attribute if the table has one.

   In MUIbase you can specify for each table a list of attributes by
which its records should be sorted.  All records are first sorted by
the first attribute in this list.  If two records are equal in an
attribute then the next attribute in the list determines the order.
For each attribute you can specify if the records should be sorted
ascending or descending.

   For determining the order of attributes the rules of the following
table are used:


@{b}Type@{ub}        @{b}Order relation@{ub}

Integer     NIL < MIN_INT < ... < -1 < 0 < 1 < ... < MAX_INT
Choice      (Choice values are treated as integers)

Real        NIL < -HUGE_VAL < ... < -1.0 < 0.0 < 1.0 < ... < HUGE_VAL

String      NIL < "" < ... < "a" < "AA" < "b" < ...
Memo        (String comparison is done case insensitive)

Date        NIL < 1.1.0000 < ... < 31.12.9999

Time        NIL < 00:00:00 < ... < 596523:14:07

Boolean     NIL < TRUE

Reference   NIL < any_record
            (Records itself are not comparable for ordering)

   If you have specified an order for a table then the records are
automatically rearranged whenever you add a new record or change an
order-relevant field of a record.


@endnode

@node "Order by a function" "MUIbase/Order by a function"
@toc "Order"

Order by a Function
===================

   Sometimes you want a more complex ordering scheme than a simple
attribute list as described in the last section.  For example, an
attribute list can't hold reference attributes, so it is not possible
to sort your records by a reference field.  The reason for this is that
with reference attributes MUIbase is not able to keep your records
ordered at all times (see @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"} in the MUIbase
programming chapter for more details).

   However, MUIbase also offers the possibility to specify a comparison
function for sorting your records.  You can specify any function that
you have written using the MUIbase program editor.  The function will
be called with two record pointers and the returned value should
reflect the order of the two records.  The function can use any
operations for comparing the records, thus it can e.g.  compare records
using reference attributes.  For more information on this mechanism,
see @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.

   If you decide to use a comparison function for ordering a table then
please note that MUIbase cannot always detect when records of the table
have to be reordered since the dependencies are unknown.  Use menu item
@{b}Table - Reorder all records@{ub} when records are becoming unsorted.


@endnode

@node "Changing orders" "MUIbase/Changing orders"
@toc "Order"

Changing Orders
===============

   To specify an order for the current table select menu item @{b}Table -
Change order@{ub}.  This will open a window containing

   * the name of the table in the window title.

   * a choice field @{b}Type@{ub} where you specify whether the table should be
     ordered by using an @{b}Attribute list@{ub} or by using a @{b}Comparison
     function@{ub}.  Depending on the state of @{b}Type@{ub} you can enter data into
     the following items.

   For an order using an attribute list, the following items exist:

   * a list of all attributes of the table that can be used in the
     order list. This list is placed in the left part of the window.
     If you double click a name then the name will be inserted into the
     order list at the current cursor position.

   * the current list of attributes used for ordering.  This list is
     placed in the right part of the window.  The top item in this list
     is the first attribute of the order list.  You can rearrange items
     by dragging them to other positions in the list.  To add further
     attributes drag them from the attribute list to the order list.
     You can remove an attribute from the order list by dragging the
     item out of the order list and dropping it onto the attribute list.

     Each entry in the order list has an arrow symbol pointing up or
     down on the left side.  You can toggle the state of the arrow by
     double-clicking it. If an arrow is pointing up then the sorting
     order for this attribute is done ascending, if it is pointing
     down, it is done descending.

   For an order using a comparison function, there is the following
item:

   * a field @{b}Function for comparing records@{ub} where you can enter the
     name of a function that should be called for comparing two records
     of the table.  You can use the pop-up button to the right of the
     string field for choosing a name from a list of all function names.
     If you leave the field empty then an empty order is used.  For
     more information on how to use a comparison function, including
     the arguments that are passed to it, see @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.

   Furthermore, the following buttons exist:

   * a @{b}Clear@{ub} button that clears all fields for an empty order.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   To enter a new attribute order list, choose @{b}Attribute list@{ub} in the
@{b}Type@{ub} field and press the @{b}Clear@{ub} button.  Then use drag & drop as
described above to build up a new list of attributes.  If you want to
have an empty order then just don't add any attributes to the order
list.

   When you are done specifying the order, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button.
MUIbase will then reorder all records of the table.


@endnode

@node "Reorder all records" "MUIbase/Reorder all records"
@toc "Order"

Reorder all Records
===================

   If you ever think that some records of a table became unsorted, e.g.
when using a comparison function for ordering, then you can choose menu
item @{b}Table - Reorder all records@{ub} for sorting all records.


@endnode

@node "Search for" "MUIbase/Search for"
@toc "Main"

Search For
**********

   For record browsing you can use a search requester to search for a
specific record.  The search feature uses a search pattern that you
provide and checks all records for a successful match with this
pattern.  If it finds one then this record will be displayed in the
table mask.


 @{" Search requester        " link "Search requester"}  How to enter a search pattern.
 @{" Forward-backward search " link "Forward-backward search"}  Go to the next/previous matching record.
 @{" Examples                " link "Search pattern examples"}  Some search pattern examples.


@endnode

@node "Search requester" "MUIbase/Search requester"
@toc "Search for"

Search Requester
================

   To open the search requester select menu item @{b}Table - Search for@{ub}.
This will open a window containing

   * a string field for entering the search pattern.  Use the
     characters @{b}*@{ub} and @{b}?@{ub} as jokers. The character @{b}*@{ub} matches any number
     of characters (including zero characters) whereas @{b}?@{ub} matches
     exactly one single character.

   * a field @{b}Case sensitive@{ub}.  If you check it, searching uses case
     sensitive string comparison, otherwise case insensitive string
     comparison is used.

   * a field @{b}All fields@{ub}.  If checked then all fields of a record are
     tested for a successful match with the search pattern.  Otherwise
     only the attribute which has been the active one when the search
     requester has been opened is tested.  In case the active object at
     the time when opening the search requester has not been an
     attribute object, this field is checked and disabled automatically.

   * two radio buttons for the search direction, @{b}Forward@{ub} and @{b}Backward@{ub}.

   * two radio buttons for specifying from which record the search
     should be started. @{b}First/last record@{ub} will start the search from
     the first or last record depending on the search direction.
     @{b}Current record@{ub} starts the search from the current record.

   * two buttons @{b}Search@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   After you have entered a search pattern and left the requester with
the @{b}Search@{ub} button MUIbase starts searching for a matching record.  The
comparison of an attribute field with the search pattern is always done
string based, attribute fields of non-string types are therefore
converted to strings first.

   If a matching record is found, it is displayed as the current record
in the table mask. Otherwise a @{b}Search pattern not found@{ub} message appears.

   If you search on an attribute that is used as the first attribute for
ordering and your search pattern doesn't start with a joker (@{b}*@{ub} or @{b}?@{ub})
then an improved search algorithm (binary search) is used that makes
use of the record order.  This can speed up searching significantly.


@endnode

@node "Forward-backward search" "MUIbase/Forward-backward search"
@toc "Search for"

Forward/Backward Search
=======================

   Two further menu items allow to search for the next and the previous
occurrence of the search pattern.  Select menu item @{b}Table - Search
forward@{ub} for browsing to the next record that matches the search
pattern, and @{b}Table - Search backward@{ub} to go to the previous matching
record.


@endnode

@node "Search pattern examples" "MUIbase/Search pattern examples"
@toc "Search for"

Search Pattern Examples
=======================

   Here are some search pattern examples:

   * @{b}Lassie@{ub} searches for records that have the string @{b}Lassie@{ub} in one of
     the search attributes.

   * @{b}*x*@{ub} searches for records that have the letter @{b}x@{ub} in one of the
     search attributes.

   * @{b}???@{ub} searches for records that have exactly three characters in one
     of the search attributes, e.g. a record with an entry @{b}UFO@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Import and Export" "MUIbase/Import and Export"
@toc "Main"

Import and Export
*****************

   For sharing your records with other databases, MUIbase offers a way
to import and export records from and to other databases.  Import and
export is done by reading and writing text files.  The text files must
follow a special format described in the next section.


 @{" File format                        " link "Import file format"}  How the format looks like.
 @{" Sample import file                 " link "Sample import file"}  An example.
 @{" Importing records                  " link "Importing records"}  How to import records.
 @{" Exporting records                  " link "Exporting records"}  How to export records.


@endnode

@node "Import file format" "MUIbase/Import file format"
@toc "Import and Export"

File Format
===========

   For importing records into MUIbase, all records of a table should be
in a single text file.  If records of several tables are to be imported,
they should be in separate import files, one for each table.

   An import file consists of lines and columns. Lines are separated by
a record delimiter, columns by a field delimiter.  The delimiters can
be specified in the import and export dialog.  Since a record field
itself may contain such a delimiter, double quotes can be used around
all fields for escaping delimiters.

   The import file should be of the following structure:

   * The first line contains the field names.  For each name the table
     where the records are imported to must contain an attribute with
     the exact same name.  In case no matching attribute is found for a
     given name, the import fails with an error message.

   * The following lines contain one record each.  Since all fields are
     given as strings, they are converted automatically to the type of
     the destination attribute.  For attributes of type Boolean, the
     field must be either NIL or TRUE (case insensitive), otherwise an
     error message is generated.  For attributes of type choice the
     exact label string must be specified (case sensitive).  For
     reference attributes the record number starting with 1 must be
     specified.  For all other types a value of NIL is used if the field
     cannot be converted to the required type.

   * If you decide to use double quotes then all record fields
     including the line containing the field names must be surrounded
     by double quotes.


@endnode

@node "Sample import file" "MUIbase/Sample import file"
@toc "Import and Export"

Sample Import File
==================

   The following sample import file uses @{b}\\n@{ub} and @{b}\\t@{ub} for record and
field delimiters and double quotes around all fields.  The file can be
imported into a table with the following attributes:

   * Name (string)

   * NumChildrens (integer)

   * Feminine (Boolean)

   * Job (choice)

   * Notes (memo)


"Name"	"NumChildrens"	"Feminine"	"Job"	"Notes"
"Janet Jackson"	"???"	"TRUE"	"Musician"	"Latest CD: The velvet rope"
"Bernt Schiele"	"???"	"NIL"	"Scientist"	"Research interests:
Robotics, Autonomy and Computer Vision"
"Gerhard"	"0"	"NIL"	"Precision mechanic"	""


@endnode

@node "Importing records" "MUIbase/Importing records"
@toc "Import and Export"

Importing Records
=================

   To import records into the active table select menu item @{b}Table -
Import records@{ub}.  This will open a window containing

   * a string field for entering the import filename.  To the right of
     this field you find three buttons.  Click on the first one to open
     a file dialog for choosing the filename.  The second button starts
     an external viewer with the entered filename while the third
     button starts an editor for editing the file contents.

   * two string fields for entering the record and field delimiters.
     You can enter a single character or an escape code by typing @{b}\\n@{ub},
     @{b}\\t@{ub}, @{b}\\f@{ub}, @{b}\\???@{ub} (octal code), or @{b}\\x??@{ub} (hex code).  Delimiter
     characters must be 7bit ASCII characters.

   * a field @{b}Double quotes@{ub} that can be checked to specify that the
     fields are surrounded by double quotes.

   * a field @{b}Overwrite records@{ub} that if selected will overwrite existing
     records with the imported data.  This can be useful in case you
     want to keep the existing records (e.g. because there are
     references to them) but update them with new information.

   * two buttons @{b}Import@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   If you press the @{b}Import@{ub} button, MUIbase will load the specified file
and import all found records.  If everything went fine and new records
were created in the table, MUIbase asks after the import process if you
really want to add the newly imported records to the table.  At this
point you can still cancel the operation.  Overwritten records,
however, can only be recovered by reverting the project.

   If an error occurs while reading the import file then an error
message is shown.

   If you need a more sophisticated import routine it is recommended to
write your own import routine as a MUIbase program.


@endnode

@node "Exporting records" "MUIbase/Exporting records"
@toc "Import and Export"

Exporting Records
=================

   To export records from the active table select menu item @{b}Table -
Export records@{ub}.  This will open a window containing

   * a string field for entering the export filename.  Right to this
     field you find a pop-up button to open a file dialog for choosing
     the filename.

   * two string fields for entering the record and field delimiters.
     You can enter a single character or an escape code by typing @{b}\\n@{ub},
     @{b}\\t@{ub}, @{b}\\f@{ub}, @{b}\\???@{ub} (octal code), or @{b}\\x??@{ub} (hex code).

   * a field @{b}Double quotes@{ub} that can be checked to specify that the
     fields should be surrounded by double quotes.

   * a field @{b}Filter@{ub}.  If checked only the records that match the
     currently installed record filter are written to the export file.

   * two buttons @{b}Export@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   After you pressed the @{b}Export@{ub} button, MUIbase will open the specified
file and write out the records including a header line containing the
attribute names.  The export feature always writes all attribute fields
of a table to the export file.

   For a more customized export routine, you can use MUIbase' query
editor (see @{"Data retrieval" link "Data retrieval"}) or you write your own export function as a
MUIbase program.


@endnode

@node "Data retrieval" "MUIbase/Data retrieval"
@toc "Main"

Data Retrieval
**************

   For data retrieval MUIbase offers two ways: the programming feature
and the query editor.

   The programming feature allows you to install buttons in table masks
which, when pressed, call program functions.  The usage of this feature
is described in the structure editor chapter (see @{"Structure editor" link "Structure editor"})
and in the chapter about programming MUIbase (see @{"Programming MUIbase" link "Programming MUIbase"}).

   This chapter describes the usage of the query editor, a requester
where you can enter queries and view the output in a scrolling
list-view.


 @{" Select-from-where queries  " link "Select-from-where queries"}  How a query looks like.
 @{" Query editor               " link "Query editor"}  How to enter and manage your queries.
 @{" Printing queries           " link "Printing queries"}  Options when printing the result of a query.
 @{" Query examples             " link "Query examples"}  Some examples.


@endnode

@node "Select-from-where queries" "MUIbase/Select-from-where queries"
@toc "Data retrieval"

Select-From-Where Queries
=========================

   MUIbase offers a select-from-where query similar to the one in SQL
database systems.  The query allows you to list the record contents
from one or more tables.  Only records matching certain criteria are
included in the output.  The (incomplete) syntax of an
select-from-where query is

     SELECT EXPRLIST FROM TABLELIST [WHERE TEST-EXPR]
     [ORDER BY ORDERLIST]

   where EXPRLIST is a comma separated list of expressions to be printed
(usually the attribute names) or a simple star @{b}*@{ub} matching all
attributes of the specified tables, TABLELIST is a comma separated list
of tables whose records are examined, TEST-EXPR is the expression that
is tested for each set of records to be included in the output, and
ORDERLIST is a comma separated list of attributes that defines the
order for listing the output.  Please note that the WHERE and ORDER BY
fields are optional, denoted by the brackets @{b}[]@{ub}.

   For example, the query

     SELECT * FROM TABLE

   lists the attribute contents of all records in the given table.

     SELECT ATTR1 FROM TABLE WHERE (LIKE ATTR2 "*Madonna*")

   lists the value of the ATTR1 field in all records of TABLE where the
contents of field ATTR2 contain the word @{b}Madonna@{ub}.

   For more information about the select-from-where query including its
full syntax, see @{"Programming MUIbase" link "Programming MUIbase"}, for more example see
@{"Query examples" link "Query examples"}.


@endnode

@node "Query editor" "MUIbase/Query editor"
@toc "Data retrieval"

Query Editor
============

   For entering and running queries, open the query editor by choosing
menu item @{b}Program - Queries@{ub}.  The query editor is able to manage
several queries, however only one query is displayed at a time.  The
query editor window contains the following items:

   * a string input field with an attached pop-up button.  The
     edit-able string field displays the name of the current query.  By
     pressing the pop-up button, a list with further query names
     together with several buttons appear.  You can select one of the
     listed queries to make it the current one, press the @{b}New@{ub} button to
     create a new query, press the @{b}Duplicate@{ub} button to get a copy of the
     activated query, click on the @{b}Sort@{ub} button to sort the list of
     queries, or press the @{b}Delete@{ub} button to delete the selected query.
     For leaving the pop-up window without changing anything, click on
     the pop-up button again.

   * a @{b}Run@{ub} button that compiles and runs the query program and displays
     the output in the output list-view.

   * a @{b}Print@{ub} button that opens a requester (see @{"Printing queries" link "Printing queries"}) for
     printing the results.

   * an editor field for entering the query program.  Here you usually
     enter a select-from-where query.  However, it is also possible to
     enter any expression of MUIbase' programming language.  This can
     be useful if you want to do simple computations or update some
     fields of a table by using a simple program.  Please note that
     MUIbase automatically surrounds your program expression with a
     pair of parenthesis, thus you can omit the outermost ones.

   * a list-view that displays the output after running the current
     query.  The output is formatted into rows and columns.  The title
     row holds the field names of the select-from-where query (usually
     the attribute names).  The other rows hold the contents of the
     query result, one set of records per row.  Each field is displayed
     in its own column.  By clicking on a column title you can sort the
     list with respect to this column.  A second click onto the same
     column title reverses the order.  On the Amiga you can set a
     secondary sort column by holding down the @{b}Shift@{ub} key when clicking
     on a title.  If you double click on entry in the list and the
     entry was generated from a record then this record is displayed in
     the corresponding table mask.  This offers an easy way to jump to
     a certain record in its table mask.

   The query editor is a non-modal requester.  This means that you can
leave the query editor open and still work with the rest of the
application.  You can close the query editor at any time by clicking on
the close button in the window title bar.


@endnode

@node "Printing queries" "MUIbase/Printing queries"
@toc "Data retrieval"

Printing Queries
================

   After you have run a query you can print the result to a file or
printer by clicking on the @{b}Print@{ub} button in the query editor.  This
opens a print requester containing the following items:

   * a field @{b}Delimiter@{ub} where you specify how the columns should be
     separated.  @{b}Spaces@{ub} pads the fields with space characters.  Padding
     is done on the left or on the right side depending on the type of
     the field (numbers are padded on the left, text on the right side).
     @{b}Tabs@{ub} inserts exactly one tab character between the columns.  This
     can be useful if you want to use the print requester for exporting
     records (see below).  @{b}Custom@{ub} allows to specify a custom delimiter
     string to be printed between fields.

   * a field @{b}Font@{ub} where you specify which font should be used for
     printing the output.  @{b}NLQ@{ub} stands for near letter quality which
     should print the output in better quality than @{b}Draft@{ub}.

   * a field @{b}Size@{ub} where you define the character size.  @{b}Pica@{ub} prints in
     a large font (10 CPI), @{b}Elite@{ub} in a medium font (12 CPI) and
     @{b}Condensed@{ub} in a small font (17 CPI).

   * a string field @{b}Init sequence@{ub} where you can enter a string for
     initializing your printer. The contents of this field are written
     directly after opening the printer.  For example you can use @{b}\\33c@{ub}
     as init sequence which resets your printer.

   * a field @{b}Indent@{ub} where you can enter a number of spaces that are
     used for indenting each output line.

   * a field @{b}Headline@{ub} that, if checked, prints the field names in the
     first line.

   * a field @{b}Escape codes@{ub}.  If not checked the output of all escape
     codes is suppressed which means that the settings of the fields
     @{b}Font@{ub} and @{b}Size@{ub} are ignored and the contents of @{b}Init sequence@{ub} are
     not printed.  Suppressing the output of all escape codes is useful
     if you want to generate an ASCII file, e.g. for exporting records.

   * a field @{b}Quotes@{ub} that, if checked, surrounds all fields with double
     quotes.

   * a field @{b}After printing@{ub} where you can specify how the output should
     be finished.  @{b}Form feed@{ub} prints a form feed character @{b}\\f@{ub}. @{b}Line
     feeds@{ub} prints a number of line feed characters @{b}\\n@{ub}.  The number of
     line feeds can be entered in the string field to the right of the
     @{b}Line feeds@{ub} button.  @{b}Nothing@{ub} doesn't write anything to the printer.

   * a string field @{b}Output@{ub} with an attached pop-up button.  You can use
     the pop-up button to open a file requester for choosing a filename
     or directly enter the filename into the string field.  For writing
     the output to your printer enter @{b}|lpr@{ub} (Linux) respectively @{b}PRT:@{ub}
     (Amiga).  For other special filenames, see @{"Program output file" link "Program output file"}.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the print requester.

   After you are done with all settings, click on the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to
start the print job.

   The print requester can also be used for exporting records to an
ASCII file.  To do this, specify @{b}Tabs@{ub} (or @{b}Custom@{ub}) in the @{b}Delimiter@{ub}
field, set the number of spaces in the @{b}Indent@{ub} field to 0, check
@{b}Headline@{ub}, un-check @{b}Escape codes@{ub} to suppress the font, size and init
sequence settings, optionally check @{b}Quotes@{ub} if you want the field
contents to be surrounded by double quotes, check @{b}Nothing@{ub} in the @{b}After
printing@{ub} field, and enter the output filename in the @{b}Output@{ub} field.
Using the query editor together with the print requester for exporting
records can be more powerful than when using MUIbase' import/export
feature (see @{"Import and Export" link "Import and Export"}) since in the query editor any query
can be entered whereas the export requester only uses a fixed query.


@endnode

@node "Query examples" "MUIbase/Query examples"
@toc "Data retrieval"

Query Examples
==============

   To give you an impression of the power of the select-from-where
queries this section gives you some sample queries.

   Suppose we have two tables @{b}Person@{ub} and @{b}Dog@{ub}.  @{b}Person@{ub} has a string
attribute @{b}Name@{ub}, an integer attribute @{b}Age@{ub}, and two reference attributes
@{b}Father@{ub} and @{b}Mother@{ub} that refer to the father and mother records in table
@{b}Person@{ub}.  The table contains the following records:

      Name      Age     Father  Mother
      --------------------------------
p1:   Steffen    26     p2      p3
p2:   Dieter     58     NIL     NIL
p3:   Marlies    56     NIL     NIL
p4:   Henning    57     NIL     NIL

@{b}   Dog@{ub} has a string attribute @{b}Name@{ub}, a choice attribute @{b}Color@{ub} and a
reference attribute @{b}Owner@{ub} that refers to the owner in the @{b}Person@{ub} table.
The table contains the following records:

      Name      Color   Owner
      -----------------------
d1:   Boy       white   p3
d2:   Streuner  grey    NIL

   Given these data the following sample select-from-where queries can
be run:

SELECT * FROM Person

   results to:

Name    Age Father Mother
--------------------------
Steffen  26 Dieter Marlies
Dieter   58
Marlies  56
Henning  57

   (For the reference attributes the @{b}Name@{ub} field of the referenced
record is printed.)

SELECT Name "Child", Age,
       Father.Name "Father", Father.Age "Age",
       Mother.Name "Mother", Mother.Age "Age"
FROM Person WHERE (AND Father Mother)

   results to:

Child   Age Father Age Mother  Age
----------------------------------
Steffen  26 Dieter  58 Marlies  56

SELECT Name, Color,
       (IF Owner Owner.Name "No owner") "Owner"
FROM Dogs

   results to:

Name     Color  Owner
------------------------
Boy      white  Marlies
Streuner grey   No owner

SELECT a.Name, a.Age, b.Name, b.Age FROM Person a, Person b
WHERE (> a.Age b.Age)

   results to:

a.Name  a.Age b.Name  b.Age
---------------------------
Dieter     58 Steffen    26
Marlies    56 Steffen    26
Henning    57 Steffen    26
Dieter     58 Marlies    56
Henning    57 Marlies    56
Dieter     58 Henning    57


@endnode

@node "Structure editor" "MUIbase/Structure editor"
@toc "Main"

Structure Editor
****************

   MUIbase has two different operating modes, the record-editing mode,
where you enter and browse records, and the structure-editing mode
where you define the structure, that is, the tables, attributes and
appearance of a project.  This chapter describes the structure editor
and explains how to manage the structure of a project.

   To switch from record-editing to structure-editing mode select menu
item @{b}Structure editor@{ub} in the @{b}Project@{ub} menu.  This closes all windows and
opens the structure editor window.  To switch back to record-editing
mode select menu item @{b}Project - Exit structure editor@{ub} or simply close
the structure editor by clicking on the close button in the window
title bar.

   The structure editor window is divided into three parts: in the
upper left part there is a field @{b}Tables@{ub} for managing the tables of the
project, the lower left part is occupied by a field @{b}Attributes@{ub} for
managing the attributes of a table, and the right part is used by a
field @{b}Display@{ub} for managing the project's GUI elements.


 @{" Table management       " link "Table management"}  How to add, change and delete tables.
 @{" Attribute management   " link "Attribute management"}  Adding, changing, and deleting attributes.
 @{" Display management     " link "Display management"}  Managing the project's GUI elements.
 @{" Export structure       " link "Export structure"}  Getting an overview of all tables and attributes.


@endnode

@node "Table management" "MUIbase/Table management"
@toc "Structure editor"

Table Management
================

   In the @{b}Tables@{ub} field of the structure editor you can create, change,
delete and sort tables.


 @{" Creating tables        " link "Creating tables"}  How to add a table.
 @{" Changing tables        " link "Changing tables"}  How to modify a table.
 @{" Deleting tables        " link "Deleting tables"}  How to remove a table.
 @{" Sorting tables         " link "Sorting tables"}  How to order the list of tables.


@endnode

@node "Creating tables" "MUIbase/Creating tables"
@toc "Table management"

Creating Tables
---------------

   To create a new table press the @{b}New@{ub} button in the @{b}Tables@{ub} field.
This will open the @{b}New table@{ub} requester containing

   * a string field for entering the name of the table.  Each table
     must have a unique name that starts with an uppercase letter
     followed by further letters, digits or underscore characters.
     Non-ASCII characters like German umlauts are not allowed.  Please
     note that in the user interface for the table it is still possible
     to display any strings including strings with non-ASCII characters.

   * a field @{b}Number of records@{ub} where you specify how many records the
     table is going to hold.  @{b}Unlimited@{ub} means that the table can hold
     any number of records, @{b}Exactly one@{ub} means that the table can have
     only one record. The latter one is sometimes useful for
     controlling the project (see @{"Tables" link "Tables"}).

   * a field @{b}Trigger functions@{ub} where you can enter the names of two
     functions.  In the @{b}New@{ub} string field you enter the name of the
     function that should be called whenever the user wants to create a
     new record, the @{b}Delete@{ub} string field holds the name of the function
     that should be called whenever the user wants to delete a record.
     You can use the pop-up buttons to the right of the string fields
     for choosing a function name from a list of all names.  If you
     leave a field empty then default actions are executed (records are
     created automatically and records are deleted after an optional
     safety requester).  For more information on how to use these
     trigger functions, including the arguments that are passed to
     them, see @{"New trigger" link "New trigger"} and @{"Delete trigger" link "Delete trigger"}.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the requester.

   When you are done with all settings, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to create
the new table.  If you made an error somewhere, e.g. you entered an
invalid name, a message window pops up giving you more information
about the error you did.  If everything goes fine, the @{b}New table@{ub}
requester will be closed and the new table is displayed in the
structure editor's table list.


@endnode

@node "Changing tables" "MUIbase/Changing tables"
@toc "Table management"

Changing Tables
---------------

   After you have created a new table you can still change it.  Just
double-click on the table's name and the @{b}Change table@{ub} requester pops
up.  This requester is similar to the one when creating a table (see
@{"Creating tables" link "Creating tables"}) and allows you to make changes in any field by
entering a new value.

   When you are done with all changes, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to leave the
requester.

   Please note that you can't change the number of records from
@{b}Unlimited@{ub} to @{b}Exactly one@{ub} if the table already contains more than one
record.


@endnode

@node "Deleting tables" "MUIbase/Deleting tables"
@toc "Table management"

Deleting Tables
---------------

   To delete a table, click on the table's name in the structure
editor's table list, then press the @{b}Del@{ub} button below the list.  Before
the table is actually deleted a safety requester pops up asking for
confirmation.  If you confirm this requester by pressing the @{b}Delete@{ub}
button, the table is deleted.

   A problem occurs if the table is used somewhere in the project's
program.  In this case the table can't simply be deleted but all
references to the table must be removed from the program.  If the table
you want to delete is used in the project's program then the program
editor pops up and displays the first occurrence to the table.  You
should now modify the program such that no references to this table
remain in the program.  After you removed a reference you can jump to
the next one by pressing the @{b}Compile@{ub} button.  At any point you can
still cancel the whole operation by pressing the @{b}Revert@{ub} button and
closing the program editor.


@endnode

@node "Sorting tables" "MUIbase/Sorting tables"
@toc "Table management"

Sorting Tables
--------------

   For sorting the tables in the @{b}Tables@{ub} field of the structure editor
you have several choices.  You can order them manually, that is, you
use drag & drop to rearrange a table, or you use the @{b}Sort@{ub} button below
the list-view which orders the tables alphabetically (@{b}Sort1@{ub}), or
according to the order in the list display (@{b}Sort2@{ub}).


@endnode

@node "Attribute management" "MUIbase/Attribute management"
@toc "Structure editor"

Attribute Management
====================

   In the @{b}Attributes@{ub} field of the structure editor you can create,
copy, change, delete and sort the attributes of the active table in the
@{b}Tables@{ub} field.


 @{" Creating attributes    " link "Creating attributes"}  How to add an attribute.
 @{" Type specific settings " link "Type specific settings"}  Settings depending on the type of an attribute.
 @{" Label editor           " link "Label editor"}  Specifying label strings, e.g. for choice attributes.
 @{" Copying attributes     " link "Copying attributes"}  Making copies of an attribute.
 @{" Changing attributes    " link "Changing attributes"}  How to modify an attribute.
 @{" Deleting attributes    " link "Deleting attributes"}  How to remove an attribute.
 @{" Sorting attributes     " link "Sorting attributes"}  How to order the list of attributes.


@endnode

@node "Creating attributes" "MUIbase/Creating attributes"
@toc "Attribute management"

Creating Attributes
-------------------

   To create a new attribute for the active table press the @{b}New@{ub} button
in the @{b}Attribute@{ub} field.  This will open the @{b}New attribute@{ub} requester
containing

   * a string field for entering the name of the attribute.  Each
     attribute in a table must have an unique name that starts with an
     uppercase letter followed by further letters, digits or underscore
     characters.  Non-ASCII characters like German umlauts are not
     allowed.  Please note that in the user interface it is still
     possible to display any strings including strings with non-ASCII
     characters for the attribute.

   * a choice field @{b}Type@{ub} where you specify the type of the attribute.
     For more information on attribute types, see @{"Attribute types" link "Attribute types"}.

   * a section below the @{b}Type@{ub} field for specifying type specific
     settings. For more information about this section, see
     @{"Type specific settings" link "Type specific settings"}.

   * a field @{b}Trigger@{ub} where you can enter the name of a function that
     should be called whenever the user wants to change the contents of
     the attribute field in a record.  You can use the pop-up button to
     the right of the string field for choosing a name from a list of
     all function names.  If you leave the field empty then a default
     action is executed, that is, the entered value is simply stored in
     the attribute field.  For more information on how to use the
     trigger function, including the arguments that are passed to it,
     see @{"Attribute trigger" link "Attribute trigger"}.

   * a field @{b}Count changes@{ub}.  If checked, every change to the attribute
     in a record counts as a change of the project.  Uncheck this item,
     if you want to ignore changes to an attribute.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the requester.

   When you are done with all settings, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to create
the new attribute.  If you made an error somewhere, e.g. you entered an
invalid name, a message window pops up giving you more information
about the error you did.  If everything goes fine, the @{b}New attribute@{ub}
requester will be closed and the new attribute is displayed in the
structure editor's attribute list.


@endnode

@node "Type specific settings" "MUIbase/Type specific settings"
@toc "Attribute management"

Type Specific Settings
----------------------

   In the type specific section the following settings can be specified:

   * For attributes of type string you have

        - an integer field @{b}Max length@{ub} for entering the maximum string
          length for this attribute field.

        - a string field @{b}Initial value@{ub} for specifying the value that is
          used for initializing the attribute field.  Any string up to
          the specified maximum length can be entered here.

   * For attributes of type integer, real, date, and time the type
     specific section offers

        - a field @{b}Initial value@{ub} where you specify the value for
          initializing the attribute field.  You can choose between @{b}NIL@{ub}
          and @{b}other@{ub}.  If you select @{b}other@{ub} then you should enter the
          initial value into the string field on the right.

        - a string field @{b}NIL string@{ub} where you enter the string that
          should be displayed when the attribute field holds the NIL
          value.

   * For Boolean attributes the type specific section contains a field
     @{b}Initial value@{ub} where you can choose between @{b}NIL@{ub} and @{b}TRUE@{ub} for the
     initial value.

   * The type specific section for choice attributes offers

        - a button @{b}Edit labels@{ub} for opening the @{b}Edit labels@{ub} window where
          you can enter the label strings for the choice field (see
          @{"Label editor" link "Label editor"}).

        - a choice field @{b}Initial value@{ub} for specifying the value for
          initializing the attribute field.

   * For reference attributes the type specific section contains

        - a list-view displaying all tables for specifying to which
          table the reference should be made.  Click on the table the
          attribute is going to reference.

        - a field @{b}Auto show@{ub}.  If checked, the referenced table gets
          updated automatically with the referenced record whenever the
          user switches to another record.

        - a field @{b}Filter@{ub}.  If checked, the reference filter of this
          attribute is turned on.  See @{"Reference filter" link "Reference filter"}, for more
          information about this feature.

     Reference attributes always have the NIL value as initial value.

   * The type specific section for virtual attributes contains a string
     field @{b}Compute@{ub} where you enter the name of a function that should
     be called for calculating the value of the attribute.  You can use
     the attached pop-up button for selecting a name from a list of all
     function names.  For more information on how to use this function,
     see @{"Programming virtual attributes" link "Programming virtual attributes"}.

   * Memo and button attributes do not have any type specific settings.
     The initial value for memo attributes is an empty string.


@endnode

@node "Label editor" "MUIbase/Label editor"
@toc "Attribute management"

Label Editor
------------

   Whenever you have to define a list of labels, e.g. the list of labels
for a choice attribute, the label editor comes into place.  The label
editor is a window containing:

   * a list-view displaying the current list of labels.  You can click
     on a label to make it the active one.  The active label is also
     displayed in the string field below the list-view.  You can use
     drag & drop to rearrange the labels.

   * a string field @{b}Label@{ub} that displays the active label and allows
     changing it.  The changes do only have effect after you pressed
     the @{b}Enter@{ub} key.  If there is currently no active label then
     pressing @{b}Enter@{ub} inserts new labels into the list.

   * a button @{b}New@{ub} that deactivates the current label which allows
     entering new labels into the @{b}Label@{ub} string field.

   * a button @{b}Remove@{ub} that removes the active label from the list.

   * a button @{b}Sort@{ub} for ordering the list of labels alphabetically.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the label editor.

   After you entered all labels or made changes to them, press the @{b}Ok@{ub}
button to leave the window.


@endnode

@node "Copying attributes" "MUIbase/Copying attributes"
@toc "Attribute management"

Copying Attributes
------------------

   In case you need a lot of similar attributes, it is possible to copy
an attribute.  Just select the desired attribute and press the @{b}Copy@{ub}
button below the attribute list.  This opens the @{b}Copy attribute@{ub}
requester where the settings of the selected attribute are displayed.
Change some of the fields, e.g. the name, and then press @{b}Ok@{ub} for
creating a copy of the attribute.


@endnode

@node "Changing attributes" "MUIbase/Changing attributes"
@toc "Attribute management"

Changing Attributes
-------------------

   After you have created a new attribute it is still possible to change
some settings of it.  Just double-click on the attribute's name and the
@{b}Change attribute@{ub} requester pops up.  This requester is similar to the
one when creating an attribute (see @{"Creating attributes" link "Creating attributes"}) and allows
you to make changes in some fields.  The fields that cannot be changed,
e.g. the attribute type, are displayed ghosted.

   The following notes should be taken into account when changing an
attribute.

   * The type of an attribute cannot be changed.  If you ever want to
     change the type of an attribute, it is best to create a new one of
     the desired type and copy the record contents from the old
     attribute to the new one by entering a simple MUIbase program in
     the query editor (see @{"Query editor" link "Query editor"}).

   * If you change the initial value of an attribute then only new
     records will get the new value for initializing the record.

   * For choice attributes you should be careful when changing its
     labels.  The labels are only used for displaying the choice field
     contents, internally, numbers are stored that are used as an index
     into the list of labels.  Thus, if you change the order of labels,
     you actually don't change the internal number but the label which
     is displayed for it!  Therefore you should not change the order of
     labels after you created a choice attribute.  Appending new labels
     to the end of the label list, however, doesn't make any problems.
     For a more flexible way of having a choice-like field where you
     can also change the order of labels, use a string attribute
     together with the @{b}List-view pop-up@{ub} feature (see
     @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}).

   * The referenced table of a reference attribute cannot be changed.

   When you are done with all changes, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to leave the
requester.


@endnode

@node "Deleting attributes" "MUIbase/Deleting attributes"
@toc "Attribute management"

Deleting Attributes
-------------------

   To delete an attribute, click on it's name in the structure editor's
attribute list and press the @{b}Del@{ub} button below the list.  Before the
attribute is actually deleted a safety requester pops up asking for
confirmation.  If you confirm this requester by pressing the @{b}Delete@{ub}
button, the attribute is deleted.

   A problem occurs if the attribute is used somewhere in the project's
program.  In this case the attribute can't simply be deleted but all
references to it must be removed from the program.  If the attribute
you want to delete is used in the project's program then the program
editor pops up and displays the first occurrence to this attribute.
You should now modify the program such that no references to this
attribute remain in the program.  After you removed a reference you can
jump to the next one by pressing the @{b}Compile@{ub} button.  At any point you
can still cancel the whole operation by pressing the @{b}Revert@{ub} button and
closing the program editor.


@endnode

@node "Sorting attributes" "MUIbase/Sorting attributes"
@toc "Attribute management"

Sorting Attributes
------------------

   For sorting the attributes in the @{b}Attributes@{ub} field of the structure
editor you have several choices.  You can order them manually, that is,
you use drag & drop to rearrange an attribute, or you use the @{b}Sort@{ub}
button below the list-view which orders the attributes alphabetically
(@{b}Sort1@{ub}) or according to the order in the list display (@{b}Sort2@{ub}).


@endnode

@node "Display management" "MUIbase/Display management"
@toc "Structure editor"

Display Management
==================

   In the @{b}Display@{ub} field of the structure editor you specify how the
database elements should be arranged in the user interface.  The field
consists of a choice field, a list-view and several buttons.


 @{" Display field              " link "Display field"}  Overview of the elements in the display field.
 @{" Panel editor               " link "Panel editor"}  Settings for a panel object.
 @{" Attribute object editor    " link "Attribute object editor"}  Settings for an attribute object.
 @{" Text editor                " link "Text editor"}  Settings for a text object.
 @{" Image editor               " link "Image editor"}  Settings for an image object.
 @{" Space editor               " link "Space editor"}  Settings for a space object.
 @{" Group editor               " link "Group editor"}  Settings for a group object.
 @{" Register group editor      " link "Register group editor"}  Settings for a register group object.
 @{" Window editor              " link "Window editor"}  Settings for a window object.


@endnode

@node "Display field" "MUIbase/Display field"
@toc "Display management"

Display Field
-------------

   The display field contains the following items:

   * a choice item with two settings, @{b}Table mask@{ub} and @{b}Main window@{ub}.  In
     @{b}Table mask@{ub} you specify how the attributes of the active table are
     arranged in the user interface.  In @{b}Main window@{ub} you specify how
     the tables are arranged.

   * a list-view that displays the current specification of the user
     interface.  The list is organized as a tree.  Items that have an
     arrow to its left are composite GUI objects and can be opened and
     closed by (double-) clicking on the arrow symbol.  A double-click
     on the item itself opens a window for editing its settings.  All
     GUI objects that have the same parent object are layed out in the
     same way (either vertically or horizontally).  How the layout is
     done is determined by the parent GUI object: tables, panels and
     windows layout their elements vertically, groups layout their
     elements according to the settings in the group editor (see
     @{"Group editor" link "Group editor"}).

   * a button @{b}+@{ub} (@{b}Add@{ub}) for adding the active table or the active
     attribute (depending on the state of the display choice field) to
     the display list-view.  Usually tables and attributes are added to
     the display list-view automatically when you create them.

   * a button @{b}-@{ub} (@{b}Rem@{ub}) for removing the active item from the display
     list-view.  If you remove a table then the whole table form is
     removed from the user interface, thus you can't see the table in
     the project's GUI.  This way you can hide entire tables.  If you
     remove an attribute from the display list-view then the attribute
     doesn't appear in the project's GUI.  This is useful for hiding
     attributes.

   * two buttons @{b}Up@{ub} and @{b}Down@{ub} for moving the active item one field up,
     respectively down, in the display list-view.

   * two buttons @{b}In@{ub} and @{b}Out@{ub} for moving the active item one hierarchical
     level down or up in the display list-view.

   * a button @{b}Panel@{ub} for adding a panel to the table.  See
     @{"Panel editor" link "Panel editor"}, for more information about setting up a panel.

   * a button @{b}Text@{ub} for adding a text object to the display list-view
     (see @{"Text editor" link "Text editor"}).

   * a button @{b}Image@{ub} for adding an image object (see @{"Image editor" link "Image editor"}).

   * a button @{b}Space@{ub} for putting space between the other objects (see
     @{"Space editor" link "Space editor"}).

   * a button @{b}Balance@{ub} for adding a balance object to the display
     list-view.  The balance object is useful for controlling the size
     of the other GUI objects.

   * a button @{b}Group@{ub} for adding a group object to the display list-view.
     Before you press the @{b}Group@{ub} button you can multi-select the items in
     the list-view that should be moved into the new group.  See
     @{"Group editor" link "Group editor"}, for more information about setting up a group
     object.

   * a button @{b}Register@{ub} for adding a register group to the display
     list-view.  As for group objects, you can multi-select the GUI
     objects that should be moved into the new register group.  For
     more information about setting up a register group see
     @{"Register group editor" link "Register group editor"}.

   * a button @{b}Window@{ub} for adding a new window to the display list-view.
     As before, you can multi-select the GUI objects that should be
     moved into the new window.  For more information about setting up
     a window, see @{"Window editor" link "Window editor"}.

   For more information about the GUI elements, including their usage,
see @{"User interface" link "User interface"}.


@endnode

@node "Panel editor" "MUIbase/Panel editor"
@toc "Display management"

Panel Editor
------------

   When you add a panel to a table's mask, or when you double click an
existing panel object in the display list-view, the @{b}Panel@{ub} window pops
up.  This window contains the following items:

   * a string field @{b}Title@{ub} for entering a title that should be displayed
     in the panel header.

   * a string field @{b}Font@{ub} with a pop-up button for selecting a font for
     the title.  If you leave the field empty, a default font is used.

   * a field @{b}Background@{ub} with a check-mark field @{b}Default@{ub} for specifying
     the background of the panel header.  If you check the @{b}Default@{ub}
     field then a default background is chosen.  Otherwise you can
     click on the @{b}Background@{ub} button to open a window for specifying a
     custom background.

   * a field @{b}Num/All@{ub}.  If checked the number of the current record and
     the number of all records are displayed in the right part of the
     panel header.

   * a field @{b}Filter@{ub} that, if checked, adds a filter button to the panel
     header.  With the filter button you can turn on and off the record
     filter of the table.  If you don't check this field then the menu
     item @{b}Table - Change filter@{ub} will also be disabled for this table,
     thus you can't enter a filter expression for the table.  For more
     information about record filters, see @{"Record filter" link "Record filter"}.

   * a field @{b}Arrows@{ub} for adding two arrow buttons to the table mask.
     The arrow buttons allows you to browse through the records of the
     table.  If you don't check this field then you can't browse the
     records of this table and all sub menu items of menu item @{b}Goto
     record@{ub} and the menu items @{b}Search for@{ub}, @{b}Search forward@{ub}, and @{b}Search
     backward@{ub} in menu @{b}Table@{ub} are disabled.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   After you are done with all settings, click on the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to
close the window.


@endnode

@node "Attribute object editor" "MUIbase/Attribute object editor"
@toc "Display management"

Attribute Object Editor
-----------------------

   When you add an attribute to the display list-view, a default GUI
object is created for it.  To change the settings of the attribute
object, a double click on it opens the @{b}Display attribute@{ub} window.  This
window contains several items depending on the type of the attribute.
The following items are included for most attribute types:

   * a string field @{b}Title@{ub} for entering a title that is displayed near
     the attribute object (or, for buttons, inside the object).  If you
     leave this field empty then no title is displayed.

   * a choice field @{b}Position@{ub} for specifying where the title (if any) is
     placed relative to the attribute object.  You can choose between
     @{b}Left@{ub}, @{b}Right@{ub}, @{b}Top@{ub}, and @{b}Bottom@{ub}.

   * a string field @{b}Shortcut@{ub} for entering a letter than can be used
     together with the @{b}Alt@{ub} key (Windows, Mac OS and Linux)     or the
     @{b}Amiga@{ub} key to activate the object.

   * a field @{b}Home@{ub}.  If checked, this attribute object becomes the home
     object.  The home object is used as the object where the cursor is
     set on whenever a new record is allocated.  This is quite useful
     if you always want to start entering data into the same attribute
     whenever you create a new record.  If you mark an attribute object
     as the home object then all other attribute objects in the same
     table loose this property.

   * a field @{b}Tab chain@{ub}.  If checked the object is part of the focus
     chain that can be cycled through by pressing the @{b}Tab@{ub} key.  Uncheck
     this item if you want to skip over the element.

   * a field @{b}Read only@{ub} that, if checked, gives the object a read only
     status.  This means that you can only read its contents but can't
     edit them.  Note however, that if you add a pop-up button to the
     object, the contents can still be changed by the selections
     offered in the pop-up.

   * a choice field @{b}Alignment@{ub} for specifying how the attribute contents
     should be presented in the object.  You can choose between @{b}Center@{ub},
     @{b}Left@{ub} and @{b}Right@{ub} for displaying the contents centered, flushed left,
     or flushed right.

   * an area @{b}Enabled/disabled@{ub}.  If @{b}Always enabled@{ub} is selected then the
     object is always enabled independent of the record shown.
     @{b}Disabled in initial@{ub} disables the object in the initial record but
     enables it otherwise.  If @{b}Compute enabled@{ub} is chosen then a
     function for computing the enabled state of the object can be
     entered to the right.  The function does not take any arguments.
     If it returns NIL then the object is disabled, otherwise enabled.
     In case the compute function is left empty or cannot be found, the
     object gets disabled.  For more information on how to use this
     trigger function, see @{"Compute enabled function" link "Compute enabled function"}.

   * a numerical field @{b}Weight@{ub} for specifying the weight of the object.
     The value of this field determines how much space, relatively to
     the other objects, the object gets in the final window layout.
     For most attribute types this field only affects the horizontal
     size of the object as most objects have a fixed height.  For a
     Memo attribute, for example, it also affects the vertical size.

   * a field @{b}Font@{ub} for selecting the font used for displaying the
     attribute contents.  If you leave the field empty, a default font
     is used.

   * a field @{b}Background@{ub} with a check-mark field @{b}Default@{ub} for specifying
     how the background of the attribute should look like.  If you
     check the @{b}Default@{ub} field then a default background is used,
     otherwise you can click on the @{b}Background@{ub} field to open a window
     for specifying a custom background.

   * an editor field @{b}Bubble help@{ub} where you can enter text that should
     be displayed as the bubble help information for this attribute
     object.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   If you are done with all settings, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to leave the
window.

Type Specific Settings
----------------------

   Besides the above items, the following type-specific items are
present:

   * for attributes of type string there is an @{b}Extras@{ub} page which
     contains:

        - a field @{b}Display picture@{ub} that, if checked, attaches an image
          field to the string attribute for displaying the image whose
          filename is taken from the attribute contents.  The image
          field is put above the string field.  If you don't check this
          item then the settings of the fields @{b}Title at string field@{ub},
          @{b}Hide string field@{ub}, and @{b}Size@{ub} are meaningless.

        - a field @{b}Title at string field@{ub}.  If checked, the title of the
          attribute object is placed to the left of the string field,
          thus the image field gets more space in the window.  If you
          don't check this field then the title is placed next to the
          image field.

        - a field @{b}Hide string field@{ub} for removing the string field from
          the user interface.  If checked, only the image field is
          displayed.

        - a field @{b}Size@{ub} for specifying how size-handling is done for the
          image area.  If @{b}Resizable@{ub} is active, the object can be
          resized and might become larger than the size of its image.
          @{b}Fixed@{ub} sets the object's size to the size of the image.  If
          the image sizes vary from record to record then the object is
          resized accordingly every time.  @{b}Scrollable@{ub} adds two
          scrollers to the object allowing to view images that are
          larger than the visible region.  If @{b}Scaled@{ub} is activated then
          the image is scaled to the size of the display object.
          @{b}Aspect-scaled@{ub} also scales the image but preserves its aspect
          ratio.

        - a field @{b}File pop-up@{ub} that, if checked, adds a pop-up button to
          the right of the string field.  This buttons serves to open a
          file requester for choosing a filename.

        - a field @{b}Font pop-up@{ub} for adding a pop-up button that opens a
          font requester.

        - a field @{b}List-view pop-up@{ub}.  If checked, a pop-up button is
          attached to the right of the string field for opening a
          list-view pop-up where you can choose a string from a list.
          The label strings for the list-view pop-up are defined to the
          right of the @{b}List-view pop-up@{ub} field.  The label items can be
          either @{b}Static@{ub} or @{b}Computed@{ub}.  If @{b}Static@{ub} is chosen then the list
          of strings can be entered in the label editor which is opened
          after pressing the @{b}Edit labels@{ub} button.  For more information
          about the label editor, see @{"Label editor" link "Label editor"}.  If @{b}Computed@{ub} is
          chosen then a trigger function can be entered in the @{b}Compute@{ub}
          field which is called whenever the pop-up button is pressed.
          This function should return a memo text with one label string
          per line, or NIL for an empty list (see
          @{"Compute list-view labels" link "Compute list-view labels"}).  Only one of the fields @{b}File
          pop-up@{ub}, @{b}Font pop-up@{ub} and @{b}List-view pop-up@{ub} can be made active.

        - a field @{b}View@{ub} that, if checked, adds a button to the right of
          the string field for launching an external viewer with the
          attribute contents as argument.  This can be useful if you
          store filenames in the attribute and want to display the
          contents of a file by starting an external viewer.  The
          external viewer can be specified in menu item @{b}Preferences -
          External viewer@{ub} (see @{"External viewer" link "External viewer"}).

   * for attributes of type choice there is a field @{b}Kind@{ub} where you
     choose whether the attribute contents should be displayed by a
     @{b}Cycle button@{ub} or by a set of @{b}Radio buttons@{ub}.  If you select @{b}Cycle
     button@{ub} then you can set the title position to one of @{b}Left@{ub}, @{b}Right@{ub},
     @{b}Top@{ub}, or @{b}Button@{ub}.  If you select @{b}Radio buttons@{ub} then two check mark
     items @{b}Frame@{ub} and @{b}Horizontal@{ub} allow drawing a border around the radio
     buttons and specifying a horizontal layout.

   * for attributes of type real there is an integer field @{b}Num decimals@{ub}
     where you can enter the number of decimals for displaying the
     floating point values.

   * for attributes of type time there is a choice field @{b}Format@{ub} for
     choosing how time values are displayed and entered.  You can
     select between @{b}HH:MM:SS@{ub}, @{b}MM:SS@{ub} and @{b}HH:MM@{ub}.  If @{b}HH:MM@{ub} is chosen, the
     number of seconds are discarded for display and single numbers on
     input are regarded as the number of minutes.

   * for reference attributes there is an @{b}Extras@{ub} page that contains the
     following items:

        - a list-view field @{b}Display@{ub} where you specify which contents of
          a referenced record should be displayed.  You can
          multi-select several items in this list.  If you select
          @{b}Record number@{ub} than the record number of a referenced record
          is included in the display.  The other items are the names of
          attributes in the referenced table.  You can rearrange the
          order of items by drag and drop.

        - an area @{b}Pop-up@{ub} where you specify which records of the
          referenced table should be made available for selection in
          the pop-up of the reference field and how they should be
          displayed.  If @{b}Records@{ub} is set to @{b}All@{ub} then all records are
          available.  If @{b}Records@{ub} is set to @{b}Match filter@{ub} then only the
          records of the referenced table that match the currently
          installed filter are available.  If @{b}Records@{ub} is set to
          @{b}Computed@{ub} then a function for computing the set of records can
          be entered in the @{b}Compute@{ub} field.  This trigger function
          should return a list that is searched for the occurrence of
          records of the referenced table.  Any such record found is
          shown in the pop-up.  Non-record items are ignored.  See
          @{"Compute reference records" link "Compute reference records"}, for more information about this
          function.  In addition to the records specified by the
          @{b}Records@{ub} setting, the initial record and the currently shown
          record in the referenced table can be added to the pop-up
          list by activating the @{b}Initial record@{ub} and @{b}Current record@{ub}
          items respectively.  The item @{b}Use multi-column list@{ub} decides
          whether the fields selected in the @{b}Display@{ub} list are shown in
          multiple columns, or if the items are concatenated by a
          separation character @{b}-@{ub}.

        - an area @{b}Quick search@{ub} where you specify how the keyboard
          type-ahead search for the reference item should be performed.
          Quick search allows to find entries in the referenced table
          when the reference field or the associated popup list view is
          the active object (see @{"Changing records" link "Changing records"}).  If @{b}Disabled@{ub} is
          selected then no searching is performed and any key presses
          are simply ignored.  Choosing @{b}In first order field@{ub} searches
          only in the attribute that has been specified as the first
          one for ordering the referenced table (see
          @{"Order by attributes" link "Order by attributes"}).  If @{b}In all fields@{ub} is active then
          searching is performed in all fields of the referenced table.
          Finally, in @{b}Prefix search only@{ub} you specify whether a found
          entry has to start with the search pattern, or if the search
          pattern can appear anywhere in a field.  Default is prefix
          search in the first order field as this kind of search can be
          performed quite efficiently.

        - a field @{b}Show@{ub}.  If checked then the GUI object for displaying
          the reference is created as a button.  Clicking on this
          button will show you the referenced record in the table mask
          of the referenced table.  For this the window the referenced
          table resides in is opened and brought to front if necessary.

        - a field @{b}Auto show@{ub} that, if checked, adds a button to the right
          of the reference field for turning auto show mode on and off
          for this attribute.  When turned on, the referenced table
          gets updated automatically with the referenced record
          whenever the user switches to another record.

        - a field @{b}Filter@{ub} that, if checked, adds a button to the right
          of the reference field for turning on and off the reference
          filter for this attribute.  See @{"Reference filter" link "Reference filter"}, for more
          information about reference filters.

   * for virtual attributes the attribute object editor contains an
     @{b}Extras@{ub} page with the following items:

        - a choice field @{b}Kind@{ub} where you specify how the contents of the
          virtual attribute should be displayed.  You can choose
          between @{b}Boolean@{ub} that uses a check-mark field for displaying
          Boolean values, @{b}Text@{ub} that uses a text field for displaying one
          line of text (including date, time, and numerical values),
          and @{b}List@{ub} which uses a list-view for displaying a list of
          lines (e.g. the result of a select-from-where query).

        - if you set the @{b}Kind@{ub} field to @{b}Text@{ub} then two further fields are
          available: @{b}Alignment@{ub} for specifying how the attribute
          contents should be presented and @{b}Num decimals@{ub} for entering
          the number of decimals that should be used if the attribute
          contents are of type real.

        - if the @{b}Kind@{ub} field has been set to @{b}List@{ub} then further fields
          @{b}Show titles@{ub}, @{b}Tab chain@{ub} and @{b}On double click@{ub} are available.  If
          @{b}Show titles@{ub} is checked, the first line of the attribute
          contents is displayed as a title row in the list-view.
          Otherwise no title row is displayed and the first line is
          ignored.  If @{b}Tab chain@{ub} is checked, the object is part of the
          focus chain that can be cycled through by pressing the @{b}Tab@{ub}
          key.  Uncheck this item if you want to skip over the element.
          In @{b}On double click@{ub} you can specify which action should take
          place when the user double-clicks a list item.  @{b}Do nothing@{ub}
          ignores the double click. @{b}Show record@{ub} displays the record
          corresponding to the clicked item in the corresponding table
          view.  If you select @{b}Call trigger@{ub} then the name of a trigger
          function can be entered to the right.  This trigger function
          is called on each double click.  For more information about
          the trigger function, including the arguments that are passed
          to it, see @{"Double click trigger" link "Double click trigger"}.

        - a field @{b}Auto update@{ub}.  If checked, the virtual attribute is
          recomputed automatically whenever a dependent item changes.
          This includes switching to a different record in a dependent
          table, changing a dependent attribute, adding or deleting a
          record in a dependent table, changing the user/admin mode of
          the project, or recompiling the project program.  The
          dependencies for the virtual attribute are obtained
          automatically from the virtual attribute's compute function.
          Use menu item @{b}Project - Export structure@{ub} for viewing all
          obtained dependencies (you might need to recompile the
          project's program in order to update the dependencies when
          you turn this feature on).  Note that the virtual attribute
          is recomputed irrespective of the record a dependent
          attribute is changed in and irrespective of whether the
          dependent attribute's value was changed in the user interface
          or during a program execution.  However, the auto-updating of
          virtual attributes usually happens only after all other
          program executions are completed.  If @{b}Auto update@{ub} is
          unchecked, the value of the virtual attribute is only
          computed when it is explicitly queried or set in a program
          function.

   * For buttons there are the following additional fields:

        - a choice field @{b}Kind@{ub} where you choose between @{b}Text button@{ub} and
          @{b}Image button@{ub}.

        - if you set the button kind to @{b}Text button@{ub} then further fields
          @{b}Title@{ub}, @{b}Font@{ub}, @{b}Background@{ub} and @{b}Default@{ub} appear for entering the
          text to be displayed in the button, the font used for
          displaying the text, and the background settings.

        - if the button kind has been set to @{b}Image button@{ub} then a field
          @{b}Image@{ub} for specifying the image to be displayed and a field
          @{b}Size@{ub} for specifying the size-handling of the image button are
          offered.


@endnode

@node "Text editor" "MUIbase/Text editor"
@toc "Display management"

Text Editor
-----------

   When you add a text object to the display list-view, or when you
change one by double clicking on it, a window @{b}Text@{ub} is opened.  This
window contains the following items:

   * a string field @{b}Title@{ub} for entering the text that should be
     displayed.

   * a numerical field @{b}Weight@{ub} for specifying the horizontal weight of
     the text object.

   * a choice field @{b}Font@{ub} for specifying the font of the text.  If you
     leave this field empty, a default font is used.

   * two fields @{b}Background@{ub} and @{b}Default@{ub} for specifying the background
     settings of the text object.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   When you are done with all settings, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to leave
the window.


@endnode

@node "Image editor" "MUIbase/Image editor"
@toc "Display management"

Image Editor
------------

   The image editor appears when you add a new image object or double
click on an existing one.  It contains the following items:

   * a field @{b}Weight@{ub} for specifying the weight of the image object in
     the final window layout.

   * a field @{b}Image@{ub} for specifying the image that should be displayed.

   * a field @{b}Size@{ub} where you specify how resize-handling should be done.
     If you select @{b}Resizable@{ub} then the image object can be resized.
     @{b}Fixed@{ub} sets the object size to the size of the displayed image.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   When you are done with all settings, click on the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to close
the window.


@endnode

@node "Space editor" "MUIbase/Space editor"
@toc "Display management"

Space Editor
------------

   After you have added a space object to the display list-view, you can
change its default settings by double clicking on it.  This will open
the @{b}Space@{ub} window containing the following items:

   * a field @{b}Delimiter@{ub} that, if checked, displays a vertical or
     horizontal bar (depending on the layout of the parent object) in
     the center of the space object.  This is useful for separating
     parts in the window layout.

   * a numerical field @{b}Weight@{ub} for specifying the weight of the object.

   * two fields @{b}Background@{ub} and @{b}Default@{ub} for specifying the background
     settings.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   After you are done with all settings, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to close
the window.


@endnode

@node "Group editor" "MUIbase/Group editor"
@toc "Display management"

Group Editor
------------

   After you have added a group object to the display list-view, you
can change its settings by double clicking on it.  This will open the
@{b}Group@{ub} window offering the following items:

   * a string field @{b}Title@{ub} for entering a title string that should be
     displayed centered above the group.  If you leave this field empty
     then no title is displayed.

   * a numerical field @{b}Weight@{ub} for specifying the weight of this object.

   * two fields @{b}Background@{ub} and @{b}Default@{ub} for specifying the background
     settings.

   * a field @{b}Border@{ub} that, if activated, draws a border frame around the
     group.

   * a field @{b}Horizontal@{ub}.  If checked, the layout of the group is done
     horizontally and the group is listed in the display list-view as
     @{b}HGroup@{ub}.  Otherwise the group is organized vertically and the
     display list-view will show a @{b}VGroup@{ub} for this group.

   * a field @{b}Spacing@{ub} that, if checked, adds some space between the
     group's child objects.  Otherwise no space is put between the
     objects.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   When you are done with all settings, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to leave
the window.


@endnode

@node "Register group editor" "MUIbase/Register group editor"
@toc "Display management"

Register Group Editor
---------------------

   Double click on a register group object in order to change its
settings.  This will open the @{b}Register group@{ub} window offering the
following items:

   * a numerical field @{b}Weight@{ub} for specifying the weight of this object.

   * an area @{b}Labels@{ub} for specifying the label of each register page.
     You should specify exactly the same number of labels as there are
     elements in the register group.  For more information on how to
     enter and edit the labels, see @{"Label editor" link "Label editor"}.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   When you are done with all settings, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to leave
the window.


@endnode

@node "Window editor" "MUIbase/Window editor"
@toc "Display management"

Window Editor
-------------

   To change the settings of a window object, double click the window
object.  This will open the window editor containing the following
items:

   * a string field @{b}Title@{ub} where you enter a string that should be
     displayed in the window title bar and in the optional window
     button.

   * a string field @{b}Id@{ub} (Amiga only) which can hold up to four
     characters defining the MUI window id.  If an id is entered, the
     window position and size can be saved using MUI's snapshot window
     facility.  Note that all ids defined within MUIbase should be
     unique.  If you accidentally reuse an already taken id then the
     windows will share the same settings for their window dimensions.
     Ids beginning with an underscore @{b}_@{ub} are reserved for internal use.
     If you leave the field empty then no MUI window id is set and the
     window dimensions are stored in the project file.  The main window
     always has the first four characters of the project name as its
     window id.  Specifying an window id is useful if a project is
     edited under different system configurations as the window
     positions are then taken from the individual configuration.

   * a field @{b}Button@{ub} that, if checked, places a button for opening the
     window into the parent window.  If this item is not checked then
     the window can only be opened from a MUIbase program using the
     SETWINDOWOPEN function (see @{"SETWINDOWOPEN" link "SETWINDOWOPEN"}).  The following items
     specify the appearance of the window button.

   * a string field @{b}Shortcut@{ub} where you enter the shortcut for
     activating the window button.

   * an area @{b}Enabled/disabled@{ub}.  If @{b}Always enabled@{ub} is selected then the
     window button is always enabled.  @{b}Disabled in initial@{ub} disables the
     button if it is inside a table and the table shows its initial
     record, otherwise it is enabled.  If @{b}Compute enabled@{ub} is chosen
     then a function for computing the enabled state of the window
     button can be entered to the right.  The function does not take
     any arguments.  If it returns NIL then the button is disabled,
     otherwise enabled.  In case the compute function is left empty or
     cannot be found, the window button gets disabled.  For more
     information on how to use this trigger function, see
     @{"Compute enabled function" link "Compute enabled function"}.  Additionally if the field @{b}Close
     window when disabled@{ub} is checked then the window is closed
     automatically when the button gets disabled.

   * a numerical field @{b}Weight@{ub} for specifying the weight of the window
     button.

   * a field @{b}Font@{ub} for selecting the font of the window button.  If you
     leave the field empty, a default font is used.

   * two fields @{b}Background@{ub} and @{b}Default@{ub} for specifying the background
     settings of the window button.

   * two buttons @{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} for leaving the window.

   When you are done with all settings, press the @{b}Ok@{ub} button to close
the window.


@endnode

@node "Export structure" "MUIbase/Export structure"
@toc "Structure editor"

Export Structure
================

   Sometimes it is useful to get an overview of all tables and
attributes of a project, e.g. when you want to write a MUIbase program.
You can do this by selecting menu item @{b}Project - Export structure@{ub}.
This will ask you for a filename where the list of tables and attributes
should be written to.

   The output will first list the project name, followed by all tables
in this project.  For each table all attributes including their types
and their optional trigger functions are listed.  For virtual
attributes also the dependencies for automatically updating the value
of the virtual field are listed.


@endnode

@node "Programming MUIbase" "MUIbase/Programming MUIbase"
@toc "Main"

Programming MUIbase
*******************

   This chapter (the largest in this manual) describes the programming
language of MUIbase, including all available functions.  This chapter,
however, is not intended as a general guide about programming.  You
should be familiar with the basics about programming and should already
have written some small (and correctly working :-)) programs.


 @{" Program editor             " link "Program editor"}  Where to enter a MUIbase program.
 @{" External program source    " link "External program source"}  Using your favorite editor for programming.
 @{" Preprocessing              " link "Preprocessing"}  Includes, conditional compilation, and constants.
 @{" Programming language       " link "Programming language"}  The syntax of expressions.

Functions

 @{" Defining commands          " link "Defining commands"}  Function and variable definitions.
 @{" Program control functions  " link "Program control functions"}  Loops, conditional expressions, and more.
 @{" Type predicates            " link "Type predicates"}  Examining the type of an expression.
 @{" Type conversion functions  " link "Type conversion functions"}  Converting types.
 @{" Boolean functions          " link "Boolean functions"}  AND, OR, and NOT.
 @{" Comparison functions       " link "Comparison functions"}  Comparing values of expressions.
 @{" Mathematical functions     " link "Mathematical functions"}  Adding, Multiplying, etc.
 @{" String functions           " link "String functions"}  Useful stuff for strings.
 @{" Memo functions             " link "Memo functions"}  Useful stuff for memos.
 @{" Date and time functions    " link "Date and time functions"}  Useful stuff for date and time values.
 @{" List functions             " link "List functions"}  List processing commands.
 @{" Input requesting functions " link "Input requesting functions"}  Asking the user for input.
 @{" I-O functions              " link "I-O functions"}  File input and output commands.
 @{" Record functions           " link "Record functions"}  Useful stuff for records.
 @{" Attribute functions        " link "Attribute functions"}  Manipulating attributes.
 @{" Table functions            " link "Table functions"}  Manipulating tables.
 @{" GUI functions              " link "GUI functions"}  Manipulating the user interface.
 @{" Project functions          " link "Project functions"}  Getting information about the project.
 @{" System functions           " link "System functions"}  Operating system related functions.
 @{" Variables                  " link "Pre-defined variables"}  Pre-defined variables.
 @{" Constants                  " link "Pre-defined constants"}  Pre-defined constant values.

Useful information

 @{" Functional parameters      " link "Functional parameters"}  Using functions as arguments in function calls.
 @{" Type specifiers            " link "Type specifiers"}  Types for variables.
 @{" Semantics of expressions   " link "Semantics of expressions"}  The meaning of an expression.
 @{" Function triggering        " link "Function triggering"}  How to use trigger functions.
 @{" List of obsolete functions " link "List of obsolete functions"}  Functions that disappeared and need replacement.

 @{" Function index             " link "Function index"}  Index of all functions.


@endnode

@node "Program editor" "MUIbase/Program editor"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Program Editor
==============

   To enter a program for a project, open the program editor by
selecting menu item @{b}Program - Edit@{ub}.  If you are using the setting
program source internal (see @{"Program source" link "Program source"}), this will open the @{b}Edit
program@{ub} window containing:

   * a text editor field where you edit the project program.

   * a button @{b}Compile & close@{ub} for compiling the program and, on
     successful compilation, leaving the program editor.

   * a button @{b}Compile@{ub} to compile the program.  If your program contains
     an error somewhere then an error description is put into the
     window title and the cursor is set on the faulty location.

   * a button @{b}Revert@{ub} that reverts all changes since the last successful
     compilation.

   The program editor is a non-modal window.  You can leave the window
open and still work with the rest of the application.  You can close
the editor at any time by clicking into its window close button.  If
you have done changes since the last successful compilation then a
safety requester pops-up asking for confirmation to close the window.

   In case you have set menu item @{b}Program - Source@{ub} to @{b}External@{ub} the
external editor (see @{"External editor" link "External editor"}) is launched with the filename of
the external source file when choosing @{b}Program - Edit@{ub}.  This allows you
to edit the program source using your favorite editor (see
@{"External program source" link "External program source"}).

   You can also compile a project's program without opening the program
editor by choosing menu item @{b}Program - Compile@{ub}.  This can be useful if
you e.g. do changes to an external include file and want to incorporate
these changes in the project's program.


@endnode

@node "External program source" "MUIbase/External program source"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

External program source
=======================

   By choosing menu item @{b}Program - Source - External@{ub} and entering a
filename you can make the program source of a project externally
available.  This allows you to load the program source into your
favorite editor for programming.

   If compilation is successful, the compiled program is set as the
project's program and used when executing trigger functions.  When you
save a project, the last successfully compiled program is store with
the project inside the project file.  Thus, after saving and closing a
project, the external source is no longer needed actually.  You can
specify if unneeded external source files should be deleted
automatically by checking menu item @{b}Preferences - Cleanup external
program source@{ub}.

   The status of menu item @{b}Program - source@{ub} is stored with the project.
If you re-open a project that uses the external source feature, the
external source file is created after opening the project.  If the
external source file already exists and is different from the version
stored inside the project, a safety requester asks for confirmation
before overwriting the file.

   On the Amiga you can send the @{b}compile@{ub} command to MUIbase' ARexx port
from your editor.  MUIbase then reads the external program source,
compiles it, and returns the compile status with an optional error
message containing filename, line and column, and an error description.
This allows you to place the cursor at the exact location of where a
compile error occurred.  See @{"ARexx compile" link "ARexx compile"}, for details on return
values and error format.


@endnode

@node "Preprocessing" "MUIbase/Preprocessing"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Preprocessing
=============

   MUIbase programs are pre-processed similar to a C compiler
preprocessing a C source file.  This section describes how to use the
preprocessing directives.

   All directives start with a hash symbol @{b}#@{ub} which should be the first
character on a line.  Space or tab characters can appear after the
initial @{b}#@{ub}.


 @{" #define            " link "#define"}  Defining constants.
 @{" #undef             " link "#undef"}  Un-defining constants.
 @{" #include           " link "#include"}  Including external files.
 @{" #if                " link "#if"}  Conditional compilation.
 @{" #ifdef             " link "#ifdef"}  Conditional compilation.
 @{" #ifndef            " link "#ifndef"}  Conditional compilation.
 @{" #elif              " link "#elif"}  Conditional compilation.
 @{" #else              " link "#else"}  Conditional compilation.
 @{" #endif             " link "#endif"}  Conditional compilation.


@endnode

@node "#define" "MUIbase/#define"
@toc "Preprocessing"

#define
-------

@{b}     #define@{ub} NAME STRING

   Defines a new symbol with the given name and contents.  The symbol
STRING can be any text including spaces and ends at the end of line.
If STRING does not fit on one line you can use further lines by using a
backslash character @{b}\\ @{ub} at the end of each line (except for the last
one).  If the symbol NAME does occur in the remaining source code then
it will be replaced by the contents of STRING.

   Example: @{b}(PRINTF "X is %i" X)@{ub} prints @{b}X is 1@{ub} (Occurrences of NAME in
strings are not altered.)

   The replacement of defined symbols is done syntactically which means
that you can replace symbols with any text, e.g. you can define your
own syntax like in the following example:

     #define BEGIN (
     #define END )
     
     BEGIN defun test ()
             ...
     END

   The replacement string of a definition may contain another symbol
that has been defined with the @{b}#define@{ub} directive to allow nested
definitions.  However there is an upper limit of 16 nested definitions.

   See also @{"#undef" link "#undef"}, @{"#ifdef" link "#ifdef"}, @{"#ifndef" link "#ifndef"}.


@endnode

@node "#undef" "MUIbase/#undef"
@toc "Preprocessing"

#undef
------

@{b}     #undef@{ub} NAME

   Removes the definition of symbol NAME.  If NAME has not been defined,
nothing happens.

   See also @{"#define" link "#define"}, @{"#ifdef" link "#ifdef"}, @{"#ifndef" link "#ifndef"}.


@endnode

@node "#include" "MUIbase/#include"
@toc "Preprocessing"

#include
--------

@{b}     #include@{ub} FILENAME

   Reads in the contents of FILENAME (a string surrounded with double
quotes) at this location.  MUIbase searches in the current directory and
in the directory specified in the preferences (see
@{"Program include directory" link "Program include directory"}) for loading the file.  The file contents
are processed by the compiler as if they were part of the current
source code.

   An external file may include one or more other external files.
However there is an limit of 16 nested @{b}#include@{ub} directives.  To protect
files from including them more than once, you can use conditional
compilation.

   Be careful when moving source code to external files!  Debugging and
tracking down errors is much harder for external files.  Move only well
tested and project independent code to external files.


@endnode

@node "#if" "MUIbase/#if"
@toc "Preprocessing"

#if
---

@{b}     #if@{ub} CONST-EXPR

   If the given constant expression results to non-NIL then the text up
to the matching @{b}#else@{ub}, @{b}#elif@{ub}, or @{b}#endif@{ub} is used for compilation,
otherwise (the expression results to NIL) the text up to the matching
@{b}#else@{ub}, @{b}#elif@{ub}, or @{b}#endif@{ub} is discarded for compilation.

   Currently you can only use TRUE and NIL as constant expressions.

   See also @{"#ifdef" link "#ifdef"}, @{"#ifndef" link "#ifndef"}, @{"#elif" link "#elif"}, @{"#else" link "#else"}, @{"#endif" link "#endif"}.


@endnode

@node "#ifdef" "MUIbase/#ifdef"
@toc "Preprocessing"

#ifdef
------

@{b}     #ifdef@{ub} NAME

   If the given symbol has been defined with a @{b}#define@{ub} directive then
the text up to the matching @{b}#else@{ub}, @{b}#elif@{ub}, or @{b}#endif@{ub} is used for
compilation, otherwise it is discarded.

   See also @{"#if" link "#if"}, @{"#ifndef" link "#ifndef"}, @{"#elif" link "#elif"}, @{"#else" link "#else"}, @{"#endif" link "#endif"}.


@endnode

@node "#ifndef" "MUIbase/#ifndef"
@toc "Preprocessing"

#ifndef
-------

@{b}     #ifndef@{ub} NAME

   If the given symbol has not been defined with a @{b}#define@{ub} directive
then the text up to the matching @{b}#else@{ub}, @{b}#elif@{ub}, or @{b}#endif@{ub} is used for
compilation, otherwise it is discarded.

   See also @{"#if" link "#if"}, @{"#ifdef" link "#ifdef"}, @{"#elif" link "#elif"}, @{"#else" link "#else"}, @{"#endif" link "#endif"}.


@endnode

@node "#elif" "MUIbase/#elif"
@toc "Preprocessing"

#elif
-----

@{b}     #elif@{ub} CONST-EXPR

   Any number of @{b}#elif@{ub} directives may appear between an @{b}#if@{ub}, @{b}#ifdef@{ub}, or
@{b}#ifndef@{ub} directive and a matching @{b}#else@{ub} or @{b}#endif@{ub} directive.  The lines
following the @{b}#elif@{ub} directive are used for compilation only if all of
the following conditions hold:

   * The constant expression in the preceding #if directive evaluated
     to NIL, the symbol name in the preceding #ifdef is not defined, or
     the symbol name in the preceding #ifndef directive was defined.

   * The constant expression in all intervening #elif directives
     evaluated to NIL.

   * The current constant expression evaluates to non-NIL.

   If the above conditions hold then subsequent @{b}#elif@{ub} and @{b}#else@{ub}
directives are ignored up to the matching @{b}#endif@{ub}.

   See also @{"#if" link "#if"}, @{"#ifdef" link "#ifdef"}, @{"#ifndef" link "#ifndef"}, @{"#else" link "#else"}, @{"#endif" link "#endif"}.


@endnode

@node "#else" "MUIbase/#else"
@toc "Preprocessing"

#else
-----

@{b}     #else@{ub}

   This inverts the sense of the conditional directive otherwise in
effect.  If the preceding conditional would indicate that lines are to
be included, then lines between the @{b}#else@{ub} and the matching @{b}#endif@{ub} are
ignored.  If the preceding conditional indicates that lines would be
ignored, subsequent lines are included for compilation.

   Conditional directives and corresponding @{b}#else@{ub} directives can be
nested.  However there is a maximum nesting count limit of 16 nested
conditional directives

   See also @{"#if" link "#if"}, @{"#ifdef" link "#ifdef"}, @{"#ifndef" link "#ifndef"}, @{"#elif" link "#elif"}, @{"#endif" link "#endif"}.


@endnode

@node "#endif" "MUIbase/#endif"
@toc "Preprocessing"

#endif
------

@{b}     #endif@{ub}

   Ends a section of lines begun by one of the conditional directives
@{b}#if@{ub}, @{b}#ifdef@{ub}, or @{b}#ifndef@{ub}.  Each such directive must have a matching
@{b}#endif@{ub}.

   See also @{"#if" link "#if"}, @{"#ifdef" link "#ifdef"}, @{"#ifndef" link "#ifndef"}, @{"#elif" link "#elif"}, @{"#else" link "#else"}.


@endnode

@node "Programming language" "MUIbase/Programming language"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Programming Language
====================

   MUIbase uses a programming language with a lisp-like syntax. Indeed
several constructs and functions have been adopted from standard lisp.
However, MUIbase is not fully compatible to standard lisp.  Many
functions are missing (e.g. destructive commands) and the meaning of
some commands is different (e.g. the @{b}return@{ub} command).


 @{" Why lisp?                          " link "Why lisp?"}  The advantages of lisp.
 @{" Lisp syntax                        " link "Lisp syntax"}  Syntax of programming language.
 @{" Kinds of programs                  " link "Kinds of programs"}  Different kinds of programs used in MUIbase.
 @{" Name conventions                   " link "Name conventions"}  Name conventions for program symbols.
 @{" Accessing record contents          " link "Accessing record contents"}  Using attributes and tables in programs.
 @{" Data types for programming         " link "Data types for programming"}  Available data types for programming.
 @{" Constants                          " link "Constants"}  Constant expressions.
 @{" Command syntax                     " link "Command syntax"}  Syntax for describing all commands.


@endnode

@node "Why lisp?" "MUIbase/Why lisp?"
@toc "Programming language"

Why Lisp?
---------

   The advantage of a lisp-like language is that you can program in
both, a functional and an imperative way.  Functional languages are
getting quite popular in mathematical applications.  The basic concept
in functional languages is the use of expressions.  Functions are
defined in a mathematical way and recursion is used heavily.

   Imperative programming languages (e.g. C, Pascal, Modula) use an
imperative description on how to compute things.  Here, the state is
the basic concept (e.g. variables) and a program computes its output by
going from one state to another (e.g. by assigning values to variables).

   Lisp combines both techniques and therefore you can choose in which
way you want to implement things.  Use the one which is more
appropriate for the specific problem or which you like more.


@endnode

@node "Lisp syntax" "MUIbase/Lisp syntax"
@toc "Programming language"

Lisp Syntax
-----------

   A lisp expression is either a constant, a variable, or a function
application.  For calling functions, lisp uses a prefix notation.  The
function and its arguments are surrounded by parenthesis.  For example,
to add two values @{b}a@{ub} and @{b}b@{ub}, you write

     (+ a b)

   All expressions return a value, e.g. in the above example the sum of
@{b}a@{ub} and @{b}b@{ub} returned.  Expressions can be nested, that is, you can place an
expression as a sub-expression into another one.

   Function evaluation is done by using a call-by-value scheme, this
means that the arguments are evaluated first before a function is
called.

   If not stated otherwise, all functions are strict, that is, @{i}all@{ui}
arguments of a function are evaluated before the function is called.
Some functions, however, are non-strict, e.g. @{b}IF@{ub}, @{b}AND@{ub} and @{b}OR@{ub}.  These
functions may not evaluate all arguments.


@endnode

@node "Kinds of programs" "MUIbase/Kinds of programs"
@toc "Programming language"

Kinds of Programs
-----------------

   MUIbase knows three kinds of programs.  The first one is the project
program kind.  In a program of this kind you can define functions and
global variables.  The functions can be used as trigger functions for
attributes.  You define a project program in the program editor (see
@{"Program editor" link "Program editor"}).

   The second kind is the query program kind. For this kind you can
enter expressions only.  An expression is allowed to contain global
variables and calls to functions that are defined in the project
program.  However, you cannot define new global variables or functions
in a query program.  Query programs are entered in the query editor
(see @{"Query editor" link "Query editor"}).

   The third kind of programs are filter expressions.  Here you can
only enter expressions that contain calls to pre-defined MUIbase
functions.  Not all pre-defined functions are available, only those
that don't have a side effect, e.g. you cannot use a function that
writes data to a file.  Filter expressions are entered in the change
filter requester (see @{"Changing filters" link "Changing filters"}).


@endnode

@node "Name conventions" "MUIbase/Name conventions"
@toc "Programming language"

Name Conventions
----------------

   In a MUIbase program you can define symbols like functions and local
or global variables.  The names of these symbols must follow the
following conventions:

   * the first character of a name must be a lowercase letter.  This
     distinguishes program symbols from table and attribute names.

   * The following characters can be any letters, digits or underscore
     characters.  Other characters like German umlauts are not allowed.


@endnode

@node "Accessing record contents" "MUIbase/Accessing record contents"
@toc "Programming language"

Accessing Record Contents
-------------------------

   To access tables and attributes in a MUIbase program, you have to
specify a path to them.  A path is a dot separated list of components
where each component is the name of a table or an attribute.

   Paths can either be relative or absolute.  Absolute paths are
specified with a table name as the first component, followed by a list
of attributes that lead to the final attribute you want to access.
E.g. the absolute path @{b}Person.Name@{ub} accesses the @{b}Name@{ub} attribute in the
current record of table @{b}Person@{ub}, or the absolute path @{b}Person.Father.Name@{ub}
accesses the @{b}Name@{ub} attribute in the record referenced by the @{b}Father@{ub}
field (a reference attribute to table @{b}Person@{ub}).

   Relative paths already have a current table to which they are
relative. For example in a filter expression the current table is the
table for which you write the filter expression.  The relative path for
an attribute in the current table is simply the attribute name itself.
For attributes that are not directly accessible from the current table
but indirectly via a reference attribute, the same rules as for
absolute paths apply.

   It is not always clear if a specified path is a relative or an
absolute one, e.g.  suppose you are writing a filter expression for a
table @{b}Foo@{ub} that has an attribute @{b}Bar@{ub} and there also exists a table @{b}Bar@{ub}.
Now entering @{b}Bar@{ub} would be ambiguous, what is meant, the table or the
attribute?  Therefore all paths are first treated as relative ones.  If
no attribute is found for the specified path than the path is treated
as global. In our example the attribute would be preferred.

   But now, what if you want to access the table in the above example?
Therefore the path must be given absolute.  To indicate that a path is
global you have to insert two colons in front of the path.  In our
example you would have to type @{b}::Bar@{ub} for accessing the table.

   To give you a better understanding of paths and their semantics,
consider in our example that the @{b}Bar@{ub} attribute in the @{b}Foo@{ub} table is a
reference to the @{b}Bar@{ub} table, and the @{b}Bar@{ub} table has an attribute @{b}Name@{ub}.
Now you can access the @{b}Name@{ub} attribute by typing @{b}Bar.Name@{ub} or @{b}::Bar.Name@{ub}.
Both expressions have a different meaning.  @{b}::Bar.Name@{ub} means to take
the current record of table @{b}Bar@{ub} and return the value of the @{b}Name@{ub}
attribute of this record, whereas @{b}Bar.Name@{ub} takes the current record of
table @{b}Foo@{ub}, extracts the record reference of the @{b}Bar@{ub} field and uses this
record for getting the value of the @{b}Name@{ub} attribute.

   To make a more complete example, consider that table @{b}Bar@{ub} has two
records.  One that contains @{b}Ralph@{ub} and one that contains @{b}Steffen@{ub} in the
@{b}Name@{ub} field.  The first record should be the current one.  Furthermore
table @{b}Foo@{ub} has one record (the current one) whose @{b}Bar@{ub} field refers to
the second record of table @{b}Bar@{ub}.  Now @{b}::Bar.Name@{ub} results to @{b}Ralph@{ub} and
@{b}Bar.Name@{ub} to @{b}Steffen@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Data types for programming" "MUIbase/Data types for programming"
@toc "Programming language"

Data Types for Programming
--------------------------

   The programming language of MUIbase knows of the following data
types:

@{b}Type@{ub}        @{b}Description@{ub}

Boolean     all expressions. Non-NIL expressions are treated as TRUE.

Integer     long integer, 32 bit, choice values are automatically
            converted to integers

Real        double, 64 bit

String      strings of arbitrary length

Memo        like strings but line oriented format

Date        date values

Time        time values

Record      pointer to a record

File        file descriptor for reading/writing

List        list of items, NIL is empty list.

   All programming types support the NIL value.


@endnode

@node "Constants" "MUIbase/Constants"
@toc "Programming language"

Constants
---------

   The programming language of MUIbase can handle constant expressions
which can be entered depending on the type of the expression:

@{b}Type@{ub}        @{b}Description@{ub}

Integer     Integer constants in the range of -2147483648 to
            2147483647 can be specified as usual.  Values
            starting with 0 are interpreted as octal numbers,
            values starting with 0x as hexadecimal numbers.

Real        Floating point constants in the range of -3.59e308
            to 3.59e308 can be specified as usual, in scientific
            or non-scientific format.  If you omit the decimal
            point then the number may not be treated as a real
            number but as an integer instead.

String      String constants are any character strings surrounded
            by double quotes, e.g. "sample string".  Within the
            double quotes you can enter any characters except
            control characters or new lines.  However there are
            special escape codes for entering such characters:

                \\n              new line (nl)
                \\t              horizontal tabulator (ht)
                \\v              vertical tabulator (vt)
                \\b              backspace (bs)
                \\r              carriage return (cr)
                \\f              form feed (ff)
                \\\\              backslash character itself
                \\"              double quote
                \\e              escape code 033
                \\NNN            character with octal code NNN
                \\xNN            character with hex code NN

Memo        Same as string constants.

Date        Constant date values can be specified in one of the
            formats @{b}DD.MM.YYYY@{ub}, @{b}MM/DD/YYYY@{ub}, or @{b}YYYY-MM-DD@{ub}, where
            @{b}DD@{ub}, @{b}MM@{ub} and @{b}YYYY@{ub} are standing for two and four digit
            values representing the day, month and year of the
            date respectively.

Time        Constant time values can be entered in the format
            @{b}HH:MM:SS@{ub}, where @{b}HH@{ub} represent the hours,
            @{b}MM@{ub} the minutes, and @{b}SS@{ub} the seconds.

   For some other pre-defined constant values, see
@{"Pre-defined constants" link "Pre-defined constants"}.


@endnode

@node "Command syntax" "MUIbase/Command syntax"
@toc "Programming language"

Command Syntax
--------------

   In the remainder of this chapter, you will find the description of
all commands and functions available for programming MUIbase.  The
following syntax is used for describing the commands:

   * text written in brackets @{b}[]@{ub} is optional.  If you omit the text
     inside the brackets then a default value is assumed.

   * text separated by a vertical bar @{b}|@{ub} denotes several options, e.g. @{b}a
     | b@{ub} means that you can specify either @{b}a@{ub} or @{b}b@{ub}.

   * text written in a font like VAR indicates a place-holder that can
     be filled with other expressions.

   * dots ... indicate that further expressions can follow.

   * all other text is obligatory.


@endnode

@node "Defining commands" "MUIbase/Defining commands"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Defining Commands
=================

   This section lists commands for defining functions and global
variables.  The commands are only available for project programs.


 @{" DEFUN      " link "DEFUN"}  Function definition.
 @{" DEFUN*     " link "DEFUN*"}  Function definition with hidden name.
 @{" DEFVAR     " link "DEFVAR"}  Global variable definition.
 @{" DEFVAR*    " link "DEFVAR*"}  Global variable that remembers its value.


@endnode

@node "DEFUN" "MUIbase/DEFUN"
@toc "Defining commands"

DEFUN
-----

@{b}   DEFUN@{ub} defines a function with the specified name, a list of arguments
that are passed to the function, and a list of expressions to evaluate.

@{b}     (DEFUN@{ub} NAME @{b}(@{ub}VARLIST@{b})@{ub} EXPR ...@{b})@{ub}

   The name of a function must start with a lowercase character,
followed by further characters, digits or underscore characters (see
@{"Name conventions" link "Name conventions"}).

   The parameters VARLIST specifies the arguments of the function:

     VARLIST: VAR1 ...

where VAR1 ... are the names for the arguments.  The names must follow
the same rules as the function name.

   It is also possible to add type specifiers to the arguments (see
@{"Type specifiers" link "Type specifiers"}).

   The function executes the expressions EXPR, ... one by one and
returns the value of the last expression.  The function may call
further functions including itself.  A self defined function can be
called like calling a pre-defined function.

   For example to count the number of elements of a list, you can
define the following function:

     (DEFUN len (l)
         (IF (= l NIL)
             0
             (+ 1 (len (REST l)))
         )
     )

   Functions defined with @{b}DEFUN@{ub} are listed in the pop-up list-views of
table and attribute requesters (see @{"Creating tables" link "Creating tables"} and
@{"Creating attributes" link "Creating attributes"}).

   This command is only available for project programs.

   See also @{"DEFUN*" link "DEFUN*"}, @{"DEFVAR" link "DEFVAR"}.


@endnode

@node "DEFUN*" "MUIbase/DEFUN*"
@toc "Defining commands"

DEFUN*
------

@{b}   DEFUN*@{ub} is the star version of @{b}DEFUN@{ub} and has the same effect as @{b}DEFUN@{ub}
(see @{"DEFUN" link "DEFUN"}).  The only difference is that functions defined with
@{b}DEFUN*@{ub} are not listed in the pop-up list-views when creating or
changing tables and attributes.  However, it is still possible to enter
the function name in the corresponding string fields.

   This command is only available for project programs.

   See also @{"DEFUN" link "DEFUN"}, @{"DEFVAR" link "DEFVAR"}.


@endnode

@node "DEFVAR" "MUIbase/DEFVAR"
@toc "Defining commands"

DEFVAR
------

@{b}     (DEFVAR@{ub} VAR [EXPR]@{b})@{ub}

   Defines a global variable with initial value of EXPR or NIL if EXPR
is missing.  The name of the variables must start with a lowercase
letter followed by further letters, digits or underscore characters
(see @{"Name conventions" link "Name conventions"}).

   You can also add a type specifier to the variable name (see
@{"Type specifiers" link "Type specifiers"}).

@{b}   DEFVAR@{ub} is only available for project programs.  All @{b}DEFVAR@{ub} commands
should be placed on top of all function definitions.

   After execution of a trigger function (when MUIbase returns to the
user interface), all global variables loose their contents.  They are
re-initialized with their initial value EXPR on the next invocation of
a trigger function.  If this is not desired, use the @{b}DEFVAR*@{ub} (see
@{"DEFVAR*" link "DEFVAR*"}) command which allows to store the value of global variables
between program calls.

   Please use global variables rarely (if at all).  All global
variables have to be initialized (and EXPR be evaluated if given)
whenever a trigger function is called from outside.

   Example: @{b}(DEFVAR x 42)@{ub} defines a global variable @{b}x@{ub} with value 42.

   There are some pre-defined global variables in MUIbase (see
@{"Pre-defined variables" link "Pre-defined variables"}).

   See also @{"DEFVAR*" link "DEFVAR*"}, @{"DEFUN" link "DEFUN"}, @{"DEFUN*" link "DEFUN*"}, @{"LET" link "LET"}.


@endnode

@node "DEFVAR*" "MUIbase/DEFVAR*"
@toc "Defining commands"

DEFVAR*
-------

@{b}     (DEFVAR*@{ub} VAR [EXPR]@{b})@{ub}

@{b}   DEFVAR*@{ub} has the same effect as the @{b}DEFVAR@{ub} command (see @{"DEFVAR" link "DEFVAR"})
except that a variable defined with @{b}DEFVAR*@{ub} does not loose its value
after the program completes.

   On the first invocation of the program, VAR is initialized with EXPR
or NIL if EXPR is omitted.  Subsequent calls of the program do not
evaluate EXPR again but use the value of VAR from the previous call.
This way it is possible to transfer information from one program call
to another without storing data in an external file or a database
table.  Note, however, that all global variables defined with @{b}DEFVAR*@{ub}
loose their contents when the project program is re-compiled.   If you
wish to permanently store information, use a (possibly hidden)
attribute in a table.

   See also @{"DEFVAR" link "DEFVAR"}, @{"DEFUN" link "DEFUN"}, @{"DEFUN*" link "DEFUN*"}, @{"LET" link "LET"}.


@endnode

@node "Program control functions" "MUIbase/Program control functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Program Control Functions
=========================

   This section lists functions for program control, e.g.  functions
for defining local variables, loop functions, conditional program
execution, loop control functions and more.


 @{" PROGN      " link "PROGN"}  Compound statement, returns last expression.
 @{" PROG1      " link "PROG1"}  Compound statement, returns first expression.
 @{" LET        " link "LET"}  Defining local variables.
 @{" SETQ       " link "SETQ"}  Setting the value of variables, attributes and tables.
 @{" SETQ*      " link "SETQ*"}  Setting the value of variables, attributes and tables.
 @{" FUNCALL    " link "FUNCALL"}  Calling a function with arguments.
 @{" APPLY      " link "APPLY"}  Applying a function to an argument list.
 @{" IF         " link "IF"}  If-then-else conditional program execution.
 @{" CASE       " link "CASE"}  Switch-case conditional program execution.
 @{" COND       " link "COND"}  Powerful conditional program execution.
 @{" DOTIMES    " link "DOTIMES"}  Loop over a range of integer values.
 @{" DOLIST     " link "DOLIST"}  Loop over a list.
 @{" DO         " link "DO"}  Generic loop.
 @{" FOR ALL    " link "FOR ALL"}  Loop over sets of records.
 @{" NEXT       " link "NEXT"}  Jumping to next loop run.
 @{" EXIT       " link "EXIT"}  Exiting a loop.
 @{" RETURN     " link "RETURN"}  Returning from a function.
 @{" HALT       " link "HALT"}  Stopping program execution.
 @{" ERROR      " link "ERROR"}  Aborting program execution with an error message.


@endnode

@node "PROGN" "MUIbase/PROGN"
@toc "Program control functions"

PROGN
-----

   To evaluate several expressions one by another the @{b}PROGN@{ub}
construction can be used.

@{b}     (@{ub}[EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

executes EXPR ... one by one.  Returns the result of the last
expression (or NIL if no expression has been specified).  In Lisp this
construct is known as @{b}(PROGN@{ub} [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}.

   Example: @{b}(1 2 3 4)@{ub} results to 4.

   See also @{"PROG1" link "PROG1"}.


@endnode

@node "PROG1" "MUIbase/PROG1"
@toc "Program control functions"

PROG1
-----

   Another way, besides the @{b}PROGN@{ub} function, to evaluate several
expressions one by another is the @{b}PROG1@{ub} expression.

@{b}     (PROG1@{ub} [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

executes EXPR ... and returns the value of the first expression (or NIL
if no expression has been specified).

   Example: @{b}(PROG1 1 2 3 4)@{ub} results to 1.

   See also @{"PROGN" link "PROGN"}.


@endnode

@node "LET" "MUIbase/LET"
@toc "Program control functions"

LET
---

@{b}   LET@{ub} defines a new block of local variables.  This is useful, e.g.,
for defining local variables of a function.  The syntax is

@{b}     (LET (@{ub}VARLIST@{b})@{ub} EXPR ...@{b})@{ub}

   where VARLIST is a list of local variables.

     VARLIST: VARSPEC ...

     VARSPEC: @{b}(@{ub}VAR EXPR@{b})@{ub} | VAR

   Here VAR is the name of the variable and must start with a lowercase
character, followed by further characters, digits or underscore
characters (see @{"Name conventions" link "Name conventions"}).

   In the case of a @{b}(@{ub}VAR EXPR@{b})@{ub} specification, the new variable is
initialized with the given expression.  In the other case the new
variable is set to NIL.

   It is also possible to add type specifiers to the variables.  (see
@{"Type specifiers" link "Type specifiers"}).

   After initializing all variables the list of expressions EXPR ...
are evaluated and the value of the last one is returned.

   For example, the following @{b}LET@{ub} expression

     (LET ((x 0) y (z (+ x 1)))
         (+ x z)
     )

   results to 1.

   See also @{"DOTIMES" link "DOTIMES"}, @{"DOLIST" link "DOLIST"}, @{"DO" link "DO"}, @{"DEFVAR" link "DEFVAR"}.


@endnode

@node "SETQ" "MUIbase/SETQ"
@toc "Program control functions"

SETQ
----

   The @{b}SETQ@{ub} function sets values to variables, attributes and tables.

@{b}     (SETQ@{ub} LVALUE1 EXPR ...@{b})@{ub}

   Sets LVALUE1 to the value of EXPR.  The dots indicate assignments
for further lvalues.  An lvalue is either a variable, an attribute in a
table, or a table.  In case of a variable, the variable must have been
previously defined (e.g. by a @{b}LET@{ub} expression).

   Setting the value of a table means setting its program or GUI record
pointer: @{b}@{b}(SETQ@{ub} TABLE EXPR@{b})@{ub}@{ub} sets the program record pointer of TABLE to
the value of EXPR, @{b}@{b}(SETQ@{ub} TABLE* EXPR@{b})@{ub}@{ub} sets the GUI record pointer of it
and updates the display.  For more information about program and GUI
record pointers, see @{"Tables" link "Tables"}.

@{b}   SETQ@{ub} returns the value of the last expression.

   Example: @{b}(SETQ a 1 b 2)@{ub} assigns 1 to the variable @{b}a@{ub}, 2 to the
variable @{b}b@{ub} and returns 2.

   See also @{"SETQ*" link "SETQ*"}, @{"LET" link "LET"}, @{"DEFVAR" link "DEFVAR"}, @{"Tables" link "Tables"}, @{"Semantics of expressions" link "Semantics of expressions"}.


@endnode

@node "SETQ*" "MUIbase/SETQ*"
@toc "Program control functions"

SETQ*
-----

@{b}   SETQ*@{ub} is the star version of @{b}SETQ@{ub} (see @{"SETQ" link "SETQ"}) and has similar
effects.  The difference is that when assigning a value to an
attribute, @{b}SETQ*@{ub} calls the trigger function of that attribute (see
@{"Attribute trigger" link "Attribute trigger"}) instead of directly assigning the value.  In case
no trigger function has been specified for an attribute, @{b}SETQ*@{ub} behaves
like @{b}SETQ@{ub} and simply assigns the value to the attribute.

   Example: @{b}(SETQ* Table.Attr 0)@{ub} calls the trigger function of
@{b}Table.Attr@{ub} with an argument of 0.

   Warning: With this function it is possible to write endless loops,
e.g.  if you have defined a trigger function for an attribute and this
function calls @{b}SETQ*@{ub} to set a value to itself.

   See also @{"SETQ*" link "SETQ*"}, @{"LET" link "LET"}, @{"DEFVAR" link "DEFVAR"}.


@endnode

@node "FUNCALL" "MUIbase/FUNCALL"
@toc "Program control functions"

FUNCALL
-------

@{b}   FUNCALL@{ub} is used to call a function with arguments.

@{b}     (FUNCALL@{ub} FUN-EXPR [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Calls the function FUN-EXPR with the given arguments.  The
expression FUN-EXPR can be any expression whose value is a pre-defined
or user-defined function, e.g. a variable holding the function to call.
If the number of arguments is not correct, an error message is
generated.

@{b}   FUNCALL@{ub} returns the return value of the function call or NIL if
FUN-EXPR is NIL.

   For more information about functional expressions, see
@{"Functional parameters" link "Functional parameters"}.

   See also @{"APPLY" link "APPLY"}.


@endnode

@node "APPLY" "MUIbase/APPLY"
@toc "Program control functions"

APPLY
-----

@{b}   APPLY@{ub} is used to apply a function to a list of arguments.

@{b}     (APPLY@{ub} FUN-EXPR [EXPR ...] LIST-EXPR@{b})@{ub}

   Applies the function FUN-EXPR to a list created by @{b}cons@{ub}'ing the
arguments EXPR ... to LIST-EXPR.  In other words: calls the function
FUN-EXPR with the arguments EXPR ... and LIST-EXPR expanded to its list
elements.

   The expression FUN-EXPR can be any expression whose value is a
pre-defined or user-defined function, e.g. a variable holding the
function to call.  The last argument LIST-EXPR must be a valid list or
NIL, otherwise an error message is generated.  If the number of
arguments is not correct, an error occurs.

@{b}   APPLY@{ub} returns the return value of the function call or NIL if
FUN-EXPR is NIL.

   For more information about functional expressions, see
@{"Functional parameters" link "Functional parameters"}.

   Example: @{b}(APPLY + 4 (LIST 1 2 3))@{ub} returns 10.

   See also @{"FUNCALL" link "FUNCALL"}.


@endnode

@node "IF" "MUIbase/IF"
@toc "Program control functions"

IF
--

@{b}   IF@{ub} is a conditional operator.

@{b}     (IF@{ub} EXPR1 EXPR2 [EXPR3]@{b})@{ub}

   The expression EXPR1 is tested.  If it results to non-NIL then the
value of EXPR2 is returned else the value of EXPR3 (or NIL if not
present) is returned.

   This function is not strict, that is, only one expression of EXPR2
or EXPR3 will be evaluated.

   See also @{"CASE" link "CASE"}, @{"COND" link "COND"}.


@endnode

@node "CASE" "MUIbase/CASE"
@toc "Program control functions"

CASE
----

@{b}   CASE@{ub} is similar to the @{b}switch@{ub} statement in the C language.

@{b}     (CASE@{ub} EXPR [CASE ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Here EXPR is the selection expression and CASE ... are pairs
consisting of:

     CASE: @{b}(@{ub}VALUE [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

where VALUE is a single expression or a list of expressions and EXPR
... are the expressions to be executed if one of the case expression
matches.

   The @{b}CASE@{ub} expression first evaluates EXPR.  Then each case pair is
checked whether it (or one of the expressions in the list) matches the
evaluated expression.  If a matching case expression is found then the
corresponding expressions are executed and the value of the last
expression is returned.  If no case matches, NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(CASE 1 ((2 3 4) 1) (1 2))@{ub} returns 2.

   See also @{"IF" link "IF"}, @{"COND" link "COND"}.


@endnode

@node "COND" "MUIbase/COND"
@toc "Program control functions"

COND
----

@{b}   COND@{ub} is, like @{b}IF@{ub}, a conditional operator.

@{b}     (COND@{ub} [@{b}(@{ub}TEST-EXPR [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub} ...]@{b})@{ub}

@{b}   COND@{ub} test the first expression of each list one by one.  For the
first one that does not result to NIL, the corresponding expressions
EXPR ... are evaluated and the value of the last expression is returned.

   If all tested expressions result to NIL then NIL is returned.

Example
-------

     (COND ((> 1 2) "1 > 2")
           ((= 1 2) "1 = 2")
           ((< 1 2) "1 < 2")
     )

results to "1 < 2".

   See also @{"IF" link "IF"}, @{"CASE" link "CASE"}.


@endnode

@node "DOTIMES" "MUIbase/DOTIMES"
@toc "Program control functions"

DOTIMES
-------

   For simple loops the @{b}DOTIMES@{ub} command can be used.

@{b}     (DOTIMES (@{ub}NAME INT-EXPR [RESULT-EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub} [LOOP-EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Here NAME is the name of a new variable which will be used in the
loop.  The name must start with a lowercase character, followed by
further characters, digits or underscore characters (see
@{"Name conventions" link "Name conventions"}).

   The number of times the loop is executed is given in INT-EXPR.  In
RESULT-EXPR ... expressions can be specified that are executed after
terminating the loop.  In LOOP-EXPR you specify the body of the loop,
that is, the expressions that are evaluated in each loop run.

   Before executing the loop, @{b}DOTIMES@{ub} computes the value of INT-EXPR to
determine the number of times the loop gets executed.  Here INT-EXPR is
evaluated only once at the start of the loop and must result to an
integer value.  Then @{b}DOTIMES@{ub} sets the loop variable to the values of 0
to INT-EXPR-1 one by one for each loop run.  First, the variable is
initialized with zero and checked if it is already greater or equal to
the value of EXPR.  If INT-EXPR is negative or NIL or if the variable
is greater or equal to the value of EXPR then the loop is terminated
and the result expressions are evaluated.  Otherwise the loop
expressions are evaluated and the variable is incremented by one.  Then
the execution returns to the termination test and, possibly, does
further loop runs.

   The @{b}DOTIMES@{ub} expression returns the value of the last result
expression or NIL if no result expression has been given.

Example
-------

     (DOTIMES (i 50 i) (PRINT i))

   Prints the numbers from 0 to 49 and returns the value 50.

   See also @{"DOLIST" link "DOLIST"}, @{"DO" link "DO"}, @{"FOR ALL" link "FOR ALL"}, @{"LET" link "LET"}.


@endnode

@node "DOLIST" "MUIbase/DOLIST"
@toc "Program control functions"

DOLIST
------

   For loops through lists the @{b}DOLIST@{ub} expression can be used.

@{b}     (DOLIST (@{ub}NAME LIST-EXPR [RESULT-EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub} [LOOP-EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Here NAME is the name of a new variable which will be used in the
loop.  The name must start with a lowercase character, followed by
further characters, digits or underscore characters (see
@{"Name conventions" link "Name conventions"}).

   In LIST-EXPR you specify the list over which the loop should be
executed, RESULT-EXPR ... are expressions which are evaluated after
terminating the loop, and LOOP-EXPR ... build the body of the loop.

   Before executing the loop, @{b}DOLIST@{ub} computes the value of LIST-EXPR.
This expression is evaluated only once at the start of the loop and
must result to a list value.  Then @{b}DOTIMES@{ub} sets the loop variable to
the nodes of the list one by one for each loop run.  First the loop
variable is initialized to the first node of the list.  If the list is
already empty (NIL) then the loop is terminated and the result
expressions are evaluated.  Otherwise the loop expressions are
evaluated and the variable is set to the next node of the list.  Then
the execution returns to the termination test and, possibly, does
further loop runs.

   The @{b}DOLIST@{ub} expression returns the value of the last result expression
or NIL if no result expression has been given.

Example
-------

     (DOLIST (i (SELECT * FROM Accounts)) (PRINT i))

   Prints all records of table @{b}Accounts@{ub} and returns NIL.

   See also @{"DOTIMES" link "DOTIMES"}, @{"DO" link "DO"}, @{"FOR ALL" link "FOR ALL"}, @{"LET" link "LET"}.


@endnode

@node "DO" "MUIbase/DO"
@toc "Program control functions"

DO
--

   With the @{b}DO@{ub} expression arbitrary loops can be programmed.

@{b}     (DO (@{ub}[BINDING ...]@{b}) (@{ub}TERM-EXPR [RESULT-EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub} [LOOP-EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

where BINDING ... are the variable bindings, each of which is either:

   * a new name for a variable (which is initialized to NIL)

   * a list of the form: @{b}(@{ub}NAME INIT [STEP]@{b})@{ub} where NAME is a name for
     the new variable, INIT is the initial value of the variable, and
     STEP is a step expression.

   Furthermore, TERM-EXPR is the termination test expression,
RESULT-EXPR ... are the result expressions (the default is nil) and
LOOP-EXPR ... build the body of the loop.

   The @{b}DO@{ub} loop first initializes all local variables with the init
expressions, then tests the termination expression. If it results to
TRUE, the loop is terminated and the result expressions are evaluated.
The value of the last result expression is returned.  Otherwise the
body of the loop @{b}(@{ub}LOOP-EXPR ...@{b})@{ub} is executed and each variable is
updated by the value of its step expression.  Then the execution
returns to test the terminating expression and so on.

Example
-------

     (DO ((i 0 (+ i 1))) ((>= i 5) i) (PRINT i))

   Prints the values 0, 1, 2, 3 and 4 and returns the value 5.  Of
course this is a quite complicated way to build a simple FOR loop.
Therefore a simpler version exists, the @{b}DOTIMES@{ub} expression.

   See also @{"DOTIMES" link "DOTIMES"}, @{"DOLIST" link "DOLIST"}, @{"FOR ALL" link "FOR ALL"}, @{"LET" link "LET"}.


@endnode

@node "FOR ALL" "MUIbase/FOR ALL"
@toc "Program control functions"

FOR ALL
-------

   The FOR ALL expression is used to loop over a list of records.

@{b}     (FOR ALL@{ub} TABLE-LIST [@{b}WHERE@{ub} WHERE-EXPR] [@{b}ORDER BY@{ub} ORDER-LIST] @{b}DO@{ub} EXPR ...@{b})@{ub}

   Here TABLE-LIST is a comma-separated list of tables, WHERE-EXPR an
expression to test each set of records, ORDER-LIST a comma-separated
list of expressions by which the record sets are ordered, and EXPR ...
are the expressions that are executed for each record set.

@{b}   FOR ALL@{ub} first generates a list of all record sets for which the loop
body should be executed.  This is done like in the @{b}SELECT@{ub} expression.
Please see @{"SELECT" link "SELECT"}, for more information about how this list is
generated.  For each element of this list the loop body EXPR ... is
executed.

   For example, summing up an attribute of a table can be done in the
following way:

     (SETQ sum 0)
     (FOR ALL Accounts DO
         (SETQ sum (+ sum Accounts.Amount))
     )

   The @{b}FOR ALL@{ub} expression returns NIL.

   See also @{"SELECT" link "SELECT"}, @{"DOTIMES" link "DOTIMES"}, @{"DOLIST" link "DOLIST"}, @{"DO" link "DO"}.


@endnode

@node "NEXT" "MUIbase/NEXT"
@toc "Program control functions"

NEXT
----

@{b}   NEXT@{ub} can be used for controlling @{b}DOTIMES@{ub}, @{b}DOLIST@{ub}, @{b}DO@{ub} and @{b}FOR ALL@{ub}
loops.

   Calling @{b}NEXT@{ub} in the body of a loop will jump to the next loop
iteration.  This can be used for skipping non-interesting loop runs,
like e.g. in the following example:

     (FOR ALL TABLE DO
         (IF NOT-INTERESTED-IN-THE-CURRENT-RECORD (NEXT))
         ...
     )

   See also @{"EXIT" link "EXIT"}, @{"DOTIMES" link "DOTIMES"}, @{"DOLIST" link "DOLIST"}, @{"DO" link "DO"}, @{"FOR ALL" link "FOR ALL"}.


@endnode

@node "EXIT" "MUIbase/EXIT"
@toc "Program control functions"

EXIT
----

@{b}   EXIT@{ub} can be used to terminate a loop.

@{b}     (EXIT@{ub} [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

@{b}   EXIT@{ub} within a loop body will terminate the loop, execute the
optional expressions EXPR ..., and return the value of the last
expression (or NIL in case of no expression) as the return value of the
loop.  Possible return expressions of the loop as for example in

     (DOTIMES (x 10 RET-EXPR ...) ...)

are not executed.

   You may use the @{b}EXIT@{ub} function for example to end a @{b}FOR ALL@{ub} loop when
you found the record you are interested in:

     (FOR ALL TABLE DO
         (IF INTERESTED-IN-THE-CURRENT-RECORD (EXIT TABLE))
         ...
     )

   See also @{"NEXT" link "NEXT"}, @{"RETURN" link "RETURN"}, @{"HALT" link "HALT"}, @{"DOTIMES" link "DOTIMES"}, @{"DOLIST" link "DOLIST"}, @{"DO" link "DO"}, @{"FOR ALL" link "FOR ALL"}.


@endnode

@node "RETURN" "MUIbase/RETURN"
@toc "Program control functions"

RETURN
------

   Within a function definition you can return to the caller by using
the @{b}RETURN@{ub} command.

@{b}     (RETURN@{ub} [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

terminates the function, executes the optional expressions EXPR ...,
and returns the value of the last expression (or NIL in case of no
expression).

Example
-------

     (DEFUN find-record (name)
         (FOR ALL Table DO
             (IF (= Name name) (RETURN Table))
         )
     )

   The example searches a record whose Name attribute matches the given
name. The function returns the first record found or NIL in case of no
record found.

   See also @{"HALT" link "HALT"}, @{"EXIT" link "EXIT"}.


@endnode

@node "HALT" "MUIbase/HALT"
@toc "Program control functions"

HALT
----

@{b}   HALT@{ub} can be used to terminate program execution.

@{b}     (HALT)@{ub}

stops program execution silently.

   See also @{"ERROR" link "ERROR"}, @{"EXIT" link "EXIT"}, @{"RETURN" link "RETURN"}.


@endnode

@node "ERROR" "MUIbase/ERROR"
@toc "Program control functions"

ERROR
-----

   For aborting program execution with an error message the @{b}ERROR@{ub}
function can be used.

@{b}     (ERROR@{ub} FMT [ARG ...]@{b})@{ub}

stops program execution and pops up a requester with an error message.
The error message is generated from FMT and the optional arguments ARG
... like in the @{b}SPRINTF@{ub} function (see @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}).

   See also @{"HALT" link "HALT"}, @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}.


@endnode

@node "Type predicates" "MUIbase/Type predicates"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Type Predicates
===============

   For each type a predicate is defined that returns TRUE if the
supplied expression is of the specified type and NIL otherwise. The
predicates are:

@{b}Predicate@{ub}           @{b}Description@{ub}

@{b}(STRP@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}        TRUE if EXPR is of type string, NIL otherwise.

@{b}(MEMOP@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}       TRUE if EXPR is of type memo, NIL otherwise.

@{b}(INTP@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}        TRUE if EXPR is of type integer, NIL otherwise.

@{b}(REALP@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}       TRUE if EXPR is of type real, NIL otherwise.

@{b}(DATEP@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}       TRUE if EXPR is of type date, NIL otherwise.

@{b}(TIMEP@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}       TRUE if EXPR is of type time, NIL otherwise.

@{b}(NULL@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}        TRUE if EXPR is NIL (an empty list), NIL otherwise.

@{b}(CONSP@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}       TRUE if EXPR is a non-empty list, NIL otherwise.

@{b}(LISTP@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}       TRUE if EXPR is a list (may be NIL), NIL otherwise.

@{b}(RECP@{ub} TABLE EXPR@{b})@{ub}  TRUE if EXPR is a record pointer of the given table.
                    If EXPR is NIL then TRUE is returned (initial record).
                    If TABLE is NIL then a check is done whether EXPR
                    is a record pointer of any table.


@endnode

@node "Type conversion functions" "MUIbase/Type conversion functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Type Conversion Functions
=========================

   This section lists functions for converting values from one type to
another one.


 @{" STR            " link "STR"}  Conversion to string.
 @{" MEMO           " link "MEMO"}  Conversion to memo.
 @{" INT            " link "INT"}  Conversion to integer.
 @{" REAL           " link "REAL"}  Conversion to real.
 @{" DATE           " link "DATE"}  Conversion to date.
 @{" TIME           " link "TIME"}  Conversion to time.


@endnode

@node "STR" "MUIbase/STR"
@toc "Type conversion functions"

STR
---

@{b}   STR@{ub} can be used to convert an expression into a string
representation.

@{b}     (STR@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

converts EXPR into a string representation. The type of EXPR determines
the conversion:

@{b}Type@{ub}            @{b}Return string@{ub}

String          The string itself.

Memo            The whole memo text in one string.

Integer         String representation of integer value.

Real            String representation of real value.
                If EXPR is an attribute then the number
                decimals specified for this attribute are used,
                otherwise 2 decimals are used.

Choice          Label string of the choice attribute.

Date            String representation of date value.

Time            String representation of time value.

Boolean         The string "TRUE"

NIL             User defined nil string if EXPR is an attribute,
                the string "NIL" otherwise.

Record          String representation of record number.

Others          String representation of internal address pointer.

   See also @{"MEMO" link "MEMO"}, @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}.


@endnode

@node "MEMO" "MUIbase/MEMO"
@toc "Type conversion functions"

MEMO
----

@{b}   MEMO@{ub} can be used to convert an expression into a memo.

@{b}     (MEMO@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

converts EXPR into a memo representation.  It treats the expression
like the @{b}STR@{ub} function (see @{"STR" link "STR"}) but returns a memo text instead of a
string.

   See also @{"STR" link "STR"}.


@endnode

@node "INT" "MUIbase/INT"
@toc "Type conversion functions"

INT
---

@{b}   INT@{ub} is used to convert an expression into an integer.

@{b}     (INT@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

converts EXPR into an integer value. Possible conversions are:

@{b}Type@{ub}            @{b}Return value@{ub}

String          If the complete string represents a valid integer value,
                it is converted into an integer.  A string starting
                with 0 is interpreted as an octal number, one starting
                with 0x as hexadecimal number.  Leading and following
                spaces are ignored.
                If the string does not represent an integer value, NIL
                is returned.

Memo            Same as for string.

Integer         The value itself.

Real            If the value lies within the integer range than the real value
                is rounded and returned, otherwise NIL is returned.

Choice          The internal number (starting with 0) of the current label.

Date            Number of days since 01.01.0000.

Time            Number of seconds since 00:00:00.

Record          Record number.

NIL             NIL

Others          An error message is generated and program execution is aborted.

   See also @{"REAL" link "REAL"}, @{"ASC" link "ASC"}.


@endnode

@node "REAL" "MUIbase/REAL"
@toc "Type conversion functions"

REAL
----

@{b}   REAL@{ub} is used to convert an expression into a value of type real.

@{b}     (REAL@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

converts EXPR into a real.  It treats the expression like the @{b}INT@{ub}
function (see @{"INT" link "INT"}) but returns a value of type real instead of an
integer.

   See also @{"INT" link "INT"}.


@endnode

@node "DATE" "MUIbase/DATE"
@toc "Type conversion functions"

DATE
----

@{b}   DATE@{ub} is used to convert an expression into a date (with your
favorite friend :-).

@{b}     (DATE@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

converts the given expression into a date value.  Possible conversions
are:

@{b}Type@{ub}            @{b}Return value@{ub}

String          If the whole string represents a date value then the
                string is converted into a date value. Leading and following
                spaces are ignored.
                If it does not represent a date value, NIL is returned.

Memo            Same as for string.

Integer         A date value is generated where the given integer represents
                the number of days since 01.01.0000. If the integer value is
                too great (date value would be greater than 31.12.9999) or
                negative then NIL is returned.

Real            Same as for integer.

Date            The value itself.

NIL             NIL

others          An error message is generated and program execution is aborted.

   See also @{"DATEDMY" link "DATEDMY"}.


@endnode

@node "TIME" "MUIbase/TIME"
@toc "Type conversion functions"

TIME
----

@{b}   TIME@{ub} is used to convert an expression into a time value.

@{b}     (TIME@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

converts the given expression into a time value.  Possible conversions
are:

@{b}Type@{ub}            @{b}Return value@{ub}

String          If the whole string represents a time value then the
                string is converted into a time value. Leading and following
                spaces are ignored.
                If it does not represent a time value, NIL is returned.

Memo            Same as for string.

Integer         A time value is generated where the given integer represents
                the number of seconds since 00:00:00.

Real            Same as for integer.

Time            The value itself.

NIL             NIL

others          An error message is generated and program execution is aborted.


@endnode

@node "Boolean functions" "MUIbase/Boolean functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Boolean Functions
=================

   This section lists Boolean operators.


 @{" AND            " link "AND"}  Conjunction of Boolean values.
 @{" OR             " link "OR"}  Disjunction of Boolean values.
 @{" NOT            " link "NOT"}  Inverting a Boolean value.


@endnode

@node "AND" "MUIbase/AND"
@toc "Boolean functions"

AND
---

@{b}   AND@{ub} checks if all of its arguments are TRUE.

@{b}     (AND@{ub} [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

checks EXPR ... one by another until one expression evaluates to NIL.
If all expressions evaluate to non-NIL then the value of the last
expression is returned.  Otherwise NIL is returned.

   This function is non-strict which means that arguments of @{b}AND@{ub} may
not be evaluated, e.g. in @{b}(AND NIL (+ 1 2))@{ub} the expression @{b}(+ 1 2)@{ub} is
not evaluated since a NIL value has already been processed, however in
@{b}(AND (+ 1 2) NIL)@{ub} the expression @{b}(+ 1 2)@{ub} gets evaluated.

   See also @{"OR" link "OR"}, @{"NOT" link "NOT"}.


@endnode

@node "OR" "MUIbase/OR"
@toc "Boolean functions"

OR
--

@{b}   OR@{ub} checks if all of its arguments are NIL.

@{b}     (OR@{ub} [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

checks EXPR ... one by another until one expression evaluates to
non-NIL.  Returns the value of the first non-NIL expression or NIL if
all expressions evaluate to NIL.

   This function is non-strict which means that arguments of @{b}OR@{ub} may not
be evaluated, e.g. in @{b}(OR TRUE (+ 1 2))@{ub} the expression @{b}(+ 1 2)@{ub} is not
evaluated since a non-NIL value (here @{b}TRUE@{ub}) has already been processed,
however in @{b}(OR (+ 1 2) TRUE)@{ub} the expression @{b}(+ 1 2)@{ub} gets evaluated.

   See also @{"AND" link "AND"}, @{"NOT" link "NOT"}.


@endnode

@node "NOT" "MUIbase/NOT"
@toc "Boolean functions"

NOT
---

@{b}   NOT@{ub} is used to invert the value of a Boolean expression.

@{b}     (NOT@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

   results to TRUE if EXPR is NIL, NIL otherwise.

   See also @{"AND" link "AND"}, @{"OR" link "OR"}.


@endnode

@node "Comparison functions" "MUIbase/Comparison functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Comparison Functions
====================

   In this section you will find functions for comparing values.


 @{" Relational operators      " link "Relational operators"}  =, <>, <, >, <=, >= and their star versions.
 @{" CMP                       " link "CMP"}  Returns an integer representing the order.
 @{" CMP*                      " link "CMP*"}  Extended comparison, e.g. case insensitive.


@endnode

@node "Relational operators" "MUIbase/Relational operators"
@toc "Comparison functions"

Relational Operators
--------------------

   For comparing two values in a MUIbase program, use

@{b}     (@{ub}OP EXPR1 EXPR2@{b})@{ub}

where OP is in {@{b}=@{ub}, @{b}<>@{ub}, @{b}<@{ub}, @{b}>@{ub}, @{b}>=@{ub}, @{b}<=@{ub}, @{b}=*@{ub}, @{b}<>*@{ub}, @{b}<*@{ub}, @{b}>*@{ub}, @{b}>=*@{ub}, @{b}<=*@{ub}}.  The
star is used for special comparison (strings are compared case
insensitive, records are compared by using the order defined by the
user).

   The following table shows all rules for comparing two values in a
MUIbase program.

@{b}Type@{ub}        @{b}Order relation@{ub}

Integer     NIL < MIN_INT < ... < -1 < 0 < 1 < ... < MAX_INT

Real        NIL < -HUGE_VAL < ... < -1.0 < 0.0 < 1.0 < ... < HUGE_VAL

String:     NIL <  "" <  "Z" <  "a"  <  "aa" <  "b" < ... (case sensitive)
            NIL <* "" <* "a" <* "AA" <* "b" < ...       (case insensitive)

Memo:       same as string

Date        NIL < 1.1.0000 < ... < 31.12.9999

Time        NIL < 00:00:00 < ... < 596523:14:07

Boolean     NIL < TRUE

Record:     NIL < any_record    (records itself are not comparable with <)
            NIL <* rec1 <* rec2 (order specified by user)

   See also @{"CMP" link "CMP"}, @{"CMP*" link "CMP*"}, @{"LIKE" link "LIKE"}.


@endnode

@node "CMP" "MUIbase/CMP"
@toc "Comparison functions"

CMP
---

@{b}   CMP@{ub} returns an integer representing the order of its arguments.

@{b}     (CMP@{ub} EXPR1 EXPR2@{b})@{ub}

   returns a value less than 0 if EXPR1 is smaller than EXPR2, 0 if
EXPR1 is equal to EXPR2, and a value greater than 0 if EXPR1 is greater
than EXPR2.  For determining the order the simple (non-star) order
relation as for relational operators (see @{"Relational operators" link "Relational operators"}) is
used.

   Do not assume that the returned value will always be -1, 0, or 1!

   Example: @{b}(CMP "Bike" "bIKE")@{ub} results to -1.

   See also @{"CMP*" link "CMP*"}, @{"Relational operators" link "Relational operators"}.


@endnode

@node "CMP*" "MUIbase/CMP*"
@toc "Comparison functions"

CMP*
----

@{b}   CMP*@{ub} is the star version of @{b}CMP@{ub}.  The difference is that @{b}CMP*@{ub} uses
the extended ordering as defined for relational operators (see
@{"Relational operators" link "Relational operators"}) where strings are compared case insensitive and
records are compared using the user defined record order.

   Example: @{b}(CMP* "Bike" "bIKE")@{ub} results to 0.

   See also @{"CMP" link "CMP"}, @{"Relational operators" link "Relational operators"}.


@endnode

@node "Mathematical functions" "MUIbase/Mathematical functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Mathematical Functions
======================

   Here, some mathematical functions are listed.


 @{" +                  " link "add"}  Adding values.
 @{" -                  " link "sub"}  Subtracting values.
 @{" 1+                 " link "1+"}  Increasing value.
 @{" 1-                 " link "1-"}  Decreasing value.
 @{" *                  " link "mul"}  Floating point multiplication.
 @{" /                  " link "fdiv"}  Floating point division.
 @{" DIV                " link "DIV"}  Integer division.
 @{" MOD                " link "MOD"}  Integer modulo.
 @{" MAX                " link "MAX"}  Maximum expression.
 @{" MIN                " link "MIN"}  Minimum expression.
 @{" ABS                " link "ABS"}  Absolute value of an expression.
 @{" TRUNC              " link "TRUNC"}  Truncating decimals of a real value.
 @{" ROUND              " link "ROUND"}  Rounding a real value.
 @{" RANDOM             " link "RANDOM"}  Random number generator.
 @{" POW                " link "POW"}  Power of numbers.
 @{" SQRT               " link "SQRT"}  Square root function.
 @{" EXP                " link "EXP"}  Exponential function.
 @{" LOG                " link "LOG"}  Logarithm of a number.


@endnode

@node "add" "MUIbase/add"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

Adding Values
-------------

   For adding values, use

@{b}     (+@{ub} EXPR ...@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the sum of the arguments EXPR ....  If any argument value is
NIL then the result is NIL.  If the values are of type real or integer
then a real (or integer) value is the result.

   You may also add strings or memos.  In this case the result is the
concatenation of the strings/memos.

   If EXPR is of type date and the rest of the arguments are
integers/reals then the sum of integers/reals are interpreted as a
number of days and added to EXPR. If the resulting date is out of range
(smaller than 1.1.0000 or greater than 31.12.9999) then NIL is the
result.

   If EXPR is of type time and the rest of the arguments are
integers/reals or other time values then the sum of integers/reals
(interpreted as a number of seconds) and time values are added to EXPR.
If the resulting time is out of range (smaller than 00:00:00 or greater
than 596523:14:07) then NIL is the result.

Examples
--------

@{b}Expression@{ub}                       @{b}Value@{ub}

(+ 1 2 3)                        6
(+ 5 1.0)                        6.0
(+ "Hello" " " "world!")         "Hello world!"
(+ 28.11.1968 +365 -28 -9)       22.10.1969
(+ 07:30:00 3600)                08:30:00
(+ 03:00:00 23:59:59)            26:59:59

   See also @{"-" link "sub"}, @{"1+" link "1+"}, @{"*" link "mul"}, @{"CONCAT" link "CONCAT"}, @{"CONCAT2" link "CONCAT2"}, @{"ADDMONTH" link "ADDMONTH"}, @{"ADDYEAR" link "ADDYEAR"}.


@endnode

@node "sub" "MUIbase/sub"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

Subtracting Values
------------------

   For subtracting values, use

@{b}     (-@{ub} EXPR1 EXPR2 ...@{b})@{ub}

   Subtracts the sum of EXPR2 ... from EXPR1.  Here the same rules
apply as for adding values (see @{"+" link "add"}), except that strings and memos
can't be subtracted.

@{b}   (- @{ub}EXPR@{b})@{ub} has a special meaning, it returns the negative value of
EXPR (integer or real), e.g.  @{b}(- (+ 1 2))@{ub} results to -3.

   See also @{"+" link "add"}, @{"1-" link "1-"}.


@endnode

@node "1+" "MUIbase/1+"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

1+
--

@{b}   1+@{ub} increases an integer or real expression by one.

@{b}     (1+@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the value of EXPR (integer or real) plus one.  If EXPR is
NIL then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"+" link "add"}, @{"1-" link "1-"}.


@endnode

@node "1-" "MUIbase/1-"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

1-
--

@{b}   1-@{ub} decreases an integer or real expression by one.

@{b}     (1-@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the value of EXPR (integer or real) minus one.  If EXPR is
NIL then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"-" link "sub"}, @{"1+" link "1+"}.


@endnode

@node "mul" "MUIbase/mul"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

Multiplying Values
------------------

   For multiplying integer/real values, use

@{b}     (*@{ub} EXPR ...@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the multiplication of the integer/real values EXPR ....  If
all arguments are integers then an integer is returned, otherwise the
result is a value of type real.

   See also @{"+" link "add"}, @{"/" link "fdiv"}.


@endnode

@node "fdiv" "MUIbase/fdiv"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

Dividing Values
---------------

   For dividing integer/real values, use

@{b}     (/@{ub} EXPR1 [EXPR2 ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Divides EXPR1 by the multiplication of the rest of the arguments.
Returns a real value.  On division by zero, NIL is returned.

   See also @{"*" link "mul"}, @{"DIV" link "DIV"}, @{"MOD" link "MOD"}.


@endnode

@node "DIV" "MUIbase/DIV"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

DIV
---

@{b}   DIV@{ub} is used for integer division.

@{b}     (DIV@{ub} INT1 INT2@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the integer division of INT1 with INT2.  For example, @{b}(DIV 5
3)@{ub} results to 1.

   See also @{"/" link "fdiv"}, @{"MOD" link "MOD"}.


@endnode

@node "MOD" "MUIbase/MOD"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

MOD
---

@{b}   MOD@{ub} is used for modulo calculation.

@{b}     (MOD@{ub} INT1 INT2@{b})@{ub}

   Returns INT1 modulo INT2.  For example, @{b}(MOD 5 3)@{ub} results to 2.

   See also @{"DIV" link "DIV"}.


@endnode

@node "MAX" "MUIbase/MAX"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

MAX
---

@{b}   MAX@{ub} returns the argument that has the largest value.

@{b}     (MAX@{ub} EXPR ...@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the maximum value of the arguments EXPR ...  (all integers
or reals). If one of the expressions is NIL then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"MIN" link "MIN"}.


@endnode

@node "MIN" "MUIbase/MIN"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

MIN
---

@{b}   MIN@{ub} returns the argument that has the smallest value.

@{b}     (MIN@{ub} EXPR ...@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the minimum value of the arguments EXPR ...  (all integers
or reals). If one of the expressions is NIL then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"MAX" link "MAX"}.


@endnode

@node "ABS" "MUIbase/ABS"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

ABS
---

@{b}   ABS@{ub} computes the absolute value of an expression.

@{b}     (ABS@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the absolute value of EXPR (integer or real).  If EXPR is
NIL then NIL is returned.


@endnode

@node "TRUNC" "MUIbase/TRUNC"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

TRUNC
-----

@{b}   TRUNC@{ub} truncates decimals of a real value.

@{b}     (TRUNC@{ub} REAL@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the largest integer (as a real number) not greater than the
specified real number. If REAL is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Examples: @{b}(TRUNC 26.1)@{ub} results to 26, @{b}(TRUNC -1.2)@{ub} results to -2.

   See also @{"ROUND" link "ROUND"}.


@endnode

@node "ROUND" "MUIbase/ROUND"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

ROUND
-----

@{b}   ROUND@{ub} rounds a real value.

@{b}     (ROUND@{ub} REAL DIGITS@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the specified real number rounded to DIGITS decimal digits.
If REAL or DIGITS are NIL then NIL is returned.

   Examples: @{b}(ROUND 70.70859 2)@{ub} results to 70.71, @{b}(ROUND 392.36 -1)@{ub}
results to 390.0.

   See also @{"TRUNC" link "TRUNC"}.


@endnode

@node "RANDOM" "MUIbase/RANDOM"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

RANDOM
------

@{b}   RANDOM@{ub} can be used to generate random numbers.

@{b}     (RANDOM@{ub} EXPR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a random number. On the first call the random number
generator is initialized with a value generated from the current time.
@{b}RANDOM@{ub} generates a random number in the range of 0 ... EXPR, excluding
the value of EXPR itself.  The type of EXPR (integer or real) is the
return type.  If EXPR is NIL then NIL is returned.

Examples:
---------

@{b}Example@{ub}                 @{b}Meaning@{ub}

(RANDOM 10)             returns a value from 0 to 9,
(RANDOM 10.0)           returns a value from 0.0 to 9.99999...


@endnode

@node "POW" "MUIbase/POW"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

POW
---

@{b}   POW@{ub} computes the power of values.

@{b}     (POW@{ub} X Y@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the value of real value X raised to the power of real value
Y.  If either X or Y are NIL, or if X is negative and Y not an integral
number, then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(POW 2 3)@{ub} results to 8.

   See also @{"SQRT" link "SQRT"}, @{"EXP" link "EXP"}.


@endnode

@node "SQRT" "MUIbase/SQRT"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

SQRT
----

@{b}   SQRT@{ub} computes the square root of a number.

@{b}     (SQRT@{ub} X@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the square root of real value X.  If X is NIL or a negative
number then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"POW" link "POW"}.


@endnode

@node "EXP" "MUIbase/EXP"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

EXP
---

@{b}   EXP@{ub} computes the exponential function.

@{b}     (EXP@{ub} X@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the value of the base of the natural logarithm raised to the
power of real value X.  If X is NIL then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"POW" link "POW"}, @{"LOG" link "LOG"}.


@endnode

@node "LOG" "MUIbase/LOG"
@toc "Mathematical functions"

LOG
---

@{b}   LOG@{ub} computes the natural logarithm of a number.

@{b}     (LOG@{ub} X@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the natural logarithm of real value X.  If X is NIL or not a
positive number then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"EXP" link "EXP"}.


@endnode

@node "String functions" "MUIbase/String functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

String Functions
================

   This section deals with functions useful for strings.


 @{" LEN                " link "LEN"}  String length.
 @{" LEFTSTR            " link "LEFTSTR"}  Left sub string.
 @{" RIGHTSTR           " link "RIGHTSTR"}  Right sub string.
 @{" MIDSTR             " link "MIDSTR"}  Individual sub string.
 @{" SETMIDSTR          " link "SETMIDSTR"}  Replacing a sub string.
 @{" INSMIDSTR          " link "INSMIDSTR"}  Inserting a string.
 @{" INDEXSTR           " link "INDEXSTR"}  First occurrence of sub string, case-sensitive.
 @{" INDEXSTR*          " link "INDEXSTR*"}  First occurrence of sub string, case-insensitive.
 @{" INDEXBRK           " link "INDEXBRK"}  First occurrence of characters, case-sensitive.
 @{" INDEXBRK*          " link "INDEXBRK*"}  First occurrence of characters, case-insensitive.
 @{" RINDEXSTR          " link "RINDEXSTR"}  Last occurrence of sub string, case-sensitive.
 @{" RINDEXSTR*         " link "RINDEXSTR*"}  Last occurrence of sub string, case-insensitive.
 @{" RINDEXBRK          " link "RINDEXBRK"}  Last occurrence of characters, case-sensitive.
 @{" RINDEXBRK*         " link "RINDEXBRK*"}  Last occurrence of characters, case-insensitive.
 @{" REPLACESTR         " link "REPLACESTR"}  Replacing sub strings, case-sensitive.
 @{" REPLACESTR*        " link "REPLACESTR*"}  Replacing sub strings, case-insensitive.
 @{" REMCHARS           " link "REMCHARS"}  Removing characters from string.
 @{" TRIMSTR            " link "TRIMSTR"}  Removing leading and trailing characters.
 @{" WORD               " link "WORD"}  Extracting word in a string.
 @{" WORDS              " link "WORDS"}  Number of words in a string.
 @{" STRTOLIST          " link "STRTOLIST"}  Convert a string into a list of sub-strings.
 @{" LISTTOSTR          " link "LISTTOSTR"}  Convert a list of items into a string.
 @{" CONCAT             " link "CONCAT"}  Concatenating strings.
 @{" CONCAT2            " link "CONCAT2"}  Concatenating strings.
 @{" COPYSTR            " link "COPYSTR"}  Creates copies of a string.
 @{" SHA1SUM            " link "SHA1SUM"}  SHA1 hash of a string.
 @{" UPPER              " link "UPPER"}  Upper case string.
 @{" LOWER              " link "LOWER"}  Lower case string.
 @{" ASC                " link "ASC"}  Unicode/8-bit value of character.
 @{" CHR                " link "CHR"}  Character of Unicode/8-bit value.
 @{" LIKE               " link "LIKE"}  Comparing strings.
 @{" SPRINTF            " link "SPRINTF"}  String formatting.


@endnode

@node "LEN" "MUIbase/LEN"
@toc "String functions"

LEN
---

@{b}   LEN@{ub} computes the length of a string.

@{b}     (LEN@{ub} STR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the length of the given string or NIL if STR is NIL.

   See also @{"WORDS" link "WORDS"}, @{"LINES" link "LINES"}, @{"MAXLEN" link "MAXLEN"}.


@endnode

@node "LEFTSTR" "MUIbase/LEFTSTR"
@toc "String functions"

LEFTSTR
-------

@{b}   LEFTSTR@{ub} extracts a sub string out of a string.

@{b}     (LEFTSTR@{ub} STR LEN@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the left part of the given string with at most LEN
characters.  If STR or LEN are NIL or if LEN is negative then NIL is
returned.

   Example: @{b}(LEFTSTR "Hello world!" 5)@{ub} results to "Hello".

   See also @{"RIGHTSTR" link "RIGHTSTR"}, @{"MIDSTR" link "MIDSTR"}, @{"WORD" link "WORD"}, @{"LINE" link "LINE"}.


@endnode

@node "RIGHTSTR" "MUIbase/RIGHTSTR"
@toc "String functions"

RIGHTSTR
--------

@{b}   RIGHTSTR@{ub} extracts a sub string out of a string.

@{b}     (RIGHTSTR@{ub} STR LEN@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the right part of the given string with at most LEN
characters.  If STR or LEN are NIL or if LEN is negative then NIL is
returned.

   Example: @{b}(RIGHTSTR "Hello world!" 6)@{ub} results to "world!".

   See also @{"LEFTSTR" link "LEFTSTR"}, @{"MIDSTR" link "MIDSTR"}, @{"WORD" link "WORD"}, @{"LINE" link "LINE"}.


@endnode

@node "MIDSTR" "MUIbase/MIDSTR"
@toc "String functions"

MIDSTR
------

@{b}   MIDSTR@{ub} extracts a sub string out of a string.

@{b}     (MIDSTR@{ub} STR POS LEN@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a part of the given string with at most LEN characters.  The
sub string starts at the POS-th position (starting with zero).  If LEN
is NIL then the full sub string starting at POS is returned.  If STR is
NIL or if LEN is negative then NIL is returned.  If POS is out of
range, that is, negative or greater than the string length, NIL is
returned.

   Example: @{b}(MIDSTR "Hello world!" 3 5)@{ub} results to "lo wo".

   See also @{"LEFTSTR" link "LEFTSTR"}, @{"RIGHTSTR" link "RIGHTSTR"}, @{"WORD" link "WORD"}, @{"LINE" link "LINE"}, @{"SETMIDSTR" link "SETMIDSTR"}, @{"INSMIDSTR" link "INSMIDSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "SETMIDSTR" "MUIbase/SETMIDSTR"
@toc "String functions"

SETMIDSTR
---------

@{b}   SETMIDSTR@{ub} replaces a sub string in a string.

@{b}     (SETMIDSTR@{ub} STR INDEX SET@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a copy of string STR where the sub string starting at INDEX
is overwritten with string SET.  The length of the returned string is
greater or equal to the length of STR.  If one of the arguments is NIL
or if INDEX is out of range then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(SETMIDSTR "Hello world!" 6 "Melanie!")@{ub} results to "Hello
Melanie!".

   See also @{"INSMIDSTR" link "INSMIDSTR"}, @{"REPLACESTR" link "REPLACESTR"}.


@endnode

@node "INSMIDSTR" "MUIbase/INSMIDSTR"
@toc "String functions"

INSMIDSTR
---------

@{b}   INSMIDSTR@{ub} is used to insert a sub string into a string.

@{b}     (INSMIDSTR@{ub} STR INDEX INSERT@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a copy of string STR where the string INSERT has been
inserted at the given index.  If one of the arguments is NIL or if
INDEX is out of range then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(INSMIDSTR "Hello world!" 6 "MUIbase-")@{ub} results to "Hello
MUIbase-world!".

   See also @{"SETMIDSTR" link "SETMIDSTR"}, @{"REPLACESTR" link "REPLACESTR"}.


@endnode

@node "INDEXSTR" "MUIbase/INDEXSTR"
@toc "String functions"

INDEXSTR
--------

@{b}   INDEXSTR@{ub} searches a string for the first occurrence of a sub string.

@{b}     (INDEXSTR@{ub} STR SUBSTR@{b})@{ub}

   Searches for the first occurrence of SUBSTR in STR.  String
comparison is done case-sensitive.  Returns the index (starting with 0)
of the sub string in STR or NIL if the sub string is not present.  If
one of the arguments is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(INDEXSTR "Hello world!" "world")@{ub} returns 6.

   See also @{"INDEXSTR*" link "INDEXSTR*"}, @{"RINDEXSTR" link "RINDEXSTR"}, @{"RINDEXSTR*" link "RINDEXSTR*"}, @{"INDEXBRK" link "INDEXBRK"}, @{"INDEXBRK*" link "INDEXBRK*"}.


@endnode

@node "INDEXSTR*" "MUIbase/INDEXSTR*"
@toc "String functions"

INDEXSTR*
---------

@{b}   INDEXSTR*@{ub} has the same effect as @{b}INDEXSTR@{ub} (see @{"INDEXSTR" link "INDEXSTR"}) except
that string comparison is done case-insensitive.

   See also @{"INDEXSTR" link "INDEXSTR"}, @{"RINDEXSTR" link "RINDEXSTR"}, @{"RINDEXSTR*" link "RINDEXSTR*"}, @{"INDEXBRK" link "INDEXBRK"}, @{"INDEXBRK*" link "INDEXBRK*"}.


@endnode

@node "INDEXBRK" "MUIbase/INDEXBRK"
@toc "String functions"

INDEXBRK
--------

@{b}   INDEXBRK@{ub} searches for the first occurrence of a character in a
string.

@{b}     (INDEXBRK@{ub} STR BRKSTR@{b})@{ub}

   Searches for the first occurrence of a character from BRKSTR in STR.
String comparison is done case-sensitive.  Returns the index (starting
with 0) of the first character found in STR or NIL if no character is
found.  If one of the arguments is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(INDEXBRK "Hello world!" "aeiou")@{ub} returns 1.

   See also @{"INDEXBRK*" link "INDEXBRK*"}, @{"RINDEXBRK" link "RINDEXBRK"}, @{"RINDEXBRK*" link "RINDEXBRK*"}, @{"INDEXSTR" link "INDEXSTR"}, @{"INDEXSTR*" link "INDEXSTR*"}.


@endnode

@node "INDEXBRK*" "MUIbase/INDEXBRK*"
@toc "String functions"

INDEXBRK*
---------

@{b}   INDEXBRK*@{ub} has the same effect as @{b}INDEXBRK@{ub} (see @{"INDEXBRK" link "INDEXBRK"}) except
that string comparison is done case-insensitive.

   See also @{"INDEXBRK" link "INDEXBRK"}, @{"RINDEXBRK" link "RINDEXBRK"}, @{"RINDEXBRK*" link "RINDEXBRK*"}, @{"INDEXSTR" link "INDEXSTR"}, @{"INDEXSTR*" link "INDEXSTR*"}.


@endnode

@node "RINDEXSTR" "MUIbase/RINDEXSTR"
@toc "String functions"

RINDEXSTR
---------

@{b}   RINDEXSTR@{ub} searches a string for the last occurrence of a sub string.

@{b}     (RINDEXSTR@{ub} STR SUBSTR@{b})@{ub}

   Searches for the last occurrence of SUBSTR in STR.  String
comparison is done case-sensitive.  Returns the index (starting with 0)
of the sub string in STR or NIL if the sub string is not present.  If
one of the arguments is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(RINDEXSTR "Do itashimashite." "shi")@{ub} returns 11.

   See also @{"RINDEXSTR*" link "RINDEXSTR*"}, @{"INDEXSTR" link "INDEXSTR"}, @{"INDEXSTR*" link "INDEXSTR*"}, @{"RINDEXBRK" link "RINDEXBRK"}, @{"RINDEXBRK*" link "RINDEXBRK*"}.


@endnode

@node "RINDEXSTR*" "MUIbase/RINDEXSTR*"
@toc "String functions"

RINDEXSTR*
----------

@{b}   RINDEXSTR*@{ub} has the same effect as @{b}RINDEXSTR@{ub} (see @{"RINDEXSTR" link "RINDEXSTR"}) except
that string comparison is done case-insensitive.

   See also @{"RINDEXSTR" link "RINDEXSTR"}, @{"INDEXSTR" link "INDEXSTR"}, @{"INDEXSTR*" link "INDEXSTR*"}, @{"RINDEXBRK" link "RINDEXBRK"}, @{"RINDEXBRK*" link "RINDEXBRK*"}.


@endnode

@node "RINDEXBRK" "MUIbase/RINDEXBRK"
@toc "String functions"

RINDEXBRK
---------

@{b}   RINDEXBRK@{ub} searches for the last occurrence of a character in a
string.

@{b}     (RINDEXBRK@{ub} STR BRKSTR@{b})@{ub}

   Searches for the last occurrence of a character from BRKSTR in STR.
String comparison is done case-sensitive.  Returns the index (starting
with 0) of the last character found in STR or NIL if no character is
found.  If one of the arguments is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(RINDEXBRK "Konnichiwa" "chk")@{ub} returns 6.

   See also @{"RINDEXBRK*" link "RINDEXBRK*"}, @{"INDEXBRK" link "INDEXBRK"}, @{"INDEXBRK*" link "INDEXBRK*"}, @{"RINDEXSTR" link "RINDEXSTR"}, @{"RINDEXSTR*" link "RINDEXSTR*"}.


@endnode

@node "RINDEXBRK*" "MUIbase/RINDEXBRK*"
@toc "String functions"

RINDEXBRK*
----------

@{b}   RINDEXBRK*@{ub} has the same effect as @{b}RINDEXBRK@{ub} (see @{"RINDEXBRK" link "RINDEXBRK"}) except
that string comparison is done case-insensitive.

   See also @{"RINDEXBRK" link "RINDEXBRK"}, @{"INDEXBRK" link "INDEXBRK"}, @{"INDEXBRK*" link "INDEXBRK*"}, @{"RINDEXSTR" link "RINDEXSTR"}, @{"RINDEXSTR*" link "RINDEXSTR*"}.


@endnode

@node "REPLACESTR" "MUIbase/REPLACESTR"
@toc "String functions"

REPLACESTR
----------

@{b}   REPLACESTR@{ub} replaces sub strings by other strings.

@{b}     (REPLACESTR@{ub} STR [SUBSTR1 REPLACESTR1 ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Replaces all occurrences of SUBSTR1 in STR by REPLACESTR1.
Continues replacing further sub strings in the new string using the next
pair of search and replacement string until all arguments have been
processed.  Note that the number of arguments must be odd with
arguments at even positions specifying the search strings each followed
by the replacement string.  Due to the fact that the result of a
replacement is used in the next following replacement, multiple
replacements can take place.  This should be considered when using this
function.  A different order of the arguments might help resolving
conflicts since replacements are done from left to right.

   If any of the strings are NIL or any search string is empty then NIL
is returned.

   Example: @{b}(REPLACESTR "black is white" "black" "white" "white "black")@{ub}
results to "black is black".

   See also @{"REPLACESTR*" link "REPLACESTR*"}, @{"SETMIDSTR" link "SETMIDSTR"}, @{"INSMIDSTR" link "INSMIDSTR"}, @{"REMCHARS" link "REMCHARS"}.


@endnode

@node "REPLACESTR*" "MUIbase/REPLACESTR*"
@toc "String functions"

REPLACESTR*
-----------

@{b}   REPLACESTR*@{ub} has the same effect as @{b}REPLACESTR@{ub} (see @{"REPLACESTR" link "REPLACESTR"})
except that string comparison is done case-insensitive for searching
sub strings.

   See also @{"REPLACESTR" link "REPLACESTR"}, @{"SETMIDSTR" link "SETMIDSTR"}, @{"INSMIDSTR" link "INSMIDSTR"}, @{"REMCHARS" link "REMCHARS"}.


@endnode

@node "REMCHARS" "MUIbase/REMCHARS"
@toc "String functions"

REMCHARS
--------

@{b}   REMCHARS@{ub} removes characters from a string.

@{b}     (REMCHARS@{ub} STR CHARS-TO-REMOVE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a copy of STR where all characters of CHARS-TO-REMOVE are
removed from.  If STR or CHARS-TO-REMOVE are NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(REMCHARS YOUR-STRING " \\t\\n")@{ub} removes all spaces, tabs
and newline characters from YOUR-STRING.

   See also @{"REPLACESTR" link "REPLACESTR"}, @{"TRIMSTR" link "TRIMSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "TRIMSTR" "MUIbase/TRIMSTR"
@toc "String functions"

TRIMSTR
-------

@{b}   TRIMSTR@{ub} removes leading and trailing characters from a string.

@{b}     (TRIMSTR@{ub} STR [FRONT BACK]@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a copy of STR where leading and trailing characters have
been removed.  If called with one argument only, spaces, form-feeds,
newlines, carriage returns, and horizontal and vertical tabs are
removed.  When called with three arguments, FRONT specifies the leading
and BACK specifies the trailing characters to be removed.  Note that
@{b}TRIMSTR@{ub} cannot be called with two arguments.

   If any of STR, FRONT, or BACK is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(TRIMSTR "  I wrecked Selma's bike.  ")@{ub}  results to "I
wrecked Selma's bike.", @{b}(TRIMSTR "007 " "0" " \\f\\n\\r\\t\\v")@{ub} results
to "7".

   See also @{"REMCHARS" link "REMCHARS"}.


@endnode

@node "WORD" "MUIbase/WORD"
@toc "String functions"

WORD
----

@{b}   WORD@{ub} returns a word of a string.

@{b}     (WORD@{ub} STR NUM@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the NUM-th word (starting with zero) of the given string.
Words in a string are non-empty sub strings separated by space-like
characters (e.g. space, tab or newline characters).

   If STR or NUM are NIL, or if NUM is out of range, that is, less than
zero or greater or equal to the number of words, then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(WORD "Therefore, I lend Selma my bike." 3)@{ub} results to
"Selma".

   See also @{"WORDS" link "WORDS"}, @{"LINE" link "LINE"}, @{"LEFTSTR" link "LEFTSTR"}, @{"RIGHTSTR" link "RIGHTSTR"}, @{"MIDSTR" link "MIDSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "WORDS" "MUIbase/WORDS"
@toc "String functions"

WORDS
-----

@{b}   WORDS@{ub} counts the number of words in a string.

@{b}     (WORDS@{ub} STR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the number of words of the given string or NIL if STR is
NIL.  Words are sub strings separated by space-like characters (e.g.
space, tab, or newline characters).

   Example: @{b}(WORDS "Actually, it wasn't really my bike.")@{ub} results to 6.

   See also @{"WORD" link "WORD"}, @{"LINES" link "LINES"}, @{"LEN" link "LEN"}.


@endnode

@node "STRTOLIST" "MUIbase/STRTOLIST"
@toc "String functions"

STRTOLIST
---------

@{b}   STRTOLIST@{ub} converts a string to a list of sub-strings.

@{b}     (STRTOLIST@{ub} STR [SEP]@{b})@{ub}

   Creates a list of sub-strings by breaking the string STR at the
occurences of the separation sequence SEP.  If SEP is not specified
then the tab character @{b}"\\t"@{ub} is used.  If SEP is the empty string @{b}""@{ub}
then a list of all characters in the string is returned.

   If STR or SEP are NIL then NIL is returned.

Examples
--------

@{b}   (STRTOLIST "I\\tlike\\tJapan.")@{ub} results to ( "I" "like" "Japan." ).

@{b}   (STRTOLIST "Name|Street|City" "|")@{ub} results to ( "Name" "Street"
"City" ).

@{b}   (STRTOLIST "abc" "")@{ub} results to ( "a" "b" "c" ).

   See also @{"MEMOTOLIST" link "MEMOTOLIST"}, @{"LISTTOSTR" link "LISTTOSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "LISTTOSTR" "MUIbase/LISTTOSTR"
@toc "String functions"

LISTTOSTR
---------

@{b}   LISTTOSTR@{ub} converts a list of items into a string.

@{b}     (LISTTOSTR@{ub} LIST [SEP]@{b})@{ub}

   Converts the given list of items into a string by concatenation of
the string representations of each list element separated by the
sequence SEP.  If SEP is not specified then the tab character @{b}"\\t"@{ub} is
used.  If LIST or SEP are NIL then NIL is returned.

Examples
--------

@{b}   (LISTTOSTR (LIST "Peter is" 18 "years old"))@{ub} results to: "Peter
is\\t18\\tyears old".

@{b}   (LISTTOSTR (LIST "Name" "Street" "City") "|")@{ub} results to:
"Name|Street|City".

   See also @{"LISTTOMEMO" link "LISTTOMEMO"}, @{"CONCAT" link "CONCAT"}, @{"CONCAT2" link "CONCAT2"}, @{"STRTOLIST" link "STRTOLIST"}.


@endnode

@node "CONCAT" "MUIbase/CONCAT"
@toc "String functions"

CONCAT
------

@{b}   CONCAT@{ub} concatenates strings.

@{b}     (CONCAT@{ub} [STR ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the concatenation of the given list of strings where space
characters have been inserted between the strings.  If one of the
strings is NIL, or the list is empty, then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(CONCAT "I" "thought" "it" "was" "an "abandoned" "bike.")@{ub}
results to "I thought it was an abandoned bike.".

   See also @{"CONCAT2" link "CONCAT2"}, @{"+" link "add"}, @{"LISTTOSTR" link "LISTTOSTR"}, @{"COPYSTR" link "COPYSTR"}, @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}.


@endnode

@node "CONCAT2" "MUIbase/CONCAT2"
@toc "String functions"

CONCAT2
-------

@{b}   CONCAT2@{ub} concatenates strings.

@{b}     (CONCAT2@{ub} INSERT [STR ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the concatenation of the given list of strings. The strings
will be separated with the given INSERT string.  If INSERT is NIL, one
of the strings is NIL, or the list is empty, then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(CONCAT2 "! " "But" "it" "wasn't!")@{ub} results to "But! it!
wasn't!".

   See also @{"CONCAT" link "CONCAT"}, @{"+" link "add"}, @{"LISTTOSTR" link "LISTTOSTR"}, @{"COPYSTR" link "COPYSTR"}, @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}.


@endnode

@node "COPYSTR" "MUIbase/COPYSTR"
@toc "String functions"

COPYSTR
-------

@{b}   COPYSTR@{ub} creates copies of a string.

@{b}     (COPYSTR@{ub} STR NUM@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a string consisting of NUM times the string STR.  If STR is
NIL, NUM is NIL or less than zero, NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(COPYSTR "+-" 5)@{ub} results to "+-+-+-+-+-".

   See also @{"CONCAT" link "CONCAT"} @{"CONCAT2" link "CONCAT2"}, @{"+" link "add"}, @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}.


@endnode

@node "SHA1SUM" "MUIbase/SHA1SUM"
@toc "String functions"

SHA1SUM
-------

@{b}   SHA1SUM@{ub} computes the SHA1 hash of a string.

@{b}     (SHA1SUM@{ub} STR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a string containing the SHA1 hash of the given string.  If
STR is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(SHA1SUM "flower, sun and beach")@{ub} results to
"47b6c496493c512b40e042337c128d85ecf15ba4".

   See also @{"ADMINPASSWORD" link "ADMINPASSWORD"}, demo @{b}Users.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "UPPER" "MUIbase/UPPER"
@toc "String functions"

UPPER
-----

@{b}   UPPER@{ub} converts a string to upper case.

@{b}     (UPPER@{ub} STR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a copy of the given string where all characters are
converted to upper case.  If STR is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(UPPER "Selma found a letter attached to my bike.")@{ub} results
to "SELMA FOUND A LETTER ATTACHED TO MY BIKE.".

   See also @{"LOWER" link "LOWER"}.


@endnode

@node "LOWER" "MUIbase/LOWER"
@toc "String functions"

LOWER
-----

@{b}   LOWER@{ub} converts a string to lower case.

@{b}     (LOWER@{ub} STR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a copy of the given string where all characters are
converted to lower case.  If STR is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(LOWER "The letter was from Silke.")@{ub} results to "the letter
was from silke.".

   See also @{"UPPER" link "UPPER"}.


@endnode

@node "ASC" "MUIbase/ASC"
@toc "String functions"

ASC
---

@{b}   ASC@{ub} converts a character to its internal integer representation.

@{b}     (ASC@{ub} STR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the internal integer code of the first character of STR.  On
Windows, Mac OS and Linux this is the unicode representation.  On
Amiga, it is the 8-bit integer code in the default character encoding.
If STR is empty, 0 is returned.  If STR is NIL, NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(ASC "A")@{ub} results to 65.

   See also @{"CHR" link "CHR"}, @{"INT" link "INT"}.


@endnode

@node "CHR" "MUIbase/CHR"
@toc "String functions"

CHR
---

@{b}   CHR@{ub} converts an integer code to a character.

@{b}     (CHR@{ub} INT@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a string containing the character with integer code INT.  On
Windows, Mac OS and Linux, INT is interpreted as a unicode character.
On Amiga, INT is the 8-bit integer in the default character encoding.
If INT is 0, an empty string is returned.  If INT is NIL or not in the
range of valid character values, NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(CHR 67)@{ub} results to "C".

   See also @{"ASC" link "ASC"}, @{"STR" link "STR"}.


@endnode

@node "LIKE" "MUIbase/LIKE"
@toc "String functions"

LIKE
----

@{b}   LIKE@{ub} compares strings.

@{b}     (LIKE@{ub} STR1 STR2@{b})@{ub}

   Returns TRUE if STR1 matches STR2, NIL otherwise.  The string STR2
may contain the joker characters '?' and '*' where '?' matches exactly
one character and '*' matches a string of any length. String comparison
is done case insensitive.

   Example: @{b}(LIKE "Silke has been in France for one year." "*France*")@{ub}
results to TRUE.

   See also @{"Comparison functions" link "Comparison functions"}.


@endnode

@node "SPRINTF" "MUIbase/SPRINTF"
@toc "String functions"

SPRINTF
-------

@{b}   SPRINTF@{ub} formats a string with various data.

@{b}     (SPRINTF@{ub} FMT [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

@{b}   SPRINTF@{ub} takes a series of arguments, converts them to strings, and
returns the formatted information as one string.  The string FMT
determines exactly what gets written to the return string and may
contain two types of items: ordinary characters which are always copied
verbatim and conversion specifiers which direct @{b}SPRINTF@{ub} to take
arguments from its argument list and format them.  Conversion
specifiers always begin with a @{b}%@{ub} character.

   Conversion specifiers always take the following form:

@{b}     %@{ub}[FLAGS][WIDTH][@{b}.@{ub}PRECISION]TYPE

where

   * The optional FLAGS field controls output justification, sign
     character on numerical values, decimal points, and trailing blanks.

   * The optional WIDTH field specifies the minimum number of
     characters to print (the field width), with padding done with
     blanks or zeros.

   * The optional PRECISION field specifies either the maximum number
     of characters to be printed for types string, Boolean, date and
     time, or the number of digits after the decimal point to be
     printed for values of type real.

   * The TYPE field specifies the actual type of the argument that
     @{b}SPRINTF@{ub} will be converting, such as string, integer, real, etc.

   Note that all of the above fields are optional except for TYPE.  The
following tables list the valid options for these fields.

Flags field
-----------

-:
     The result is left justified, with padding done on the right using
     blanks.  By default when @{b}-@{ub} is not specified, the result is right
     justified with padding on the left with @{b}0@{ub}'s or blanks.

+:
     The result will always have a @{b}-@{ub} or @{b}+@{ub} character prepended to it if
     it is a numeric conversion.

0:
     For numbers padding on the left is done using leading zeros
     instead of spaces.

@{i}space@{ui}:
     Positive numbers begin with a space instead of a @{b}+@{ub} character, but
     negative values still have a prepended @{b}-@{ub}.

Width field
-----------

N:
     A minimum of N characters are output.  If the conversion has less
     than N characters, the field is padded with blanks or leading
     zeros.

*:
     The width specifier is supplied in the argument list as an integer
     or real value, before the actual conversion argument.  This value
     is limited to the range of 0 to 999.

Precision field
---------------

.N:
     For string, Boolean, date and time values, N is the maximum number
     of characters written from the converted item.  For conversions of
     real values, N specifies the number of digits after the decimal
     point (conversions @{b}f@{ub} and @{b}e@{ub}) or the number of significant digits
     (conversion @{b}g@{ub}).  For integer conversions this field is ignored.

.*:
     The precision is supplied in the argument list as an integer or
     real value, before the actual conversion argument.  This value is
     limited to the range of 0 to 999.

Type field
----------

b:
     Converts a Boolean parameter to "TRUE" or "NIL".

i:
     Converts an integer value to a signed decimal notation.

o:
     Converts an integer value to an unsigned octal notation.

x:
     Converts an integer value to an unsigned hexadecimal notation
     using lowercase letters @{b}abcdef@{ub}.

X:
     Converts an integer value to an unsigned hexadecimal notation
     using uppercase letters @{b}ABCDEF@{ub}.

e:
     Converts a real number using the format [-]d.ddde+dd.  Exactly one
     digit is before the decimal point, followed by an @{b}e@{ub}, followed by
     an exponent. The number of digits after the decimal point is
     determined by the precision field, or is 2 if precision is not
     specified. The decimal point will not appear if precision is 0.

f:
     Converts a real value using the format [-]ddd.ddd.  The number of
     digits after the decimal point is determined by the precision
     field, or is 2 if precision is not specified.  The decimal point
     will not appear if precision is 0.

g:
     Converts a real value using style @{b}e@{ub} or @{b}f@{ub} depending on the number
     of digits for representing the value.  If the precision is not
     specified then 15 significant digits are used.  Trailing zeros
     other than a single zero after the decimal point are removed.

s:
     Writes a string value until either the end of string is reached or
     the number of characters written equals the precision field.

d:
     Converts a date value.

t:
     Converts a time value.

%:
     The character @{b}%@{ub} is written, and no argument is converted.

@{b}   SPRINTF@{ub} returns the formatted string or NIL in case FMT is NIL.

Examples
--------

@{b}Call@{ub}                      @{b}Result@{ub}

(SPRINTF "Hello")                "Hello"
(SPRINTF "%s" "Hello")           "Hello"
(SPRINTF "%10s" "Hello")         "     Hello"
(SPRINTF "%-10.10s" "Hello")     "Hello     "
(SPRINTF "%010.3s" "Hello")      "       Hel"
(SPRINTF "%-5.3b" TRUE)          "TRU  "
(SPRINTF "%i" 3)                 "3"
(SPRINTF "%03i" 3)               "003"
(SPRINTF "%0- 5.3i" 3)           " 3   "
(SPRINTF "%f" 12)                "12.00"
(SPRINTF "%10e" 12.0)            "  1.20e+01"
(SPRINTF "%+-10.4f" 12.0)        "+12.0000  "
(SPRINTF "%10.5t" 12:30:00)      "     12:30"
(SPRINTF "%d" 28.11.1968)        "28.11.1968"
(SPRINTF "He%s %5.5s!"
   "llo"
   "world champion ship")        "Hello world!"

   See also @{"PRINTF" link "PRINTF"}, @{"FPRINTF" link "FPRINTF"}, @{"STR" link "STR"}, @{"+" link "add"}, @{"CONCAT" link "CONCAT"}, @{"CONCAT2" link "CONCAT2"}, @{"COPYSTR" link "COPYSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "Memo functions" "MUIbase/Memo functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Memo Functions
==============

   This section deals with functions useful for memos.


 @{" LINE               " link "LINE"}  Extracting a line in a memo.
 @{" LINES              " link "LINES"}  Number of lines in a memo.
 @{" MEMOTOLIST         " link "MEMOTOLIST"}  Converting memo into list.
 @{" LISTTOMEMO         " link "LISTTOMEMO"}  Converting list into memo.
 @{" FILLMEMO           " link "FILLMEMO"}  Filling in a memo.
 @{" FORMATMEMO         " link "FORMATMEMO"}  Formatting a memo.
 @{" INDENTMEMO         " link "INDENTMEMO"}  Indenting a memo.


@endnode

@node "LINE" "MUIbase/LINE"
@toc "Memo functions"

LINE
----

@{b}   LINE@{ub} extracts a line in a memo.

@{b}     (LINE@{ub} MEMO NUM@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the NUM-th line (starting with zero) of the given memo.  The
line string will not have a terminating newline character.  If MEMO or
NUM are NIL or if NUM is out of range, that is, less than zero or
greater or equal to the number of lines, then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"LINES" link "LINES"}, @{"WORD" link "WORD"}.


@endnode

@node "LINES" "MUIbase/LINES"
@toc "Memo functions"

LINES
-----

@{b}   LINES@{ub} returns the number of lines in a memo.

@{b}     (LINES@{ub} MEMO@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the number of lines of the given memo or NIL if MEMO is NIL.

   See also @{"LINE" link "LINE"}, @{"WORDS" link "WORDS"}, @{"LEN" link "LEN"}.


@endnode

@node "MEMOTOLIST" "MUIbase/MEMOTOLIST"
@toc "Memo functions"

MEMOTOLIST
----------

@{b}   MEMOTOLIST@{ub} converts a memo into a list of strings.

@{b}     (MEMOTOLIST@{ub} MEMO [EXPANDSTR]@{b})@{ub}

   Converts the given memo to a list. If MEMO is NIL then NIL is
returned, otherwise a list is generated where each element contains one
line of the memo.

   If EXPANDSTR is given and is not NIL then resulting list of strings
is further processed by applying @{b}STRTOLIST@{ub} to each list element.  This
results into a list of lists of strings.

Examples
--------

@{b}   (MEMOTOLIST "My insurance\\npays for\\nthe wrecked bike.")@{ub} results
to ( "My insurance" "pays for" "the wrecked bike." ).

@{b}   (MEMOTOLIST "Here is\\ta multi-columned\\nexample." TRUE)@{ub} results to
( ( "Here is" "a multi-columned" ) ( "example" ) ).

   See also @{"STRTOLIST" link "STRTOLIST"}, @{"LISTTOMEMO" link "LISTTOMEMO"}.


@endnode

@node "LISTTOMEMO" "MUIbase/LISTTOMEMO"
@toc "Memo functions"

LISTTOMEMO
----------

@{b}   LISTTOMEMO@{ub} converts a list into a memo.

@{b}     (LISTTOMEMO@{ub} LIST@{b})@{ub}

   Converts the given list into a memo. If LIST is NIL then NIL is
returned, otherwise a memo is generated where each line consists of the
string representation of the corresponding list element.  If a list
element is a sub-list then @{b}LISTTOSTR@{ub} (see @{"LISTTOSTR" link "LISTTOSTR"}) is applied on it
before integrating the resulting string into the memo.

Examples
--------

@{b}   (LISTTOMEMO (LIST "Silke" "lends me" "'my' bike" "till" 01.09.1998)@{ub}
results to: "Silke\\nlends me\\n'my' bike\\ntill\\n01.09.1998".

@{b}   (LISTTOMEMO (LIST (LIST "Name" "Birthday") (LIST "Steffen"
28.11.1968)@{ub} results to: "Name\\tBirthday\\nSteffen\\t28.11.1968".

   See also @{"LISTTOSTR" link "LISTTOSTR"}, @{"MEMOTOLIST" link "MEMOTOLIST"}.


@endnode

@node "FILLMEMO" "MUIbase/FILLMEMO"
@toc "Memo functions"

FILLMEMO
--------

@{b}   FILLMEMO@{ub} fills in a memo with the results of expressions.

@{b}     (FILLMEMO@{ub} MEMO@{b})@{ub}

   Creates a copy of the given memo where all substrings of the form
@{b}$(EXPR)@{ub} are replaced by their results after evaluation.

   Example: @{b}(FILLMEMO "(+ 1 1) is $(+ 1 1).")@{ub} results to "(+ 1 1) is 2."

   Please use only small expressions in the memo as debugging and
tracking down errors is not easy here.

   See also @{"FORMATMEMO" link "FORMATMEMO"}, @{"INDENTMEMO" link "INDENTMEMO"}.


@endnode

@node "FORMATMEMO" "MUIbase/FORMATMEMO"
@toc "Memo functions"

FORMATMEMO
----------

@{b}   FORMATMEMO@{ub} formats a memo.

@{b}     (FORMATMEMO@{ub} MEMO WIDTH [FILL [SINGLELINESEC]]@{b})@{ub}

   Formats MEMO to a memo with lines not longer than WIDTH characters.
If FILL is given and non-NIL then spaces are used to pad the lines to
exactly WIDTH characters.  The memo is processed section-wise.  A
section starts at the first non-white-space character.  If
SINGLELINESEC is specified and non-NIL then all characters until the
end of this line are taken as the section.  Otherwise, all characters
on this and the following lines are counted as the section until a line
starting with a white-space character is reached.  The whole section is
formated word-wise, that is, as many words are put on one line as there
are space for.  Remaining words are then put on the next line and so on.

   See also @{"FILLMEMO" link "FILLMEMO"}, @{"INDENTMEMO" link "INDENTMEMO"}.


@endnode

@node "INDENTMEMO" "MUIbase/INDENTMEMO"
@toc "Memo functions"

INDENTMEMO
----------

@{b}   INDENTMEMO@{ub} indents a memo by putting spaces to the left.

@{b}     (INDENTMEMO@{ub} MEMO INDENT@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a copy of the given memo where each line is indented by
INDENT space characters.  If MEMO or INDENT is NIL then NIL is returned.
If INDENT is negative, a value of 0 is used.

   See also @{"FILLMEMO" link "FILLMEMO"}, @{"FORMATMEMO" link "FORMATMEMO"}.


@endnode

@node "Date and time functions" "MUIbase/Date and time functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Date and Time Functions
=======================

   This section deals with functions useful for date and time values.


 @{" DAY        " link "DAY"}  Extracting day field of a date.
 @{" MONTH      " link "MONTH"}  Extracting month field of a date.
 @{" YEAR       " link "YEAR"}  Extracting year field of a date.
 @{" DATEDMY    " link "DATEDMY"}  Creating date value from day, month and year.
 @{" MONTHDAYS  " link "MONTHDAYS"}  Number of days of a month.
 @{" YEARDAYS   " link "YEARDAYS"}  Number of days of a year.
 @{" ADDMONTH   " link "ADDMONTH"}  Adding a number of months to a date value.
 @{" ADDYEAR    " link "ADDYEAR"}  Adding a number of years to a date value.
 @{" TODAY      " link "TODAY"}  Getting current date.
 @{" NOW        " link "NOW"}  Getting current time.


@endnode

@node "DAY" "MUIbase/DAY"
@toc "Date and time functions"

DAY
---

@{b}   DAY@{ub} extracts the day field of a date.

@{b}     (DAY@{ub} DATE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns an integer representing the day of the given date value.  If
DATE is NIL then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"MONTH" link "MONTH"}, @{"YEAR" link "YEAR"}, @{"DATEDMY" link "DATEDMY"}.


@endnode

@node "MONTH" "MUIbase/MONTH"
@toc "Date and time functions"

MONTH
-----

@{b}   MONTH@{ub} extracts the month field of a date.

@{b}     (MONTH@{ub} DATE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns an integer representing the month of the given date value.
If DATE is NIL then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"DAY" link "DAY"}, @{"YEAR" link "YEAR"}, @{"DATEDMY" link "DATEDMY"}, @{"MONTHDAYS" link "MONTHDAYS"}.


@endnode

@node "YEAR" "MUIbase/YEAR"
@toc "Date and time functions"

YEAR
----

@{b}   YEAR@{ub} extracts the year field of a date.

@{b}     (YEAR@{ub} DATE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns an integer representing the year of the given date value.
If DATE is NIL then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"DAY" link "DAY"}, @{"MONTH" link "MONTH"}, @{"DATEDMY" link "DATEDMY"}, @{"YEARDAYS" link "YEARDAYS"}.


@endnode

@node "DATEDMY" "MUIbase/DATEDMY"
@toc "Date and time functions"

DATEDMY
-------

@{b}   DATEDMY@{ub} creates a date value from day, month, and year.

@{b}     (DATEDMY@{ub} DAY MONTH YEAR@{b})@{ub}

   Creates a date value from the given day, month, and year.  If any of
DAY, MONTH, or YEAR is NIL or out of the valid range, or if the
resulting date is invalid, then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(DATEDMY 28 11 1968)@{ub} results to the 28th of November, 1968.

   See also @{"DATE" link "DATE"}, @{"TODAY" link "TODAY"}, @{"DAY" link "DAY"}, @{"MONTH" link "MONTH"}, @{"YEAR" link "YEAR"}.


@endnode

@node "MONTHDAYS" "MUIbase/MONTHDAYS"
@toc "Date and time functions"

MONTHDAYS
---------

@{b}   MONTHDAYS@{ub} gets the number of days of a month.

@{b}     (MONTHDAYS@{ub} MONTH YEAR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the number of days of the given month and year as an integer.
If MONTH is NIL or out of the valid range (less than 1 or greater than
12) then NIL is returned.  If YEAR is NIL then a non-leap year is
considered for computing the number of days.  If YEAR is invalid (less
than 0 or greater than 9999) then NIL is returned.

   Examples: @{b}(MONTHDAYS 2 2004)@{ub} results to 29, @{b}(MONTHDAYS 2 NIL)@{ub}
results to 28.

   See also @{"YEARDAYS" link "YEARDAYS"}, @{"MONTH" link "MONTH"}.


@endnode

@node "YEARDAYS" "MUIbase/YEARDAYS"
@toc "Date and time functions"

YEARDAYS
--------

@{b}   YEARDAYS@{ub} gets the number of days of a year.

@{b}     (YEARDAYS@{ub} YEAR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the number of days of the given year as an integer.  If YEAR
is NIL or out of the valid range (less than 0 or greater than 9999)
then NIL is returned.

   Examples: @{b}(YEARDAYS 2004)@{ub} results to 366, @{b}(YEARDAYS 2005)@{ub} results to
365.

   See also @{"MONTHDAYS" link "MONTHDAYS"}, @{"YEAR" link "YEAR"}.


@endnode

@node "ADDMONTH" "MUIbase/ADDMONTH"
@toc "Date and time functions"

ADDMONTH
--------

@{b}   ADDMONTH@{ub} adds a number of months to a date.

@{b}     (ADDMONTH@{ub} DATE MONTHS@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a date value where the given number of months has been added
to the given date value.  Negative values for MONTHS subtract months.
If DATE or MONTHS is NIL, or the resulting date is invalid, then NIL is
returned.

@{b}   ADDMONTH@{ub} handles over- and underflow of the month field by adjusting
the year field accordingly.  In case the day field exceeds the maximum
number of days of the resulting month, it is decremented to the maximum
allowed day.

   Examples: @{b}(ADDMONTH 30.01.2004 1)@{ub} results to 29.02.2004, @{b}(ADDMONTH
30.01.2004 -1)@{ub} results to 30.12.2003.

   See also @{"ADDYEAR" link "ADDYEAR"}, @{"+" link "add"}.


@endnode

@node "ADDYEAR" "MUIbase/ADDYEAR"
@toc "Date and time functions"

ADDYEAR
-------

@{b}   ADDYEAR@{ub} adds a number of years to a date.

@{b}     (ADDYEAR@{ub} DATE YEARS@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a date value where the given number of years has been added
to the given date value.  Negative values for YEARS subtract years.  If
DATE or YEARS is NIL, or the resulting date is invalid, then NIL is
returned.

@{b}   ADDYEAR@{ub} decrements the day field by 1 in case DATE represents
February 29th and the resulting year is not a leap year.

   Examples: @{b}(ADDYEAR 29.02.2004 1)@{ub} results to 28.02.2005, @{b}(ADDMONTH
04.02.2004 -1962)@{ub} results to 04.02.0042.

   See also @{"ADDMONTH" link "ADDMONTH"}, @{"+" link "add"}.


@endnode

@node "TODAY" "MUIbase/TODAY"
@toc "Date and time functions"

TODAY
-----

@{b}   TODAY@{ub} returns the current date.

@{b}     (TODAY)@{ub}

   Returns the current date as a date value.

   See also @{"NOW" link "NOW"}, @{"DATEDMY" link "DATEDMY"}.


@endnode

@node "NOW" "MUIbase/NOW"
@toc "Date and time functions"

NOW
---

@{b}   NOW@{ub} returns the current time.

@{b}     (NOW)@{ub}

   Returns the current time as a time value.

   See also @{"TODAY" link "TODAY"}.


@endnode

@node "List functions" "MUIbase/List functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

List Functions
==============

   This section lists functions for processing lists.


 @{" CONS               " link "CONS"}  Elementary list constructor.
 @{" LIST               " link "LIST"}  Generating a list of elements.
 @{" LENGTH             " link "LENGTH"}  Getting number of list elements.
 @{" FIRST              " link "FIRST"}  Extracting first element of a list.
 @{" REST               " link "REST"}  Getting remainder of a list.
 @{" LAST               " link "LAST"}  Extracting last element of a list.
 @{" NTH                " link "NTH"}  Extracting n-th element of a list.
 @{" APPEND             " link "APPEND"}  Concatenating lists.
 @{" REVERSE            " link "REVERSE"}  Reversing a list.
 @{" MAPFIRST           " link "MAPFIRST"}  Applying a function to all list elements.
 @{" SORTLIST           " link "SORTLIST"}  Sorting elements of a list.
 @{" SORTLISTGT         " link "SORTLISTGT"}  Sorting elements of a list.


@endnode

@node "CONS" "MUIbase/CONS"
@toc "List functions"

CONS
----

@{b}   CONS@{ub} builds a pair of expressions.

@{b}     (CONS@{ub} ELEM LIST@{b})@{ub}

   Constructs a new list. The first element of the new list is ELEM,
the rest are the elements of LIST (which should be a list or NIL).  The
list LIST is not copied, only a pointer is used to reference it!

   Example: @{b}(CONS 1 (CONS 2 NIL))@{ub} results to ( 1 2 ).

   The elements of a list can be of any type, e.g. it's also possible
to have a list of lists (e.g. see @{"SELECT" link "SELECT"}).  The @{b}CONS@{ub} constructor can
also be used to build pairs of elements, e.g.  @{b}(CONS 1 2)@{ub} is the pair
with the two integers 1 and 2.

   See also @{"LIST" link "LIST"}, @{"FIRST" link "FIRST"}, @{"REST" link "REST"}.


@endnode

@node "LIST" "MUIbase/LIST"
@toc "List functions"

LIST
----

@{b}   LIST@{ub} generates a list out of its arguments.

@{b}     (LIST@{ub} [ELEM ...]@{b})@{ub}

takes the arguments ELEM ... and generates a list of it.  This is
equivalent to calling @{b}(CONS@{ub} ELEM @{b}(CONS@{ub} ... @{b}NIL))@{ub}.  Note that NIL alone
stands for an empty list.

   See also @{"CONS" link "CONS"}, @{"LENGTH" link "LENGTH"}.


@endnode

@node "LENGTH" "MUIbase/LENGTH"
@toc "List functions"

LENGTH
------

@{b}   LENGTH@{ub} determines the length of a list.

@{b}     (LENGTH@{ub} LIST@{b})@{ub}

returns the length of the given list.

   Example: @{b}(LENGTH (LIST "a" 2 42 3))@{ub} results to 4.

   See also @{"LIST" link "LIST"}.


@endnode

@node "FIRST" "MUIbase/FIRST"
@toc "List functions"

FIRST
-----

@{b}   FIRST@{ub} extracts the first element in a list.

@{b}     (FIRST@{ub} LIST@{b})@{ub}

returns the first element of the given list. If LIST is empty (NIL)
then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"REST" link "REST"}, @{"LAST" link "LAST"}, @{"NTH" link "NTH"}, @{"CONS" link "CONS"}.


@endnode

@node "REST" "MUIbase/REST"
@toc "List functions"

REST
----

@{b}   REST@{ub} returns the sub-list after the first element of a list.

@{b}     (REST@{ub} LIST@{b})@{ub}

returns the rest of the given list (the list without the first
element). If LIST is empty (NIL) then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(REST (LIST 1 2 3))@{ub} results to ( 2 3 ).

   See also @{"FIRST" link "FIRST"}, @{"CONS" link "CONS"}.


@endnode

@node "LAST" "MUIbase/LAST"
@toc "List functions"

LAST
----

@{b}   LAST@{ub} extracts the last element in a list.

@{b}     (LAST@{ub} LIST@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the last element of the given list or NIL if LIST is NIL.

   See also @{"FIRST" link "FIRST"}, @{"NTH" link "NTH"}.


@endnode

@node "NTH" "MUIbase/NTH"
@toc "List functions"

NTH
---

@{b}   NTH@{ub} extracts the n-th element of a list.

@{b}     (NTH@{ub} N LIST@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the N-th element of the given list (starting with 0) or NIL
if the element doesn't exist.

   See also @{"FIRST" link "FIRST"}, @{"LAST" link "LAST"}.


@endnode

@node "APPEND" "MUIbase/APPEND"
@toc "List functions"

APPEND
------

@{b}   APPEND@{ub} concatenates lists.

@{b}     (APPEND@{ub} [LIST ...]@{b})@{ub}

returns the concatenation of LIST ....

   Example: @{b}(APPEND (list 1 2) (list 3 4) (list 5))@{ub} results to ( 1 2 3
4 5 ).

   See also @{"LIST" link "LIST"}.


@endnode

@node "REVERSE" "MUIbase/REVERSE"
@toc "List functions"

REVERSE
-------

@{b}   REVERSE@{ub} reverses a list.

@{b}     (REVERSE@{ub} LIST@{b})@{ub}

returns the reverse list.

   Example: @{b}(REVERSE (list 1 2 3))@{ub} results to ( 3 2 1 ).


@endnode

@node "MAPFIRST" "MUIbase/MAPFIRST"
@toc "List functions"

MAPFIRST
--------

@{b}   MAPFIRST@{ub} applies a function to all list elements.

@{b}     (MAPFIRST@{ub} FUNC LIST [...]@{b})@{ub}

   Builds a list whose elements are the result of the specified function
called with the arguments of the given list elements one by one.  The
length of the returned list is as long as the length of the longest
specified list.  If one of the specified lists is too short then the
list is padded with NIL elements.

Examples
--------

@{b}Expression@{ub}                                    @{b}Value@{ub}

(MAPFIRST 1+ (LIST 1 2 3))             ( 2 3 4 )
(MAPFIRST + (LIST 1 2 3) (LIST 2 3))   ( 3 5 NIL )


@endnode

@node "SORTLIST" "MUIbase/SORTLIST"
@toc "List functions"

SORTLIST
--------

@{b}   SORTLIST@{ub} sorts the elements of a list.

@{b}     (SORTLIST@{ub} FUNC LIST@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a copy of the specified list that has been sorted using the
function FUNC for ordering.  The order function must take two arguments
one for each element and return an integer value less than zero if the
first element is smaller than the second one, a value greater then zero
if the first element is greater than the second one, and a value of
zero if the two elements are equal.

   Example for a string comparing function usable for sorting:

     (DEFUN cmp_str (x y)
         (COND
             ((< x y) -1)
             ((> x y) 1)
             (TRUE 0)
         )
     )

   Now you can sort a list by calling:

     (SORTLIST cmp_str (LIST "hi" "fine" "great" "ok"))

which results to ( "fine" "great" "hi" "ok" ).

   See also @{"SORTLISTGT" link "SORTLISTGT"}, @{"MAPFIRST" link "MAPFIRST"}.


@endnode

@node "SORTLISTGT" "MUIbase/SORTLISTGT"
@toc "List functions"

SORTLISTGT
----------

@{b}   SORTLIST@{ub} sorts the elements of a list.

@{b}     (SORTLISTGT@{ub} GTFUNC LIST@{b})@{ub}

   Like @{b}SORTLIST@{ub} but here you specify an order function that returns a
value not equal to NIL if the first element is greater then the second
one, and NIL otherwise.

   Example: @{b}(SORTLISTGT > (LIST "hi" "fine" "great" "ok"))@{ub} result to (
"fine" "great" "hi" "ok" ).

   See also @{"SORTLIST" link "SORTLIST"}, @{"MAPFIRST" link "MAPFIRST"}.


@endnode

@node "Input requesting functions" "MUIbase/Input requesting functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Input Requesting Functions
==========================

   For requesting information from the user, the following functions
can be used.


 @{" ASKFILE      " link "ASKFILE"}  Requesting a filename.
 @{" ASKDIR       " link "ASKDIR"}  Requesting a directory name.
 @{" ASKSTR       " link "ASKSTR"}  Requesting a string.
 @{" ASKINT       " link "ASKINT"}  Requesting an integer.
 @{" ASKCHOICE    " link "ASKCHOICE"}  Requesting one item out of many items.
 @{" ASKCHOICESTR " link "ASKCHOICESTR"}  Requesting a string, offering predefined ones.
 @{" ASKOPTIONS   " link "ASKOPTIONS"}  Requesting some items out of many items.
 @{" ASKBUTTON    " link "ASKBUTTON"}  Requesting the user to press a button.
 @{" ASKMULTI     " link "ASKMULTI"}  Requesting several informations.


@endnode

@node "ASKFILE" "MUIbase/ASKFILE"
@toc "Input requesting functions"

ASKFILE
-------

@{b}   ASKFILE@{ub} prompts the user for entering a filename.

@{b}     (ASKFILE@{ub} TITLE OKTEXT DEFAULT SAVEMODE@{b})@{ub}

   Pops up a file-requester for entering a filename.  The window title
can be set in TITLE, the text of the @{b}Ok@{ub} button in OKTEXT, and the
initial filename in DEFAULT.  You may specify NIL for one of them to
use default values.  The last argument SAVEMODE (Boolean) allows setting
the file-requester to a save mode.  This mode should be used when
asking for a filename to write something to.

@{b}   ASKFILE@{ub} returns the entered filename as string or NIL in case the
user canceled the requester.

   See also @{"ASKDIR" link "ASKDIR"}, @{"ASKSTR" link "ASKSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "ASKDIR" "MUIbase/ASKDIR"
@toc "Input requesting functions"

ASKDIR
------

@{b}   ASKDIR@{ub} prompts the user for entering a directory name.

@{b}     (ASKDIR@{ub} TITLE OKTEXT DEFAULT SAVEMODE@{b})@{ub}

   Pops up a file-requester for entering a directory name.  The
arguments are used in the same way as in @{b}ASKFILE@{ub} (see @{"ASKFILE" link "ASKFILE"}).

@{b}   ASKDIR@{ub} returns the entered directory name as string or NIL in case
the user canceled the requester.

   See also @{"ASKFILE" link "ASKFILE"}, @{"ASKSTR" link "ASKSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "ASKSTR" "MUIbase/ASKSTR"
@toc "Input requesting functions"

ASKSTR
------

@{b}   ASKSTR@{ub} prompts the user for entering a string.

@{b}     (ASKSTR@{ub} TITLE OKTEXT DEFAULT MAXLEN [SECRET]@{b})@{ub}

   Pops up a requester asking for a string to enter.  The window title,
the text of the @{b}Ok@{ub} button, and the initial value can be set in TITLE,
OKTEXT, and DEFAULT respectively (strings or NIL for default values),
MAXLEN determines the maximum characters the user can enter.  If SECRET
is given and is not NIL then the entered string is made invisible by
displaying a bullet sign for each string character.

@{b}   ASKSTR@{ub} returns the entered string or NIL in case the user canceled.

   See also @{"ASKFILE" link "ASKFILE"}, @{"ASKDIR" link "ASKDIR"}, @{"ASKCHOICESTR" link "ASKCHOICESTR"}, @{"ASKINT" link "ASKINT"}.


@endnode

@node "ASKINT" "MUIbase/ASKINT"
@toc "Input requesting functions"

ASKINT
------

@{b}   ASKINT@{ub} prompts the user for entering an integer value.

@{b}     (ASKINT@{ub} TITLE OKTEXT DEFAULT MIN MAX@{b})@{ub}

   Pops up a requester asking for an integer to enter.  The window
title and the text of the @{b}Ok@{ub} button can be specified in TITLE and OKTEXT
(strings or NIL for default values). In DEFAULT you pass the initial
integer value or NIL to start with an empty editing field.  In MIN and
MAX you can set the integer range.  Entered values outside this range
are not accepted by the requester.  Use NIL for default min and max
values.

@{b}   ASKINT@{ub} returns the entered integer or NIL if the user canceled the
requester.

   See also @{"ASKSTR" link "ASKSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "ASKCHOICE" "MUIbase/ASKCHOICE"
@toc "Input requesting functions"

ASKCHOICE
---------

@{b}   ASKCHOICE@{ub} prompts the user to select one item out of many items.

@{b}     (ASKCHOICE@{ub} TITLE OKTEXT CHOICES DEFAULT [TITLES]@{b})@{ub}

   Pops up a requester allowing the user to choose one item out of a
list of items.  You can set the window title and the text of the @{b}Ok@{ub}
button in TITLE and OKTEXT (strings or NIL for default values).  In
CHOICES you specify a list of choices.  You can use a multi-column
format by providing each choice item as a list of sub-items.  The
initial choice value can be set in DEFAULT and is the index in the list
of choices (starting with index 0 for the first item).  Use NIL for no
initial choice.  If the optional argument TITLES is specified and is
non-NIL then a list header containing TITLES is shown.  For using a
multi-column format, specify TITLES as a list of column titles.

   Both, CHOICES and TITLES, can also be given as a memo and a string
(instead of lists).  If so, they are converted to lists automatically
by calling @{b}(MEMOTOLIST CHOICES TRUE)@{ub} (see @{"MEMOTOLIST" link "MEMOTOLIST"}) and @{b}(STRTOLIST
TITLES)@{ub} (see @{"STRTOLIST" link "STRTOLIST"}) respectively.

@{b}   ASKCHOICE@{ub} returns the index of the chosen item or NIL if the user
canceled the requester.

Example
-------

     (LET ((items (LIST "First Entry" 2 3.14 "Last entry")) index)
         (SETQ index (ASKCHOICE "Choose one item" "Ok" items NIL))
         (IF index
             (PRINTF "User chose item num %i with contents <%s>\\n"
                 index (STR (NTH index items))
             )
         )
     )

   Consider the case where you would like to ask the user to select a
certain record in a table.  The table shall be called @{b}Article@{ub} with
attributes @{b}Name@{ub}, @{b}Number@{ub}, and @{b}Prize@{ub}.  The following code fragment shows
how to use ASKCHOICE for asking to select a record with Prize larger
than 10 and ordered by Name:

     (LET ((query (SELECT Article, Name, Number, Prize from Article
     	      WHERE (> Prize 10) ORDER BY Name))
          (recs (MAPFIRST FIRST (REST query)))	; record pointers
          (items (MAPFIRST REST (REST query)))	; choices
          (titles (REST (FIRST query)))		; titles
          (index (ASKCHOICE "Choose" "Ok" items NIL titles))
          (rec (NTH index recs)))
          ; now rec holds the selected record (or NIL on cancel)
     )

   See also @{"ASKCHOICESTR" link "ASKCHOICESTR"}, @{"ASKOPTIONS" link "ASKOPTIONS"}.


@endnode

@node "ASKCHOICESTR" "MUIbase/ASKCHOICESTR"
@toc "Input requesting functions"

ASKCHOICESTR
------------

@{b}   ASKCHOICESTR@{ub} prompts the user for entering a string value offering
several pre-defined ones.

@{b}     (ASKCHOICESTR@{ub} TITLE OKTEXT STRINGS DEFAULT [TITLES]@{b})@{ub}

   Pops up a requester allowing the user to choose one string out of
many strings or to enter any other string in a separate string field.
You can set the window title and the text of the @{b}Ok@{ub} button in TITLE and
OKTEXT (strings or NIL for default values).  In STRINGS you specify a
list of choices.  You can use a multi-column format by providing each
choice item as a list of sub-items.  The initial value of the string
field can be set in DEFAULT (string or NIL for an empty string field).
If the optional argument TITLES is specified and is non-NIL then a list
header containing TITLES is shown.  For using a multi-column format,
specify TITLES as a list of column titles.

   Both, STRINGS and TITLES, can also be given as a memo and a string
(instead of lists).  If so, they are converted to lists automatically
by calling @{b}(MEMOTOLIST STRINGS TRUE)@{ub} (see @{"MEMOTOLIST" link "MEMOTOLIST"}) and @{b}(STRTOLIST
TITLES)@{ub} (see @{"STRTOLIST" link "STRTOLIST"}) respectively.

@{b}   ASKCHOICESTR@{ub} returns the chosen string or NIL if the user canceled
the requester.

Example
-------

     (LET ((strings (LIST "Claudia" "Mats" "Ralphie")) likebest)
         (SETQ likebest
             (ASKCHOICESTR "Who do you like the best?" "Ok" strings
     	    "My collies!"
     	)
         )
         (IF likebest (PRINTF "User chose <%s>\\n" likebest))
     )

   See also @{"ASKCHOICE" link "ASKCHOICE"}, @{"ASKOPTIONS" link "ASKOPTIONS"}.


@endnode

@node "ASKOPTIONS" "MUIbase/ASKOPTIONS"
@toc "Input requesting functions"

ASKOPTIONS
----------

@{b}   ASKOPTIONS@{ub} prompts the user for selecting several items out of a
list of items.

@{b}     (ASKOPTIONS@{ub} TITLE OKTEXT OPTIONS SELECTED [TITLES]@{b})@{ub}

   Pops up a requester allowing the user to select several options out
of a list of options.  You can set the window title and the text of the
@{b}Ok@{ub} button in TITLE and OKTEXT (strings or NIL for default values).  In
OPTIONS you specify a list of options.  You can use a multi-column
format by providing each option item as a list of sub-items.  The
initial selection state can be set in SELECTED as a list of integers
each specifying an index whose corresponding item in OPTIONS should
initially be selected.  Use NIL for all items being unselected.  If the
optional argument TITLES is specified and is non-NIL then a list header
containing TITLES is shown.  For using a multi-column format, specify
TITLES as a list of column titles.

   Both, OPTIONS and TITLES, can also be given as a memo and a string
(instead of lists).  If so, they are converted to lists automatically
by calling @{b}(MEMOTOLIST OPTIONS TRUE)@{ub} (see @{"MEMOTOLIST" link "MEMOTOLIST"}) and @{b}(STRTOLIST
TITLES)@{ub} (see @{"STRTOLIST" link "STRTOLIST"}) respectively.

@{b}   ASKOPTIONS@{ub} returns a list of integers each specifying the index of a
selected item, or NIL in case the user canceled or did not choose any
item.

Example
-------

     (LET ((options (LIST "Salva Mea" "Insomnia" "Don't leave" "7 days & 1 week"))
             (selected (LIST 0 1 3))
         )
         (SETQ selected (ASKOPTIONS "Select music titles" "Ok" options selected))
         (IF selected
             (
                 (PRINTF "User has selected the following items:\\n")
                 (DOLIST (i selected)
                     (PRINTF "\\tnum: %i contents: <%s>\\n" i (STR (NTH i options)))
                 )
             )
         )
     )


@endnode

@node "ASKBUTTON" "MUIbase/ASKBUTTON"
@toc "Input requesting functions"

ASKBUTTON
---------

@{b}   ASKBUTTON@{ub} prompts the user for pressing a button.

@{b}     (ASKBUTTON@{ub} TITLE TEXT BUTTONS CANCELTEXT@{b})@{ub}

   Pops up a requester with the specified window title (string or NIL
for a default title) and specified description text (string or NIL for
no text).  The function waits until the user presses one of the buttons
specified in BUTTONS (list of strings) or the @{b}Cancel@{ub} button.  The text
of the cancel button can be set in CANCELTEXT. If you specify NIL here
then a default text based on the number of buttons you specified is
used.

@{b}   ASKBUTTON@{ub} returns the number of the pressed button (starting with 0
for the first (leftmost) button) or NIL if the user pressed the @{b}Cancel@{ub}
button.

Examples
--------

     (LET ((buttons (LIST "At home" "In bed" "In front of my computer")) index)
         (SETQ index (ASKBUTTON "Please answer:"
             "Where do you want to be tomorrow?" buttons "Don't know")
         )
         (IF index
             (PRINTF "User chose: <%s>\\n" (NTH index buttons))
         )
     )
     
     (ASKBUTTON "Info" "MUIbase is great!" NIL NIL)

   See also @{"ASKCHOICE" link "ASKCHOICE"}.


@endnode

@node "ASKMULTI" "MUIbase/ASKMULTI"
@toc "Input requesting functions"

ASKMULTI
--------

@{b}   ASKMULTI@{ub} prompts the user to enter various kinds of information.

@{b}     (ASKMULTI@{ub} TITLE OKTEXT ITEMLIST@{b})@{ub}

@{b}   ASKMULTI@{ub} is a multi-purpose requester.  It opens a window with the
specified title, a set of GUI objects for editing data, and two buttons
(@{b}Ok@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub}) for terminating the requester.  The text of the @{b}Ok@{ub}
button can be set in OKTEXT (string or NIL for default text).  The set
of GUI objects are specified in ITEMLIST which is a list of items where
each item has one of the following forms:

    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"String"@{ub} INITIAL [HELP [SECRET]]@{b})@{ub}  for editing one line of text,
    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"Memo"@{ub} INITIAL [HELP]@{b})@{ub}     for editing multi-line text,
    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"Integer"@{ub} INITIAL [HELP]@{b})@{ub}  for editing an integer,
    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"Real"@{ub} INITIAL [HELP]@{b})@{ub}     for editing a real,
    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"Date"@{ub} INITIAL [HELP]@{b})@{ub}     for editing a date,
    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"Time"@{ub} INITIAL [HELP]@{b})@{ub}     for editing a time,
    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"Bool"@{ub} INITIAL [HELP]@{b})@{ub}     for a Boolean field,
    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"Choice"@{ub} INITIAL
        @{b}(LIST@{ub} CHOICE ...@{b})@{ub} [HELP]
    @{b})@{ub}                                      for a choice field.
    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"ChoiceList"@{ub} INITIAL
        @{b}(LIST@{ub} CHOICE ...@{b})@{ub} [HELP]
    @{b})@{ub}                                      for selecting one item of a list.
    @{b}(LIST@{ub} TITLE @{b}"Options"@{ub} INITIAL
        @{b}(LIST@{ub} OPTION ...@{b})@{ub} [HELP]
    @{b})@{ub}                                      for selecting several items of a list.
    NON-LIST-EXPR                          for static text

   The title (string or NIL for no title) will be displayed to the left
of the GUI object.  If the initial value is NIL then a default value is
used (e.g. an empty text field).  For choice fields the initial value
must be the index (starting with 0) for the initial active entry, for
choice list fields the initial value may be NIL (no item is activated),
and for options fields the initial value must be a list of integers
representing the indices (starting with 0) of the items that are
initially selected.  The optional help field (string) can be used for
giving more information to the user about the usage of the field.  For
string fields an additional parameter @{b}secret@{ub} can be specified.  If
non-NIL then the contents of the string field are made invisible by
displaying a bullet sign for each string character.

@{b}   ASKMULTI@{ub} returns a list of result values which the user has edited
and acknowledged by pressing the @{b}Ok@{ub} button.  Each result value of a
field has the same format as the one for the initial value, e.g. for a
choice list field the result value is the index of the selected item
(or NIL if no item has been selected), or for an options field the
result value is a list of integers representing the indices of the
selected items.  For static text a value of NIL is returned.

   E.g. if you have specified a date field, a static text field, a
choice field, an options field, and a string field with initial value
"world", and the user has entered 11.11.1999, selected the choice entry
with index number 2, selected the 3rd and 4th item in the options field,
and left the string field untouched then the function returns the list
( 11.11.1999 NIL 2 ( 3 4 ) "world" ).

   If the user cancels the requester, NIL is returned.

Example
-------

     (ASKMULTI "Please edit:" NIL (LIST
         (LIST "N_ame" "String" "")
         (LIST "_Birthday" "Date" NIL)
         (LIST "_Sex" "Choice" 0 (LIST "male" "female"))
         (LIST "_Has car?" "Bool" NIL)
         (LIST "_Likes" "Options" (LIST 0 2)
             (LIST "Beer" "Wine" "Whisky" "Wodka" "Schnaps")
         ))
     )

   Please see also the project @{b}AskDemo.mb@{ub} for further examples.


@endnode

@node "I-O functions" "MUIbase/I-O functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

I/O Functions
=============

   This sections lists functions and variables for input and output
(e.g. printing) of data.


 @{" FOPEN              " link "FOPEN"}  Opening a file for reading/writing.
 @{" FCLOSE             " link "FCLOSE"}  Closing a file.
 @{" stdout             " link "stdout"}  Standard output file handle.
 @{" PRINT              " link "PRINT"}  Printing an expression to stdout.
 @{" PRINTF             " link "PRINTF"}  Formatted printing to stdout.
 @{" FPRINTF            " link "FPRINTF"}  Formatted printing to a file.
 @{" FERROR             " link "FERROR"}  Error checking of a file.
 @{" FEOF               " link "FEOF"}  Detecting end of file.
 @{" FSEEK              " link "FSEEK"}  Setting position in a file.
 @{" FTELL              " link "FTELL"}  Getting current position in a file.
 @{" FGETCHAR           " link "FGETCHAR"}  Reading the next input character from a file.
 @{" FGETCHARS          " link "FGETCHARS"}  Reading several input characters from a file.
 @{" FGETSTR            " link "FGETSTR"}  Reading a string from a file.
 @{" FGETMEMO           " link "FGETMEMO"}  Reading a memo from a file.
 @{" FPUTCHAR           " link "FPUTCHAR"}  Writing a character to a file.
 @{" FPUTSTR            " link "FPUTSTR"}  Writing a string to a file.
 @{" FPUTMEMO           " link "FPUTMEMO"}  Writing a memo to a file.
 @{" FFLUSH             " link "FFLUSH"}  Flushing a file.


@endnode

@node "FOPEN" "MUIbase/FOPEN"
@toc "I-O functions"

FOPEN
-----

@{b}   FOPEN@{ub} opens a file for reading/writing.

@{b}     (FOPEN@{ub} FILENAME MODE [ENCODING]@{b})@{ub}

   Opens the file specified by FILENAME (string).  The MODE parameter
(string) controls the access mode.  Use @{b}"w"@{ub} to open a file for writing,
@{b}"a"@{ub} to append to a file, and @{b}"r"@{ub} for reading from a file.  You may also
use other flags (or combination of flags) like @{b}"r+"@{ub} for reading and
writing.  There is no check done that tests if you have specified a
valid flag string.  However if the file can't be opened, NIL is
returned.

   The optional parameter ENCODING controls the encoding of the file and
is one of the following strings:

@{b}"none"@{ub}:
     No interpretation of characters is performed.  Use this for binary
     files.

@{b}"UTF-8"@{ub}:
     Text is encoded in UTF-8.  Reading and writing converts from/to
     UTF-8.

@{b}"locale"@{ub}:
     Text is encoded in your system locale.  On Windows this is the
     system's code page.  On Mac OS and Linux it is the setting of the
     @{b}LANG@{ub} and @{b}LC_*@{ub} environment variables, see @{b}man locale@{ub}.  On Amiga it
     is the default 8 bit encoding.

@{b}"8-bit"@{ub}:
     Text is encoded in the default 8-bit codeset.  On Windows, Mac OS
     and Linux this is the ISO-8859-1 (latin 1) encoding.  On Amiga it
     is the system's default 8 bit encoding (same as @{b}locale@{ub}).

@{b}"auto"@{ub}:
     The encoding is auto-detected.  If the file is readable then the
     encoding is determined as follows: If all contents conform to
     UTF-8 then @{b}"UTF-8"@{ub} is assumed.  Else if the system's locale is not
     UTF-8 then @{b}"locale"@{ub} is assumed.  Otherwise @{b}"8-bit"@{ub} is assumed.
     When writing and the encoding has not been determined yet then
     first the system's locale encoding is tried.  If there were no
     conversion errors then @{b}"locale"@{ub}, otherwise @{b}"UTF-8"@{ub} is used.

   If no ENCODING parameter is given then @{b}"auto"@{ub} is used.

@{b}   FOPEN@{ub} returns a file handle on success.  On failure NIL is returned.
If FILENAME, MODE or ENCODING are NIL then NIL is returned.

Examples
--------

@{b}   (FOPEN "index.html" "w" "utf-8")@{ub} opens and returns a file handle for
writing to the file @{b}index.html@{ub} and encoding it in UTF-8.

@{b}   (FOPEN "output.txt" "a+")@{ub} opens file @{b}output.txt@{ub} for appending it
using the same text encoding as is already present in the file.  Note
that if you only specify @{b}"a"@{ub} as mode then MUIbase might not be able to
read the file and decide the existing encoding.  In this case the
encoding is decided when writing to the file (and might be different
from the exising one).

   See also @{"FCLOSE" link "FCLOSE"}, @{"stdout" link "stdout"}, @{"FFLUSH" link "FFLUSH"}.


@endnode

@node "FCLOSE" "MUIbase/FCLOSE"
@toc "I-O functions"

FCLOSE
------

@{b}   FCLOSE@{ub} closes a file.

@{b}     (FCLOSE@{ub} FILE@{b})@{ub}

   Closes the given file. Returns 0 on success, NIL if an error has
occurred.  If FILE is NIL then 0 is returned (no error).  After closing
a file accessing the file handle is an illegal operation and results in
aborting program execution with an error message.

   See also @{"FOPEN" link "FOPEN"}, @{"FFLUSH" link "FFLUSH"}.


@endnode

@node "stdout" "MUIbase/stdout"
@toc "I-O functions"

stdout
------

   The global variable @{b}stdout@{ub} holds the file handle to MUIbase's
standard output file.  The output filename can be set in menu item
@{b}Program - Output file@{ub} (see @{"Program output file" link "Program output file"}).

   The output file is openend on the first access of this variable
(e.g. when calling @{b}(FPRINTF stdout ...)@{ub}, or when calling @{b}(PRINTF ...)@{ub}).
The file is not pre-opened on program execution.  This avoids opening
the file when no output is generated, e.g. when you simply want to do
some calculations and change some record contents.

   When opening the output file the mode parameter is either @{b}"w"@{ub} or
@{b}"a+"@{ub} depending on the @{b}Append@{ub} setting in menu item @{b}Program - Output file@{ub}.
The encoding is set to @{b}"auto"@{ub}.

   If MUIbase can't open the program output file then execution is
aborted and an error message is generated.

   See also @{"FOPEN" link "FOPEN"}, @{"PRINTF" link "PRINTF"}.


@endnode

@node "PRINT" "MUIbase/PRINT"
@toc "I-O functions"

PRINT
-----

@{b}   PRINT@{ub} converts an expression to a string and prints it.

@{b}     (PRINT@{ub} ELEM@{b})@{ub}

   Converts the value of ELEM to a readable string and prints it to
@{b}stdout@{ub}.  This function mainly exists for debug purposes.

   See also @{"PRINTF" link "PRINTF"}, @{"stdout" link "stdout"}.


@endnode

@node "PRINTF" "MUIbase/PRINTF"
@toc "I-O functions"

PRINTF
------

@{b}   PRINTF@{ub} prints a formatted string.

@{b}     (PRINTF@{ub} FORMAT [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Formats a string using the given format string and arguments and
prints it to @{b}stdout@{ub}.  Formatting is done like in @{b}SPRINTF@{ub} (see @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}).

@{b}   PRINTF@{ub} returns the number of output characters or NIL on failure.
If FORMAT is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(PRINTF "%i days and %i week" 7 1)@{ub} prints the string "7
days and 1 week" to @{b}stdout@{ub} and returns 17.

   See also @{"PRINT" link "PRINT"}, @{"FPRINTF" link "FPRINTF"}, @{"stdout" link "stdout"}.


@endnode

@node "FPRINTF" "MUIbase/FPRINTF"
@toc "I-O functions"

FPRINTF
-------

@{b}   FPRINTF@{ub} prints a formatted string to a file.

@{b}     (FPRINTF@{ub} FILE FORMAT [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Formats a string using the given format string and arguments and
prints it to the specified file.  Formatting is done like in @{b}SPRINTF@{ub}
(see @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}).

@{b}   FPRINTF@{ub} returns the number of output characters or NIL on failure.
If FILE is NIL then @{b}FPRINTF@{ub} still returns the number of potentially
written characters but no output is actually written.  If FORMAT is NIL
then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"PRINTF" link "PRINTF"}, @{"FOPEN" link "FOPEN"}.


@endnode

@node "FERROR" "MUIbase/FERROR"
@toc "I-O functions"

FERROR
------

@{b}   FERROR@{ub} checks if an file I/O error has occurred.

@{b}     (FERROR@{ub} FILE@{b})@{ub}

returns TRUE if an error for the given file has occurred, NIL
otherwise. If @{b}file@{ub} is NIL, NIL is returned.

   See also @{"FEOF" link "FEOF"}, @{"FOPEN" link "FOPEN"}, @{"FCLOSE" link "FCLOSE"}.


@endnode

@node "FEOF" "MUIbase/FEOF"
@toc "I-O functions"

FEOF
----

@{b}   FEOF@{ub} checks for an end of file status.

@{b}     (FEOF@{ub} FILE@{b})@{ub}

   Tests the end-of-file indicator for the given file and returns TRUE
if it is set.  Otherwise NIL is returned.  If @{b}file@{ub} is NIL, NIL is
returned.

   See also @{"FERROR" link "FERROR"}, @{"FTELL" link "FTELL"}, @{"FOPEN" link "FOPEN"}, @{"FCLOSE" link "FCLOSE"}.


@endnode

@node "FSEEK" "MUIbase/FSEEK"
@toc "I-O functions"

FSEEK
-----

@{b}   FSEEK@{ub} sets the read/write position in a file.

@{b}     (FSEEK@{ub} FILE OFFSET WHENCE@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the read/write position for the given file.  The new position,
measured in bytes, is obtained by adding OFFSET bytes to the position
specified by WHENCE.  If WHENCE is set to SEEK_SET, SEEK_CUR, or
SEEK_END, the OFFSET is relative to the start of the file, the current
position, or end-of-file, respectively.

   On success, @{b}FSEEK@{ub} returns 0.  Otherwise NIL is returned and the file
position stays unchanged.  If FILE, OFFSET, or WHENCE is NIL, or if
WHENCE is not one of the constant values SEEK_SET, SEEK_CUR, or SEEK_END
then NIL is returned.

   Note that after a read operation calling @{b}FSEEK@{ub} with WHENCE as
SEEK_CUR is only supported for encoding @{b}"none"@{ub}.

   See also @{"FTELL" link "FTELL"}, @{"FOPEN" link "FOPEN"}, @{"Pre-defined constants" link "Pre-defined constants"}.


@endnode

@node "FTELL" "MUIbase/FTELL"
@toc "I-O functions"

FTELL
-----

@{b}   FTELL@{ub} returns the read/write position of a file.

@{b}     (FTELL@{ub} FILE@{b})@{ub}

   Determines the current read/write position of the given file
relative to the beginning of the file and returns it as an integer.  If
an error occurs or if @{b}file@{ub} is NIL, then NIL is returned.

   Note that after a read operation calling @{b}FTELL@{ub} is only supported for
encoding @{b}"none"@{ub}.

   See also @{"FSEEK" link "FSEEK"}, @{"FOPEN" link "FOPEN"}, @{"FEOF" link "FEOF"}.


@endnode

@node "FGETCHAR" "MUIbase/FGETCHAR"
@toc "I-O functions"

FGETCHAR
--------

@{b}   FGETCHAR@{ub} reads a character from a file.

@{b}     (FGETCHAR@{ub} FILE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the next character from the given file as a string or NIL if
FILE is NIL, end of file has been reached, or an error has happened.
If the next character is a null character, an empty string is returned.

   See also @{"FGETCHARS" link "FGETCHARS"}, @{"FGETSTR" link "FGETSTR"}, @{"FPUTCHAR" link "FPUTCHAR"}.


@endnode

@node "FGETCHARS" "MUIbase/FGETCHARS"
@toc "I-O functions"

FGETCHARS
---------

@{b}   FGETCHARS@{ub} reads characters from a file.

@{b}     (FGETCHARS@{ub} NUM FILE@{b})@{ub}

returns a string containing the next NUM characters from the given file.
If end of file has been reached before reading NUM characters or if a
null character has been read then only these characters are returned.
If NUM or FILE are NIL, NUM is negative, end of file has been reached
before reading the first character, or a read error has happened then
NIL is returned.

   See also @{"FGETCHAR" link "FGETCHAR"}, @{"FGETSTR" link "FGETSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "FGETSTR" "MUIbase/FGETSTR"
@toc "I-O functions"

FGETSTR
-------

@{b}   FGETSTR@{ub} reads a string from a file.

@{b}     (FGETSTR@{ub} FILE@{b})@{ub}

returns the next line of the given file as a string or NIL if FILE is
NIL, end of file has been reached, or an error happened.  The end of a
line is detected if either a newline character or a null character is
read, or if end of file is detected.  In either case the string does
not contain any newline characters.

   See also @{"FGETCHAR" link "FGETCHAR"}, @{"FGETCHARS" link "FGETCHARS"}, @{"FGETMEMO" link "FGETMEMO"}, @{"FPUTSTR" link "FPUTSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "FGETMEMO" "MUIbase/FGETMEMO"
@toc "I-O functions"

FGETMEMO
--------

@{b}   FGETMEMO@{ub} reads a memo from a file.

@{b}     (FGETMEMO@{ub} FILE@{b})@{ub}

returns a memo that contains the contents of the given file up to the
next null character or up to the end of file.  If FILE is NIL, end of
file has been reached before reading any characters, or an error
occurred then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"FGETSTR" link "FGETSTR"}, @{"FPUTMEMO" link "FPUTMEMO"}.


@endnode

@node "FPUTCHAR" "MUIbase/FPUTCHAR"
@toc "I-O functions"

FPUTCHAR
--------

@{b}   FPUTCHAR@{ub} writes a character to a file.

@{b}     (FPUTCHAR@{ub} STR FILE@{b})@{ub}

   Writes the first character of STR to the given file.  If STR is
empty, a null character is written, if STR or FILE are NIL, nothing
happens.  Returns STR or NIL in case an output error occurred.

   See also @{"FPUTSTR" link "FPUTSTR"}, @{"FGETCHAR" link "FGETCHAR"}.


@endnode

@node "FPUTSTR" "MUIbase/FPUTSTR"
@toc "I-O functions"

FPUTSTR
-------

@{b}   FPUTSTR@{ub} writes a string to a file.

@{b}     (FPUTSTR@{ub} STR FILE@{b})@{ub}

   Prints STR together with a newline character to the given file.  If
STR or FILE are NIL, nothing happens.  Returns STR or NIL in case an
output error occurred.

   See also @{"FPUTCHAR" link "FPUTCHAR"}, @{"FPUTMEMO" link "FPUTMEMO"}, @{"FGETSTR" link "FGETSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "FPUTMEMO" "MUIbase/FPUTMEMO"
@toc "I-O functions"

FPUTMEMO
--------

@{b}   FPUTMEMO@{ub} writes a memo to a file.

@{b}     (FPUTMEMO@{ub} MEMO FILE@{b})@{ub}

   Prints MEMO to the given file.  If MEMO or FILE are NIL, nothing
happens.  Returns MEMO or NIL in case an output error occurred.

   See also @{"FPUTSTR" link "FPUTSTR"}, @{"FGETMEMO" link "FGETMEMO"}.


@endnode

@node "FFLUSH" "MUIbase/FFLUSH"
@toc "I-O functions"

FFLUSH
------

@{b}   FFLUSH@{ub} flushes pending data to a file.

@{b}     (FFLUSH@{ub} FILE@{b})@{ub}

   Flushes all pending output for the given file.  Returns 0 on
success, NIL if an error occurred.  If FILE is NIL then 0 is returned
(no error).

   See also @{"FOPEN" link "FOPEN"}, @{"FCLOSE" link "FCLOSE"}.


@endnode

@node "Record functions" "MUIbase/Record functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Record Functions
================

   This section lists functions that deal with records.


 @{" NEW                " link "NEW"}  Allocating new record.
 @{" NEW*               " link "NEW*"}  Allocating new record by calling trigger function.
 @{" DELETE             " link "DELETE"}  Deleting a record.
 @{" DELETE*            " link "DELETE*"}  Deleting a record by calling trigger function.
 @{" DELETEALL          " link "DELETEALL"}  Deleting all records of a table.
 @{" GETMATCHFILTER     " link "GETMATCHFILTER"}  Getting the match-filter state of a record.
 @{" SETMATCHFILTER     " link "SETMATCHFILTER"}  Setting the match-filter state of a record.
 @{" GETISSORTED        " link "GETISSORTED"}  Checking if a record is in the right order.
 @{" SETISSORTED        " link "SETISSORTED"}  Telling a record its order state.
 @{" RECNUM             " link "RECNUM"}  Getting the record number of a record.
 @{" COPYREC            " link "COPYREC"}  Copying the contents of a record.


@endnode

@node "NEW" "MUIbase/NEW"
@toc "Record functions"

NEW
---

@{b}   NEW@{ub} allocates a new record for a table.

@{b}     (NEW@{ub} TABLE INIT@{b})@{ub}

   Allocates a new record in the given table. The parameter INIT
specifies the record which should be used for initializing the new
record.  A value of NIL stands for the initial record.

@{b}   NEW@{ub} returns a record pointer to the new record.

   The @{b}NEW@{ub} function has the side effect of setting the program record
pointer of the given table (see @{"Tables" link "Tables"}) to the new record.

   Example: @{b}(NEW table NIL)@{ub} allocates a new record in the given table
and initializes it with the initial record.

   See also @{"NEW*" link "NEW*"}, @{"DELETE" link "DELETE"}, @{"Tables" link "Tables"}.


@endnode

@node "NEW*" "MUIbase/NEW*"
@toc "Record functions"

NEW*
----

@{b}   NEW*@{ub} is the star version of @{b}NEW@{ub} (see @{"NEW" link "NEW"}).

@{b}     (NEW*@{ub} TABLE INIT@{b})@{ub}

@{b}   NEW*@{ub} checks if you have specified a @{b}New@{ub} trigger function for the
given table (see @{"New trigger" link "New trigger"}).  If so then this trigger function is
called for allocating the record and its result is returned.  The INIT
parameter can be used to specify a record with which the new record
should be initialized (use NIL for the initial record).

   If no trigger function has been specified, the function behaves like
the @{b}NEW@{ub} function.

   Warning: With this function it is possible to write endless loops,
e.g.  if you have defined a @{b}New@{ub} trigger function for a table and this
function calls @{b}NEW*@{ub} to allocate the record.

   See also @{"NEW" link "NEW"}, @{"DELETE*" link "DELETE*"}.


@endnode

@node "DELETE" "MUIbase/DELETE"
@toc "Record functions"

DELETE
------

@{b}   DELETE@{ub} deletes a record in a table.

@{b}     (DELETE@{ub} TABLE REQUESTER@{b})@{ub}

   Deletes the current program record of the given table after an
optional delete requester.  The first argument specifies the table for
which the current program record should be deleted, the second argument
is a Boolean expression.  If it is NIL then the record is deleted
silently, if it is not NIL then the state of preferences menu item
@{b}Record delete requester@{ub} is checked.  If it is not set, the record is
deleted silently, otherwise the standard delete requester appears
asking for confirmation.  If the users cancels the delete operation
then the record will not be deleted.

   The return code of the @{b}DELETE@{ub} function reflects the selected action.
If it returns TRUE then the record has been deleted, otherwise (the
user has canceled the operation) NIL is returned.

   On deletion, @{b}DELETE@{ub} sets the program record pointer (see @{"Tables" link "Tables"}) of
the specified table to NIL.

   Example: @{b}(DELETE table NIL)@{ub} deletes the current record in the given
table silently.

   See also @{"DELETE*" link "DELETE*"}, @{"DELETEALL" link "DELETEALL"}, @{"NEW" link "NEW"}, @{"Tables" link "Tables"}.


@endnode

@node "DELETE*" "MUIbase/DELETE*"
@toc "Record functions"

DELETE*
-------

@{b}   DELETE*@{ub} is the star version of @{b}DELETE@{ub} (see @{"DELETE" link "DELETE"}).

@{b}     (DELETE*@{ub} TABLE REQUESTER@{b})@{ub}

@{b}   DELETE*@{ub} checks if you have specified a @{b}Delete@{ub} trigger function for
the given table (see @{"Delete trigger" link "Delete trigger"}).  If so then this trigger
function is called for deleting the record and its result is returned.
The REQUESTER parameter can be used to specify if the trigger function
should pop up a confirmation requester before deleting the record.

   If no trigger function has been specified, the function behaves like
the @{b}DELETE@{ub} function.

   Warning: With this function it is possible to write endless loops,
e.g.  if you have defined a @{b}Delete@{ub} trigger function for a table and
this function calls @{b}DELETE*@{ub} to delete the record.

   See also @{"DELETE" link "DELETE"}, @{"DELETEALL" link "DELETEALL"}, @{"NEW*" link "NEW*"}.


@endnode

@node "DELETEALL" "MUIbase/DELETEALL"
@toc "Record functions"

DELETEALL
---------

@{b}   DELETEALL@{ub} deletes all records of a table.

@{b}     (DELETEALL@{ub} TABLE[@{b}*@{ub}]@{b})@{ub}

   Deletes all records of the specified table.  If you add a star behind
the table name then only those records that match the current filter of
the table are deleted.  There is no safety requester before deleting
the records.

@{b}   DELETEALL@{ub} returns TRUE on successful deletion of all records,
otherwise NIL is returned.  If TABLE is NIL then NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(DELETEALL table*)@{ub} deletes all records in the given table
that match the filter of the table.

   See also @{"DELETE" link "DELETE"}, @{"Tables" link "Tables"}.


@endnode

@node "GETMATCHFILTER" "MUIbase/GETMATCHFILTER"
@toc "Record functions"

GETMATCHFILTER
--------------

@{b}   GETMATCHFILTER@{ub} returns the match-filter state of a record.

@{b}     (GETMATCHFILTER@{ub} REC@{b})@{ub}

   Returns TRUE if the specified record matches the filter of its
table, NIL otherwise.  If the filter of the table is currently not
active then TRUE is returned.  If REC is NIL (the initial record) then
NIL is returned.

   See also @{"SETMATCHFILTER" link "SETMATCHFILTER"}, @{"GETISSORTED" link "GETISSORTED"}, @{"GETFILTERSTR" link "GETFILTERSTR"}, @{"SETFILTERSTR" link "SETFILTERSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "SETMATCHFILTER" "MUIbase/SETMATCHFILTER"
@toc "Record functions"

SETMATCHFILTER
--------------

@{b}   SETMATCHFILTER@{ub} sets the match-filter state of a record.

@{b}     (SETMATCHFILTER@{ub} REC ON@{b})@{ub}

   Changes the match-filter state of the specified record to the value
of ON.  @{b}SETMATCHFILTER@{ub} returns the new match-filter state of the given
record.  The new state may be different from the expected one because
setting the match-filter state to NIL does only work when the filter of
the corresponding table is currently active, otherwise TRUE is returned.
Calling @{b}SETMATCHFILTER@{ub} with a value of NIL for REC (the initial record)
will always return NIL.

   See also @{"GETMATCHFILTER" link "GETMATCHFILTER"}, @{"SETISSORTED" link "SETISSORTED"}, @{"GETFILTERSTR" link "GETFILTERSTR"}, @{"SETFILTERSTR" link "SETFILTERSTR"}.


@endnode

@node "GETISSORTED" "MUIbase/GETISSORTED"
@toc "Record functions"

GETISSORTED
-----------

@{b}   GETISSORTED@{ub} returns the sorted state of a record.

@{b}     (GETISSORTED@{ub} REC@{b})@{ub}

   Returns TRUE if the specified record is sorted in the order that has
been defined for its table, NIL otherwise.  If REC is NIL then NIL is
returned.

   See also @{"SETISSORTED" link "SETISSORTED"}, @{"GETMATCHFILTER" link "GETMATCHFILTER"}, @{"REORDER" link "REORDER"}, @{"GETORDERSTR" link "GETORDERSTR"},
@{"SETORDERSTR" link "SETORDERSTR"}, @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.


@endnode

@node "SETISSORTED" "MUIbase/SETISSORTED"
@toc "Record functions"

SETISSORTED
-----------

@{b}   SETISSORTED@{ub} sets the sorted state of a record.

@{b}     (SETISSORTED@{ub} REC ON@{b})@{ub}

   Changes the sorted state of the specified record to the value of ON.
Use this function if you think that a certain record is in the right
order (ON = TRUE), or it it should be reordered (ON = NIL).  Reordering
all unsorted records can be done by calling the @{b}REORDER@{ub} function (see
@{"REORDER" link "REORDER"}).

@{b}   SETISSORTED@{ub} returns the new sorted state of the given record.
Calling @{b}SETISSORTED@{ub} with a value of NIL for REC (the initial record)
will return NIL.

   For an example on how to use this function, see @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.

   See also @{"GETISSORTED" link "GETISSORTED"}, @{"SETMATCHFILTER" link "SETMATCHFILTER"}, @{"REORDER" link "REORDER"}, @{"GETORDERSTR" link "GETORDERSTR"},
@{"SETORDERSTR" link "SETORDERSTR"}, @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.


@endnode

@node "RECNUM" "MUIbase/RECNUM"
@toc "Record functions"

RECNUM
------

@{b}   RECNUM@{ub} returns the record number of a record.

@{b}     (RECNUM@{ub} RECORD@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the record number of the given record.  Please note that the
numbering for records is different than e.g. for lists.  For lists,
strings and others the counting begins with zero, however for records
it begins with 1 for the first record.  The number 0 is reserved for
the initial record.  This seems to be inconsistent with the rest of the
MUIbase programming functions, but it does really makes sense here as
the record numbers are also used in the window display.

   See also @{"RECORDS" link "RECORDS"}, @{"INT" link "INT"}.


@endnode

@node "COPYREC" "MUIbase/COPYREC"
@toc "Record functions"

COPYREC
-------

@{b}   COPYREC@{ub} copies records.

@{b}     (COPYREC@{ub} REC SOURCE@{b})@{ub}

   Copies the contents of record SOURCE to record REC.  If SOURCE is
NIL then REC is set to the values of the initial record.  If REC is NIL
then an error message is generated.

@{b}   COPYREC@{ub} returns REC.

   See also @{"NEW" link "NEW"}.


@endnode

@node "Attribute functions" "MUIbase/Attribute functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Attribute Functions
===================

   This section lists functions that work on attributes of a table.


 @{" ATTRNAME             " link "ATTRNAME"}  Getting the name of an attribute.
 @{" MAXLEN               " link "MAXLEN"}  Maximum number of characters for a string attribute.
 @{" GETLABELS            " link "GETLABELS"}  Getting the labels of a choice or string attribute.
 @{" SETLABELS            " link "SETLABELS"}  Setting the list-view labels of a string attribute.


@endnode

@node "ATTRNAME" "MUIbase/ATTRNAME"
@toc "Attribute functions"

ATTRNAME
--------

@{b}   ATTRNAME@{ub} returns the name of an attribute.

@{b}     (ATTRNAME@{ub} ATTR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a string containing the name of the specified attribute.

   See also @{"TABLENAME" link "TABLENAME"}


@endnode

@node "MAXLEN" "MUIbase/MAXLEN"
@toc "Attribute functions"

MAXLEN
------

@{b}   MAXLEN@{ub} returns the maximum size of a string attribute.

@{b}     (MAXLEN@{ub} STRING-ATTR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the maximum number of characters that the given string
attribute can hold.

   See also @{"LEN" link "LEN"}.


@endnode

@node "GETLABELS" "MUIbase/GETLABELS"
@toc "Attribute functions"

GETLABELS
---------

@{b}   GETLABELS@{ub} returns all labels of a choice or string attribute.

@{b}     (GETLABELS@{ub} ATTR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the labels of the given choice or string attribute.  In case
of a choice attribute, the labels you entered in the attribute
requester (see @{"Type specific settings" link "Type specific settings"}) are returned, in case of a
string attribute, the static labels you entered for the list-view
pop-up (see @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}) are returned (note that this
function is only useful for static labels).

   The labels are returned in one single string and are separated by
newline characters.

   For example, consider you have a choice attribute with the labels
@{b}Car@{ub}, @{b}House@{ub}, and @{b}Oil@{ub}.  Then calling @{b}GETLABELS@{ub} on that attribute will
result to the string "Car\\nHouse\\nOil".

   Note: you can easily convert the result string to a list by calling
@{b}MEMOTOLIST@{ub} (see @{"MEMOTOLIST" link "MEMOTOLIST"}) on the result string.

   See also @{"SETLABELS" link "SETLABELS"}.


@endnode

@node "SETLABELS" "MUIbase/SETLABELS"
@toc "Attribute functions"

SETLABELS
---------

@{b}   SETLABELS@{ub} is used to set the labels of a string attribute.

@{b}     (SETLABELS@{ub} ATTR STR@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the static labels of the string attribute ATTR to the labels
listed in the STR argument.  The STR argument consists of lines each of
which holds one label.  The labels replace the ones you have entered
for the pop-up list-view in the attribute object editor (see
@{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}).  Note that this function is only useful for
static labels.

@{b}   SETLABELS@{ub} returns the value of its STR argument.

   Example: @{b}(SETLABELS Table.String "My house\\nis\\nyour house")@{ub} sets
the static list-view labels of the specifies string attribute to @{b}My
house@{ub}, @{b}is@{ub}, and @{b}your house@{ub}.

   Note: you can easily convert a list of labels to the required string
format by calling @{"LISTTOMEMO" link "LISTTOMEMO"} on the list.

   See also @{"GETLABELS" link "GETLABELS"}.


@endnode

@node "Table functions" "MUIbase/Table functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Table Functions
===============


 @{" TABLENAME          " link "TABLENAME"}  Getting the name of a table.
 @{" GETORDERSTR        " link "GETORDERSTR"}  Getting record order.
 @{" SETORDERSTR        " link "SETORDERSTR"}  Setting record order.
 @{" REORDER            " link "REORDER"}  Reordering unsorted records.
 @{" REORDERALL         " link "REORDERALL"}  Reorder all records of a table.
 @{" GETFILTERACTIVE    " link "GETFILTERACTIVE"}  Getting record filter state.
 @{" SETFILTERACTIVE    " link "SETFILTERACTIVE"}  Setting record filter state.
 @{" GETFILTERSTR       " link "GETFILTERSTR"}  Getting record filter expression.
 @{" SETFILTERSTR       " link "SETFILTERSTR"}  Setting record filter expression.
 @{" RECORDS            " link "RECORDS"}  Number of records.
 @{" RECORD             " link "RECORD"}  Getting pointer to a record.
 @{" SELECT             " link "SELECT"}  Select-from-where queries.


@endnode

@node "TABLENAME" "MUIbase/TABLENAME"
@toc "Table functions"

TABLENAME
---------

@{b}   TABLENAME@{ub} returns the name of a table.

@{b}     (TABLENAME@{ub} TABLE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns a string containing the name of the specified table.

   See also @{"ATTRNAME" link "ATTRNAME"}


@endnode

@node "GETORDERSTR" "MUIbase/GETORDERSTR"
@toc "Table functions"

GETORDERSTR
-----------

@{b}   GETORDERSTR@{ub} returns the record order of a table.

@{b}     (GETORDERSTR@{ub} TABLE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the current order expression of the given table.  If the
table uses an attribute list for ordering then the returned string
contains the attribute names separated by spaces. Each attribute name
is prepended by a @{b}+@{ub} or a @{b}-@{ub} sign indicating ascending or descending
order.

   If the table is ordered by a comparison function then the name of
this function is returned.

   An empty string means no ordering.

Example
-------

   Consider a table @{b}Person@{ub} which is ordered by the Attributes @{b}Name@{ub}
(ascending), @{b}Town@{ub} (ascending), and @{b}Birthday@{ub} (descending).  Then
@{b}(ORDERSTR Person)@{ub} will result to the string "+Name +Town -Birthday".

   See also @{"SETORDERSTR" link "SETORDERSTR"}, @{"REORDER" link "REORDER"}, @{"REORDERALL" link "REORDERALL"}, @{"GETISSORTED" link "GETISSORTED"},
@{"SETISSORTED" link "SETISSORTED"}, @{"Order" link "Order"}, @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.


@endnode

@node "SETORDERSTR" "MUIbase/SETORDERSTR"
@toc "Table functions"

SETORDERSTR
-----------

@{b}   SETORDERSTR@{ub} sets the record order of a table.

@{b}     (SETORDERSTR@{ub} TABLE ORDER@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the order of the given table according to the ORDER string.
The ORDER string can either hold a list of attribute names or the name
of a comparison function.

   For sorting using an attribute list, the ORDER string must contain
the attribute names separated by any number of spaces, tabs or
newlines.  Each attribute name may be prepended by a @{b}+@{ub} or a @{b}-@{ub} sign
indicating ascending or descending order.  If you omit this sign then
ascending ordering is assumed.

   For sorting using a comparison function, the ORDER string must hold
the name of the function.

@{b}   SETORDERSTR@{ub} returns TRUE if it has been able to set the new order,
NIL otherwise, e.g. if an unknown attribute has been specified or the
type of the attribute is not allowed for ordering.  If you specify NIL
for the ORDER argument then nothing happens and NIL is returned.

   Note: For building the order string you should not directly write the
attribute names into the string because when you change an attribute
name then the order string will not be updated.  Better use the
@{b}ATTRNAME@{ub} function (see @{"ATTRNAME" link "ATTRNAME"}) to copy the attribute's name into the
order string.

Example
-------

   Consider a table @{b}Person@{ub} with the attributes @{b}Name@{ub}, @{b}Town@{ub}, and @{b}Birthday@{ub}.
Then @{b}(SETORDERSTR Person (SPRINTF "+%s" (ATTRNAME Person.Name)))@{ub} will
set the order of table @{b}Person@{ub} using @{b}Name@{ub} as (ascending) order attribute.

   See also @{"GETORDERSTR" link "GETORDERSTR"}, @{"REORDER" link "REORDER"}, @{"REORDERALL" link "REORDERALL"}, @{"GETISSORTED" link "GETISSORTED"},
@{"SETISSORTED" link "SETISSORTED"}, @{"Order" link "Order"}, @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.


@endnode

@node "REORDER" "MUIbase/REORDER"
@toc "Table functions"

REORDER
-------

@{b}   REORDER@{ub} brings all unsorted records back into the right order.

@{b}     (REORDER@{ub} TABLE@{b})@{ub}

   Examines all records of the given table for unsorted ones and
reinserts them to their right positions.  After reinserting an unsorted
record, the sorted state of the record is set to TRUE, thus on the
return of @{b}REORDER@{ub} the sorted state of all records is TRUE.

@{b}   REORDER@{ub} returns NIL.

   Usually you only need to call this function, when you are using a
comparison function for defining the order of a table.  Orders defined
by an attribute list are automatic, that is, a record is reordered
automatically when needed.

   For an example on how to use this function, see @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.

   See also @{"REORDERALL" link "REORDERALL"}, @{"GETORDERSTR" link "GETORDERSTR"}, @{"SETORDERSTR" link "SETORDERSTR"}, @{"GETISSORTED" link "GETISSORTED"},
@{"SETISSORTED" link "SETISSORTED"}, @{"Order" link "Order"}, @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.


@endnode

@node "REORDERALL" "MUIbase/REORDERALL"
@toc "Table functions"

REORDERALL
----------

@{b}   REORDERALL@{ub} reorders all records of a table.

@{b}     (REORDERALL@{ub} TABLE@{b})@{ub}

   Reorders all records of the given table by setting the sorted state
of all records to NIL and then calling @{b}REORDER@{ub} for reordering
everything.

@{b}   REORDERALL@{ub} returns NIL.

   See also @{"REORDER" link "REORDER"}, @{"GETORDERSTR" link "GETORDERSTR"}, @{"SETORDERSTR" link "SETORDERSTR"}, @{"GETISSORTED" link "GETISSORTED"},
@{"SETISSORTED" link "SETISSORTED"}, @{"Order" link "Order"}, @{"Comparison function" link "Comparison function"}.


@endnode

@node "GETFILTERACTIVE" "MUIbase/GETFILTERACTIVE"
@toc "Table functions"

GETFILTERACTIVE
---------------

@{b}   GETFILTERACTIVE@{ub} returns the filter state of a table.

@{b}     (GETFILTERACTIVE@{ub} TABLE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns TRUE if the filter of the specified table is currently
activated and NIL otherwise.

   See also @{"SETFILTERACTIVE" link "SETFILTERACTIVE"}, @{"GETFILTERSTR" link "GETFILTERSTR"}, @{"GETMATCHFILTER" link "GETMATCHFILTER"}.


@endnode

@node "SETFILTERACTIVE" "MUIbase/SETFILTERACTIVE"
@toc "Table functions"

SETFILTERACTIVE
---------------

@{b}   SETFILTERACTIVE@{ub} sets the filter state of a table.

@{b}     (SETFILTERACTIVE@{ub} TABLE BOOL@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the filter state of the specified table.  If BOOL is non-NIL
then the filter is activated, otherwise it is deactivated.

@{b}   SETFILTERACTIVE@{ub} returns the new state of the filter.  The new state
may not be the expected one in case you activate the filter but an
error condition occurs and the filter can't be activated.  However
deactivating the filter always succeeds.

   See also @{"GETFILTERACTIVE" link "GETFILTERACTIVE"}, @{"SETFILTERSTR" link "SETFILTERSTR"}, @{"SETMATCHFILTER" link "SETMATCHFILTER"}.


@endnode

@node "GETFILTERSTR" "MUIbase/GETFILTERSTR"
@toc "Table functions"

GETFILTERSTR
------------

@{b}   GETFILTERSTR@{ub} returns the record filter expression of a table.

@{b}     (GETFILTERSTR@{ub} TABLE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the record filter expression of the specified table as a
string.  An empty string means that no filter expression has been set
for this table.

   See also @{"SETFILTERSTR" link "SETFILTERSTR"}, @{"GETFILTERACTIVE" link "GETFILTERACTIVE"}, @{"GETMATCHFILTER" link "GETMATCHFILTER"}.


@endnode

@node "SETFILTERSTR" "MUIbase/SETFILTERSTR"
@toc "Table functions"

SETFILTERSTR
------------

@{b}   SETFILTERSTR@{ub} sets the record filter expression of a table.

@{b}     (SETFILTERSTR@{ub} TABLE FILTER-STR@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the record filter expression of the specified table to the
expression in the FILTER-STR argument (which must be a string and not
the actual expression itself!).  If the filter of the given table is
currently active then the new filter expression is directly applied to
all records and the match-filter state of all records are recomputed.

@{b}   SETFILTERSTR@{ub} returns TRUE if it has been able to compile the given
filter string expression, otherwise NIL is returned.  Note that you
only get the result of the compilation.  If the filter of the given
table is currently active and recomputing all match-filter states of
the corresponding records fails then you will not notice that from the
result of this function.  The recommended way to set a new filter
expression is like follows:

     (SETFILTERACTIVE Table NIL)               ; always succeeds.
     (IF (NOT (SETFILTERSTR Table filter-string))
         (ERROR "Can't set filter string for %s!" (TABLENAME Table))
     )
     (IF (NOT (SETFILTERACTIVE Table TRUE))
         (ERROR "Can't activate filter for %s!" (TABLENAME Table))
     )

   If @{b}SETFILTERSTR@{ub} is called with a value of NIL for the FILTER-STR
argument then nothing happens and NIL is returned.

   Example: @{b}(SETFILTERSTR Table "(> Value 0.0)")@{ub}.

   See also @{"GETFILTERSTR" link "GETFILTERSTR"}, @{"SETFILTERACTIVE" link "SETFILTERACTIVE"}, @{"SETMATCHFILTER" link "SETMATCHFILTER"}.


@endnode

@node "RECORDS" "MUIbase/RECORDS"
@toc "Table functions"

RECORDS
-------

@{b}   RECORDS@{ub} returns the number of records in a table.

@{b}     (RECORDS@{ub} TABLE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the number of records in the given table.  You may append a
star to the table name for counting the number of records that match
the filter of the table.

   See also @{"RECORD" link "RECORD"}, @{"RECNUM" link "RECNUM"}.


@endnode

@node "RECORD" "MUIbase/RECORD"
@toc "Table functions"

RECORD
------

@{b}   RECORD@{ub} returns a record pointer for a given record number.

@{b}     (RECORD@{ub} TABLE NUM@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the record pointer to the NUM-th record in the given table
or NIL if a record with this number doesn't exist.  You may add a star
to the table name to get the NUM-th record that matches the record
filter of the table.

   Please note that record numbers start with 1 and record number 0 is
used for the initial record.

   See also @{"RECORDS" link "RECORDS"}, @{"RECNUM" link "RECNUM"}.


@endnode

@node "SELECT" "MUIbase/SELECT"
@toc "Table functions"

SELECT
------

@{b}   SELECT@{ub} extracts and returns various data from records.

@{b}     (SELECT@{ub} [@{b}DISTINCT@{ub}] EXPRLIST @{b}FROM@{ub} TABLELIST
             [@{b}WHERE@{ub} WHERE-EXPR] [@{b}ORDER BY@{ub} ORDERLIST]@{b})@{ub}

where EXPRLIST is either a simple star @{b}*@{ub} or a list of expressions with
optional titles separated by commas:

     EXPRLIST:     @{b}*@{ub} | EXPR @{b}"title",@{ub} ...

and TABLELIST is a list of table names:

     TABLELIST:      TABLE[@{b}*@{ub}] [@{b}ident@{ub}]@{b},@{ub} ...

   For each table in the table list you can specify an identifier.
This can be very useful if a table occurs more than once in the table
list (see example of comparing ages below).  If you add a star to a
table then only the records matching the currently defined filter of
that table will be examined.

   The orderlist has the following syntax:

     ORDERLIST:    EXPR [@{b}ASC@{ub} | @{b}DESC@{ub}]@{b},@{ub} ...

where EXPR, ... can be arbitrary expressions or field numbers.  For
example @{b}(SELECT Name FROM ... ORDER BY 1)@{ub} will sort the result by the
@{b}Name@{ub} attribute.  You may specify @{b}ASC@{ub} or @{b}DESC@{ub} for an ascending or
descending order.  If none of them are present then an ascending order
is assumed.

How it works
------------

   The select-from-where query builds the (mathematical) cross product
of all tables in the table list (it examines all sets of records in
TABLE, ...)  and checks the where-expression (if any).  If the
where-expression results to TRUE (or there is no where-expression) then
a list is build whose elements are calculated by the expression list in
the select-part.  If you have specified a single star for the
expression list then the list contains the values of all attributes
belonging to tables in the table list (except virtual attributes and
buttons).

   The result of the query is a list of lists. The first list entry
contains the title strings, the remaining ones contain the values of
the from-list in the matching records.

Examples
--------

   See @{"Query examples" link "Query examples"}, for some examples using the @{b}SELECT@{ub} function.

   See also @{"FOR ALL" link "FOR ALL"}.


@endnode

@node "GUI functions" "MUIbase/GUI functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

GUI Functions
=============

   This section describes functions for manipulating GUI elements.


 @{" SETCURSOR          " link "SETCURSOR"}  Placing the cursor on a GUI element.
 @{" GETWINDOWOPEN      " link "GETWINDOWOPEN"}  Getting open/close state of a window.
 @{" SETWINDOWOPEN      " link "SETWINDOWOPEN"}  Opening/closing of a window.
 @{" GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE " link "GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE"}  Getting the active line of a virtual attribute.
 @{" SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE " link "SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE"}  Setting the active line of a virtual attribute.


@endnode

@node "SETCURSOR" "MUIbase/SETCURSOR"
@toc "GUI functions"

SETCURSOR
---------

@{b}   SETCURSOR@{ub} sets the cursor on a GUI element.

@{b}     (SETCURSOR@{ub} ATTR-OR-TABLE@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the cursor on the given attribute or table GUI object.  The
function also opens the window where the attribute/table resides in if
the window was not open.

@{b}   SETCURSOR@{ub} returns TRUE if everything went ok (window could be
opened) or NIL on failure.

   See also @{"SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE" link "SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE"}.


@endnode

@node "GETWINDOWOPEN" "MUIbase/GETWINDOWOPEN"
@toc "GUI functions"

GETWINDOWOPEN
-------------

@{b}   GETWINDOWOPEN@{ub} returns the open state of a window.

@{b}     (GETWINDOWOPEN@{ub} ATTR-OR-TABLE@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the open state of the window where the given attribute/table
resides.

   See also @{"SETWINDOWOPEN" link "SETWINDOWOPEN"}.


@endnode

@node "SETWINDOWOPEN" "MUIbase/SETWINDOWOPEN"
@toc "GUI functions"

SETWINDOWOPEN
-------------

@{b}   SETWINDOWOPEN@{ub} opens and closes a window.

@{b}     (SETWINDOWOPEN@{ub} ATTR-OR-TABLE OPEN@{b})@{ub}

   Opens or closes the window in which the given attribute/table
resides.  If OPEN is non-NIL then the window is opened, otherwise it is
closed.  You cannot close the main window of a project.

@{b}   SETWINDOWOPEN@{ub} returns the new open state of the window.

   See also @{"GETWINDOWOPEN" link "GETWINDOWOPEN"}.


@endnode

@node "GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE" "MUIbase/GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE"
@toc "GUI functions"

GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE
--------------------

@{b}   GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE@{ub} returns the index of the active line of a
virtual attribute that uses the @{b}List@{ub} kind for display.

@{b}     (GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE@{ub} VIRTUAL-ATTR@{b})@{ub}

   Returns the logical index (starting with 1) of the currently active
line in the specified virtual attribute.  The logical index is the line
number in the original list used when setting the virtual attribute.
It can differ from the display order in case the user changed the
sorting, e.g. by clicking on a column title.  If the GUI element of
VIRTUAL-ATTR is not visible, or if it does not use the @{b}List@{ub} kind for
display, or if no line is active, then NIL is returned.

   See also @{"SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE" link "SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE"}.


@endnode

@node "SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE" "MUIbase/SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE"
@toc "GUI functions"

SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE
--------------------

@{b}   SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE@{ub} sets the active line of a virtual attribute
that uses the @{b}List@{ub} kind for display.

@{b}     (SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE@{ub} VIRTUAL-ATTR NUM@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the active line of the given virtual attribute to the NUM-th
logical line (starting with 1).  The logical line is the line number in
the original list used when setting the virtual attribute and can
differ from the display order in case the user changed the sorting,
e.g. by clicking on a column title.

   Returns NUM, or NIL if the GUI element of VIRTUAL-ATTR is not
visible, does not use the @{b}List@{ub} kind for display, or if NUM is out of
range (less than 1 or greater than the number of lines).

@{b}   SETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE@{ub} does not set the cursor to the attribute's GUI
element, use @{b}SETCURSOR@{ub} (see @{"SETCURSOR" link "SETCURSOR"}) for doing so.

   See also @{"GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE" link "GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE"}, @{"SETCURSOR" link "SETCURSOR"}.


@endnode

@node "Project functions" "MUIbase/Project functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Project Functions
=================

   This section lists functions dealing with projects.


 @{" PROJECTNAME " link "PROJECTNAME"}  Getting the project name.
 @{" CHANGES    " link "CHANGES"}  Getting number of changes made to current project.
 @{" GETADMINMODE " link "GETADMINMODE"}  Checking for admin or user mode.
 @{" SETADMINMODE " link "SETADMINMODE"}  Setting admin or user mode.
 @{" ADMINPASSWORD " link "ADMINPASSWORD"}  SHA1 hash of admin password.


@endnode

@node "PROJECTNAME" "MUIbase/PROJECTNAME"
@toc "Project functions"

PROJECTNAME
-----------

@{b}   PROJECTNAME@{ub} returns the project name.

@{b}     (PROJECTNAME)@{ub}

@{b}   PROJECTNAME@{ub} returns the name of the current project as a string or
NIL if no name has been defined yet.  The project name is the pathname
of the project directory in the file system.

   See also @{"CHANGES" link "CHANGES"}.


@endnode

@node "CHANGES" "MUIbase/CHANGES"
@toc "Project functions"

CHANGES
-------

@{b}   CHANGES@{ub} returns the number of changes in the current project.

@{b}     (CHANGES)@{ub}

   Returns an integer containing the number of changes since the last
save operation of the current project.

   See also @{"PROJECTNAME" link "PROJECTNAME"}.


@endnode

@node "GETADMINMODE" "MUIbase/GETADMINMODE"
@toc "Project functions"

GETADMINMODE
------------

@{b}   GETADMINMODE@{ub} tells whether the current project is in admin mode or
user mode.

@{b}     (GETADMINMODE)@{ub}

   Returns TRUE if the current project is in admin mode, NIL otherwise.

   See also @{"SETADMINMODE" link "SETADMINMODE"}, @{"ADMINPASSWORD" link "ADMINPASSWORD"}, @{"onAdminMode" link "onAdminMode"}.


@endnode

@node "SETADMINMODE" "MUIbase/SETADMINMODE"
@toc "Project functions"

SETADMINMODE
------------

@{b}   SETADMINMODE@{ub} changes the current project to admin mode or user mode.

@{b}     (SETADMINMODE@{ub} ADMIN@{b})@{ub}

   If ADMIN is NIL then the current project is set into user mode,
otherwise into admin mode.  Note that there is no authentification
dialog when changing from user to admin mode using this function.

   Returns TRUE if the project has been set to admin mode, or NIL if
set to user mode.

   See also @{"GETADMINMODE" link "GETADMINMODE"}, @{"ADMINPASSWORD" link "ADMINPASSWORD"}, @{"onAdminMode" link "onAdminMode"}, demo @{b}Users.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "ADMINPASSWORD" "MUIbase/ADMINPASSWORD"
@toc "Project functions"

ADMINPASSWORD
-------------

@{b}   ADMINPASSWORD@{ub} obtains the admin password as SHA1 hash string.

@{b}     (ADMINPASSWORD)@{ub}

   Returns a string containing the SHA1 hash of the admin password of
the current project.  If no admin password has been set, NIL is
returned.

   See also @{"GETADMINMODE" link "GETADMINMODE"}, @{"SETADMINMODE" link "SETADMINMODE"}, @{"SHA1SUM" link "SHA1SUM"}, demo @{b}Users.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "System functions" "MUIbase/System functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

System Functions
================

   This section lists functions accessing the operating system.


 @{" EDIT       " link "EDIT"}  Launching external editor synchronously.
 @{" EDIT*      " link "EDIT*"}  Launching external editor asynchronously.
 @{" VIEW       " link "VIEW"}  Launching external viewer synchronously.
 @{" VIEW*      " link "VIEW*"}  Launching external viewer asynchronously.
 @{" SYSTEM     " link "SYSTEM"}  Calling external commands synchronously.
 @{" SYSTEM*    " link "SYSTEM*"}  Calling external commands asynchronously.
 @{" STAT       " link "STAT"}  Examining a file.
 @{" TACKON     " link "TACKON"}  Creating pathname from components.
 @{" DIRNAME    " link "DIRNAME"}  Getting directory name from a path.
 @{" FILENAME   " link "FILENAME"}  Getting last component of a path.
 @{" MESSAGE    " link "MESSAGE"}  Showing messages to the user.
 @{" COMPLETEMAX " link "COMPLETEMAX"}  Setting max number of progress steps.
 @{" COMPLETEADD " link "COMPLETEADD"}  Increasing current progress state.
 @{" COMPLETE   " link "COMPLETE"}  Setting absolute progress state.
 @{" GC         " link "GC"}  Forcing garbage collection.
 @{" PUBSCREEN  " link "PUBSCREEN"}  Name of public screen (Amiga).


@endnode

@node "EDIT" "MUIbase/EDIT"
@toc "System functions"

EDIT
----

@{b}   EDIT@{ub} launches the external editor.

@{b}     (EDIT@{ub} FILENAME@{b})@{ub}

   Starts the external editor for editing the specified file.  The
external editor can be set in menu item @{b}Preferences - External editor@{ub}
(see @{"External editor" link "External editor"}).  @{b}EDIT@{ub} starts the external editor synchronously,
that is, it waits until the user exits the editor.

@{b}   EDIT@{ub} returns the return code of the external editor as an integer.

   See also @{"EDIT*" link "EDIT*"}, @{"VIEW" link "VIEW"}, @{"SYSTEM" link "SYSTEM"}.


@endnode

@node "EDIT*" "MUIbase/EDIT*"
@toc "System functions"

EDIT*
-----

@{b}   EDIT*@{ub} is the star version of @{b}EDIT@{ub} and has the same effect as @{b}EDIT@{ub}
(see @{"EDIT" link "EDIT"}).  The only difference is that @{b}EDIT*@{ub} starts the external
editor asynchronously, thus the function returns immediately.

@{b}   EDIT*@{ub} returns 0 if it was successful in starting the editor,
otherwise it returns a non-zero integer value representing a system
specific error code.

   See also @{"EDIT" link "EDIT"}, @{"VIEW*" link "VIEW*"}, @{"SYSTEM*" link "SYSTEM*"}.


@endnode

@node "VIEW" "MUIbase/VIEW"
@toc "System functions"

VIEW
----

@{b}   VIEW@{ub} launches the external viewer.

@{b}     (VIEW@{ub} FILENAME@{b})@{ub}

   Starts the external viewer for displaying the specified file.  The
external viewer can be set in menu item @{b}Preferences - External viewer@{ub}
(see @{"External viewer" link "External viewer"}).  @{b}VIEW@{ub} starts the external viewer synchronously,
that is, it waits until the user exits the viewer.  Note that on some
systems, the call might return immediately if an instance of the viewer
is already running.

@{b}   VIEW@{ub} returns the return code of the external viewer as an integer.

   See also @{"VIEW*" link "VIEW*"}, @{"EDIT" link "EDIT"}, @{"SYSTEM" link "SYSTEM"}.


@endnode

@node "VIEW*" "MUIbase/VIEW*"
@toc "System functions"

VIEW*
-----

@{b}   VIEW*@{ub} is the star version of @{b}VIEW@{ub} and has the same effect as @{b}VIEW@{ub}
(see @{"VIEW" link "VIEW"}).  The only difference is that @{b}VIEW*@{ub} starts the external
viewer asynchronously, thus the function returns immediately.

@{b}   VIEW*@{ub} returns 0 if it was successful in starting the viewer,
otherwise it returns a non-zero integer value representing a system
specific error code.

   See also @{"VIEW" link "VIEW"}, @{"EDIT*" link "EDIT*"}, @{"SYSTEM*" link "SYSTEM*"}.


@endnode

@node "SYSTEM" "MUIbase/SYSTEM"
@toc "System functions"

SYSTEM
------

@{b}   SYSTEM@{ub} calls an external program.

@{b}     (SYSTEM@{ub} FMT [ARG ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Calls an external program.  The command line to call the program is
generated from FMT and the optional arguments like in the @{b}SPRINTF@{ub}
function (see @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}).  For interpreting the command line, a system
specific shell is used (ShellExecute on Windows, /bin/sh on Mac OS and
Linux, the user shell on Amiga).  @{b}SYSTEM@{ub} waits until the called program
exits.

@{b}   SYSTEM@{ub} returns the return code of the executed command as an integer.

   See also @{"SYSTEM*" link "SYSTEM*"}, @{"EDIT" link "EDIT"}, @{"VIEW" link "VIEW"}.


@endnode

@node "SYSTEM*" "MUIbase/SYSTEM*"
@toc "System functions"

SYSTEM*
-------

@{b}   SYSTEM*@{ub} is the star version of @{b}SYSTEM@{ub} and has the same effect as
@{b}SYSTEM@{ub} (see @{"SYSTEM" link "SYSTEM"}).  The only difference is that @{b}SYSTEM*@{ub} executes the
command line asynchronously, thus the function returns immediately.

@{b}   SYSTEM*@{ub} returns 0 if it was successful in starting execution of the
command line, otherwise it returns a non-zero integer value
representing a system specific error code.

   See also @{"SYSTEM" link "SYSTEM"}, @{"EDIT*" link "EDIT*"}, @{"VIEW*" link "VIEW*"}.


@endnode

@node "STAT" "MUIbase/STAT"
@toc "System functions"

STAT
----

@{b}   STAT@{ub} examines a filename.

@{b}     (STAT@{ub} FILENAME@{b})@{ub}

   Examines if the specified filename exists in the file system.  @{b}STAT@{ub}
returns NIL if the filename could not be found, 0 if the filename
exists and is a directory, and an integer value greater than 0 if the
filename exists and is a regular file.


@endnode

@node "TACKON" "MUIbase/TACKON"
@toc "System functions"

TACKON
------

@{b}   TACKON@{ub} creates a pathname.

@{b}     (TACKON@{ub} DIRNAME [COMPONENT ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Joins DIRNAME and all components in [COMPONENT ...]  to a pathname.
@{b}TACKON@{ub} knows how to deal with special characters used as path
separators at the end of each argument.  It returns the pathname as a
string or NIL if any of the arguments is NIL.  Note that @{b}TACKON@{ub} does
not perform any check whether the resulting path actually refers to an
existing file or directory in the filesystem.

   Example: @{b}(TACKON "Sys:System" "CLI")@{ub} results to "Sys:System/CLI".

   See also @{"FILENAME" link "FILENAME"}, @{"DIRNAME" link "DIRNAME"}.


@endnode

@node "FILENAME" "MUIbase/FILENAME"
@toc "System functions"

FILENAME
--------

@{b}   FILENAME@{ub} extracts the filename part of a path name.

@{b}     (FILENAME@{ub} PATH@{b})@{ub}

   Extracts the last component of the given path name.  There is no
check whether PATH actually refers to a file, thus it is also possible
to use @{b}FILENAME@{ub} to get the name of a sub-directory.  @{b}FILENAME@{ub} returns
its result as a string or NIL if PATH is NIL.

   Example: @{b}(FILENAME "Sys:System/CLI")@{ub} results to "CLI".

   See also @{"DIRNAME" link "DIRNAME"}, @{"TACKON" link "TACKON"}.


@endnode

@node "DIRNAME" "MUIbase/DIRNAME"
@toc "System functions"

DIRNAME
-------

@{b}   DIRNAME@{ub} extracts the directory part of a path name.

@{b}     (DIRNAME@{ub} PATH@{b})@{ub}

   Extracts the directory part of the given path name.  There is no
check whether PATH actually refers to a file, thus it is also possible
to use @{b}DIRNAME@{ub} to get the name of a parent directory.  @{b}DIRNAME@{ub} returns
its result as a string or NIL if PATH is NIL.

   Example: @{b}(DIRNAME "Sys:System/CLI")@{ub} results to "Sys:System".

   See also @{"FILENAME" link "FILENAME"}, @{"TACKON" link "TACKON"}.


@endnode

@node "MESSAGE" "MUIbase/MESSAGE"
@toc "System functions"

MESSAGE
-------

@{b}   MESSAGE@{ub} displays a message to the user.

@{b}     (MESSAGE@{ub} FMT [ARG ...]@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the window title of the pause/abort window (if it is open).
The title string is generated from FMT and the optional arguments like
in the @{b}SPRINTF@{ub} function (see @{"SPRINTF" link "SPRINTF"}).

@{b}   MESSAGE@{ub} returns the formatted title string.

   Example: @{b}(MESSAGE "6 * 7 = %i" (* 6 7))@{ub}.

   See also @{"PRINT" link "PRINT"}, @{"PRINTF" link "PRINTF"}.


@endnode

@node "COMPLETEMAX" "MUIbase/COMPLETEMAX"
@toc "System functions"

COMPLETEMAX
-----------

@{b}   COMPLETEMAX@{ub} sets the maximum number of progress steps.

@{b}     (COMPLETEMAX@{ub} STEPS@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the maximum number of steps for showing the progress of your
MUIbase program to the user.  The default (if you do not call this
function) is 100 steps.  The argument STEPS must be an integer value.
If STEPS is NIL or 0 then no progress bar is displayed.  The progress
bar is part of the pause/abort window that pops up after a short delay
when executing a MUIbase program.

@{b}   COMPLETEMAX@{ub} returns its argument STEPS.

   See also @{"COMPLETEADD" link "COMPLETEADD"}, @{"COMPLETE" link "COMPLETE"}.


@endnode

@node "COMPLETEADD" "MUIbase/COMPLETEADD"
@toc "System functions"

COMPLETEADD
-----------

@{b}   COMPLETEADD@{ub} increases the progress state.

@{b}     (COMPLETEADD@{ub} ADD@{b})@{ub}

   Adds the integer expression ADD to the current progress value.
Initially, the progress value is set to 0.  If ADD is NIL then the
progress value is reset to 0 and no progress bar is shown.

@{b}   COMPLETEADD@{ub} returns its argument ADD.

Example:
--------

         (SETQ num ...)
         (COMPLETEMAX num)
         (DOTIMES (i num)
             (COMPLETEADD 1)
         )

   See also @{"COMPLETEMAX" link "COMPLETEMAX"}, @{"COMPLETE" link "COMPLETE"}.


@endnode

@node "COMPLETE" "MUIbase/COMPLETE"
@toc "System functions"

COMPLETE
--------

@{b}   COMPLETE@{ub} sets the progress state.

@{b}     (COMPLETE@{ub} CUR@{b})@{ub}

   Sets the current progress value to the integer expression CUR.  If
CUR is NIL or 0 then no progress bar is shown.

@{b}   COMPLETE@{ub} returns its argument CUR.

Example:
--------

         (COMPLETE 10)
         ...
         (COMPLETE 50)
         ...
         (COMPLETE 100)

   See also @{"COMPLETEMAX" link "COMPLETEMAX"}, @{"COMPLETEADD" link "COMPLETEADD"}.


@endnode

@node "GC" "MUIbase/GC"
@toc "System functions"

GC
--

@{b}   GC@{ub} forces garbage collection.

@{b}     (GC)@{ub}

   Forces garbage collection and returns NIL.  Normally garbage
collection is done automatically from time to time.


@endnode

@node "PUBSCREEN" "MUIbase/PUBSCREEN"
@toc "System functions"

PUBSCREEN
---------

@{b}   PUBSCREEN@{ub} returns name of public screen.

@{b}     (PUBSCREEN)@{ub}

   On Amiga, @{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} returns the name of the public screen MUIbase is
running on, or NIL in case the screen is not public.

   On other systems @{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} returns NIL.


@endnode

@node "Pre-defined variables" "MUIbase/Pre-defined variables"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Pre-Defined Variables
=====================

   MUIbase knows some pre-defined global variables.

   In the current version there exists only one global variable: @{b}stdout@{ub}
(see @{"stdout" link "stdout"}).


@endnode

@node "Pre-defined constants" "MUIbase/Pre-defined constants"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Pre-Defined Constants
=====================

   The following pre-defined constants can be used in any expression
for programming.

Name            Type            Value           Comment
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
@{b}NIL@{ub}             any             NIL
@{b}TRUE@{ub}            Boolean         TRUE
@{b}RESET@{ub}           string          "\\33c"
@{b}NORMAL@{ub}          string          "\\33[0m"
@{b}ITON@{ub}            string          "\\33[3m"
@{b}ITOFF@{ub}           string          "\\33[23m"
@{b}ULON@{ub}            string          "\\33[4m"
@{b}ULOFF@{ub}           string          "\\33[24m"
@{b}BFON@{ub}            string          "\\33[1m"
@{b}BFOFF@{ub}           string          "\\33[22m"
@{b}ELITEON@{ub}         string          "\\33[2w"
@{b}ELITEOFF@{ub}        string          "\\33[1w"
@{b}CONDON@{ub}          string          "\\33[4w"
@{b}CONDOFF@{ub}         string          "\\33[3w"
@{b}WIDEON@{ub}          string          "\\33[6w"
@{b}WIDEOFF@{ub}         string          "\\33[5w"
@{b}NLQON@{ub}           string          "\\33[2\\"z"
@{b}NLQOFF@{ub}          string          "\\33[1\\"z"
@{b}INT_MAX@{ub}         integer         2147483647      Maximum integer value
@{b}INT_MIN@{ub}         integer         -2147483648     Minimum integer value
@{b}HUGE_VAL@{ub}        real            1.797693e+308   Largest absolute real value
@{b}PI@{ub}              real            3.14159265359
@{b}OSTYPE@{ub}          string          <OS type>       "Windows", "MacOSX", "Unix" or "Amiga"
@{b}OSVER@{ub}           integer         <OS version>
@{b}OSREV@{ub}           integer         <OS revision>
@{b}MBVER@{ub}           integer         <MUIbase version>
@{b}MBREV@{ub}           integer         <MUIbase revision>
@{b}LANGUAGE@{ub}        string          depends         Default language
@{b}SEEK_SET@{ub}        integer         see stdio.h     Seek from beg. of file
@{b}SEEK_CUR@{ub}        integer         see stdio.h     Seek from current pos
@{b}SEEK_END@{ub}        integer         see stdio.h     Seek from end of file

   See @{"Constants" link "Constants"}, for more information about constants.  For defining
your own constants, use the @{b}#define@{ub} preprocessing directive (see
@{"#define" link "#define"}).


@endnode

@node "Functional parameters" "MUIbase/Functional parameters"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Functional Parameters
=====================

   You can pass a function as an argument to another function.  This is
useful for defining functions of higher order, e.g.  for sorting or
mapping a list.

   To call a function that has been passed in an argument you have to
use the @{b}FUNCALL@{ub} function (see @{"FUNCALL" link "FUNCALL"}).

Example:
--------

     (DEFUN map (l fun)              # arguments: list and function
         (LET (res)                  # local variable res, initialized with NIL
             (DOLIST (i l)           # for all items one by one
                 (SETQ res
                     (CONS (FUNCALL fun i) res)       # calls function and
                 )                                    # build new list
             )
             (REVERSE res)           # we need to reverse the new list
         )
     )

   You can now use the map function for example to increment all items
of a list of integers:

@{b}   (map (LIST 1 2 3 4) 1+)@{ub} results to ( 2 3 4 5 ).

   See also @{"FUNCALL" link "FUNCALL"}, @{"APPLY" link "APPLY"}, @{"MAPFIRST" link "MAPFIRST"}.


@endnode

@node "Type specifiers" "MUIbase/Type specifiers"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Type Specifiers
===============

   It is possible to specify the type of a variable by adding a type
specifier behind the name.  The following type specifiers exist:

@{b}Specifier@{ub}   @{b}Description@{ub}

:INT        for integers
:REAL       for reals
:STR        for strings
:MEMO       for memos
:DATE       for dates
:TIME       for times
:LIST       for lists
:FILE       for file handles
:FUNC       for functions of any type
:TABLE      for record pointers to TABLE

   The type specifier appends the variable name as in the following
example:

     (LET (x:INT (y:REAL 0.0) z) ...)

   The example defines three new variables @{b}x@{ub}, @{b}y@{ub} and @{b}z@{ub}, where @{b}x@{ub} is of
type integer and initialized with NIL, @{b}y@{ub} is of type real and
initialized with 0.0, and @{b}z@{ub} is an untyped variable initialized with NIL.

   The advantage of the type specifiers is that the compiler can detect
more type errors, e.g. if you have a function:

     (DEFUN foo (x:INT) ...)

and call it with @{b}(foo "bar")@{ub} then the compiler generates an error
message.  However, if you call @{b}foo@{ub} with an untyped value, e.g. @{b}(foo
(FIRST list))@{ub} then no error checking can be done at compile time
because the type of @{b}(FIRST list)@{ub} is unknown.

   For reasons of speed no type checking is currently done at run time.
It could be implemented but then would add a little overhead which is
not really necessary as the wrong type will result in a type error
sooner or later anyway.

   Type specifiers for record pointers have another useful feature.  If
you tag a variable as a record pointer to a table then you can access
all attributes of this table by using the variable name instead of the
table name in the attribute path.  E.g. if you have a table @{b}Foo@{ub} with an
attribute @{b}Bar@{ub}, and you define a variable @{b}foo@{ub} as:

     (LET (foo:Foo)

then you can print the @{b}Bar@{ub} attribute of the third record by using:

     (SETQ foo (RECORD Foo 3)) (PRINT foo.Bar)

   Note that in a select-from-where expression, variables defined in the
from list automatically have a type of record pointer to the
corresponding table.


@endnode

@node "Semantics of expressions" "MUIbase/Semantics of expressions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Semantics of Expressions
========================

   The semantics of expressions are very important for understanding
what a program does.  This section lists the semantics depending on
syntactical expressions.

@{b}(@{ub}FUNC [EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}
     Evaluates EXPR ... and then calls the function FUNC (call by
     value).  Returns the return value of the called function.  In
     MUIbase there exists some non-strict functions, e.g.  @{b}AND@{ub}, @{b}OR@{ub} and
     @{b}IF@{ub}.  These functions may not evaluate all expressions.  For more
     information about non-strict functions, see @{"Lisp syntax" link "Lisp syntax"}, @{"AND" link "AND"},
     @{"OR" link "OR"}, and @{"IF" link "IF"}.

@{b}(@{ub}[EXPR ...]@{b})@{ub}
     Evaluates EXPR ... and returns the value of the last expression
     (see @{"PROGN" link "PROGN"}).  An empty expression @{b}()@{ub} evaluates to NIL.

TABLE
     Returns the program record pointer of the given table.

TABLE*
     Returns the GUI record pointer of the given table.

ATTRPATH
     Returns the contents of the specified attribute.  The attribute
     path specifies which record is used to extract the attribute value.
     For example @{b}Table.Attribute@{ub} uses the program record of @{b}Table@{ub} to
     extract the value of the attribute,
     @{b}Table.ReferenceAttribute.Attribute@{ub} uses the program record of
     @{b}Table@{ub} to extract the value of the reference attribute (which is a
     record pointer) and then uses this record to extract the value of
     @{b}Attribute@{ub}.

VAR
     Returns the contents of the global or local variable VAR.  Global
     variables can be defined with @{b}DEFVAR@{ub} (see @{"DEFVAR" link "DEFVAR"}), local
     variables e.g. with @{b}LET@{ub} (see @{"LET" link "LET"}).

VAR.ATTRPATH
     Uses the record pointer of VAR to determine the value of the
     specified attribute.


@endnode

@node "Function triggering" "MUIbase/Function triggering"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

Function Triggering
===================

   For automatic execution of MUIbase programs you can specify trigger
functions for projects, tables and attributes which are called in
specific cases.  This section lists all available trigger possibilities.


 @{" onOpen                     " link "onOpen"}  Trigger after opening a project.
 @{" onClose                    " link "onClose"}  Trigger when closing a project.
 @{" onAdminMode                " link "onAdminMode"}  Trigger when entering/leaving admin mode.
 @{" onChange                   " link "onChange"}  Trigger when changing a project.
 @{" New trigger                " link "New trigger"}  Trigger for allocating a new record.
 @{" Delete trigger             " link "Delete trigger"}  Trigger for deleting a record.
 @{" Comparison function        " link "Comparison function"}  For comparing records of a table.
 @{" Attribute trigger          " link "Attribute trigger"}  Trigger for changing an attribute.
 @{" Virtual attributes         " link "Programming virtual attributes"}  How to write functions for virtual attributes.
 @{" Compute enabled function   " link "Compute enabled function"}  For computing the enabled state of an object.
 @{" Double click trigger       " link "Double click trigger"}  Trigger for double clicks in a virtual list.
 @{" Compute list-view labels   " link "Compute list-view labels"}  Trigger when pressing list-view pop-up.
 @{" Compute reference records  " link "Compute reference records"}  Trigger when pressing reference pop-up.


@endnode

@node "onOpen" "MUIbase/onOpen"
@toc "Function triggering"

onOpen
------

   After opening a project, MUIbase searches the project's program for
a function called @{b}onOpen@{ub}.  If such a function exists then this function
is called without any arguments.

Example
-------

     (DEFUN onOpen ()
         (ASKBUTTON NIL "Thank you for opening me!" NIL NIL)
     )

   See also @{"onClose" link "onClose"}, @{"onAdminMode" link "onAdminMode"}, @{"onChange" link "onChange"}, demo @{b}Trigger.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "onClose" "MUIbase/onClose"
@toc "Function triggering"

onClose
-------

   Before closing a project, MUIbase searches the project's program for
a function called @{b}onClose@{ub}.  If such a function exists then this
function is called without any arguments.  In the current version the
result of the trigger function is ignored and the project is closed
regardless of its return value.

   If you do changes to the project in the @{b}onClose@{ub} function then
MUIbase will ask you for saving the project first before it is actually
closed.  If you use menu item @{b}Project - Save & Close@{ub} for closing the
project, the trigger function is called before saving the project, thus
the changes are saved automatically.

Example
-------

     (DEFUN onClose ()
         (ASKBUTTON NIL "Good bye!" NIL NIL)
     )

   See also @{"onOpen" link "onOpen"}, @{"onChange" link "onChange"}, demo @{b}Trigger.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "onAdminMode" "MUIbase/onAdminMode"
@toc "Function triggering"

onAdminMode
-----------

   Whenever a project is set into admin mode or user mode and a
function called @{b}onAdminMode@{ub} exists in the project's program then this
function is called.  The funnction receives one argument ADMIN telling
whether the project is in admin mode (ADMIN is non-NIL) or in user mode
(ADMIN is NIL).

Example
-------

     (DEFUN onAdminMode (admin)
         (IF admin
     	(ASKBUTTON NIL "Now in admin mode" NIL NIL)
     	(ASKBUTTON NIL "Back to user mode" NIL NIL)
         )
     )

   See also @{"onOpen" link "onOpen"}, @{"onChange" link "onChange"}, @{"SETADMINMODE" link "SETADMINMODE"}, demo @{b}Users.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "onChange" "MUIbase/onChange"
@toc "Function triggering"

onChange
--------

   Whenever the user makes changes to a project or after saving a
project, MUIbase searches the project's program for a function called
@{b}onChange@{ub}.  If such a function exists then this function is called
without any arguments.  This can be used to count the changes a user
does to a project.

Example
-------

     (DEFUN onChange ()
         (SETQ Control.NumChanges (CHANGES))
     )

   In the above example @{b}Control.NumChanges@{ub} could be a virtual attribute
somewhere in an @{b}exactly-one-record@{ub} table for displaying the project's
number of changes.

   See also @{"onOpen" link "onOpen"}, @{"onClose" link "onClose"}, @{"onAdminMode" link "onAdminMode"}, demo @{b}Trigger.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "New trigger" "MUIbase/New trigger"
@toc "Function triggering"

New Trigger
-----------

   When the user wants to allocate a new record by selecting one of the
menu items @{b}New record@{ub} or @{b}Duplicate record@{ub} and the @{b}New@{ub} trigger of that
table has been set to a MUIbase program function then this trigger
function is executed.  The @{b}New@{ub} trigger function can be set in the table
requester (see @{"Creating tables" link "Creating tables"}).

   The trigger function receives NIL or a record pointer as the first
and only argument.  NIL means that the user wants to allocate a new
record, a record pointer means that the user wants to duplicate this
record.  If the trigger function has more than one argument then these
are initialized with NIL.  The trigger function should allocate the new
record by calling the @{b}NEW@{ub} function (see @{"NEW" link "NEW"}).  The result returned by
the trigger function will be examined.  If it returns a record pointer
then this record will be displayed.

   The @{b}New@{ub} trigger is also called when a MUIbase program calls the @{b}NEW*@{ub}
function (see @{"NEW*" link "NEW*"}).

Sample New trigger function
---------------------------

     (DEFUN newRecord (init)
         (PROG1                      ; for returning the result of NEW
             (NEW Table init)
             ...
         )
     )

   See also @{"NEW" link "NEW"}, @{"NEW*" link "NEW*"}, @{"Delete trigger" link "Delete trigger"}.


@endnode

@node "Delete trigger" "MUIbase/Delete trigger"
@toc "Function triggering"

Delete Trigger
--------------

   When the user wants to delete a record by selecting menu item @{b}Delete
record@{ub} and the @{b}Delete@{ub} trigger of that table has been set to a MUIbase
program function then this trigger function is executed.  The @{b}Delete@{ub}
trigger function can be set in the table requester (see
@{"Creating tables" link "Creating tables"}).

   The trigger function receives a Boolean argument as its only
argument.  If the argument is non-NIL then the function should ask the
user if he really wants to delete the record.  If so, the function
should call @{b}DELETE@{ub} (see @{"DELETE" link "DELETE"}) for deleting the record.

   The @{b}Delete@{ub} trigger is also called when a MUIbase program calls the
@{b}DELETE*@{ub} function (see @{"DELETE*" link "DELETE*"}).

Sample Delete trigger function
------------------------------

     (DEFUN deleteRecord (requester)
         (DELETE Table requester)
     )

   See also @{"DELETE" link "DELETE"}, @{"DELETE*" link "DELETE*"}, @{"New trigger" link "New trigger"}.


@endnode

@node "Comparison function" "MUIbase/Comparison function"
@toc "Function triggering"

Comparison Function
-------------------

   For defining an order on the records of a table you can use a
comparison function. See @{"Changing orders" link "Changing orders"}, for information on how to
specify such a function for a table.  The function takes two record
pointers as arguments and returns an integer value reflecting the order
relation of the two records.  The comparison function should return a
value smaller than 0 if its first argument is smaller than the second,
0 if they are equal and a value larger than 0 it the first argument is
greater then the second one.

   For example, if you have a table @{b}Persons@{ub} with a string attribute
@{b}Name@{ub} then you could use the following function for comparing two
records:

     (DEFUN cmpPersons (rec1:Persons rec2:Persons)
         (CMP rec1.Name rec2.Name)
     )

   This will order all records according to the @{b}Name@{ub} field using case
sensitive string comparison. Note that by using an attribute list you
could not archive the same ordering as string comparison is done case
insensitive for attribute lists.

   Using a comparison function you can define very complex order
relations.  Be careful not to create recursive functions that will call
itself.  MUIbase will stop program execution and prompt you with an
error message if you try to do so.  Also you should not use commands
that cause side effects, e.g. setting a value to an attribute.

   When using a comparison function, MUIbase does not always know when
it has to reorder its records.  E.g. consider in the above example
another table @{b}Toys@{ub} with a string attribute @{b}Name@{ub} and a reference
attribute @{b}Owner@{ub} referring to @{b}Persons@{ub}, and the following function for
comparing records:

     (DEFUN cmpToys (rec1:Toys rec2:Toys)
         (CMP* rec1.Owner rec2.Owner)
     )

   This function is using the order of @{b}Persons@{ub} for determining the
order of the records, thus the records of @{b}Toys@{ub} are sorted according to
the order of @{b}Persons@{ub}.

   Now if the user changes one record in the @{b}Persons@{ub} table and this
record gets a new position then also records in @{b}Toys@{ub} that refer to this
record have to be reordered.  MUIbase, however, does not know of this
dependency.

   Besides using menu item @{b}Table - Reorder all records@{ub} on the @{b}Toys@{ub}
table for rearranging the order, you can implement an automatic
reordering yourself by specifying the following trigger function for
the @{b}Name@{ub} attribute of @{b}Persons@{ub}:

     (DEFUN setName (newValue)
         (SETQ Persons.Name newValue)
         (FOR ALL Toys WHERE (= Toys.Owner Persons) DO
             (SETISSORTED Toys NIL)
         )
         (REORDER Toys)
     )

   The function clears the sorted flag for all records that refer to
the current record of table @{b}Persons@{ub} and then reorders all unsorted
records of table @{b}Toys@{ub}.

   See also @{"Order" link "Order"}, @{"CMP" link "CMP"}, @{"GETISSORTED" link "GETISSORTED"}, @{"SETISSORTED" link "SETISSORTED"}, @{"REORDER" link "REORDER"},
@{"REORDERALL" link "REORDERALL"}, @{"GETORDERSTR" link "GETORDERSTR"}, @{"SETORDERSTR" link "SETORDERSTR"}, demo @{b}Order.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Attribute trigger" "MUIbase/Attribute trigger"
@toc "Function triggering"

Attribute Trigger
-----------------

   In the attribute requester (see @{"Creating attributes" link "Creating attributes"}) you can define
a trigger function that is called whenever the user wants to change the
attribute contents.

   If you have defined such a trigger function for an attribute and the
user changes the value of that attribute then the record contents are
not automatically updated with the new value.  Instead the value is
passed to the trigger function as first argument.  The trigger function
can now check the value and may refuse it.  To store the value in the
record you have to use the @{b}SETQ@{ub} function.

   The trigger function should return the result of the @{b}SETQ@{ub} call or
the old value of the attribute if it decides to refuse the new one.

   The trigger function is also called when a MUIbase program calls the
@{b}SETQ*@{ub} function (see @{"SETQ*" link "SETQ*"}) for setting a value to the attribute.

Sample attribute trigger function
---------------------------------

     (DEFUN setAmount (amount)
         (IF SOME-EXPRESSION
             (SETQ Table.Amount amount)
             (ASKBUTTON NIL "Invalid value!" NIL NIL)
         )
         Table.Amount                        ; return current value
     )

   See also @{"SETQ*" link "SETQ*"}


@endnode

@node "Programming virtual attributes" "MUIbase/Programming virtual attributes"
@toc "Function triggering"

Programming Virtual Attributes
------------------------------

   In MUIbase virtual attributes are special attributes that calculate
their value on the fly whenever it is needed.  E.g. if you go to
another record by clicking on one of the arrow buttons in a table's
panel bar then a virtual attribute in that table is automatically
recomputed and displayed (given appropriate settings for the virtual
attribute, see @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}).  For computing the value the
attribute's @{b}Compute@{ub} trigger function is called.  This trigger function
can be specified in the attribute requester (see
@{"Type specific settings" link "Type specific settings"}).  The return value of this function defines
the value of the virtual attribute.  If you don't specify a @{b}Compute@{ub}
trigger function for a virtual attribute then the attribute's value is
NIL.

   You can also trigger the calculation of a virtual attribute by
simply accessing it in an MUIbase program, so e.g. if you have a button
that should compute the value of the virtual attribute, you only need
to specify a function for the button like the following one:

     (DEFUN buttonHook ()
         VIRTUAL-ATTR
     )

   You can also set a virtual attribute to any value by using the @{b}SETQ@{ub}
function:

     (SETQ VIRTUAL-ATTR EXPR)

   However if you access the virtual attribute after the @{b}SETQ@{ub} call then
the value of the virtual attribute is recomputed.

   There is no caching of the value of a virtual attribute because it's
not easy to know when the value has to be recomputed and when not. Thus
you should access virtual attributes rarely and cache the value in
local variables for further use by yourself.

   For an example on how to use virtual attributes please check the
@{b}Movie.mb@{ub} demo.

   See also @{"Virtual" link "Virtual"}, demo @{b}Movie.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Compute enabled function" "MUIbase/Compute enabled function"
@toc "Function triggering"

Compute Enabled Function
------------------------

   For attribute objects and window buttons you can specify a trigger
function for computing the enabled state of the object.  See
@{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"} and @{"Window editor" link "Window editor"}, for information on how to
specify this trigger function.

   The trigger function is called without any arguments.  It should
return NIL for disabling the object and non-NIL for enabling it.

   For example the compute enabled function for an object, that gets
enabled when a certain virtual attribute using the @{b}List@{ub} kind has an
active item, could look like this:

     (DEFUN enableObject ()
         (GETVIRTUALLISTACTIVE VIRTUAL-LIST-ATTR)
     )

   See also @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}, @{"Window editor" link "Window editor"}, demo @{b}Users.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Double click trigger" "MUIbase/Double click trigger"
@toc "Function triggering"

Double Click Trigger
--------------------

   For virtual attributes that use the list kind for displaying its
contents, a trigger function can be specified which gets called
whenever the user double clicks on an item in the list.  See
@{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}, for information on how to specify this
trigger function for a virtual attribute object.

   The trigger functions is called with three arguments.  The first
argument holds the row number of the clicked field, starting with 1 for
the first line (row 0 refers to the list header).  The second argument
holds the column number starting with 0.  The third argument is a
pointer to the record the list field has been generated from, or NIL if
the entry has not been generated directly from one.  The return code of
the function is ignored.

   A typical example of a double click trigger is the following.

     (DEFUN doubleClickTrigger (row col rec:TABLE)
         ...
     )

   Here REC is declared as a record pointer to TABLE.  This way
attributes of TABLE can be accessed directly from REC.

   In case there is more than one possible table the record argument
could belong to, the following construction using type predicates to
different tables is useful.

     (DEFUN doubleClickTrigger (row col rec)
         (COND
     	((RECP TABLE1 rec) (SETQ TABLE1 rec) ...)
             ((RECP TABLE2 rec) (SETQ TABLE2 rec) ...)
     	...
         )
     )

   The list item the user clicked on might not be related to any record.
In this case, the third argument can be ignored and the list element be
accessed like in the following example.

     (DEFUN doubleClickTrigger (row col)
         (PRINT (NTH col (NTH row VIRTUAL-ATTR)))
     )

   See also @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}, demo @{b}Movie.mb@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Compute list-view labels" "MUIbase/Compute list-view labels"
@toc "Function triggering"

Compute Listview Labels
-----------------------

   For string attributes, the GUI object can contain a listview pop-up
that when pressed opens a list of label strings the user can choose
from.  The labels in this list can be static labels or they can be
computed by a trigger function.  See @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}, for
information on how to select between static and computed labels and how
to specify the trigger function.

   The trigger function for computing the labels does not have any
arguments.  It should return a memo text with one label per line or NIL
for no labels.

   For example the compute function could look like this:

     (DEFUN computeLabels ()
         "Tokyo\\nMunich\\nLos Angeles\\nRome"
     )

   See also @{"Compute reference records" link "Compute reference records"}, @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}.


@endnode

@node "Compute reference records" "MUIbase/Compute reference records"
@toc "Function triggering"

Compute Reference Records
-------------------------

   For reference attributes, the GUI object usually contains a pop-up
button that when pressed opens a list of records the user can choose
from.  The list of records in this pop-up can be computed by a trigger
function.  See @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}, for information on how to
specify the trigger function for reference fields.

   The function for computing the list of records does not have any
arguments.  It should return a list that is searched for the occurrence
of records of the referenced table.  Any such record found is added to
the list shown in the reference pop-up.  Items that are not records of
the referenced table are ignored silently.

   A typical compute function for reference records is the following
example.  Say a project contains a table @{b}Person@{ub} with a Boolean attribute
@{b}Female@{ub}.  Then the following compute function only shows the female
persons in the reference popup:

     (DEFUN computeFemaleRecords ()
         (SELECT Person FROM Person WHERE Female)
     )

   See also @{"Compute list-view labels" link "Compute list-view labels"}, @{"Attribute object editor" link "Attribute object editor"}.


@endnode

@node "List of obsolete functions" "MUIbase/List of obsolete functions"
@toc "Programming MUIbase"

List of Obsolete Functions
==========================

   The following functions are obsolete starting with MUIbase version
2.7.

   * @{b}GETDISABLED@{ub}

   * @{b}SETDISABLED@{ub}

   * @{b}GETWINDOWDISABLED@{ub}

   * @{b}SETWINDOWDISABLED@{ub}

   Obsolete functions are not working as expected any longer and calling
any of them is either ignored (resulting in a no-operation), opens a
warning dialog, or causes an error, depening on the setting of menu item
@{b}Program - Obsolete functions@{ub} (see @{"Obsolete functions" link "Obsolete functions"}).

   It is recommended to remove these functions from a project program
and implement the functionality using the enabled/disabled setting of
attribute objects and window buttons (see @{"Compute enabled function" link "Compute enabled function"}).


@endnode

@node "ARexx interface" "MUIbase/ARexx interface"
@toc "Main"

ARexx Interface
***************

   The ARexx interface is only available in the MUIbase version for
Amiga.

   ARexx is a standard interface for Amiga programs to enable access to
functions and data from other programs.  MUIbase provides such an ARexx
port with a small but well defined set of commands that enable an
external program to virtually compute everything a MUIbase program can
compute.  Furthermore MUIbase' ARexx interface implements a transaction
mechanism similar to other relational databases.


 @{" Port name                           " link "ARexx port name"}  How to address the ARexx port.
 @{" Command syntax                      " link "ARexx command syntax"}  How MUIbase ARexx commands look like.
 @{" Return codes                        " link "ARexx return codes"}  Meaning of return values.

Application (MUI)

 @{" Quit                                " link "ARexx quit"}  Quit MUIbase.
 @{" Hide                                " link "ARexx hide"}  Iconifying MUIbase windows.
 @{" Show                                " link "ARexx show"}  Deiconifying MUIbase windows.
 @{" Info                                " link "ARexx info"}  Information about program and author.
 @{" Help                                " link "ARexx help"}  Printing available commands.

Programming

 @{" Compile                             " link "ARexx compile"}  Read & compile external program source.

Database

 @{" Connect                             " link "ARexx connect"}  Opening a project.
 @{" Disconnect                          " link "ARexx disconnect"}  Closing a project.
 @{" Connections                         " link "ARexx connections"}  Displaying all connections.
 @{" Eval                                " link "ARexx eval"}  Running a query.
 @{" Transaction                         " link "ARexx transaction"}  Starting a transaction.
 @{" Commit                              " link "ARexx commit"}  Saving changes of transaction.
 @{" Rollback                            " link "ARexx rollback"}  Ignoring changes of transaction.

   Example ARexx scripts for MUIbase can be found in the @{b}rexx@{ub} directory.


@endnode

@node "ARexx port name" "MUIbase/ARexx port name"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Port Name
=========

   The port name of the MUIbase ARexx port is @{b}MUIbase.N@{ub} where N is a
counter starting with 1.  Usually, if you start MUIbase only once, the
port name is @{b}MUIbase.1@{ub}.

   You need the port name in the ARexx @{b}address@{ub} statement before calling
any of MUIbase' ARexx commands.  The following program fragment shows
how to check for the presence of a MUIbase ARexx port, start MUIbase if
needed, and address the port.

     if ~show(ports, MUIbase.1) then
     do
         address command 'run <nil: >nil: MUIbase:MUIbase -n'
         address command 'waitforport MUIbase.1'
     end
     
     address MUIbase.1

   See also sample ARexx script @{b}address.rexx@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "ARexx command syntax" "MUIbase/ARexx command syntax"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Command Syntax
==============

   After addressing the MUIbase ARexx port you can call any of MUIbase'
ARexx commands.  The syntax is the same as for most other
implementations:

     CMD [ARG1 ...]

   where CMD is one of the commands described further down in this
chapter, and ARG1 ... are optional arguments to the command.

   Since the ARexx interpreter evaluates the command line before
sending it to MUIbase, it is sometimes useful to quote some or all of
the arguments.  It is recommended to use single quotes (') around
arguments which should not be further evaluated by the ARexx
interpreter.  This way you can still place double quotes ("), e.g. for
string constants, in the arguments.  Furthermore you can integrate the
value of ARexx variables by unquoting them.  Here is an example using
MUIbase' @{b}eval@{ub} command.

     search = @{b}@{ub}
     eval handle 'select Name from Person where (like Name "*'search'*")'

   See also @{"Eval" link "ARexx eval"}.


@endnode

@node "ARexx return codes" "MUIbase/ARexx return codes"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Return Codes
============

   After calling one of MUIbase' ARexx commands several ARexx variables
are updated with the result of the command.  For reading all of the
results of a command you should enable the ARexx results option by
adding the following line at the beginning of your ARexx script.

     options results

   There are 3 ARexx variables that can be set by the MUIbase ARexx
interface: RC, RESULTS and LASTERROR.  Variable RC is always set and
reflects the success or failure of a command.  If a command was
successful, RESULTS holds the actual result of the command, whereas in
the case of an unsuccessful command, LASTERROR can hold additional
information describing the error.

   For variable RC the following return codes exist:


@{b}Return code@{ub}  @{b}Meaning@{ub}

   0         Success.  Variable RESULT holds the actual result.
  -1         Implementation error.  Should never happen.
  -2         Out of memory.
  -3         Unknown ARexx command.
  -4         Syntax error.
<= -10       Other error.  Error description can be found in LASTERROR.
 -12         Compilation error (only for @{b}compile@{ub} command).

   Note that only for RC <= -10 variable LASTERROR holds a valid error
description.  In the future more error codes might be added to enable a
more detailed error handling.

   Here is a typical code fragment showing how to examine the result of
a MUIbase ARexx command.

     eval handle 'select * from Accounts'
     if (rc == 0) then
         say result
     else if (rc == -1) then
         say "Implementation error"
     else if (rc == -2) then
         say "Out of memory"
     else if (rc == -3) then
         say "Unknown command"
     else if (rc == -4) then
         say "Command syntax error"
     else if (rc <= -10) then
         say lasterror
     else
         say "Error: " rc


@endnode

@node "ARexx quit" "MUIbase/ARexx quit"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Quit
====

   The @{b}quit@{ub} command causes MUIbase to exit.  See also the MUI
documentation.


@endnode

@node "ARexx hide" "MUIbase/ARexx hide"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Hide
====

   Command @{b}hide@{ub} iconifies all open MUIbase windows.  See also the MUI
documentation.


@endnode

@node "ARexx show" "MUIbase/ARexx show"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Show
====

   Command @{b}show@{ub} deiconifies MUIbase and reopens the windows.  See also
the MUI documentation.


@endnode

@node "ARexx info" "MUIbase/ARexx info"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Info
====

   The @{b}info@{ub} command provides information about title, author,
copyright, description, version, base and screen of a MUI application.


@{b}Command@{ub}           @{b}Value of RESULT@{ub}

info title        Title of application
info author       Author of application
info copyright    Copyright message
info description  Short description
info version      Version string
info base         Name of ARexx port
info screen       Name of public screen

   See also the MUI documentation.


@endnode

@node "ARexx help" "MUIbase/ARexx help"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Help
====

   The @{b}help@{ub} command writes a file containing all available ARexx
commands of a MUI application.

@{b}     help@{ub} FILENAME

   ARexx commands are listed using the AmigaDos command line syntax.
See the MUI documentation for more information and your AmigaDos manual
for the command line syntax.


@endnode

@node "ARexx compile" "MUIbase/ARexx compile"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Compile
=======

   The @{b}compile@{ub} command compiles an external program source file.

@{b}     compile@{ub} SOURCE [@{b}update@{ub}]

   The command compiles the external program source of the project whose
external source filename points to the same file as SOURCE.  On
success, the command returns 0 and, if @{b}update@{ub} has been specified,
re-writes the external source file.  Updating the source file allows to
pretty print the MUIbase keywords.  A successfully compiled program is
then used as the project's program and used when executing trigger
functions.

   If compilation fails, an error code of -12 is returned and LASTERROR
is set to a string containing 4 lines:

   * The first line holds the name of the file the error occurred.

   * The second line holds the error line number starting with 1.

   * The third line holds the error column starting with 1.

   * The fourth line describe the error in readable text.

   Note that a project must have already been opened before sending the
@{b}compile@{ub} command for compiling its external source.  In case no project
whose external source file points to SOURCE is found, an error code <=
-10 (but different from -12) is returned and LASTERROR is set.


@endnode

@node "ARexx connect" "MUIbase/ARexx connect"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Connect
=======

   The @{b}connect@{ub} command opens the communication to a MUIbase project.

@{b}     connect@{ub} PROJECT-NAME [@{b}GUI@{ub}]

   The command first checks if the project specified by @{b}project-name@{ub}
has already been opened and loads it if needed.  A project is only
opened once and multiple connections to the same project share the
access to the database.  Next a unique communication handle is
generated.  A communication handle is an integer value not equal to
zero.  If the keyword @{b}GUI@{ub} has been added to the command line then also
the graphical user interface of the MUIbase project is opened.
Otherwise no graphical user interface is generated allowing to process
MUIbase ARexx commands in the background without direct user
interaction.

   On success, the command returns 0 and sets RESULT to the value of
the handle.

   Example: @{b}connect "MUIbase:Demos/Movies.mb"@{ub} establishes a connection
to the sample movie database.

   See also @{"Disconnect" link "ARexx disconnect"}, @{"Connections" link "ARexx connections"}, @{"Return codes" link "ARexx return codes"}.


@endnode

@node "ARexx disconnect" "MUIbase/ARexx disconnect"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Disconnect
==========

   The @{b}disconnect@{ub} command closes an existing connection.

@{b}     disconnect@{ub} HANDLE

   Closes the database connection given in HANDLE.  If this was the
only connection to the project HANDLE refers to and there is no
graphical user interface for the project then the project is closed and
removed from memory.  Otherwise the project stays open.

   Example: @{b}disconnect 1@{ub} closes connection with handle value 1.

   See also @{"Connect" link "ARexx connect"}, @{"Connections" link "ARexx connections"}, @{"Return codes" link "ARexx return codes"}.


@endnode

@node "ARexx connections" "MUIbase/ARexx connections"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Connections
===========

   To find out about existing connections, use the @{b}connections@{ub} command.

@{b}     connections@{ub}

   On success, @{b}connections@{ub} returns 0 and sets RESULT to a readable
string where each line shows a connection consisting of handle value
and project name.

   Example: the RESULT variable after a @{b}connections@{ub} call could look
like the following:

        3 MUIbase:Demos/Accounts.mb
        5 MUIbase:Demos/Movies.mb
        6 MUIbase:Demos/Movies.mb
        7 MUIbase:Demos/Movies.mb

   See also @{"Connect" link "ARexx connect"}, @{"Disconnect" link "ARexx disconnect"}, @{"Return codes" link "ARexx return codes"}.


@endnode

@node "ARexx eval" "MUIbase/ARexx eval"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Eval
====

   The main interface of MUIbase' ARexx port for retrieving and updating
data is through the @{b}eval@{ub} command.

@{b}     eval@{ub} HANDLE LISP-CMD

   The @{b}eval@{ub} command interprets the given command LISP-CMD (written in
MUIbase' lisp language) on the project specified by HANDLE.  A handle
can be obtained by the @{b}connect@{ub} command.  The command LISP-CMD can be
any expression of MUIbase' programming language.  Optionally the
outmost parenthesis around the expression can be omitted.  It is
recommended to surround LISP-CMD by single quotes as described in
@{"Command syntax" link "ARexx command syntax"}.

   If successful, @{b}eval@{ub} returns 0 and sets RESULT to a string
representation of the return value of LISP-CMD.  The string
representation is done in a way that still allows to find out what kind
of data is returned, e.g. strings are surrounded by double quotes and
lists are surrounded by parenthesis with items separated by spaces or
newline characters.  If you want to ensure a certain format, use your
own formatting withing the specified lisp command.

   If you did changes to the database within the @{b}eval@{ub} command and did
not start a transaction first (see @{"Transaction" link "ARexx transaction"}) then the changes are
automatically made permanent (auto commit).  Otherwise (you did start a
transaction before calling @{b}eval@{ub}) the changes are kept in memory until a
@{b}commit@{ub} command makes them permanent or a @{b}rollback@{ub} command undoes the
changes.

   Example:

     options results
     address MUIbase.1
     connect "MUIbase:Demos/Movie.mb"
     if (rc == 0) then
     do
         handle = result
         eval handle 'select Title, Director from Movies'
     end
     if (rc == 0) then
         say result
The output of the above example could look like this:

     ( ( "Title" "Director" )
       ( "Batman" "Tim Burton" )
       ( "Batman Returns" "Tim Burton" )
       ( "Speechless" "Ron Underwood" )
       ( "Tequila Sunrise" "Robert Towne" )
       ( "Mad Max" "George Miller (II)" )
       ( "Braveheart" "Mel Gibson" )
       ( "2010" "Peter Hyams" ) )

   See also @{"Connect" link "ARexx connect"}, @{"Command syntax" link "ARexx command syntax"}, @{"Return codes" link "ARexx return codes"}, @{"Transaction" link "ARexx transaction"},
@{"Commit" link "ARexx commit"}, sample ARexx script @{b}movies.rexx@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "ARexx transaction" "MUIbase/ARexx transaction"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Transaction
===========

   MUIbase' ARexx port allows to do transactions on a database.  A
transaction is a set of commands to a database (allowing modifications
of data in the database) that is either executed and made permanent
completely (commit) or withdrawn at any point within the transaction
(rollback).  A transaction can be started by issuing the following
command:

@{b}     transaction@{ub} HANDLE
   where HANDLE refers to a project as obtained by the @{b}connect@{ub} command
(see @{"Connect" link "ARexx connect"}).

   After issuing a @{b}transaction@{ub} command you can put as many @{b}eval@{ub}
commands as you like without actually changing the database.  At some
point, however, you have to decide if you want to make changes
permanent (see @{"Commit" link "ARexx commit"}) or to go back to the state before issuing the
@{b}transaction@{ub} command (see @{"Rollback" link "ARexx rollback"}).

   After issuing a @{b}transaction@{ub} command, access to the corresponding
project is made exclusive to the specified handle.  Thus other programs
trying to access the database including the user accessing MUIbase by
its graphical user interface are blocked (or delayed in case of another
ARexx connection) until the exclusive access is released by calling the
@{b}commit@{ub} or @{b}rollback@{ub} command.

   Usually the @{b}transaction@{ub} command returns 0.  In case another ARexx
connection gained exclusive access to the same project as HANDLE refers
to, the call is blocked until the other connection finished by
committing or rolling back the database.

   See also @{"Eval" link "ARexx eval"}, @{"Commit" link "ARexx commit"}, @{"Rollback" link "ARexx rollback"}, @{"Return codes" link "ARexx return codes"}.


@endnode

@node "ARexx commit" "MUIbase/ARexx commit"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Commit
======

   The @{b}commit@{ub} command is used at the end of a transaction to make
changes permanent.

@{b}     commit@{ub} HANDLE

   The @{b}commit@{ub} command ends a transaction (see @{"Transaction" link "ARexx transaction"}) by saving
the project the argument HANDLE refers to.  On success, @{b}commit@{ub} returns
0.  If you did not start a transaction before calling @{b}commit@{ub} or if some
other error occurs a value not equal to 0 is returned.

   See also @{"Rollback" link "ARexx rollback"}, @{"Transaction" link "ARexx transaction"}, @{"Return codes" link "ARexx return codes"}.


@endnode

@node "ARexx rollback" "MUIbase/ARexx rollback"
@toc "ARexx interface"

Rollback
========

   To cancel changes made in a transaction use the @{b}rollback@{ub} command.

@{b}     rollback@{ub} HANDLE

   All changes made in the project referred to by HANDLE since the
beginning of the current transaction (see @{"Transaction" link "ARexx transaction"}) are withdrawn
and the state of the project before the transaction is restored.  If
successful @{b}rollback@{ub} returns 0.

   See also @{"Commit" link "ARexx commit"}, @{"Transaction" link "ARexx transaction"}, @{"Return codes" link "ARexx return codes"}.


@endnode

@node "Menus" "MUIbase/Menus"
@toc "Main"

Menus
*****


Menu Project

 @{" Info                 " link "Info"}  Information about a project.

 @{" New                  " link "New project"}  Starts a new project.
 @{" Clear - Project      " link "Clear project"}  Resets a project.
 @{" Clear - Records      " link "Clear project"}  Deletes all records.
 @{" Open - Project       " link "Open project"}  Loads a project.
 @{" Open - Structure     " link "Open project"}  Loads project without records.

 @{" Save                 " link "Save project"}  Saves project to disk.
 @{" Save & reorg         " link "Save project"}  Saves and reorganizes a project.
 @{" Save & reorg as      " link "Save project"}  Saves and reorganizes with new filename.
 @{" Revert to saved      " link "Save project"}  Reload project when it was saved last.

 @{" Change to admin mode " link "Admin and user mode"}  Restricting access to project structure.
 @{" Change admin password " link "Admin and user mode"}  Authentication for admin mode.

 @{" Check data integrity " link "Check data integrity"}  If your project ever gets corrupted.
 @{" Swap records         " link "Swap records"}  Flush all records to disk.
 @{" Structure editor     " link "Structure editor"}  Open structure editor.
 @{" Export structure     " link "Export structure"}  Overview of all tables and attributes.

 @{" Close                " link "Close project"}  When your are done with a project.
 @{" Save & Close         " link "Close project"}  Saves then closes project.
 @{" Quit                 " link "Getting started"}  Exit MUIbase.

Menu Preferences

 @{" User settings    " link "User settings"}  Global settings stored in user environment.

 @{" Formats              " link "Formats"}  Real and date formats.
 @{" External editor      " link "External editor"}  Specify your external editor.
 @{" External viewer      " link "External viewer"}  Specify your external viewer.

 @{" Extra buttons in Tab chain " link "Extra buttons in Tab chain"}  Include extra buttons in the Tab chain.
 @{" Advance on <Enter>   " link "Advance on Enter"}  Move to next field when pressing @{b}Enter@{ub} key.
 @{" Confirm quit         " link "Confirm quit"}  Safety requester when quitting MUIbase.

 @{" MUI                  " link "MUI"}  MUI's preferences.

 @{" Project settings " link "Project settings"}  Settings stored with a project.

 @{" Record memory        " link "Record memory"}  Size of record buffer.
 @{" Record delete requester " link "Record delete requester"}  Safety requester when deleting records.

 @{" Paths relative to project " link "Paths relative to project"}  How relative path names are treated.
 @{" Confirm save & reorg " link "Confirm save & reorg"}  Safety requester when reorganizing a project.

 @{" Save as default      " link "Save as default"}  Saves project settings for future projects.

Menu Table

 @{" New record           " link "Adding records"}  Adding a new record.
 @{" Duplicate record     " link "Adding records"}  Copying a record.
 @{" Delete record        " link "Deleting records"}  If you don't need a record any more.
 @{" Delete all records   " link "Deleting records"}  If you want to start from scratch.
 @{" Goto Record          " link "Browsing records"}  Browsing records.

 @{" Change filter        " link "Changing filters"}  Specify a filter expression.
 @{" Change order         " link "Changing orders"}  How to specify an order.
 @{" Reorder all records  " link "Reorder all records"}  If records ever become unsorted.

 @{" Search for           " link "Search requester"}  How to search for a record.
 @{" Search forward       " link "Forward-backward search"}  Go to the next matching record.
 @{" Search backward      " link "Forward-backward search"}  Go to the previous matching record.

 @{" Import records       " link "Importing records"}  How to import records.
 @{" Export records       " link "Exporting records"}  How to export records.

Menu Program

 @{" Edit                 " link "Program editor"}  Where to enter a MUIbase program.
 @{" Compile              " link "Program editor"}  Compiling a program.

 @{" Program source       " link "Program source"}  Internal or external program source.
 @{" Cleanup external program source " link "Cleanup external program source"}  Delete external source files when no longer needed.
 @{" Embed debug information " link "Program debug information"}  Compile with or without debug information.
 @{" Obsolete functions   " link "Obsolete functions"}  How to handle calls of obsolete functions.
 @{" Sort trigger functions " link "Sort trigger functions"}  Alphabetical sorting in pop-up windows.

 @{" Include directory    " link "Program include directory"}  Where to look for external include files.
 @{" Output file          " link "Program output file"}  Where program output goes.

